phenomenology: A philosophy or method of inquiry based on the premise that reality consists of objects and events as they are perceived or understood in human consciousness and not of anything independent of human consciousness.

inchoate: Being in a beginning or early stage; incipient.

pendulograph: A tracing made by an instrument in which the movements of two or more pendulums are combined so as to trace a compound curve which represents a musical tone.

velar: Of or relating to a velum.

proteolyze: To cause the hydrolytic decomposition of albumins in (a substance), notably by means of ferments and mineral acids.

acrotomophilia: A paraphilia in which sexual gratification is derived from fantasies or acts involving an amputee.

shrewd: Having or showing a clever awareness or resourcefulness, especially in practical matters.

gynophilia: Alternative spelling of gynephilia. (The love of women).

bolide: A meteoric flash or flare created when a meteoroid explodes or vaporizes as it passes through Earth's atmosphere.

scow: A large flatbottom boat with square ends, used chiefly for transporting freight.

gelotophobia: The fear of being laughed at.

exotherm: In chem., a compound substance in the formation of which from its constituents heat is evolved, and in its decomposition, energy (frequently heat) is absorbed.

nateglinide: An oral hypoglycemic drug, C19H27NO3, that stimulates the release of insulin from the pancreas and is used to treat type 2 diabetes.

amicus curiae: A party that is not involved in a particular litigation but that is allowed by the court to advise it on a matter of law or policy directly affecting the litigation.

morceau: A bit; a morsel; a small piece.

Anthropocene: The current geological period, wherein human activities have a powerful effect on the global environment.

bardolatry: excessive or religious worship of William Shakespeare

lymphatic: Of or relating to lymph or to the nodes or vessels of the lymphatic system.

integumentary: Covering or investing in general, as a skin, rind, or peel.

adequate: Sufficient to satisfy a requirement or meet a need. synonym:sufficient.

chlorophyll: Any of a group of green pigments that absorb light energy used in photosynthesis and that are found in the chloroplasts of plants and other photosynthetic organisms such as cyanobacteria, especially.

groove: A long narrow furrow or channel.

sorghum: A cultivated grass (Sorghum bicolor) native to sub-Saharan Africa, several varieties of which are widely grown for their grain, as forage, or as a source of syrup.

deplete: To consume or reduce to a very low amount; use up.

codec: A device or program capable of performing transformations on a data stream or signal.

vermiculate: To adorn or decorate with wavy or winding lines.

anthophobia: A morbid dislike or even fear of flowers.

pozzolana: A type of volcanic ash used for mortar or for cement which sets under water.

hepatotoxic: toxic to the liver; causing hepatotoxicity

satyagraha: The policy of nonviolent resistance as used by Mahatma Gandhi during the struggle for Indian independence.

capercaillie: A large grouse (Tetrao urogallus), native to northern Europe and having dark plumage and a fanlike tail.

bondieuserie: Any devotional ornament or church object, especially one having little artistic value; a religious knick-knack.

anacoluthia: Want of grammatical sequence or coherence; the passing from one construction to another in the same sentence. For examples, see anacoluthon. Also spelled anakoluthia and anakolouthia.

audiophile: A person having an ardent interest in stereo or high-fidelity sound reproduction.

cosmothetic: Supposing the existence of an external world; affirming the real existence of the external world.

vagitus: The cry of a new-born child.

metathesis: Transposition within a word of letters, sounds, or syllables, as in the change from Old English brid to modern English bird or in the confusion of modren for modern.

obscurantism: The principles or practice of obscurants.

mythopeic: Myth-making; producing or tending to produce myths; suggesting or giving rise to myths. Also mythopoetic.

capsheaf: The top sheaf of a stack of grain; the crowner.

Nibelung: Any of a race of subterranean dwarfs whose hoard of riches and magic ring were taken from them by Siegfried.

reverberate: To resound in a succession of echoes; reecho: synonym:echo.

chevauchement: In surgery, the riding of one bone over another after fracture, giving rise to shortening of the limb.

ngwee: A currency of Zambia, 100 ngwee equal 1 kwacha.

zarzuela: A short drama with incidental music, like a vaudeville. It is said to have been first introduced into Spain at Zarzuela in the seventeenth century.

epithelium: Membranous tissue composed of one or more layers of cells separated by very little intercellular substance and forming the covering of most internal and external surfaces of the body and its organs.

fantods: Plural form of fantod. To have “the fantods” is to be in a state of nervousness, distress, or anxiety.

encroach: To take another's possessions or rights gradually or stealthily.

chalet: A wooden dwelling with a low-pitched roof and wide eaves, common in Alpine regions.

thermantidote: An apparatus used in India for cooling the air. It consists of a revolving wheel fitted to a window, and usually inclosed in wet tatties, through which the air is forced.

cyclas: An upper tunic of ornamental character worn by women under the Roman empire, and assumed by some emperors considered effeminate, as Caligula.

jussive: A word, mood, or form used to express command.

acetylsalicylic: Describing any derivative of salicylic acid in which the phenolic hydroxyl has been acetylated.

Delphinidae: A taxonomic family within the suborder Odontoceti — the dolphins etc.

grift: Money made dishonestly, as in a swindle.

omnibus: A long motor vehicle for passengers; a bus.

aplustre: The ornament rising above the stern of ancient ships.

kepi: A French military cap with a flat circular top and a visor.

leviathan: Something unusually large of its kind, especially a ship.

lithology: The gross physical character of a rock or rock formation.

omphaloskepsis: Contemplation of or meditation upon one's navel.

shard: A broken piece or fragment, as of pottery or glass.

mycotoxin: A toxin produced by a fungus.

futilitarian: Holding or based on the view that human endeavor is futile.

chockablock: Nautical, jammed: said of a tackle when the blocks are hauled close together.

arabica: A species of coffee, Coffea arabica, originating in Ethiopia and Yemen and widely cultivated for its high-quality, commercially valuable seeds.

sequester: To remove or set apart; segregate or hide: synonym:isolate.

acherontic: Of or pertaining to Acheron or the infernal regions; dark; gloomy: as, Acherontic mists.

ratiocination: The mental process of passing from the cognition of premises to the cognition of the conclusion; reasoning.

epigeal: Living or occurring on or near the surface of the ground.

macédoine: A mixture of finely cut vegetables or fruits, sometimes jellied, and served as a salad, a dessert, or an appetizer.

coquandite: A triclinic-pinacoidal mineral containing antimony, hydrogen, oxygen, and sulfur.

bibliobibuli: The sort of people who read too much.

prescind: To separate or detach in thought.

carlin: An old woman: a contemptuous term for any woman.

pyramidion: In architecture, the apex in the shape of a small pyramid which often terminates the top of an obelisk, and was very commonly sheathed with a cap of metal: often applied to any comparatively small structure or member of pyramidal shape.

synastry: Coincidence as regards stellar influence; the state of having similar starry influences presiding over one's fortune, as determined by astrological calculation.

appurtenance: Something associated with another, more important thing; an accessory. synonym:attachment.

nidifugous: Leaving the nest a short time after hatching. Used of a bird.

parosmia: A distortion of the sense of smell, as in smelling odors that are not present.

devoir: An act or expression of respect or courtesy; civility.

glasnost: An official policy of the former Soviet government emphasizing candor with regard to discussion of social problems and shortcomings.

perestroika: The restructuring of the Soviet economy and bureaucracy that began in the mid 1980s.

ethical: Of, relating to, or dealing with ethics.

et cetera: And other unspecified things of the same class; and so forth.

ajwain: The seed of the carom plant, having an aroma of thyme; used in some Asian cooking

Ljubljana: The capital and largest city of Slovenia, in the central part of the country on the Sava River. Founded by the Romans in the first century BC, Ljubljana came under Habsburg rule in AD 1277. It passed to Yugoslavia in 1918 and became the capital of the newly independent republic of Slovenia in 1991.

pachyderm: Any of various large, thick-skinned, hoofed mammals such as the elephant, rhinoceros, or hippopotamus.

inimical: Injurious or harmful in effect; adverse.

vancomycin: An antibiotic, C66H75Cl2N9O24, produced by the actinomycete Amycolatopsis orientalis (formerly Streptomyces orientalis), found in Indonesian and Indian soil, and effective against staphylococci and spirochetes.

idiographic: Relating to or concerned with discrete or unique facts or events.

etiquette: The practices and forms prescribed by social convention or by authority.

illeism: The unnecessarily frequent use of the pronoun he by a writer, especially in reference to himself in the third person; also, an instance of this use.

Qashqai: a tribal confederation of clans of Turkic origin in Iran

hyperuricemia: The presence of an abnormally high concentration of uric acid in the blood, as in gout.

ithyphallic: Of or relating to the phallus carried in the ancient festival of Bacchus.

gadabout: One who roams or roves about, as in search of pleasure or amusement.

troche: A small, circular medicinal lozenge; a pastille.

philopena: A custom or game of reputed German origin: two persons share a nut containing two kernels, and one of them incurs the obligation of giving something as forfeit to the other, either by being first addressed by the latter with the word philopena at their next meeting, or by receiving something from the other's hand, or by answering a question with yes or no, or by some other similar test as agreed upon.

longueur: A tedious passage in a work of literature or performing art.

teetotaler: One who abstains completely from alcoholic beverages.

connate: Existing at birth or from the beginning; inborn or inherent.

gargantuan: Of immense size, extent, or quantity. synonym:enormous.

dollop: A large lump or portion of a solid matter.

swinge: To punish with blows; thrash; beat.

quillon: One of the arms or branches of the cross-guard of a sword. See cross-guard, cross-hilt, cut in next column, and cut under hilt.

chelate: Having chelae or resembling a chela.

finnan: haddock usually baked but sometimes broiled with lots of butter

prandial: Of or relating to a meal.

xanthic: Tending toward a yellow color; of or relating to xanthin; yellow, referring to the color of the urine.

nomothetic: Of or relating to lawmaking; legislative.

faunistic: Of or relating to the geographic distribution of animals.

impresario: One who sponsors or produces entertainment, especially the director of an opera company.

carom: A collision followed by a rebound.

mea culpa: An acknowledgment of a personal error or fault.

cephalalgia: Pain in the head; a headache.

phatic: Of or relating to communication used to perform a social function rather than to convey information or ideas.

eskrima: The traditional martial arts of the Philippines, which emphasize weapon-based fighting with sticks, knives, and various improvised weapons.

jahiliyyah: The age of ignorance, barbarism and unbelief in Arabia before the coming of Islam; more recently its meaning has been expanded to mean Western non-Muslims.

salvific: Having the intention or power to bring about salvation or redemption.

galea: A helmet-shaped part, such as the upper petal of certain plants or part of the maxilla of an insect.

stria: A thin, narrow groove or channel.

campestral: Of, relating to, or growing in uncultivated land or open fields.

fledgling: A young bird that has recently acquired its flight feathers.

auspicate: To begin or inaugurate with a ceremony intended to bring good luck.

saic: A Turkish or Grecian vessel, very common in the Levant, a kind of ketch which has no top-gallantsail nor mizzen-topsail.

oyez: Said loudly three times in succession to call a court to order when the session begins.

millefleur: Having a background with a pattern of flowers and plants.

monger: A dealer in a specific commodity. Often used in combination.

armscye: an opening in a garment for the attachment of a sleeve; an armhole

skopos: The function of a written or spoken text, especially in the context of translating and interpreting.

ahistorical: Conceived or done without consideration of history or historical context.

acheronian: dark and dismal as of the rivers Acheron and Styx in Hades

immure: To confine within or as if within walls; imprison.

chorology: The science of describing localities; chorography.

collieshangie: A noisy quarrel or dispute; a confused uproar.

logogriph: A word puzzle, such as an anagram or one in which clues are given in a set of verses.

dowry: Money or property brought by a bride to her husband at marriage.

candelabrum: A candleholder, especially a large or ornate one with several arms or branches.

dram: A unit of weight in the US Customary System equal to1/16of an ounce or 27.34 grains (1.77 grams).

kylix: A shallow, stemmed, two-handled drinking cup of ancient Greece.

trimillennial: The 3,000th anniversary of an event or happening.

kludge: A system, especially a computer system, that is constituted of poorly matched elements or of elements originally intended for other applications.

nychthemeron: The whole natural day, or day and night, consisting of twenty-four hours.

xeric: Of, characterized by, or adapted to an extremely dry habitat.

truant: One who is absent without permission, especially from school.

zambomba: A rude Spanish musical instrument, consisting of an earthen jar the top of which is covered with parchment, through which a stick is inserted.

grievance: An actual or supposed circumstance regarded as just cause for complaint.

distinct: Readily distinguishable from all others; discrete.

revere: A Middle English form of river.

skim: To remove floating matter from (a liquid).

girder: A beam, as of steel, wood, or reinforced concrete, used as a main horizontal support in a building or bridge.

cling: To hold fast or adhere to something, as by grasping, sticking, embracing, or entwining.

glint: A momentary flash of light; a sparkle.

mend: To make repairs or restoration to; fix.

cocozelle: a squash plant having a dark green fruit with skin mottled with light green or yellow.

pandowdy: Sliced fruit baked with sugar and spices in a deep dish, with a thick top crust.

quirk: A peculiarity of behavior; an idiosyncrasy.

trudgen: A swimming stroke in which alternating overarm movements are combined with a scissors kick.

nanoemulsion: An emulsion in which the disperse phase consists of nanosized particles

exiguousness: The character of being exiguous; exiguity; diminutiveness.

parvitude: Littleness; minuteness. Glanville, Vanity of Dogmatizing, viii.

aikido: A Japanese art of self-defense that employs holds and locks and that uses the principles of nonresistance in order to debilitate the strength of the opponent.

panopticon: A hypothetical prison proposed by Jeremy Bentham, having circular tiers of cells surrounding a central observation tower.

conurbation: A predominantly urban region including adjacent towns and suburbs; a metropolitan area.

susurrous: Whispering; full of sounds resembling whispers; rustling.

sippet: A small piece of toast or bread soaked in gravy or other liquid or used as a garnish.

amphipod: Any of numerous small, chiefly aquatic crustaceans of the order Amphipoda, such as the beach flea, having a laterally compressed body with no carapace.

scienter: Knowledge that one's actions are wrong or contrary to law, where such knowledge is an element of a criminal offense or a basis for liability.

voluptuary: A person whose life is given over to luxury and sensual pleasures; a sensualist.

berimbau: A musical instrument with a gourd resonator and a single steel wire stretched across a long pole or stick.

lapsarian: Of or pertaining to the fall of man from innocence, especially to the role of women in that fall.

whigmaleerie: Any fantastical ornament; a trinket; a knickknack; also, a whim or crotchet. Also used attributively.

alestake: A stake having a garland or bush of twigs at the top of it, set up as a sign before an ale-house.

fontanelle: In pathology, an opening for the discharge of pus.

illation: The act of inferring or drawing conclusions.

solmization: The act or a system of using syllables, especially sol-fa syllables, to represent the tones of the scale.

valorous: Marked by or possessing great personal bravery; valiant. synonym:brave.

lagging: Insulation used to prevent heat diffusion, as from a steam pipe.

kolacky: A sweet bun made from yeasted dough and usually having a fruit or poppy seed filling.

klaxon: a kind of loud horn formerly used on motor vehicles.

daunorubicin: A particular anthracycline drug used in chemotherapy.

dopester: One who analyzes and forecasts future events, as in sports or politics.

usury: The practice of lending money and charging the borrower interest, especially at an exorbitant or illegally high rate.

lauroyl: The univalent radical derived from lauric acid by loss of the hydroxy group

hijab: Any of several cloth head coverings worn by Muslim women.

horologer: One versed in horology; a writer on horology.

mannitol: A white, crystalline, water-soluble, slightly sweet alcohol, C6H8(OH)6, used as a dietary supplement and dietetic sweetener and in medical tests of renal function.

ostent: To show; make a display of; flourish.

chancellor: Any of various officials of high rank, especially.

peristeronic: Pertaining to or concerned with pigeons: as, The National Peristeronic Society.

caphar: A post or station where money is collected from passengers for maintaining the security of the roads.

verbose: Using or containing a great and usually an excessive number of words; wordy. synonym:wordy.

penumbra: A partial shadow, as in an eclipse, between regions of complete shadow and complete illumination.

connive: To cooperate secretly in an illegal or wrongful action; collude.

fanion: Milit., a small flag carried with the baggage of a brigade.

pamphleteer: A writer of pamphlets or other short works taking a partisan stand on an issue.

multitudinous: Very numerous; existing in great numbers.

caterwaul: To cry or screech like a cat in heat.

ghazal: A poetic form of Persian origin, consisting of five or more syntactically complete couplets linked by rhyme and the repetition of a closing word or phrase.

hocus-pocus: Nonsense words or phrases used as a formula by quack conjurers.

cardioid: A heart-shaped plane curve, the locus of a fixed point on a circle that rolls on the circumference of another circle with the same radius.

drachma: The primary unit of currency in Greece before the adoption of the euro.

medaka: A small Japanese fish (Oryzias latipes) that is commonly found in rice paddies and is often used in biological research or in stocking aquariums.

huipil: A loose brocaded blouse worn by Maya women in Mexico and Central America.

cytoplasm: The protoplasm enclosed by the plasma membrane of cell, excluding the nucleus in eukaryotic cells and cellular DNA in prokaryotic cells.

eclat: Brilliancy of success or effort; splendor; brilliant show; striking effect; glory; renown.

synagogue: A building or place of meeting for worship and religious instruction in the Jewish faith.

albugineous: Pertaining to or resembling the white of the eye or of an egg. Equivalent forms are albuginean and albuginous.

coquelicot: Wild poppy; corn-rose; hence, the color of wild poppy; a color nearly red, or red mixed with orange.

haemal: Pertaining to the blood or blood vessels; also, ventral. See hemal.

Pijin: A language spoken on the Solomon Islands.

stere: A unit of volume equal to one cubic meter.

oviparous: Producing eggs that hatch outside the body.

indoctrinate: To instruct in a body of doctrine or principles.

dirigible: That may be directed, controlled, or steered.

artivism: The practice of promoting a political agenda through acts considered to be art, such as the defacing of advertisements.

cytochrome: Any of a class of usually colored proteins that contain a heme group, are electron carriers, and catalyze oxidation-reduction reactions during cellular respiration.

pekoe: A grade of black tea consisting of the leaves around the buds.

buckminsterfullerene: An extremely stable, ball-shaped carbon molecule, C60, reminiscent of a geodesic dome, and believed to occur naturally in soot. It was the first fullerene to be discovered.

linguaphile: A lover of languages and words.

aglet: A tag or sheath, as of plastic, on the end of a lace, cord, or ribbon to facilitate its passing through eyelet holes.

de rigueur: Required by the current fashion or custom; socially obligatory.

rete: An anatomical mesh or network, as of veins, arteries, or nerves.

totem: An animal, plant, or natural object serving among certain tribal or traditional peoples as the emblem of a clan or family and sometimes revered as its founder, ancestor, or guardian.

ploce: In rhetoric, repetition of a word one or more times in close succession; especially, such repetition with a change of meaning or application: as, a man should be a man.

prosopopeia: A figure of speech in which an absent or imaginary person is represented as speaking.

epeiric: Describing the part of a sea that lies over a continental shelf

pylon: A movable, brightly colored cone or shaft of rubber that is used to signal something to be avoided, such as a hazard or work zone on a roadway.

itinerant: Traveling from place to place, especially to perform work or a duty.

innatism: The view that the mind is born with certain ideas or knowledge, as opposed to the idea of the "blank slate" or tabula rasa.

cuboargyrite: An isometric-hexoctahedral grayish black mineral containing antimony, silver, and sulfur.

concoct: To prepare by mixing ingredients, as in cooking.

silymarin: A mixture of flavonolignans extracted from the blessed milk thistle (Silybum marianum), used as a source of silibinin.

glutathione: A polypeptide, C10H17N3O6S, of glycine, cysteine, and glutamic acid that occurs widely in plant and animal tissues and is important in biological oxidation-reduction reactions.

antihistamine: A drug used to counteract the physiological effects of histamine production in allergic reactions and colds.

threaten: To express a threat against or give indications of taking hostile action against.

onomastic: Of, relating to, or explaining a name or names.

tergiversation: The act of tergiversating; a shifting; shift; subterfuge; evasion.

dene: A sandy tract or dune by the seashore.

patzer: A poor or amateurish chess player.

mellow: Soft, sweet, juicy, and full-flavored because of ripeness.

shroom: A mushroom, especially one taken as a psychedelic drug.

purveyor: One that furnishes or sells something, especially food.

quoin: An exterior angle of a wall or other piece of masonry.

gastroenteritis: Inflammation of the mucous membrane of the stomach and intestines.

megalodon: An extinct genus of Pelecypoda typifying the family Megalodontidæ. It is characterized by ponderous heart-shaped shells with amphidetic area, opisthodetic ligament, and large and heavy cardinal teeth. The earliest species are Devonian, but the shells are most abundant in the Triassic rocks. Properly Megalodus.

rachitic: In anatomy, of or pertaining to the spinal column; spinal; vertebral.

argilliferous: Producing or containing clay or argil.

rupestrine: In zoology and botany, rock-inhabiting; living or growing on or among rocks; rupicoline; saxicoline.

susurration: A soft, whispering or rustling sound; a murmur.

emblazon: To adorn (a surface) with a prominent marking, such as a logo or heraldic symbol.

battue: The beating of woods and bushes to flush game.

cosmogony: The astrophysical study of the origin and evolution of the universe.

backronym: An acronym coined from an existing word or name. For example, wiki is a backronym when used for what I know is because wiki is a word whose original meaning is “collaborative website.”

lunk: A tall, brawny man, especially a sexually attractive one.

plateresque: Pertaining to an ornate style of architecture of 16th century Spain suggestive of silver plate.

palilogy: The repetition of a word, or part of a sentence, for the sake of greater emphasis.”

nous: Reason and knowledge as opposed to sense perception.

hyaloid: Glassy or transparent in appearance; hyaline.

polyhistidine: Several histidine residues linked together (usually at least six)

nugacity: Futility; triviality; something trifling or nonsensical.

orexigenic: Stimulating the appetite. An orexigenic and stomachic action which is not to be lightly esteemed.

mishnaic: Of or pertaining to the Mishnah; traditional.

extrinsic: Not forming an essential or inherent part of a thing; extraneous.

buhl: An elaborate inlay of tortoiseshell, ivory, and metal, used especially in decorating furniture.

anthraconite: The name given to varieties of calcareous spar (calcite), darkly colored by the presence of carbonaceous matter.

pleiotaxy: In bot., a multiplication of the number of whorls—that is, the production of additional distinct whorls, as in many so-called double flowers. Pleiotaxy may affect the bracts, calyx, corolla, andrœcium, gynæcium, or perianth as a whole.

Pygmalion: A king of Cyprus who carved and then fell in love with a statue of a woman, which Aphrodite brought to life as Galatea.

spruik: To promote a thing or idea to another person.

Atomic number 53; atomic weight 126.9045; melting point 113.7°C; boiling point 184.4°C; density of gas 11.27 grams per liter; specific gravity (solid, at 20°C) 4.93; valence 1, 3, 5, 7. cross-reference:Periodic Table.

gyromagnetic: Of, relating to, or resulting from the magnetic properties of an electrically charged particle or substance that is spinning.

Puerto Vallarta: A city of west-central Mexico on the Pacific Ocean west of Guadalajara. It is a popular coastal resort.

amphigory: A meaningless rigmarole, as of nonsense-verses or the like; a nonsensical parody.

dehort: To dissuade; advise to the contrary; urge not to do or not to undertake a certain thing; deter.

hem: An edge or border on a piece of cloth, especially a finished edge, as for a garment or curtain, made by folding an edge under and stitching it down.

picayune: Of little value or importance; paltry. synonym:trivial.

debilitate: To sap the strength or energy of; enervate.

sommelier: A restaurant employee who orders and maintains the wines sold in the restaurant and usually has extensive knowledge about wine and food pairings.

dago: Used as a disparaging term for a person of Italian, Spanish, or Portuguese descent.

coryphée: A ballet-dancer who takes a leading part.

myeloablative: Of, pertaining to, or causing myeloablation

falciparum: The parasitic protozoan Plasmodium falciparum that causes falciparum malaria

bullyrag: To mistreat or intimidate by bullying.

disneyfy: To make something (especially a location) more acceptable or marketable by removing potentially distasteful, controversial or boring elements, particularly at the cost of its historical nature. Or, to make a place sterile and disingenuous, thus diminishing its cultural and social significance. For example: I was sitting in the Blues City Café about to feast on some fabulous ribs when I looked around and realized the place was not disneyfied. In fact, Beale Street is not disneyfied at all, thank God.

sandhi: Modification of the sound of a word or morpheme when juxtaposed with another, especially in fluent speech, as the modification of the pronunciation of don't in don't you from its pronunciation in isolation or in a phrase like don't we.

jharal: The East Indian thar, Hemitragus jemlaicus, one of the wild goats.

exorbitant: Going beyond what is reasonable or customary, especially in cost or price.

aphthous: In pathology, of the nature of or characterized by aphthæ.

exfoliant: A product that is applied to the surface of the skin to remove dead cells.

isotherm: A line drawn on a weather map or chart linking all points of equal or constant temperature.

atavism: The reappearance of a characteristic in an organism after several generations of absence.

obvert: To turn (something) so as to present another side or aspect to view.

doldrums: A period of stagnation or slump.

superluminal: faster-than-light; having a speed greater than light.

layette: A set of clothing and bedding for a newborn child.

sonatina: A sonata having shorter movements and often less technically demanding than the typical sonata.

thyroidectomy: Surgical removal of the thyroid gland.

bavituximab: A chimeric monoclonal antibody with potential applications in the treatment of cancers and viral infections.

petroliferous: Abounding in petroleum; productive of petroleum; containing or yielding petroleum: as, petroliferous strata.

denigrate: To attack the character or reputation of; speak ill of; defame.

proficient: Having or marked by an advanced degree of competence, as in an art, vocation, profession, or branch of learning.

uniaxially: So as to be or become uniaxial; in a uniaxial manner; as, to grow uniaxially.

Malta: An island country in the Mediterranean Sea south of Sicily, comprising the island of Malta and two smaller islands. Occupied successively by Phoenicians, Greeks, Carthaginians, Romans, Saracens, and Normans, Malta was granted to the Knights Hospitalers in 1530 and passed to France in 1798 and Great Britain in 1800. The country became independent in 1964. Valletta, on Malta Island, is the capital.

fortissimo: In a very loud manner. Used chiefly as a direction.

craythur: Whiskey. The term is analogous to uisge beatha (the water of life). 'A drop of the craythur' is a popular if old expression.

antiquarian: One who studies, collects, or deals in antiquities.

vaudeville: Stage entertainment offering a variety of short acts such as slapstick turns, song-and-dance routines, and juggling performances.

diastrophism: The process of deformation by which the major features of the earth's crust, including continents, mountains, ocean beds, folds, and faults, are formed.

cartilaginous: Of, relating to, or consisting of cartilage.

koinonia: Communion by intimate participation, associated with the Christian church.

peroration: The concluding part of an oration, in which the speaker recapitulates the principal points of his discourse or argument, and urges them with greater earnestness and force, with a view to make a deep impression on his hearers; hence, the conclusion of a speech, however constructed.

lambency: The quality of being lambent; that which is lambent; a lambent gleam.

Benelux: An economic union of Belgium, the Netherlands, and Luxembourg, originally established as a customs union (1948).

chyme: The thick semifluid mass of partly digested food that is passed from the stomach to the duodenum.

attrite: Worn by rubbing or friction. Milton.

azadirachtin: a triterpenoid (C35H44O16) isolated from the seeds of the neem tree (Azadirachta indica), used as an insecticide.

concupiscent: Characterized by illicit desire or appetite; sensual; libidinous; lustful.

mise en scène: The arrangement of performers and properties on a stage for a theatrical production or before the camera in a film.

hydrozoa: a large group of marine animals, of the class Hydrozoa, whose life cycles contain a sexual and asexual stage

castrato: A male singer castrated before puberty so as to retain a soprano or alto voice.

hypaethral: Wholly or partly open to the sky.

palpebral: Of or pertaining to the eyelids: as, the palpebral muscles; palpebral folds of conjunctiva.

falafel: A mixture of ground spiced chickpeas or fava beans that is shaped into balls and deep-fried.

ague: A febrile condition in which there are alternating periods of chills, fever, and sweating. Used chiefly in reference to the fevers associated with malaria.

chrysemys: A genus of fresh-water turtles or terrapins, of the family Emydidæ.

fuchsia: Any of various tropical shrubs or trees of the genus Fuchsia, widely cultivated for their showy, drooping, purplish, reddish, or white flowers.

lazuline: Of the color of lapis lazuli; bluish.

obreptitious: Done or obtained by surprise or with secrecy, falsehood, or concealment of truth.

mump: To mumble or mutter, as in sulkiness.

enantiodromia: The principle whereby the superabundance of one force inevitably produces its opposite, as with physical equilibrium.

dysgeusia: The distortion or loss of the sense of taste.

epigynum: In the Arachnida, the opening of the female genital organs; the epigyne.

amphoriskos: A type of Greek vase resembling the amphora but much smaller, being about 3 or 4 inches high.

antiandrogenic: That counters the effects of androgens

jackleg: Lacking skill or training; incompetent. Used especially of lawyers or preachers.

epileptogenic: Having the capacity to induce epilepsy.

cremnophobia: Morbid fear of being near the edge of a cliff or precipice.

gangliosidosis: A disorder caused by the accumulation of gangliosides.

civvie: civilian, someone not in the military

archenteron: The central cavity of the gastrula, which ultimately becomes the intestinal or digestive cavity.

exclave: A part of a country that is isolated from the main part and is surrounded by foreign territory.

chasidic: of or relating to the Jewish Hasidim or its members or their beliefs and practices

epimorphism: A map f such that whenever g composed with f equals h composed with f, then g=h. In most everyday categories, a map is an epimorphism iff it's surjective

monoid: In ancient prosody, containing but one kind of foot: noting certain meters. Monoid meters are also called pure meters or simple meters, and distinguished from compound (episynthetic) meters and mixed or logaœdic meters.

antisymmetric: Of a relation R on a set S, having the property that for any two distinct elements of S, at least one is not related to the other via R.

titillation: The act of titillating, or the state of being titillated; a tickling or itching sensation or state of feeling; hence, a passing or momentary excitation, physical or mental.

Chang Jiang: An alternative name for the Yangtze River in central China.

marinism: Extreme mannerism in literature, like that of the school of Italian poets of the seventeenth century founded by G. B. Marini (1569-1625), which was characterized by extravagance in the use of metaphor, antitheses, and forced conceits.

cateran: A kern; a Highland or Irish irregular soldier.

Jimbaran: a fishing village and tourist resort in Bali, Indonesia.

ankh: A cross shaped like a T with a loop at the top, especially as used in ancient Egypt as a symbol of life.

esthete: Properly, one who cultivates the sense of the beautiful; one in whom the artistic sense or faculty is highly developed; one very sensible of the beauties of nature or art.

ultramundane: Extending or being beyond the world or the limits of the universe.

au pair: A young foreigner who does domestic work for a family in exchange for room and board and a chance to learn the family's language.

adultescent: An adult who continues to participate in and enjoy youth culture.

marivaudage: In lit., a style resembling that of Marivaux, whose writings were a mixture of subtle metaphysics and bizarre trivialities, with over-refined sentiments which were mingled with the most ordinary colloquialisms: the word has come to note an affected attempt at refinement.

affiance: To bind in a pledge of marriage; betroth.

phylarch: In ancient Greece, the chief or head of a tribe; in Athens, the commander of the cavalry of a tribe, the ten phylarchs being under the orders of the two state hipparchs, the commanders-in-chief of the cavalry.

carcinogenic: Causing or tending to cause cancer.

porraceous: Resembling the leek in color; greenish.

muliebrity: The state of being a woman.

unfettered: Unchained; unshackled; free from restraint; unrestrained.

besot: To muddle or stupefy, as with alcoholic liquor or infatuation.

hobbesian: Of or pertaining to Thomas Hobbes or his doctrines. See Hobbism.

saprogenic: Of, producing, or resulting from putrefaction.

bezonian: An indigent wretch; a beggar or scoundrel.

aggress: To initiate an attack, war, quarrel, or fight.

Machu Picchu: An ancient Inca fortress city in the Andes northwest of Cuzco, Peru. Its extensive ruins and elaborate terraces became famous after an American explorer published a description of them in 1911.

adequation: A making or being equal; an equivalence or equivalent.

ptisan: A medicinal infusion, such as sweetened barley water.

propylbenzene: The hydrocarbon CH3-CH2-CH2-C6H5 that is the parent compound of the lignans

lignan: Any of a class of phytoestrogens characterized by the presence of a pair of propylbenzene groupings

bossage: In building: A stone which projects beyond the face of the adjacent work, and is laid rough, to be afterward carved into some ornamental or significant form.

epithelial: Pertaining to epithelium, in any sense; constituting or consisting of epithelium: as, epithelial cells; epithelial tissue.

ought: Used to indicate obligation or duty.

kanawha: The Kanawha River, a tributary of the Ohio River.

feygele: A male who is or who is thought to be homosexual.

megalomania: A psychopathological condition characterized by delusional fantasies of wealth, power, or omnipotence.

embolization: A nonsurgical, minimally invasive procedure that effects the selective occlusion of blood vessels by purposely introducing emboli.

isopach: A line on a chart joining parts of a stratigraphic unit that have the same thickness; an isopachous line

anthologizer: Agent noun of anthologize; one who creates an anthology.

Icarus: The son of Daedalus who, in escaping from Crete on artificial wings made for him by his father, flew so close to the sun that the wax with which his wings were fastened melted, and he fell into the Aegean Sea.

scrumpy: A rough cider, normally more alcoholic than usual, and typically produced through natural fermentation.

obsequiousness: The quality or state of being obsequious; ready obedience; prompt compliance with the commands of another; servile submission; officious or superserviceable readiness to serve.

Rocephin: a parenteral cephalosporin (trade name Rocephin) used for severe infection of the lungs or throat or ears or urinary tract

ostiary: One who is ordained in the lowest of the former minor orders.

mettle: The ability to meet a challenge or persevere under demanding circumstances; determination or resolve.

hypocorism: A name of endearment; a pet name.

pensive: Engaged in deep and serious thought.

incumbency: The quality or condition of being incumbent.

cottabus: An ancient Greek game, which consisted in throwing portions of wine left in drinking-cups into a vessel or upon a specified object, as a plate of bronze, so as to produce a clear sound and without scattering the fluid. From the successful performance of this feat good fortune, especially in love affairs, was augured.

abamectin: A widely-used insecticide, acaricide and anthelminthic.

cordillera: An extensive chain of mountains or mountain ranges, especially the principal mountain system of a continent.

infomania: Impairment of concentration caused by frequent response to text messages, e-mails, and other forms of digital communication.

gobemouche: A gaping simpleton who believes everything that he hears; a credulous person.

decimate: To destroy or kill a large part of (a group of people or organisms).

ablution: A washing or cleansing of the body, especially as part of a religious rite.

barlow: An inexpensive, one- or two-bladed pocketknife.

flocculate: To cause (individual particles of clay) to aggregate into clotlike masses or precipitate into small lumps.

agonistic: Of or relating to an agonist.

cinquefoil: Any of various herbs or shrubs chiefly of the genus Potentilla of the rose family, native to northern temperate regions and having yellow or sometimes white or red flowers and compound leaves that in some species bear five leaflets.

bandura: A traditional Ukrainian stringed musical instrument shaped like a lute, having many strings.

levant: To leave hurriedly or in secret to avoid unpaid debts.

hymnal: A book or collection of church hymns.

tercet: A group of three lines of verse, often rhyming together or with another triplet.

swallet: Water breaking in upon the miners at their work; -- so called among tin miners.

Quercus: A taxonomic genus within the family Fagaceae — the oak trees.

zidovudine: A nucleoside analog reverse transcriptase inhibitor, a type of antiretroviral drug, the first approved treatment for HIV.

rocaille: A style of decorative art associated with the rococo and characterized by intricate rock, shell, and scroll motifs.

sumpitan: The blow-gun of the Malays and the Dyaks of Borneo.

booboisie: A class of people regarded as stupid and gullible.

fraudulence: The quality of being fraudulent; dishonesty; trickery.

hieroglyph: A picture or symbol used in hieroglyphic writing.

feint: A military attack or maneuver that is meant to divert attention away from a planned point of attack.

hypocotyl: The part of a plant embryo or seedling plant that is between the cotyledons and the radicle or root.

indoleamine: Any of various derivatives of indole, such as serotonin, containing an amine group.

tussie-mussie: A small bouquet of flowers; a nosegay.

hyperekplexia: A neurological disorder characterized by an exaggerated startle response in situations of distress.

ophthalmoscope: An instrument for examining the interior structures of the eye, especially the retina, consisting essentially of a mirror that reflects light into the eye and a central hole through which the eye is examined.

epopee: Epic poetry, especially as a literary genre.

vagility: The degree to which an organism or taxon can or does move or spread within an environment.

adhocracy: An organizational system designed to be flexible and responsive to the needs of the moment rather than excessively bureaucratic.

spica: A bandage applied in overlapping opposite spirals to immobilize a digit or limb.

vicuna: A South American hoofed mammal, Vicugna vicugna, closely related to the alpaca, llama, and guanaco.

jiffy: A short space of time; a moment. synonym:moment.

cholla: Any of several spiny, shrubby or treelike opuntias having cylindrical stem segments.

masochist: someone who enjoys pain, or who derives pleasure from harming oneself or being harmed by others

toxicosis: A diseased condition resulting from poisoning.

murrain: Any of various highly infectious diseases of cattle, as anthrax.

montezuma: evergreen tree with large leathery leaves and large pink to orange flowers; considered a link plant between families Bombacaceae and Sterculiaceae

ronnel: A white or light brown solid, C8H8Cl3O3PS, used as an insecticide, especially against flies and cockroaches.

sibyl: One of a number of women regarded as oracles or prophets by the ancient Greeks and Romans.

tyche: In Greek myth, the goddess of fortune, a divinity whose protection was believed to assure prosperity, wealth, and good luck: often in the form Agathe Tyche (Good Fortune). Compare agathodæmon.

capote: A long, usually hooded cloak or coat.

wanigan: A boat or small chest equipped with supplies for a lumber camp.

acapnia: A condition marked by an unusually low concentration of carbon dioxide in the blood and tissues.

eukaryotic: having cells with visible nuclei surrounded by a nuclear membrane; pertaining to eukaryotes.Contrasted with prokaryotic.

prokaryotic: Of or having the characteristics of prokaryotes, especially bacteria.

chromatin: A complex of nucleic acids and proteins, primarily histones, in the cell nucleus that stains readily with basic dyes and condenses to form chromosomes during cell division.

traduce: To make false or malicious statements about (someone) in order to cause humiliation or disgrace. synonym:malign.

fuddle: To put into a state of confusion. synonym:befuddle.

sillage: Wake; track; specifically, the disturbance of the ether produced by the movement through it of an electrified corpuscle or electron.

cathexis: Concentration of emotional energy on an object or idea.

vowess: A woman who has taken a vow; a nun.

ptarmigan: Any of various grouse of the genus Lagopus, inhabiting arctic, subarctic, and alpine regions of the Northern Hemisphere and having feathered legs and feet and plumage that is brown or gray in summer and white in winter.

cytokinesis: The division of the cytoplasm of a cell following the division of the nucleus.

egret: Any of several usually white herons of the genera Ardea, Bubulcus, and Egretta, characteristically having long, showy plumes during the breeding season.

phytoplankton: Plankton that consists of minute plants and other photosynthetic organisms, including cyanobacteria, diatoms, and dinoflagellates.

esophagus: The muscular tube by which food passes from the pharynx to the stomach; the gullet.

amniocentesis: A procedure in which a small sample of amniotic fluid is drawn out of the uterus through a needle inserted in the abdomen. The fluid is then analyzed to detect genetic abnormalities in the fetus or to determine the sex of the fetus.

poignant: Arousing deep emotion, especially pity or sorrow; touching: synonym:moving.

oxymoron: A rhetorical figure in which incongruous or contradictory terms are combined, as in a deafening silence and a mournful optimist.

hemera: In geology, a subdivision of a zone corresponding to the vertical distribution of characteristic species.

obento: A Japanese box lunch, traditionally packed in a partitioned lacquered box.

silole: A five-membered heterocycle having four carbon atoms, one silicon atom and two double bonds; it is analogous to cyclopentadiene

omnishambles: A situation that is bad or mismanaged in every way.

pyroxene: Any of a group of crystalline silicate minerals common in igneous and metamorphic rocks and containing two metallic oxides, as of magnesium, iron, calcium, sodium, or aluminum.

marsupium: An external pouch or fold on the abdomen of most female marsupials, containing the mammary glands and in which the young continue to develop after leaving the uterus.

neuron: Any of the impulse-conducting cells that constitute the brain, spinal column, and nerves in vertebrates, consisting of a nucleated cell body with one or more dendrites and a single axon.

finagle: To obtain or achieve by cleverness or deceit, especially in persuading someone.

haemony: A magical plant, said to be good against enchantments.

homophobia: Fear, hatred, or mistrust of lesbians and gay men.

monophobia: An abnormal fear of being alone.

coterie: A small, often select group of persons who associate with one another frequently.

dodecagon: A polygon with 12 sides and 12 angles.

asparagine: A crystalline amino acid, C4H8N2O3, found in many proteins, and present in large amounts in some plants, such as asparagus, that is easily hydrolyzed to aspartic acid.

tummler: One, such as a social director or entertainer, who encourages guest or audience participation.

celesta: A musical instrument with a keyboard and metal plates struck by hammers that produce bell-like tones.

andesite: A gray, fine-grained volcanic rock consisting chiefly of plagioclase feldspar and one or more mafic minerals.

gracious: Characterized by kindness and warm courtesy.

weem: An earth-house; an artificial cave or subterranean building.

resplendent: Splendid or dazzling in appearance; brilliant.

alidade: An indicator or a sighting apparatus on a plane table, used in angular measurement.

tutiorism: Rigorism, especially in a mild form.

succinct: Characterized by clear, precise expression in few words; concise and terse.

carking: Distressing; perplexing; giving anxiety: now scarcely used except in the phrase carking care or cares.

recalcitrant: Stubbornly resistant to or defiant of authority or guidance. synonym:obstinate.

mbaqanga: A form of popular dance music that originated in the black townships of South Africa, characterized by choral singing and prominent basslines played on electronically amplified guitars.

cotyledon: A leaf of the embryo of a seed plant, which upon germination either remains in the seed or emerges, enlarges, and becomes green.

serrefine: Small forceps used for clamping an artery.

bayadere: A fabric with contrasting horizontal stripes.

narcolepsy: A disorder characterized by sudden and uncontrollable, though often brief, attacks of deep sleep, sometimes accompanied by paralysis and hallucinations.

sabotage: The deliberate destruction of property or obstruction of normal operations, as by civilians or enemy agents in a time of war.

metronome: A device used to mark time by means of regularly recurring ticks or flashes at adjustable intervals.

geophysicist: A student of geophysics; one who studies the relations between the features of the earth and the laws of physics.

polarity: Intrinsic polar separation, alignment, or orientation, especially of a physical property.

oblivion: The condition or quality of being completely forgotten.

whelk: An inflamed swelling, such as a pimple or pustule.

kluski: Noodles prepared in an ethnic Polish manner, specifically, thin strips of dough, as opposed to filled shells.

dae-han-min-gook: an Asian peninsula (off Manchuria) separating the Yellow Sea and the Sea of Japan; the Korean name is Dae-Han-Min-Gook or Han-Gook

guayule: A shrub (Parthenium argentatum) native to Texas and Mexico that yields large amounts of latex.

sophrosyne: The quality of wise moderation; sound-mindedness; discreet good sense: referring especially to Greek art and philosophy.

escheat: Reversion of land held under feudal tenure to the manor in the absence of legal heirs or claimants.

dysgraphia: Impairment of the ability to write, usually caused by brain dysfunction or disease.

daeva: A supernatural entity of disagreeable nature.

oxter: The armpit; also, the embrace of the arms.

entrepreneurialism: The spirit or state of acting in an entrepreneurial manner.

Achilles: The hero of Homer's Iliad, the son of Peleus and Thetis and slayer of Hector.

oleaster: Any of various small trees or shrubs of the family Elaeagnaceae, having olivelike fruit and silvery or brown scales on the stems and leaves, especially one of the genus Elaeagnus, such as Russian olive or silverberry.

malevolent: Having or exhibiting ill will; wishing harm to others; malicious.

clavulanic: Of or pertaining to clavulanic acid or its derivatives

biopsychology: The investigation of mind in its relations to life; psychology as based upon or approached by way of biology.

veld: Any of the open grazing areas of southern Africa.

Shangri-la: An imaginary remote paradise on earth; utopia.

phenology: The scientific study of periodic biological phenomena, such as flowering, breeding, and migration, in relation to climatic conditions.

oligarch: A member of a small governing faction.

invigilator: One appointed to watch students during examination: proctors, examiners, and others are selected for this purpose.

Mauna Loa: An active volcano, 4,169 m (13,679 ft) high, on the island of Hawaii south of Mauna Kea.

omnipresently: In an omnipresent manner; in such a way or with such powers as to be present everywhere.

bimble: A gentle, meandering walk with no particular haste or purpose.

pharmacodynamics: The study of the action or effects of drugs on living organisms.

fealty: The fidelity owed by a vassal to his feudal lord.

droog: A violent young gang member or a hooligan.

murkiness: The state of being murky; darkness; gloominess; gloom.

billowy: Swelling or swelled into large waves; full of billows or surges; having an appearance or effect as of billows: as, “the billowie ocean,”

angustirostrate: In zoology, having a narrow, slender, or (especially) compressed beak: opposed to latirostrate.

grumous: Resembling or containing grume; thick; viscid; clotted: as, grumous blood.

maar: A broad, shallow, generally flat-floored volcanic crater of explosive origin that is often filled with water.

voyeuristic: of, relating to, or derived from voyeurism or a voyeur

Maarianhamina: a town that is the chief port of the Aland islands

refinished: Simple past tense and past participle of refinish.

leukapheresis: A laboratory procedure where white blood cells are separated from a sample of blood.

declivity: A downward slope, as of a hill.

quamassia: genus of scapose herbs of North and South America having large edible bulbs

quantum: The smallest amount of a physical quantity that can exist independently, especially a discrete quantity of electromagnetic radiation.

thallium: A soft, malleable, highly toxic metallic element, used in photocells, infrared detectors, low-melting glass, and formerly in rodent and ant poisons. A radioactive isotope, Tl-201, is used in medical imaging. Atomic number 81; atomic weight 204.38; melting point 304°C; boiling point 1,473°C; specific gravity 11.85 (20°C); valence 1, 3. cross-reference:Periodic Table.

bismuth: A brittle, crystalline, highly diamagnetic metallic element with a very low thermal conductivity and a pinkish-white luster, used in alloys to form sharp castings for objects sensitive to high temperatures and in various low-melting alloys for fire-safety devices. Atomic number 83; atomic weight 208.98; melting point 271.3°C; boiling point 1,564°C; specific gravity 9.78; valence 3, 5. cross-reference:Periodic Table.

molt: To shed part or all of a coat or an outer covering, such as feathers, cuticle, or skin, which is then replaced by a new growth.

cathode: A negatively charged electrode, as of an electrolytic cell, a storage battery, or an electron tube.

malathion: An organophosphate compound, C10H19O6PS2, used as an insecticide.

fibril: A small slender fiber or filament.

apparatus: An appliance or device for a particular purpose.

feculent: Full of foul or impure matter; fecal.

monsoon: A wind system that influences large climatic regions and reverses direction seasonally.

agglomeration: The act or process of gathering into a mass.

grandiose: Characterized by greatness of scope or intent; grand.

trioxide: An oxide containing three oxygen atoms per molecule.

tetrachloride: A chemical compound containing four chlorine atoms per molecule.

dioxide: A compound with two oxygen atoms per molecule.

monoxide: An oxide with each molecule containing one oxygen atom.

Atomic number 16; atomic weight 32.066; melting point 115.21°C; boiling point 444.61°C; specific gravity at 20°C (rhombic) 2.07, (monoclinic) 2.00; valence 2, 4, 6. cross-reference:Periodic Table.

bort: Poorly crystallized diamonds used for industrial cutting and abrasion.

ariose: Characterized by melody, as distinguished from harmony.

enormity: The quality of passing all moral bounds; excessive wickedness or outrageousness.

listerize: To treat by Sir Joseph Lister's antiseptic method. See Listerism. Also spelled Listerise.

bravado: A show of bravery or defiance, often in order to make a false impression or mislead someone.

caudal: Of, at, or near the tail or hind parts; posterior.

nitrate: The univalent anionic group NO3, derived from nitric acid, or a compound containing this group.

Celsius: Of or relating to a temperature scale that registers the freezing point of water as 0° and the boiling point as 100° under normal atmospheric pressure.

solubility: The quality or condition of being soluble.

prevaricate: To speak or write evasively; equivocate. synonym:lie.

laud: To give praise to; glorify. synonym:praise.

squatarola: A genus of true plovers which have four toes.

solitudinarian: One leading a solitary or secluded life.

deracinate: To pull out by the roots; uproot.

tumult: A great noise, as of a crowd.

merism: The repetition of parts in an organism in such a way as to form a regular pattern, as in radial and bilateral symmetry, serial homology, etc.

binational: Of, relating to, or involving two nations.

aspersion: A false or damaging accusation or insinuation.

allozyme: Either form of an enzyme specified by an allelic gene

yegg: A thief, especially a burglar or safecracker.

stridulant: Strident or stridulous, as an insect; capable of stridulating; specifically, of or pertaining to the Stridulantia.

gook: Used as a disparaging term for a person of East Asian birth or descent.

anemochore: A plant whose seeds, fruits, or other parts are dispersed by wind.

calibogus: An American cant name for a drink made of rum and spruce beer.

technetronic: Relating to or involving both technology and electronics.

oyabun: The Father. The absolute leader in a Yakuza clan. He has an advisor called a Saiko-komon. Besides that he has an army of advocates, accountants, secretaries and advisors.

accipiter: A hawk of the genus Accipiter, characterized by short wings and a long tail.

farce: A light dramatic work in which highly improbable plot situations, exaggerated characters, and often slapstick elements are used for humorous effect.

polemology: the study of human conflict and war

kyoodle: A mutt, dog of mixed breed of little value; noisy dog.

sylph: A slim, graceful woman or girl.

acetyl: The methyl acyl group, CH3CO, formally derived from acetic acid.

exenatide: A synthetic polypeptide that mimics the hormone incretin and is used for the treatment of diabetes

aphelion: The point on the orbit of a celestial body that is farthest from the sun.

dreadnought: A battleship armed with six or more guns having calibers of 12 inches or more.

telegenic: Having a physical appearance and exhibiting personal qualities that are deemed highly appealing to television viewers.

photolysis: Chemical decomposition induced by light or other radiant energy.

thraward: Cross-grained; perverse; stubborn; tough; also, reluctant.

circumferential: Relating or pertaining to the circumference; situated in the circumference; surrounding.

microdermabrasion: A cosmetic procedure in which a very thin layer of facial skin is abraded with a high-pressure spray of crystals in order to diminish the appearance of fine wrinkles, discoloration, scars, and other blemishes.

quinzhee: A shelter made by hollowing out a pile of snow.

heap: A group of things placed or thrown, one on top of the other.

kyogen: A form of traditional Japanese theatre, once performed alongside noh as a comic intermission.

gerontology: The scientific study of the biological, psychological, and sociological phenomena associated with old age and aging.

hydrokinetics: The branch of physics that deals with fluids in motion.

eschatologist: One versed in or engaged in the study of eschatology.

Naoussa: A city in the Imathia prefecture in Greece

atheroma: A deposit or degenerative accumulation of lipid-containing plaques on the innermost layer of the wall of an artery.

paraselene: A luminous spot on a lunar halo.

lexicographer: One who writes, compiles, or edits a dictionary.

krummholz: An area of stunted windblown trees growing at high elevations on mountain slopes.

attenuate: To make slender, fine, or small.

disparagingly: In a manner to disparage or dishonor.

Behrouz: A male given name (بهروز in Persian), of Persian origin.

bouquetin: The European ibex or steinbok, Capra ibex; hence, a name of the rock-goats of the genus Ibex.

Anguilla: An island of the British West Indies in the northern Leeward Islands. Inhabited by Arawaks when British settlers arrived in the 17th century, Anguilla was part of the self-governing colony of St. Kitts-Nevis-Anguilla until 1967, when it seceded unilaterally. A bid for full independence led to the landing of British troops in 1969. Anguilla became a separate British dependency in 1980.

vendible: Suitable or fit for sale; salable.

meander: To follow a winding and turning course.

demonym: A name for an inhabitant or native of a specific place that is derived from the name of the place.

agnoiology: In metaphysics, the doctrine or theory of ignorance, which seeks to determine what we are necessarily ignorant of.

cicisbeism: The practice of acting as, or the custom of having, a cicisbeo; the practice of dangling about women.

elliptical: In a shape reminding of an ellipse; oval.

andromeda: Any of several evergreen shrubs of the genera Pieris or Andromeda in the heath family.

cacique: An Indian chief, especially in the Spanish West Indies and other parts of Latin America during colonial and postcolonial times.

negligence: The state or quality of being negligent.

inexecution: Lack or neglect of execution; nonperformance: as, the inexecution of a treaty.

Gloxinia: A genus of gosneraceous plants, low and almost stemless, with creeping rhizomes and large, nodding, bell -shaped flowers.

stachys: A genus of plants, of the order Labiatæ, type of the tribe Stachydeæ.

balmacaan: A loose, full overcoat with raglan sleeves, originally made of rough woolen cloth.

azymous: Unleavened; unfermented: as, sea-biscuit is azymous.

quartile: The value of the boundary at the 25th, 50th, or 75th percentiles of a frequency distribution divided into four parts, each containing a quarter of the population.

herm: A rectangular, often tapering stone post bearing a carved head or bust, usually of Hermes, used as a boundary marker in ancient Greece and for decorative purposes in later periods.

netizen: A person who is a frequent or habitual user of the Internet.

abet: To approve, encourage, and support (an action or a plan of action); urge and help on.

cursory: Performed with haste and scant attention to detail.

speleothem: A mineral deposit, such as a stalagmite or stalactite, formed in a cave from the dripping of mineral-rich water.

deave: To render deaf; deafen; stun with noise.

tzimmes: a stew of fruit or vegetables traditionally served on Rosh Hashana

jodhpurs: Wide-hipped riding pants of heavy cloth, fitting tightly from knee to ankle.

ostrog: In Siberia, a stockaded house or village.

negligee: A woman's loose dressing gown, often of soft, delicate fabric.

lucubrate: To study or write in a scholarly fashion.

Pythagorean: Of or pertaining to Pythagoras, a Greek philosopher (perhaps 532 b. c.), or the school founded at Crotona (modern Cotrone), in Italy.

uracil: A pyrimidine base, C4H4N2O2, that is an essential constituent of RNA.

thymine: A pyrimidine base, C5H6N2O2, that is an essential constituent of DNA.

adenine: A purine base, C5H5N5, that is the constituent involved in base pairing with thymine in DNA and with uracil in RNA.

misology: Hatred of reason, argument, or enlightenment.

cytosine: A pyrimidine base, C4H5N3O, that is the constituent of DNA and RNA involved in base-pairing with guanine.

guanine: A purine base, C5H5ON5, that is an essential constituent of both RNA and DNA.

remora: Any of several marine fishes of the family Echeneidae, having on the head a sucking disk with which they attach themselves to sharks and other fishes, whales, sea turtles, or the hulls of ships.

catalyze: To modify, especially to increase, the rate of (a chemical reaction) by catalysis.

glucose: A monosaccharide sugar, C6H12O6, occurring widely in most plant and animal tissue. It is the principal circulating sugar in the blood and the major energy source of the body.

enzyme: Any of numerous proteins or conjugated proteins produced by living organisms and functioning as biochemical catalysts.

amino: Relating to an amine or other chemical compound containing an NH2 group.

foal: The young offspring of a horse or other equine animal, especially one under a year old.

equine: Of, relating to, or characteristic of a horse.

psychotomimetic: Tending to induce hallucinations, delusions, or other symptoms of a psychosis. Used of a drug.

cladogram: A branching, treelike diagram in which the endpoints of the branches represent individual species of organisms. It is used to illustrate phylogenetic relationships and to show points at which various species are presumed to have diverged from common ancestral forms.

carpal: Of, relating to, or near the carpus.

helix: A three-dimensional curve that lies on a cylinder or cone, so that its angle to a plane perpendicular to the axis is constant.

nucleotide: Any of various compounds consisting of a nucleoside combined with a phosphate group and forming the basic constituent of DNA and RNA.

humerus: The long bone of the arm or forelimb, extending from the shoulder to the elbow.

homology: The quality or condition of being homologous.

porpoise: Any of various marine toothed whales of the genus Phocoena and related genera, characteristically having a blunt snout and a triangular dorsal fin. Porpoises are placed either in their own family, Phocoenidae, or with the dolphins in the family Delphinidae.

hyperforeignism: The misapplication of foreign pronunciation or usage.

tutti: All. Used chiefly as a direction to indicate that all performers are to take part.

hyetal: Of or relating to rain or rainy regions.

advowson: The right in English ecclesiastical law of presentation to a vacant benefice.

crepe: A light soft thin fabric of silk, cotton, wool, or another fiber, with a crinkled surface.

mesic: Of, characterized by, or adapted to a moderately moist habitat.

miscreant: One who behaves badly, often by breaking rules of conduct or the law.

hyperborean: One of a race of people in Greek mythology living in the extreme north, beyond the north wind.

curtal: An animal with a docked tail.

meld: To declare or display (a card or combination of cards in a hand) for inclusion in one's score in various card games, such as pinochle.

rhinotillexomania: Compulsive nose-picking, insertion of finger into one's nose.

theoretical: Of, relating to, or based on theory.

sudser: A foaming agent used in detergents etc.

intersectionality: A feminist sociological methodology of studying the relationships among multiple dimensions and modalities of social relationships and subject formations.

riposte: A quick thrust given after parrying an opponent's lunge in fencing.

camaraderie: Goodwill and lighthearted rapport between or among friends; comradeship.

demarcate: To set the boundaries of; delimit.

epigrammatic: Of or having the nature of an epigram.

enology: The study of wine and the making of wine.

toxotes: A genus of fishes, typical of the family Toxotidæ; the archer-fishes. See cut under archerfish.

presuppositional: Of or pertaining to a presupposition.

fandangle: A fancy or fantastic trinket or ornament.

biddable: Strong enough to be bid. Used of a hand of cards.

objurgate: To scold or rebuke sharply; berate.

jinriksha: A small, two-wheeled carriage drawn by one or two persons.

equipollent: Equal in force, power, effectiveness, or significance.

causation: The act or process of causing.

correlation: A relationship or connection between two things based on co-occurrence or pattern of change.

appraisal: The act or an instance of appraising.

empirical: Relying on or derived from observation or experiment.

semiautobiographical: Of, relating to, or being a work that falls between fiction and autobiography.

illth: That which conduces to ill or evil.

riel: The monetary unit of Cambodia, equivalent to 100 sen, and to 10 kak. Symbol: ៛

isoamyl: A univalent organic radical, Its derivatives, such as isoamyl alcohol, isoamyl iodide, etc., are prepared from certain portions of fusel-oil.

euploid: Having a chromosome number that is an exact multiple of the haploid number for the species.

madeleine: A small rich cake, baked in a shell-shaped mold.

schmooze: To converse casually, especially in order to gain an advantage or make a social connection.

covereth: Third-person singular simple present indicative form of cover.

canthus: The angle formed by the meeting of the upper and lower eyelids at either side of the eye.

luge: A sport in which a small open sled is ridden by one or two people lying face-up with the feet pointed downhill, usually over an ice-covered course in a timed competition.

protocol: The forms of ceremony and etiquette observed by diplomats and heads of state.

biathlon: A competition that combines events in cross-country skiing and rifle shooting.

An essential trace element in plant nutrition, it is used in fertilizers, dyes, enamels, and reagents. Atomic number 42; atomic weight 95.96; melting point 2,623°C; boiling point 4,639°C; specific gravity 10.22 (at 20°C); valence 2, 3, 4, 5, 6. cross-reference:Periodic Table.

It is alloyed with steel to increase strength, hardness, wear resistance, and other properties and with other metals to form highly ferromagnetic materials. Atomic number 25; atomic weight 54.938; melting point 1,246°C; boiling point 2,061°C; specific gravity 7.21 to 7.44; valence 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7. cross-reference:Periodic Table.

agonistarch: In Greek antiquity, one who trained persons to compete in public games and contests.

reinstitute: To institute for a second or subsequent time

ubiquinol: A certain benzoquinol, the reduced product of ubiquinone, also called coenzyme Q10.

ardent: Expressing or characterized by warmth of feeling; passionate.

frataxin: A class of protein found in mitochondria

sacrilegious: Committing sacrilege or characterized by sacrilege.

pied: Patchy in color; splotched or piebald.

videlicet: That is; namely. Used to introduce examples, lists, or items.

preternatural: Surpassing what is normal or usual; extraordinary.

epistemic: Of, relating to, or involving knowledge; cognitive.

drusy: In mineralogy, covered or lined with very minute crystals.

zucchetto: A skullcap worn by certain Roman Catholic clerics, varying in color according to rank.

omphalopsychite: One of a body of monks who believed that deep contemplation of the navel induced communion with God: same as Hesychast.

ceilidh: A social gathering with traditional Irish or Scottish music, dancing, and storytelling.

syndic: One appointed to represent a corporation, university, or other organization in business transactions; a business agent.

crannog: An ancient Irish dwelling or fort built on an artificial island in a lake or marsh.

gnomology: A collection of or treatise on maxims or sententious and pithy reflections.

antiquation: The act of antiquating, or the state of being antiquated.

hypocycloidal: Of the nature of a hypocycloid.

riotousness: The state or condition of being riotous.

poltroonery: The character or nature of a poltroon; cowardice; baseness of mind; want of spirit.

tasso: A particular style of pickled pork.

mazer: A large drinking bowl or goblet made of metal or hard wood.

vulnerary: Used in the healing or treating of wounds.

ombrophilous: Loving rain; inviting the contact of rain: in phytogeography, said of plants or their parts, chiefly their foliage, or of the abstract character. Ombrophilous character is manifested by the fact that the leaves or other parts are wettable: opposed to ombrophobous.

granulopoiesis: The formation and development of granulocytes

aquarelle: A painting done in transparent watercolors.

cabriole: A form of furniture leg that curves outward and then narrows downward into an ornamental foot, characteristic of Queen Anne and Chippendale furniture.

euskara: The native name of the Basque language. See Basque.

voguing: A stylized form of modern dance characterized by photographic-style poses integrated with angular, linear and rigid movements.

momentous: Of utmost importance; of outstanding significance or consequence.

kamancheh: A stringed instrument with three metal strings, played with a bow. Common among peoples of Caucasus, Anatolia and the Near East.

hyperhidrosis: A medical condition with the primary symptom of excessive sweating, in excess of that required for regulation of body temperature..

styrax: Any member of the genus Styrax of about 130 species of large shrubs or small trees, mostly native to temperate or tropical regions of the Northern Hemisphere.

saxony: A high-grade wool fabric originally made from the wool of sheep raised in Saxony.

hemianopsia: In pathology, complete or partial loss of sight, affecting one half of the field of vision.

chrysocracy: The power or rule of gold or wealth.

chalcogenide: Any binary compound of a chalcogen with a more electropositive element.

paradoxically: In a paradoxical manner, or in a manner seemingly absurd or contradictory; in such a way or sense as to involve an apparent contradiction or absurdity.

hierophany: A physical manifestation of the holy or sacred, serving as a spiritual eidolon for emulation or worship.

hydromancy: Divination by the observation of water.

sarsaparilla: Any of several tropical American plants of the genus Smilax, having fragrant roots used as a flavoring.

chemiosmosis: Any chemical reaction that occurs through an intervening semipermeable membrane, especially through a membrane in a biological cell

catalepsy: A condition characterized by lack of response to external stimuli and by muscular rigidity, so that the limbs remain in whatever position they are placed. It is known to occur in a variety of physical and psychological disorders, such as epilepsy and schizophrenia, and can be induced by hypnosis.

paleontologically: In a paleontological sense; from a paleontological point of view.

allemande: A stately 16th-century dance in duple meter.

kilojoule: A practical unit of energy equal to 1000 joules or to 1 × 10 ergs.

paralipsis: A pretended or suggested omission for rhetorical effect, usually introduced by “I say nothing of,” “not to mention,” or the like.

calamondin: A small evergreen citrus tree (Citrofortunella ×mitis), widely cultivated as a houseplant for its glossy foliage and ornamental fruits.

erastianism: The doctrine of the supremacy of the state over the church. See Erastian, a.

emaciated: having become so thin that the bones noticeably protude under the skin.

tabaret: A strong upholstery fabric having alternating stripes of satin and moiré.

quipu: A cord about 2 feet in length, tightly spun from variously colored threads, and having a number of smaller threads attached to it in the form of a fringe: used among the ancient Peruvians and elsewhere for recording events, etc.

letrozole: A nonsteroidal drug that inhibits the enzyme aromatase, C17H11N5, used to treat breast cancer in postmenopausal women.

The original Turkic inhabitants were overrun by the Mongols in the 1200s and ruled by various khanates until the Russian conquest of 1730 to 1863. The region was incorporated into the USSR in 1920 and was named the Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic from 1936 to 1991, when it gained its independence. Astana is the capital, and Almaty is the largest city.

opsimath: One who is late in learning or in beginning to learn.

chelonian: A reptile of the order Chelonia; a turtle or tortoise.

melancholiac: A person affected with melancholia; a melancholy maniac.

monophthong: A single vowel articulated without change in quality throughout the course of a syllable, as the vowel of English bed.

paean: A song of joyful praise or exultation.

rayon: Any of several synthetic textile fibers produced by forcing a cellulose solution through fine spinnerets and solidifying the resulting filaments.

chitinous: Consisting of or having the nature of chitin.

laccolith: A mass of igneous rock intruded between layers of sedimentary rock, resulting in uplift.

zoonomy: The laws of animal life collectively considered; the science which treats of the causes and relations of the phenomena of living animals; the vital economy of animals; animal physiology.

papule: A small, solid, usually inflammatory elevation of the skin that does not contain pus.

vatic: Of or characteristic of a prophet; oracular.

reticuloendothelial: Of or relating to the reticuloendothelial system.

tarhonya: A kind of egg-based pasta in the shape of small balls.

witenagemot: An Anglo-Saxon advisory council to the king, composed of about 100 nobles, prelates, and other officials, convened at intervals to discuss administrative and judicial affairs.

emeritus: Retired but retaining an honorary title corresponding to that held immediately before retirement.

astrakhan: A fabric with a curly looped pile, made to resemble karakul.

ormer: A European abalone (Haliotis tuberculata) found chiefly in the Channel Islands.

amusette: A light field-cannon, invented by Marshal Saxe, designed for outpost service.

twinge: A sharp, sudden physical pain. synonym:pain.

azure: A bright blue, as of a clear sky.

crèche: A representation of the Nativity, usually with statues or figurines.

burgoo: Any of several thick stews, originally an oatmeal porridge.

maqam: A modal structure characterizing the art of music of countries in North Africa, the Middle East and Central Asia.

hydroxypropyl: Either of three isomeric univalent radicals in which a hydrogen atom of a propyl radical is replaced with a hydroxy group

mitigation: The act of mitigating, or the state of being mitigated; alleviation; abatement or diminution of anything harsh, painful, severe, afflictive, calamitous, or the like.

taleggio: a soft Italian cheese from Lombardy

kinkajou: An arboreal mammal (Potos flavus) of Central and South America, having brownish fur and a long, prehensile tail.

rongorongo: An early glyphic writing system of Easter Island, written in reverse boustrophedon and as yet undeciphered.

apophyge: The outward curve at the top and bottom of a column where the shaft joins the capital or base.

bezantée: A molding ornamented with roundels or small disks resembling bezants, of frequent occurrence in Norman architecture.

helicobacter: Any member of the Helicobacter bacteria.

alcogene: The vapor-cooler in a distilling apparatus.

South Africa: A country of southern Africa on the Atlantic and Indian Oceans. Originally inhabited by the San and Khoikhoi, the region was settled by various Bantu peoples c. 1500. European settlement began with the Dutch in the mid-1600s. The region passed to Great Britain in 1814 but was hotly contested by descendants of the Dutch settlers in the Boer War (1899–1902), in which Britain took possession of the entire territory, creating the Union of South Africa in 1910. South Africa declared itself a republic in 1961, severed ties with the British Commonwealth, and further consolidated the apartheid system, which was repealed beginning in 1989. An interim constitution ending white rule was adopted in 1993, and the first multiracial elections were held in 1994. Pretoria is the administrative capital; Cape Town, the legislative capital; and Bloemfontein, the judicial capital. Johannesburg is the largest city.
