paradigm: One that serves as a pattern or model.

claque: A group of persons hired to applaud at a performance.

diptera: An order of metabolous hexapod insects.

mulct: A penalty such as a fine.

telestich: A poem in which the final letters of the lines make a name.

gubernatorial: Of or relating to a governor.

archaeological: Relating to the science or research of archaeology.

lollygag: To waste time by puttering aimlessly; dawdle.

cafila: A caravan of travelers; a military supply train or government caravan; a string of pack horses.

effervescence: Natural ebullition; that commotion of a fluid which takes place when some part of the mass flies off in a gaseous form, producing small bubbles: as, the effervescence or working of new wine, cider, or beer; the effervescence of a carbonate with nitric acid, in consequence of chemical action and decomposition producing carbon dioxid or carbonic-acid gas.

philosophises: Third-person singular simple present indicative form of philosophise.

haustellate: Fitted for sucking; suctorial; siphonostomous, as an insect or a crustacean, or the mouth-parts of such creatures.

ecotopia: Any ecologically ideal place or situation

emtricitabine: An antiretroviral drug, C8H10FN3O3S, that is a nucleoside analog and inhibits replication of HIV by inhibiting reverse transcriptase.

pneumatic: Of or relating to air or other gases.

hastilude: Spear-play: a name given to justs or tilts, and less accurately to tourneys or tournaments. See these words.

verisimilar: Appearing to be true or real; probable.

alabaster: A dense, translucent, white or tinted fine-grained gypsum.

glabrous: Having no hairs or pubescence; smooth.

bitumen: Any of various flammable mixtures of hydrocarbons and other substances, occurring naturally or obtained by distillation from coal or petroleum, that are a component of asphalt and tar and are used for surfacing roads and for waterproofing.

steatite: Soapstone: an impure massive variety of talc. Also called potstone.

carnelian: A pale to deep red or reddish-brown variety of clear chalcedony, used in jewelry.

demography: The study of the characteristics of human populations, such as size, growth, density, distribution, and vital statistics.

somnambulist: One who is subject to somnambulism; a person who walks in his sleep.

tanorexia: A condition whose sufferers believe they are too pale and become obsessed with tanning.

Macquarie: A river of southeast Australia flowing about 950 km (590 mi) northwest to the Darling River.

bisulphide: A sulphide having two atoms of sulphur in the molecule; a disulphide, as in iron pyrites, FeS2; -- less frequently called bisulphuret.

claxon: a kind of loud horn formerly used on motor vehicles.

acoustic: Of or relating to sound, the sense of hearing, or the science of sound.

lamback: A beating; a cudgeling; a blow.

zechstein: In geology, the uppermost of the two divisions of the Permian, the lower being the so-called “Rothliegende.”

wryneck: Either of two small woodpeckers, Jynx torquilla of Eurasia and Africa or J. ruficollis of sub-Saharan Africa, having a sharply pointed bill and the ability to twist the neck almost all the way around.

phyllomania: In botany, the production of leaves in unusual numbers or in unusual places.

prudish: Marked by or exhibiting the characteristics of a prude; priggish.

esemplastic: Molding, shaping, or fashioning into one.

shewedst: Second-person singular past form of shew

beautician: One skilled in giving cosmetic treatments.

okonomiyaki: A savoury pan-fried Japanese batter cake including many vegetables.

myoglobinuria: The presence of myoglobin in the urine, usually associated with rhabdomyolysis or muscle destruction.

odoriferous: Having or giving off an odor.

allargando: In a gradually broadening style and slowing tempo. Used chiefly as a direction.

Bahasa Malaysia: the Malay language spoken in Malaysia

anhedonia: The inability to experience pleasure, as seen in certain mood disorders.

commerce: The buying and selling of goods, especially on a large scale, as between cities or nations. synonym:business.

berlingot: A carriage of the berlin type, with the front quarter removed and cut longitudinally to half its original width: fitted for only one passenger.

kurta: A loose long-sleeved shirt or tunic, often extending to the knees, worn primarily in South Asia.

adjacency: The state of being adjacent; contiguity.

divvy: To divide. Often used with up:

perennial: Lasting an indefinitely long time; enduring.

kilin: A fabulous creature mentioned in Chinese mythology.

isobath: A line connecting places that have the same depth below sea-level; an isobathymetric line.

ontogeny: The origin and development of an individual organism from embryo to adult.

paleobiology: The branch of paleontology that deals with the fossils of plants, animals, and other organisms.

geriatrician: A physician who specializes in geriatrics.

bibliotaph: One who hides or buries books, or keeps them under lock and key.

mercantilism: The theory and system of political economy prevailing in Europe after the decline of feudalism, based on national policies of accumulating bullion, establishing colonies and a merchant marine, and developing industry and mining to attain a favorable balance of trade.

allegro: In a quick, lively tempo, usually considered to be faster than allegretto but slower than presto. Used chiefly as a direction.

disworship: To dishonor; deprive of worship or dignity; disgrace.

heinousness: The condition or quality of being heinous; odiousness; enormity: as, the heinousness of a vice or crime.

Osceola: Seminole leader who resisted the American government's removal of his people from Florida in the 1830s. He died in prison after being tricked into surrendering (1837).

dinocyst: A dormant zygotic stage of the life cycle of dinoflagellates

knowledgeableness: The state, quality, or measure of being knowledgeable; wisdom.

aerodigestive: Pertaining to the airway and digestive tract.

excavate: To make a hole in; hollow out.

anastrophe: Inversion of the normal syntactic order of words; for example,

caricaturist: One who draws or writes caricatures; specifically, one who occupies himself with drawing pictorial caricatures.

hypogeal: Living or occurring under the earth's surface.

amplexus: The copulatory embrace of frogs and toads, during which the male fertilizes the eggs that are released by the female.

capillary: Relating to or resembling a hair; fine and slender.

proa: A swift Malayan sailboat with a triangular sail and single outrigger.

cosmopolitanism: The state of being cosmopolitan; universality of extent, distribution, feeling, etc.; especially, the character of a cosmopolite, or citizen of the world. Also called cosmopolitism.

trichocyst: An organelle in certain protozoans, especially ciliates, consisting of filamentous fibers that are discharged suddenly.

deuterocanonical: Of, relating to, or being a second canon, especially that consisting of sections of the Old and New Testaments not included in the original Roman Catholic canon but accepted by theologians in 1548 at the Council of Trent.

apocrypha: Certain writings which are received by some Christians as an authentic part of the Holy Scriptures, but are rejected by others.

importunity: An importunate request; an insistent or pressing demand.

mediocre: Of ordinary or undistinguished quality. synonym:average.

mediocracy: A social hierarchy in which the mediocre prevails.

Lobachevskian: Of or pertaining to Nikolai Ivanovich Lobachevsky (1792–1856), Russian mathematician, or to his work, most notably on non-Euclidean geometry.

aseity: The mode of being of that which is underived from anything else; independent existence; existence by self-origination.

emergent: Coming into view, existence, or notice.

chemosensory: Relating to the perception of a chemical stimulus by sensory means. Used especially of olfactory reception.

tallith: The mantle or, as in present Jewish usage, scarf-like garment worn by the Jews, especially at prayer. Also talith, talles, tallis.

sedentary: Characterized by or requiring much sitting.

obscuration: The act of obscuring or darkening; the state of being darkened or obscured; the act or state of being made obscure or indistinct: as, the obscuration of the moon in an eclipse.

Barrymore: Family of American actors, including Lionel (1878–1954), who won an Oscar in 1931 for Free Soul; his sister Ethel (1879–1959), who appeared mainly on stage but also won an Academy Award in 1944 for None but the Lonely Heart; and their brother John (1882–1942), known as “the Great Profile,” who appeared on stage as Hamlet and Richard III and in many motion pictures, including Dinner at Eight (1933).

corpulent: Having an abundance or excess of flesh or fat. synonym:fat.

vengeance: Infliction of punishment in return for a wrong committed; retribution.

chicle: The coagulated milky latex of the sapodilla, formerly used as the principal ingredient of chewing gum.

histology: The anatomical study of the microscopic structure of animal and plant tissues.

tourbillon: A rotating frame, containing the escapement of a clock or watch, that attempts to compensate for the effects of gravity.

imbrex: A gutter-tile or other tile of curved surface; a pantile.

spandrel: The roughly triangular space between the left or right exterior curve of an arch and the rectangular framework surrounding it.

bacitracin: A polypeptide antibiotic obtained from a strain of a bacterium (Bacillus subtilis) and used as a topical ointment in the treatment of certain bacterial infections, especially those caused by cocci.

esterification: A chemical reaction resulting in the formation of at least one ester product.

preta: A hungry ghost (a supernatural being in Buddhist folklore, the spirit of a greedy person whose divine retribution is to never be sated)

odalisque: A woman slave in a harem.

toque: Any of several styles of small, usually brimless, close-fitting hats.

catabolic: Relating to or of the nature of catabolism.

menology: A register of months, or of occurrences in the order of the months.

piña colada: A mixed drink made of rum, coconut cream, and unsweetened pineapple juice.

zombie: In voodoo belief and popular folklore, a corpse that has been reanimated, especially by means of a supernatural power or spell.

taboo: A ban or inhibition resulting from social custom or emotional aversion.

expelling: any of several bodily processes by which substances go out of the body.

seismograph: An instrument for automatically detecting and recording the intensity, direction, and duration of a movement of the ground, especially of an earthquake.

sea anemone: Any of numerous often colorful marine anthozoans of the order Actiniaria, having a flexible cylindrical body and a mouth surrounded by tentacles, and resembling a flower.

Verdun: A city of northeast France on the Meuse River west of Metz. Dating to Roman times and an important Carolingian commercial center, it was the site of a prolonged World War I battle (February–December 1916) in which French forces repelled a massive German offensive. The total casualties have been estimated at more than 700,000. The city was rebuilt after the war.

gelded: Simple past tense and past participle of geld.

erastes: An adult man who courted or was in an pederastic relationship with an adolescent boy, who was called an eromenos.

abide: To put up with; tolerate: synonym:endure.

zoologist: One who is versed in zoölogy; a biologist.

colophon: An inscription placed usually at the end of a book, giving facts about its publication.

hypogynous: Having the floral parts, such as sepals, petals, and stamens, borne on the receptacle beneath the ovary.

sipuleucel: A vaccine therapy used to treat some cancers

kaolinite: A mineral, Al2Si2O5(OH)4, that is the principal constituent of kaolin.

allelomorph: A distinct phenotype associated with a specific allele.

proxemics: The study of the cultural, behavioral, and sociological aspects of spatial distances between individuals.

vanquish: To defeat or conquer in battle; subjugate.

paphiopedilum: horticulturally important genus of mainly terrestrial orchids including many hybrids; southeastern Asia and Indonesia to Philippines and Solomon Islands; Paphiopedilum species sometimes included in genus Cypripedium

Solomon Islands: An island group of the western Pacific Ocean east of New Guinea. Inhabited primarily by Melanesian peoples since at least 2000 BC, these volcanic islands were first visited by European explorers in the 1560s and were divided between Germany and Great Britain in the late 1800s. Australia assumed control of the northern islands in 1920. Today the northern Solomons are part of Papua New Guinea. The southern islands are an independent country.

marcassin: In heraldry, the young wild boar, used as a bearing.

thiazide: Any of a group of drugs that block reabsorption of sodium in the distal tubules of the kidneys, used as diuretics primarily in the treatment of hypertension.

Calabria: A region of southern Italy forming the toe of the Italian “boot.” Founded as a Greek colony, it was subsequently held by Rome, the Byzantine Empire, the Normans, and the kingdom of Naples before becoming part of a united Italy in 1861.

fanzine: An amateur-produced magazine written for a subculture of enthusiasts devoted to a particular interest.

debase: To lower in character, quality, or value; degrade.

unctuously: In an unctuous manner with unctuousness.

Catharism: A Christian religious sect of mediaeval Europe, with dualistic and gnostic elements.

mimsy: Miserable and flimsy: a blend-word, or bruneh-word (which see).

solleret: A steel shoe made of overlapping plates, forming a part of a medieval suit of armor.

talaria: Winged sandals such as those worn by Hermes and Iris as represented in Greco-Roman painting and sculpture.

mantua: A woman's garment of the 1600s and 1700s consisting of a bodice and full skirt cut from a single length of fabric, with the skirt designed to part in front to reveal a contrasting underskirt.

totara: A coniferous tree, Podocarpus Totara, the most valuable timber-tree of New Zealand.

actinopterygian: Any of the ray-finned fish of the subclass Actinopterygii

encenia: Festive ceremonies observed in early times in honor of the construction of cities or the consecration of churches, and in later times at the universities of Oxford and Cambridge in honor of founders and benefactors: exceptionally used as a singular.

amphiscii: In geography, the inhabitants of the intertropical regions, whose shadows at noon are cast in one part of the year to the north and in the other part to the south, according as the sun is in the southern or the northern signs.

yclept: Forms of the preterit and past participle of clepe.

slubber: To daub; stain; sully; soil; obscure.

crapulence: Sickness caused by excessive eating or drinking.

abecedarian: One who teaches or studies the alphabet.

pilgarlic: One who has lost his hair by disease; a sneaking fellow, or one who is hardly used.

borborygmus: A rumbling noise produced by the movement of gas through the intestines.

incendiary: Causing or designed to cause fires.

pashm: A kind of wool produced in Tibet.

exodus: A departure of a large number of people.

indigestibility: The state or quality of being indigestible.

tithe: A portion of one's annual income contributed voluntarily or due as a tax, especially a contribution of one tenth of one's income for the support of the clergy or church.

inquisitive: Inclined to investigate; eager for knowledge.

manege: The art of breaking, training, and riding horses; the art of horsemanship.

armamentarium: The complete equipment of a physician or medical institution, including books, supplies, and instruments.

gannet: Any of several large seabirds of the genus Morus, especially M. bassanus of the North Atlantic, having a pointed bill and tail, long wings, and white plumage with black wingtips.

dismission: The act of sending away; leave or command to depart; dismissal: as, the dismission of the grand jury.

deipnosophist: One who converses learnedly at dinner: in allusion to the title (see the etymology) of a celebrated work of Athenæus, in which a number of learned men are represented as at dinner discoursing on literature and matters of the table.

hagiology: Literature dealing with the lives of saints.

hew: To make or shape with or as if with an ax.

abrasively: In an abrasive manner; in a rude and unkind manner; acting in a way that may hurt other people's feelings.

entitled: Simple past tense and past participle of entitle.

bourrée: An old French dance resembling the gavotte, usually in 3/4 or 2/2 time beginning with an upbeat.

anadiplosis: Rhetorical repetition at the beginning of a phrase of the word or words with which the previous phrase ended; for example, He is a man of loyalty—loyalty always firm.

quarrel: To find cause of complaint; find fault; cavil.

antidisestablishmentarian: One who believes that the Church of England should retain its formal constitutional relationship with the state.

intuition: The faculty of knowing or understanding something without reasoning or proof. synonym:reason.

Diwali: Hindu festival of lights, celebrated over several days in October and November.

balagan: A thatched pyramidal wooden hut of eastern Siberia, raised on piles to a height of about 10 feet, and reached by a ladder consisting of a notched tree-stem.

muqaddam: Any of various Arabic or Islamic officials.

buqsha: A former currency unit of Yemen.

contamination: The act or process of contaminating.

motif: A recurrent thematic element in an artistic or literary work.

lathe: A machine for shaping a piece of material, such as wood or metal, by rotating it rapidly along its axis while pressing a fixed cutting or abrading tool against it.

probabilist: One who holds the doctrine of probabilism.

smug: Exhibiting or feeling great or offensive satisfaction with oneself or with one's situation; self-righteously complacent.

atheist: One who denies the existence of God, or of a supreme intelligent being.

jaunty: Having or expressing a buoyant or self-confident air.

acrocephalic: In ethnology, pertaining to or characterized by acrocephaly; high-skulled: as, acrocephalic men or tribes.

kleptomania: An obsessive impulse to steal regardless of economic need.

Suquamish: A member of a Native American people inhabiting an area of the eastern shore of Puget Sound.

frisson: A moment of intense excitement; a shudder.

Waldemar: A variety of velveteen, or cotton velvet, apparently a superior quality of fustian.

catallactics: The science of exchanges: adopted by Whately as a designation of political economy.

intrapersonal: Existing or occurring within the individual self or mind.

calve: To give birth to a calf.

palliate: To make less severe or intense; mitigate. synonym:relieve.

quill: The hollow stemlike main shaft of a feather.

centrist: One who has moderate political views.

bellerophon: Any of the genus Bellerophon of fossil univalve shells, believed to belong to the Heteropoda, and peculiar to the Paleozoic age.

medley: An often jumbled assortment; a mixture.

bacilliform: Of the form of a small rod; rod-shaped; bacillar in form.

Georgia: A country in the Caucasus on the Black Sea. It developed as a kingdom around the 4th century BC and reached the height of its prosperity in the 12th and 13th centuries. Ruled by both Turkey and Persia at various times, Georgia was acquired by Russia between 1801 and 1878. The region was briefly independent (1918–1921), but was invaded by the Red Army in 1921 and proclaimed a Soviet republic. It was joined with Armenia and Azerbaijan to form the Transcaucasian Soviet Federated Socialist Republic from 1922 to 1936, when it became a separate republic, known as the Georgian Soviet Socialist Republic until declaring its independence in 1991. The capital and largest city is Tbilisi.

rhabdoid: In botany, a spindle-shaped or acicular body, chemically related to the plastids, which occurs in certain cells of plants exhibiting irritability, such as Drosera, Dionæa, etc., and which probably plays an important part in this function. The position in the cell is such that it stretches diagonally across the cell from end to end.

virgate: In geology, noting a system of faults, the minor members of which branch from a central one as twigs from a bough.

myofibroblast: A cell that is intermediate between a fibroblast and smooth muscle

paleothermometer: Anything found in the natural record (such as a tree ring) that can be used to deduce the temperature at some time in the past.

Oglala: A member of a Native American people constituting a subdivision of the Lakota, formerly inhabiting the Black Hills region of western South Dakota, with a present-day population in southwest South Dakota.

hlonipa: A custom among the Zulus and certain other tribes of South Africa according to which they must show respect to certain of their relatives and to the head men of the tribe.

impala: A reddish-brown African antelope (Aepyceros melampus) that has long, curved horns in the male and is noted for its ability to leap.

absinthe: A perennial aromatic Eurasian herb (Artemisia absinthium) in the composite family, naturalized in North America and having pinnatifid, silvery, silky leaves and numerous nodding flower heads.

hellraiser: A person who is of wild, wanton behavior.

interdigitate: To insert between the fingers; interweave like the joined fingers of the two hands.

Algonquian: A family of North American Indian languages spoken or formerly spoken in an area from Labrador to the Carolinas between the Atlantic coast and the Rocky Mountains.

rummy: Of or pertaining to rum: as, a rummy flavor.

ampicillin: A semisynthetic penicillin that has a broader antibacterial spectrum of action than that of penicillin G, is effective against gram-negative and gram-positive bacteria, and is used to treat infections of the intestinal, urinary, and respiratory tracts.

Nickelodeon: A small, rudimentary movie theater that charged five cents for admission, popular in North America from about 1905 to 1915.

leukotriene: Any of several lipid compounds that contain 20 carbon atoms, are related to prostaglandins, and mediate the inflammatory response.

tendentious: Marked by or favoring a particular point of view; partisan.

disengage: To release from something that holds fast, connects, or entangles. synonym:extricate.

Agamemnon: The king of Mycenae and leader of the Greeks in the Trojan War, who was the son of Atreus and the father of Orestes, Electra, and Iphigenia. He was killed by his wife Clytemnestra upon his return from Troy.

inflict: To cause (something injurious or harmful), as to a person, group, or area.

clinicopathological: Relating both to the symptoms of disease and to the lesions produced by it.

herpetologist: One versed in herpetology, or engaged in the study of it.

cantillation: A chanting, intoning, or recitation in a half-singing style: especially used in Jewish synagogues. Also spelled cantilation.

logion: A saying attributed to Jesus in the Gospels or in other ancient sources.

eczematous: Pertaining to or produced by eczema: as, eczematous eruptious.

apoplexy: Sudden impairment of neurological function, especially that resulting from a cerebral hemorrhage; a stroke.

subpixel: Any of the units that make up a pixel. Each pixel usually has one red, one blue, and one green subpixel.

pathetic: Arousing or deserving of sympathetic sadness and compassion.

indulgent: Showing, characterized by, or given to permissiveness or generosity with regard to others.

onanistic: Of, pertaining to, or caused by onanism.

skirl: To produce a high, shrill, wailing tone. Used of bagpipes.

antilogy: Self-contradiction; contradiction or inconsistency between different statements by the same person or different parts of the same thing.

homoscedastic: Having the same finite variance for all elements.

esprit de corps: A common spirit of comradeship, enthusiasm, and devotion to a cause among the members of a group.

begrudge: To envy (someone) the possession or enjoyment of (something).

edifice: A building, especially one of imposing appearance or size.

prodigious: Impressively great in size, force, or extent; enormous.

prospectus: A formal summary of a proposed venture or project.

euripus: A sea channel characterized by turbulent and unpredictable currents.

aguaji: A Cuban name for species of large bass-like fishes or groupers, especially for Mycteroperca bonaci.

tremella: A genus of gelatinous hymenomycetous fungi, typical of the order Tremellineæ, having a nonpapillate hymenium which surrounds the whole of the fungus. See fairy-butter.

criollo: A Spanish American of European, usually Spanish ancestry.

unbar: To remove the bars from or become unbarred.

amain: With force, strength, or violence; violently; furiously; suddenly; at full speed; hastily.

godet: A triangular piece of fabric usually set into the hem of a garment to add fullness.

biretta: A stiff square cap with three or four ridges across the crown. Birettas are worn especially by Roman Catholic clergy and are black for priests, purple for bishops, and red for cardinals.

prehension: The act of grasping or seizing.

madison: A two-man track cycling event in which partners take turns to race round the track a number of times, and then must exchange places with a partner by means of a hand sling.

pamphlet: An unbound printed work, usually with a paper cover.

upcycle: To convert (waste materials etc.) into new materials or products of higher quality and greater functionality.

Lahmu: In Akkadian mythology, name of a protective and beneficent deity, the first-born son of Apsu and Tiamat.

pomace: The pulpy material remaining after the juice has been pressed from fruit, such as apples or grapes.

zenzizenzizenzic: the eighth power of a number

almacabala: The mystic explanation of numbers and of relations of numbers.

alma: A Turkish measure of capacity, equal to 1.15 gallons.

tantivy: At full gallop; at top speed.

scut: Routine or tedious work often viewed as menial.

ancientism: Favor to things ancient; the belief that ancient times were better than the present.

antic: A foolish or ludicrous act; a caper.

menstruum: A solvent, especially one used in extracting compounds from the tissues of organisms.

cucurbit: Any of various mostly climbing or trailing plants of the family Cucurbitaceae, which includes the squash, pumpkin, cucumber, gourd, watermelon, and cantaloupe.

penitent: Feeling or expressing remorse for one's misdeeds or sins; contrite.

shiur: A lesson on a topic in the Torah.

qaeda: a terrorist network intensely opposed to the United States that dispenses money and logistical support and training to a wide variety of radical Islamic terrorist groups; has cells in more than 50 countries

miscellany: A collection of various items, parts, or ingredients, especially one composed of diverse literary works.

antechamber: A smaller room serving as an entryway into a larger room.

cladogenesis: An evolutionary process that involves the splitting off or branching of new taxa from an ancestral form.

salubrious: Conducive or favorable to health or well-being.

trencher: A wooden plate or platter (originally a square piece of board or slice of wood) for the table or the kitchen.

eggar: Any of various moths of the family Lasiocampidae, whose larvae often construct tentlike webs among the branches of trees.

gerrymandering: The practice of redrawing electoral districts to gain an electoral advantage for a political party.

folio: A large sheet of paper folded once in the middle, making two leaves or four pages of a book or manuscript.

agrypnia: Sleeplessness; insomnia; morbid wakefulness or vigilance.

crinoidea: A class of Echinodermata containing globular or cup-shaped echinoderms, having, normally, jointed arms furnished with pinnules, and stalked and fixed during some or all of their lives: so called from the resemblance of their rayed bodies, borne upon a jointed stem, to a lily or tulip.

exsanguinous: Destitute of or deficient in blood, as an animal; anemic. Also exsanguineous.

valetudinary: Of, relating to, or typical of a valetudinarian.

perch: Any of several spiny-finned freshwater fishes of the genus Perca, especially either of two edible species, the yellow perch of North America, and P. fluviatilis of Europe.

coot: Any of several waterbirds of the widely distributed genus Fulica, having dark-gray plumage, a black head and neck, and a white bill.

adenomyxosarcoma: A tumor composed of glandular, mucous, and sarcomatous elements.

antidicomarianite: One of a Christian sect which originated in Arabia in the latter part of the fourth century, who denied the perpetual virginity of Mary, holding that she was the real wife of Joseph, and had children by him after the birth of Jesus. Also called Antimarian.

tumultuary: Marked by haste, confusion, disorder, and irregularity.

clepsydra: An ancient device that measured time by marking the regulated flow of water through a small opening.

circumgyration: The act of circumgyrating; rolling or revolving.

almanac: An annual publication including calendars with weather forecasts, astronomical information, tide tables, and other related tabular information.

arbitrager: A banker or a broker who engages in arbitrage operations.

alkekengi: The winter-cherry, a solanaceous plant, Physalis Alkekengi.

alecost: Costmary, Tanacetum Balsamita, a plant put into ale to give it an aromatic, flavor. See costmary.

coquina: Any of various small marine clams of the genus Donax having variously colored, often striped or banded wedge-shaped shells, and found especially on sandy beaches along the Atlantic coast of the United States.

fugue: A contrapuntal musical composition whose basic structure consists of a theme or themes stated successively in different voices.

clapperclaw: To beat, claw, and scratch; thrash; drub.

nangka: In Guam, the edible seeds of the fertile breadfruit, Artocarpus communis, which, like those of the jack-fruit of the Philippines, are roasted and eaten, and resemble chestnuts in taste. See dugdug.

halligan: A tool, used mostly by firemen, to pry open buildings, manholes, wrecked cars, etc.

lingula: A little tongue or tongue-like part or process; a ligula.

Brachiopoda: A class of mollusk-like animals distinguished by the development of two labial (generally called brachial) appendages, diverging from either side of the mouth.

anthologize: To compile or publish an anthology.

samfie: A confidence trickster, especially one who pretends to have supernatural powers.

betide: To happen to. Used chiefly in the phrase woe betide. synonym:happen.

aggiornamento: The process of bringing an institution or organization up to date; modernization.

bamboozler: One who bamboozles; a cheat; one who plays tricks upon another.

vermiform: Having the shape of a worm.

agammaglobulinemia: A congenital or acquired deficiency of gamma globulins in the blood.

amatungulu: a very large closely branched South African shrub (Carissa grandiflora) of the dogbane family having forked bright green spines, white flowers, shiny leaves, and red berries. Also called natal plum.

anabolism: The phase of metabolism in which simple substances are synthesized into the complex materials of living tissue.

glandule: A small gland; any gland. See glandula.

hordeolum: In pathology, a sty or small inflammatory tumor on the edge of the eyelid.

aeromancy: Divination by use of atmospheric conditions.

docosahexaenoic acid: An omega-3 fatty acid and essential fatty acid found in fish oils, metabolized to form the docosanoids.

anathematize: To proclaim an anathema on; curse.

monticule: A minor cone of a volcano.

catharsis: Purgation, especially for the digestive system.

baccivorous: Eating or subsisting on berries: as, baccivorous birds.

haranguer: One who harangues or is fond of haranguing; a noisy declaimer.

fugacity: The quality of being fugacious; disposition to flee or escape; volatility; transitoriness.

reata: A rope, usually of rawhide, with or without a noose, used in western and Spanish America for catching or picketing animals; a lariat.

heresy: An opinion or a doctrine at variance with established religious beliefs, especially dissension from or denial of Roman Catholic dogma by a professed believer or baptized church member.

eyeliner: Makeup used to outline the eyes.

Blender: An open source, cross-platform suite of tools for the creation of 3D graphics.

agalma: In law, the impression or image of anything upon a seal.

quadratics: The branch of algebra that deals with quadratic equations.

naziism: a form of socialism featuring racism and expansionism and obedience to a strong leader

perijove: The point in an orbit around the planet Jupiter where the orbiting body is closest to the planet.

aposelene: apoapsis in orbit around the moon

tittle: A small diacritic mark, such as an accent, vowel mark, or dot over an i.

allochthonous: Originating or formed in a place other than where found.

pinscher: Any of several breeds of dog originally developed in Europe, especially the Doberman pinscher.

affenpinscher: A dog of a small breed developed in Germany, having a rough shaggy coat, a hairy face with a short muzzle, and usually cropped ears.

premade: Simple past tense and past participle of premake.

abominableness: The quality or state of being abominable, detestable, or odious.

arbiter: One agreed upon or appointed to judge or decide a disputed issue; an arbitrator.

limbo: A kind of coarse cotton cloth worn by South Africans.

tattersall: A pattern of dark lines forming squares on a light background.

thatcherism: (England) the political policy of Margaret Thatcher

antrum: A cavity or chamber, especially one in a bone.

supermodel: An extremely successful and internationally famous fashion model.

defied: Simple past tense and past participle of defy.

dotard: A person who is in his or her dotage.

lablab: The Egyptian or black bean, Dolichos Lablab, a native of India, widely cultivated, and naturalized in most warm countries.

dote: To show excessive fondness or love.

yukked: Simple past tense and past participle of yuk.

verein: Union; a union, association, or society.

deciduous: Shedding or losing foliage at the end of the growing season.

yeasty: Of, similar to, or containing yeast.

twinleaf: An eastern North American woodland plant (Jeffersonia diphylla) having basal leaves deeply cleft into two kidney-shaped lobes and a solitary white flower borne on a long scape.

baba ganoush: A Lebanese dish made from a purée of roasted aubergine (eggplant), garlic and tahini used as a dip etc.

eschatology: The branch of theology that is concerned with the end of the world or of humankind.

bruxomania: compulsive grinding of the teeth (while awake)

pad thai: A Thai dish of stir-fried rice noodles, egg, bean sprouts, shrimp, peanuts, and seasonings.

Liguria: A region of northwest Italy on the Ligurian Sea, an arm of the Mediterranean Sea between northwest Italy and Corsica. Named for an ancient pre-Indo-European people, the Ligurii, the region was subdued by the Romans in the 2nd century BC and was later (16th–19th century) controlled by Genoa. A small section of the coastline surrounding Genoa formed the Ligurian Republic from 1797 until 1815.

mura: luminance non-uniformity of a display device.

preponderance: Superiority in weight, force, importance, or influence.

senile: Relating to or having diminished cognitive function, as when memory is impaired, because of old age.

windsock: A tapered fabric tube pivotally attached to a standard, that indicates the direction of the wind blowing through it.

ají: A red pepper. See pepper, chilli, and pimento.

bayamo: A violent blast of wind, accompanied by vivid lightning, blowing from the land on the south coast of Cuba, and especially from the Bight of Bayamo.

apocynthion: The point in an orbit around the Moon that is most distant from that body.

maki: A true lemur or macaco, such as the ring-tailed lemur, Lemur catta. Dwarf makis are species of the genus Chirogaleus. See cut under Chirogaleus.

bibimbap: A Korean dish of white rice topped with vegetables, beef, a whole egg, and gochujang (chile pepper paste).

holus-bolus: All at a gulp; altogether; all at once: as, he swallowed it holus-bolus.

apyrexia: The absence or intermission of pyrexia or fever; the interval between the paroxysms in intermittent fevers. Also apyrexy.

incandescent: Emitting visible light as a result of being heated.

prophylactic: Acting to defend against or prevent something, especially disease; protective.

milliner: One that makes, trims, designs, or sells hats.

mannequin: A life-size full or partial representation of the human body, used for the fitting or displaying of clothes; a dummy.

Acanthorhynchus: A taxonomic genus within the family Meliphagidae — two spinebillls.

motmot: Any of various tropical American birds of the family Momotidae, usually having green and blue plumage with long tail feathers that have paddle- or racket-shaped tips.

casuistry: Specious or excessively subtle reasoning intended to rationalize or mislead.

tref: Unlawful; unclean: opposed to kosher as used by Hebrews.

eigenstate: One of a set of quantum-mechanical descriptions of the possible state of a physical system, using the mathematics of eigenvectors and generally existing in a state of superposition until the moment of observation.

flexion: The act of bending a joint or limb in the body by the action of flexors.

hyperproliferation: An abnormally high rate of proliferation of cells by rapid division

uraninite: A complex brownish-black mineral, UO2, forming the chief ore of uranium and containing variable amounts of radium, lead, thorium, and other elements. It is isomorphous with thorianite.

visnaga: A name applied in the Mediterranean region to Ammi Visnaga, a carrot-like plant, the peduncles of which become dilated into disks which boar the umbel-rays. These harden into spines and become erect and connivent. They are used for toothpicks, giving to the plant the name toothpick, or picktooth-plant. See picktooth, 2.

krump: Krumping: an energetic style of hip-hop dance

perambulation: The act of perambulating, or of passing or wandering through or over.

endemic: Prevalent in or limited to a particular locality, region, or people.

politic: Showing sound or pragmatic judgment; prudent; judicious.

enticing: Alluring; attracting; charming. Formerly also inticing.

posthumously: After one's death; especially, after an author's death.

cadre: A nucleus of trained personnel around which a larger organization can be built and trained.

voyageur: A woodsman, boatman, or guide employed by a fur company to transport goods and supplies between remote stations in Canada or the US Northwest.

churr: The sharp whirring or trilling sound made by some insects and birds, such as the grasshopper and partridge.

organza: A sheer, stiff fabric of silk or synthetic material used for trim, neckwear, and evening dresses.

physiocrat: One who advocates the doctrines of physiocracy; specifically, one of a group of French philosophers and political economists, followers of François Quesnay (1694-1774), which rose to prominence in the latter half of the eighteenth century, and maintained that a natural constitution or order exists in society, the violation of which has been the cause of all the evils suffered by man.

sinecure: A position or office that requires little or no work but provides a salary.

antinome: One that is contradictory or contrary to another; an opposite.

tulle: A fine, often starched net of silk, rayon, or nylon, used especially for veils, tutus, or gowns.

a cheval: Astride; with a part on each side; -- used specif. in designating the position of an army with the wings separated by some line of demarcation, as a river or road.

tenesmus: A painfully urgent but ineffectual attempt to urinate or defecate.

marginalia: Notes in the margin or margins of a book.

inoculate: To introduce a serum, vaccine, or antigenic substance into (the body of a person or animal), especially to produce or boost immunity to a specific disease.

kayfabe: The portrayal of events within the industry as real; the portrayal of professional wrestling and the accompanying storylines as not staged or worked.

conquer: To gain control of or subdue by military force.

masscult: The modern industrial equivalent of culture, mass-produced and anonymously consumed, without specialization or connoisseurship.

doublet: A close-fitting jacket, with or without sleeves, worn by European men from the late 1300s to around 1650.

stratum: A horizontal layer of material, especially one of several parallel layers arranged one on top of another.

peridotite: Any of various coarse-grained igneous rocks that consist mainly of olivine and pyroxene and are believed to be a main constituent of the earth's mantle.

hyrax: Any of several herbivorous mammals of the family Procaviidae of Africa and the Middle East, resembling woodchucks or similar rodents but more closely related to the hoofed mammals.

damask: A rich patterned fabric of cotton, linen, silk, or wool.

shenanigan: A playful or mischievous act; a prank.

bedizen: To ornament or dress in a showy or gaudy manner.

batik: A method of dyeing a fabric by which the parts of the fabric not intended to be dyed are covered with removable wax.

capsanthin: A di-hydroxy, keto carotenoid, which, together with capsorubin, constitutes the red pigment of paprika.

Mantidae: A taxonomic family within the order Mantodea — a family of praying mantises.

fossick: To search for gold, especially by reworking washings or waste piles.

shoo: Used to frighten away animals or birds.

targum: An Aramaic translation of the Tanakh written or compiled between the Second Temple period and the early Middle Ages.

atingle: Experiencing a prickling sensation, as from excitement; being in a state of tingling.

cenoby: A place where persons live in community.

totemic: Of or pertaining to a totem; characterized by a totem: as, a totemic relative or relationship.

khedive: One of several Turkish viceroys ruling Egypt from 1867 to 1914.

cleat: A strip of wood or iron used to strengthen or support the surface to which it is attached.

fungible: Returnable or negotiable in kind or by substitution, as a quantity of grain for an equal amount of the same kind of grain.

tartan: A vessel used in the Mediterranean for commercial and other purposes.

banlieue: The territory without the walls, but within the legal limits, of a town or city. Sometimes erroneously spelled banlieu, as if from French lieu, a place.

quayage: A charge for the use of a quay.

alula: A small joint in the middle of a bird's wing, homologous with the thumb and bearing three or four quill-like feathers.

propagate: To cause (an organism) to multiply or breed.

odd-come-shortly: Some day soon to come; an early day; some time; any time.

amphigoric: Of, relating to, or consisting of amphigory; absurd; nonsensical.

hurricane: A severe tropical cyclone having winds greater than 64 knots (74 miles per hour; 119 kilometers per hour), originating in the equatorial regions of the Atlantic Ocean or Caribbean Sea or eastern regions of the Pacific Ocean, traveling north, northwest, or northeast from its point of origin, and usually involving heavy rains.

fathomless: Too deep to be fathomed or measured.

mandarin: A member of any of the nine ranks of high public officials in the Chinese Empire.

radome: A domelike shell transparent to radio-frequency radiation, used to house a radar antenna.

tortilla: A thin disk of unleavened bread made from masa or wheat flour and baked on a hot surface.

eleemosynary: Of, relating to, or dependent on charity. synonym:benevolent.

philanthropic: Of, relating to, or marked by philanthropy or charitable assistance. synonym:benevolent.

aristocort: a synthetic corticosteroid (trade names Aristocort or Aristopak or Kenalog) used as an anti-inflammatory agent

neonate: A newborn infant, especially one less than four weeks old.

subapical: Located below or near an apex.

annihilation: The act or process of annihilating.

cybernaut: A person who uses a virtual reality system.

fruition: Realization of something desired or worked for; accomplishment.

cynosure: An object that serves as a focal point of attention and admiration.

abiogenesis: The supposed development of living organisms from nonliving matter.

gemshorn: An organ stop with conical tin pipes.

peccancy: The state or quality of being peccant; badness.

pisco: A liquor distilled from grapes (a brandy) made in wine-producing regions of Peru and Chile. It is the most widely consumed spirit in Argentina, Bolivia, Chile and Peru.

Ajax: The son of Telamon of Salamis and a warrior of great stature and prowess who fought against Troy.

narcotize: To place under the influence of a narcotic.

vociferous: Making, given to, or marked by noisy and vehement outcry.

parergon: A work executed incidentally; a work subordinate or subsidiary to another: as, Ayliffe's “Parergon”.

Cheviot: Any of a breed of hornless sheep with thick crimped wool, originally raised in the Cheviot Hills.

paletot: A loose outer garment for a man or a woman.

screed: A long monotonous speech or piece of writing.

brogue: A strong dialectal accent, especially a strong Irish or Scottish accent when speaking English.

ornamentation: The act or process of decorating, adorning, or embellishing.

colloquium: An informal meeting for the exchange of views.

idyllic: Of or relating to an idyll.

corvee: In feudal law, an obligation imposed upon the inhabitants of a district to perform certain services, as the repair of roads, etc., for the sovereign or the feudal lord.

stiletto: A small dagger with a slender, tapering blade.

elixir: A sweetened aromatic solution of alcohol and water, serving as a vehicle for medicine.

aconite: Any of various usually poisonous perennial herbs of the genus Aconitum in the buttercup family, having tuberous roots, palmately lobed leaves, and blue, purple, or white flowers with a large hoodlike upper sepal.

ideate: To form an idea of; imagine or conceive.

illude: To play upon; mock; deceive with false hopes.

septenary: Consisting of or relating to seven: as, a septenary number.

obdormition: Sleep; the state or condition of being asleep.

chuckwalla: Any of several large herbivorous lizards of the genus Sauromalus of the southwest United States and Mexico, especially S. ater.

moccasin: A soft leather slipper traditionally worn by certain Native American peoples.

geometry: The mathematics of the properties, measurement, and relationships of points, lines, angles, surfaces, and solids.

outwit: To surpass in cleverness or cunning; outsmart.

ditto: The same as stated above or before.

phlogiston: A hypothetical substance formerly thought to be a volatile constituent of all combustible substances, released as flame in combustion.

lysimeter: An instrument for determining the quantity of matter held in solution in a liquid.

brontide: A sound like that of distant thunder, some of which may have seismic origins.

papilla: A small nipplelike projection, such as a protuberance on the skin, at the root of a hair or feather, or at the base of a developing tooth.

cadaver: A dead body, especially one intended for dissection.

interstice: A space, especially a small or narrow one, between things or parts.

balize: A sea-mark or beacon at the mouth of a river or the entrance to a harbor; a barrel-buoy, a pole surmounted by a peculiar flag or other object, etc.

Oaxaca: A city of southeast Mexico south-southwest of Veracruz. It was founded c. 1490 as an Aztec garrison post and was conquered by the Spanish in 1521.

chef-d'oeuvre: A masterpiece, especially in literature or art.

meshugaas: Crazy or senseless activity or behavior; craziness.

coalesce: To come or grow together into a single mass.

hesperidium: A berry having a thickened leathery rind and juicy pulp divided into segments, as an orange or other citrus fruit.

pasticcio: A work or style produced by borrowing fragments, ingredients, or motifs from various sources; a potpourri.

quaint: Charmingly odd, especially in an old-fashioned way.

emissary: An agent sent on a mission to represent or advance the interests of another.

straddle: To stand or sit with a leg on each side of; bestride.

Phrygia: An ancient region of central Asia Minor in modern-day central Turkey. It was settled c. 1200 BC and flourished from the eighth to the sixth century, after which it came under the influence of Lydia, Persia, Greece, Rome, and Byzantium.

alexandrite: A greenish chrysoberyl that appears red in artificial light, used as a gemstone.

armiger: A bearer of armor for a knight; a squire.

anaglyph: An ornament carved in low relief.

swath: The width of a scythe stroke or a mowing-machine blade.

guan: Any of several large game birds of the family Cracidae, native to tropical forests of Central and South America and resembling the curassows.

chokeslam: a wrestling move in which someone is picked up by their neck and is driven into the mat

fiduciary: Of or relating to a duty of acting in good faith with regard to the interests of another.

torrential: Resembling, flowing in, or forming torrents.

contortionist: One who contorts, especially an acrobat capable of twisting into extraordinary positions.

humstrum: A musical instrument out of tune or rudely constructed; a hurdy-gurdy.

Quetzalcoatl: A god of the Toltecs and Aztecs, often represented as a plumed serpent, who was worshiped as co-creator of the world along with his adversary Tezcatlipoca.

lorgnon: An eye-glass, or a pair of eye-glasses, shutting into a frame which when in use serves as a handle, intended for examining objects at a little distance: also sometimes used as synonymous with opera-glass or lorgnette.

gaskin: The part of the hind leg of a horse or related animal between the stifle and the hock.

bloviate: To discourse at length in a pompous or boastful manner.

perspicuity: The quality of being perspicuous; clearness and lucidity.

ausubo: The name in Porto Rico of the West Indian mastic-tree, Sideroxylon fætidissimum. Its timber is the most important and widely used on the island, being noted for its great durability.

guaiacum: Any of several tropical American trees of the genus Guaiacum; a lignum vitae.

quaalude: A capsule or tablet of the illicit drug methaqualone.

cuirass: A piece of armor for protecting the breast and back, often consisting of two pieces fastened together.

dapagliflozin: A drug that inhibits glucose reabsorption in the kidney, and may be used in the treatment of diabetes

synoptic: Of or constituting a synopsis; presenting a summary of the principal parts or a general view of the whole.

bahut: A dress for masquerading: a damino.

batterie: A roll upon the side- or snaredrum.

arpeggio: The sounding of the tones of a chord in rapid succession rather than simultaneously.

glockenspiel: A percussion instrument with a series of metal bars tuned to the chromatic scale and played with two light hammers.

Tetragrammaton: The four Hebrew letters usually transliterated as YHWH or JHVH, used as a biblical proper name for God.

anthropomorphism: Attribution of human motivation, characteristics, or behavior to inanimate objects, animals, or natural phenomena.

anadem: A wreath or garland for the head.

drupe: A fleshy fruit, such as a peach, plum, or cherry, usually having a single hard stone that encloses a seed.

amiuchi: A kimarite in which the attacker throws his opponent behind him by pulling his arm with both hands and twisting backwards; resembles casting a fishing net.

galuchat: A kind of shark's skin or shagreen usually dyed green, used to cover cases, boxes, etc. As prepared it retains the tubercles with which it is studded in the natural state.

sansho: any of the three special prizes awarded at the end of a basho

keir: In bleaching, a large boiler which contains the bleaching-liquor; the alkaline vat of a bleachery. See bucking and keeve.

blogosphere: The set of all blogs on the Internet along with those who compile them and comment upon them, viewed as an interconnected community or as a phenomenon.

prebendal: Of or pertaining to a prebend or a prebendary.

Vienna: The capital and largest city of Austria, in the northeast part of the country on the Danube River. Originally a Celtic settlement, it became the official residence of the house of Habsburg in 1278 and a leading cultural center in the 1700s, particularly under the reign (1740–1780) of Maria Theresa.

moral: Of or concerned with the judgment of right or wrong of human action and character.

quaquaversal: Inclined outward in all directions from a central point or area: used chiefly in geology, as in the phrase quaquaversal dip, a dipping in all directions from a central area.

interpenetrate: To become mixed or united by penetration.

bandoleer: A belt fitted with small pockets or loops for carrying cartridges and worn across the chest by soldiers.

bycoket: A type of ancient cap or headdress, worn by military men and also ornamentally by men and women, including by the kings of England (the upper part of which was in the form of a double crown).

incantation: Ritual recitation of verbal charms or spells to produce a magic effect.

spodumene: A greenish to pinkish or lilac mineral, LiAlSi2O6, that is used as a source of lithium and in transparent varieties as a gemstone.

defunct: Having ceased to exist or live.

comstockery: Censorship of literature and performances because of especially broad definitions of obscenity or immorality.

flamen: A priest, especially of an ancient Roman deity.

oche: A line behind which a player's front foot must be placed when throwing a dart.

Abuja: The capital of Nigeria, in the central part of the country. Laid out in the 1970s according to a comprehensive plan, Abuja replaced Lagos as the country's capital in 1991.

withered: Shriveled, shrunken, or faded from or as if from loss of moisture or sustenance.

astral: Of, relating to, emanating from, or resembling the stars.

cipher: The mathematical symbol (0) denoting absence of quantity; zero.

chromosomal: Of or pertaining to the chromosomes.

Chengdu: A city of south-central China west-northwest of Chongqing. It is the capital of Sichuan province.

askew: To one side or out of proper alignment; awry.

heterozygous: Having different alleles at one or more corresponding chromosomal loci.

theine: A bitter crystallizable volatile principle (C8H10N4O2) found in tea, coffee, and some other plants, tea yielding from 2 to 4 per cent.

Ayrshire: Any of a breed of reddish-brown and white dairy cattle that originated in Ayr, Scotland.

enosis: the union of Greece and Cyprus (which is the goal of a group of Greek Cypriots)

octet: A composition for eight voices or eight instruments.

psittacine: Relating to, resembling, or characteristic of parrots.

microbiome: A microbial biome, such as the community of microbes within the human gut.

waif: A homeless person, especially a forsaken or orphaned child.

badigeon: A mixture of plaster and freestone, ground together and sifted, used by sculptors to fill the small holes and repair the defects of the stones used by them.

colonne: One of the three columns, of twelve figures each, stamped upon a roulette-table.

bovine: Of, relating to, or resembling a ruminant mammal of the bovid subfamily Bovinae, especially one in the genus Bos, such as a cow, ox, or buffalo.

condemned: Under condemnation or sentence; doomed: applied to persons: as, a condemned murderer.

kibitzer: A person who offers unsolicited views, advice, or criticism; one who kibitzes.

yeanling: The young of a sheep or goat; a lamb or kid.

Kahoolawe: An island of south-central Hawaii southwest of Maui. The low and unfertile island has been used as a prison and a military target range.

abatis: A defensive obstacle made by laying felled trees on top of each other with branches, sometimes sharpened, facing the enemy.

boeuf: meat from an adult domestic bovine.

Oporto: A city of northwest Portugal near the mouth of the Douro River north of Lisbon. Probably of pre-Roman origin, it was captured by the Moors in 716. Its wine trade was established in 1678.

excelsior: Slender, curved wood shavings used especially for packing.

perfunctory: Done routinely and with little interest or care.

paludal: Of or relating to a swamp; marshy.

gerah: An ancient Hebrew coin and unit of weight.

avolation: The act of flying away; flight; escape; exhalation; evaporation.

wadi: A valley, gully, or streambed in northern Africa and southwest Asia that remains dry except during the rainy season.

trilobite: Any of numerous extinct marine arthropods of the class Trilobita, of the Paleozoic Era, having a segmented body divided by grooves into three longitudinal lobes and found as fossils throughout the world.

Zonda: A local foehn wind occurring at the eastern base of the Andes, in the vicinity of San Juan, Argentine Republic.

cecils: In cookery, minced meat, crumbs of bread, onions, chopped parsley, etc., with seasoning, made up into balls and fried.

hackle: To hack roughly; haggle. See haggle.

Bardolino: A town in the province of Verona in the Veneto

arraign: To call (an accused person) before a criminal court to hear and answer the charge made against him or her.

bigotry: The attitude, state of mind, or behavior characteristic of a bigot; intolerance.

iconoclastic: Of or pertaining to iconoclasm, or to the opinions and practices of the Iconoclasts; given to breaking images, or to exposing errors of belief or false pretensions: as, iconoclastic enthusiasm.

scofflaw: One who habitually violates laws, especially laws that do not involve serious criminal offenses.

bifurcate: To divide into two parts or branches.

necrophilia: Obsessive fascination with death and corpses.

tumorigenesis: The formation or production of tumors.

ammonite: An extinct cephalopod mollusk of the order Ammonitida of the Permian to Cretaceous Periods, having a thick, usually coiled shell characterized by intricate suture patterns where the septa between individual chambers join the outer shell wall.

dabster: One who is skilled; one who is expert; a master of his business; a dab.

antitumorigenic: Opposing tumorigenesis; serving to counteract the formation of tumors.

Wicca: A Neopagan nature religion based in part on pre-Christian Celtic beliefs and practices, typically centering on a mother goddess or a goddess-god pair and the practice of ceremonial witchcraft.

aqualung: an apparatus containing compressed air or other oxygen-gas mixture, permitting a person to breathe under water; -- also called a scuba.

ammonites: The leading genus of ammonites, named in this form by Breyn in 1732, better established by Bruguière in 1789, giving name to the family Ammonitidæ.

sapiosexual: A person sexually attracted to intelligence or the human mind.

vermicular: Having the shape of a worm; vermiform.

caynard: A wretch; a rascal; a good-for-nothing.

myeloma: A malignant tumor formed by the cells of the bone marrow.

loureth: Third-person singular simple present indicative form of lour.

periapt: A charm worn as protection against mischief and disease; an amulet.

ipecac: A low-growing tropical American shrub (Psychotria ipecacuanha syn. Cephaelis ipecacuanha) having roots and rhizomes that yield emetine.

satyric: Of or pertaining to satyrs: as, a satyric drama.

snorkel: A breathing apparatus for swimmers and surface divers that allows swimming or continuous use of a face mask without lifting the head to breathe, consisting of a tube that curves out of the mouth and extends above the surface of the water.

temporize: To act or speak in order to gain time, avoid an argument, or postpone a decision.

picturesque: Of, suggesting, or suitable for a picture.

erudite: Having or showing great knowledge or learning. synonym:learned.

industrialization: a process of social and economic change whereby a human society is transformed from a pre-industrial to an industrial state

materialise: To take physical form, to appear seemingly from nowhere.

adjourned: Simple past tense and past participle of adjourn.

fondant: A sweet creamy sugar paste used in candies and icings.

borough: A self-governing incorporated town in some US states, such as New Jersey.

twistical: Somewhat twisted or crooked, physically, mentally, or morally; odd; questionably honest.

caulis: In architecture, one of the main stalks or leaves which spring from between the acanthusleaves of the second row on each side of the typical Corinthian capital, and are carried up to support the volutes at the angles. Compare cauliculus

Djibouti: A country of eastern Africa on the Gulf of Aden. Djibouti was a French colony from 1896 until 1946 and a territory from 1946 until its independence in 1977. It was called French Somaliland from 1896 to 1967 and the French Territory of Afars and Issas from 1967 to 1977. Djibouti is the capital and largest city.

bellicose: Warlike or hostile in manner or temperament. synonym:belligerent.

tisri: The seventh month of the Jewish ecclesiastical year, answering to a part of September with a part of October.

diuretic: Tending to increase the discharge of urine.

autotheist: One who believes in autotheism.—2. One who ascribes to himself the possession of divine powers.

penduline: Building a pendulous or pensile nest: as, the penduline titmouse, Ægithalus pendulinus.

elemi: Any of various oily resins derived from certain tropical trees, especially Canarium luzonicum of the Philippines, and used in making varnishes and inks.

garble: To mix up or distort to such an extent as to make misleading or incomprehensible.

vinaigrette: A cold sauce or dressing made of vinegar or lemon juice and oil, often flavored with finely chopped onions, herbs, and other seasonings.

marzipan: A confection made of ground almonds or almond paste, egg whites, and sugar, often molded into decorative shapes.

ventifact: A stone that has been shaped or polished by wind-driven sand.

doddering: Trembling, tottering, or exhibiting mental impairment associated with aging.

scenography: The art of representing objects in perspective, especially as applied in the design and painting of theatrical scenery.

Gaborone: The capital of Botswana, in the southeast part near the South African border. It was founded c. 1890.

Botswana: A country of south-central Africa. Originally inhabited by the San and later (after the 18th century) by the Tswana, the region became a British protectorate as Bechuanaland (1885) and gained full independence in 1966. Gaborone is the capital and the largest city.

nidus: A central point or focus of infection by bacteria or other pathogens.

arsenal: A governmental establishment for the storing, development, manufacturing, testing, or repairing of arms, ammunition, and other war materiel.

aperient: Gently stimulating evacuation of the bowels; laxative.

immense: Very great in size, extent, or amount.

adit: An almost horizontal entrance to a mine.

candor: Frankness or sincerity of expression; openness.

moat: A deep wide ditch, usually filled with water, typically surrounding a fortified medieval town, fortress, or castle as a protection against assault.

heir: A person who inherits or is entitled by law or by the terms of a will to inherit the estate of another.

tripartite: Composed of or divided into three parts.

intellectual: Of or relating to the intellect.

palsy-walsy: Being in a close, friendly relationship.

antitussive: Capable of relieving or suppressing coughing.

appassionato: Impassioned; emotional: in music, noting passages to be so rendered.

elude: To evade or escape from, as by daring, cleverness, or skill: synonym:evade.

widgiemoolthalite: A nickel analogue of hydromagnesite discovered in Western Australia.

deign: To do something that one considers beneath one's dignity; condescend: synonym:stoop.

ashen: Pertaining to the ash-tree or its timber; made of ash.

loam: Soil composed of a mixture of sand, clay, silt, and organic matter.

egotism: An inflated sense of one's own importance; conceit. synonym:conceit.

abdominocardiac: Of or pertaining to the abdomen and the heart.

Staphylococcus: A taxonomic genus within the family Staphylococcaceae — the staphylococcus bacteria.

trochee: A metrical foot consisting of a stressed syllable followed by an unstressed syllable, as in season.

Fontainebleau: A town of northern France southeast of Paris. Its chateau (built by Francis I) was long a royal palace and is now the summer residence of the president of France. The revocation of the Edict of Nantes was signed here in 1685.

syllabub: A drink made of sweetened milk or cream curdled with wine or spirits.

regimen: A regulated system, as of medication, diet, or exercise, used to promote health or treat illness or injury.

clonogenic: Having the ability to form clones

kerplunk: To fall with a sound like that of a heavy object falling into water.

Perak: State in western Malaysia which has Ipoh as its capital.

impanel: To add or include (a person's name) on a list of persons selected for jury duty.

toffee: A hard, chewy candy made of brown sugar or molasses and butter.

trifle: Something of little importance or value.

paladin: A paragon of chivalry; a heroic champion.

tranter: Specifically, a seller of fish; a name applied to a boatman who visits vessels in harbor for the purpose of supplying them with fish.

iamb: A metrical foot consisting of an unstressed syllable followed by a stressed syllable, as in delay.

facet: One of the flat polished surfaces cut on a gemstone or occurring naturally on a crystal.

banoffee: A British cream filling made from banana and toffee.

compote: Fruit stewed or cooked in syrup.

thermophile: Any of various organisms, such as certain bacteria, requiring temperatures between 45°C and 80°C to thrive.

chukka: A short, ankle-length boot having two or three pairs of eyelets.

strobilus: A cone of a gymnosperm or of a seedless vascular plant such as a horsetail or a club moss.

perimenopausal: Of or pertaining to the perimenopause.

confectionery: Candies and other confections considered as a group.

solecize: To commit solecisms. Also spelled solecise.

opiniator: One who holds obstinately to his own opinion; an opinionative person.

neoromantic: Belonging to or characteristic of the later romantic school.

bacterioplankton: The bacterial component of marine plankton

Barbados: A country occupying the easternmost island of the West Indies. First inhabited by Arawaks and Caribs, Barbados was held briefly by the Portuguese before being settled by the British in the early 1600s. It became a separate colony in 1885 and gained full independence in 1966. Bridgetown is the capital and the largest city.

diminution: The act or process of diminishing; a lessening or reduction.

anoesis: The reception of impressions or sensations (by the brain) without any intellectual understanding.

frappé: A frozen, fruit-flavored mixture that is similar to sherbet and served as a dessert or appetizer.

neocracy: Government by new or inexperienced officials; the rule or supremacy of upstarts.

roselle: A tropical African plant (Hibiscus sabdariffa) having flowers with yellow petals and a persistent, bright red calyx that has a pleasantly acid flavor and is used to make jelly and beverages.

plasmon: The aggregate of cytoplasmic or extranuclear genetic material in an organism.

heathenish: Of or pertaining to gentiles or pagans; characteristic of or practised by the heathen: as, heathenish rites.

irreverent: Lacking or exhibiting a lack of reverence; disrespectful.

mulligrubs: A pain in the intestines; colic.

ocotillo: A shrub (Fouquieria splendens) of Mexico and the southwest United States, having long spiny stems and clusters of scarlet tubular flowers.

laari: A subdenomination of the rufiyaa, 100 laari=1 rufiyaa

lassi: A beverage made of yogurt and water and flavored with spices, fruit, or other ingredients.

antigropelos: Spatterdashes; long riding- or walking-boots for wet weather.

celebutante: A young, fashionable, and usually wealthy person who is the subject of frequent media attention.

luteous: Of a light or moderate greenish yellow.

troubleshooting: The identification and resolution of problems, especially problems of a technical nature.

imparisyllabic: Not consisting of an equal number of syllables.

autarky: A policy of national self-sufficiency and nonreliance on imports or economic aid.

stoichiometric: Of or pertaining to stoichiometry; employed in, or obtained by, stoichiometry.

Riyadh: The capital and largest city of Saudi Arabia, in the east-central part of the country east-northeast of Mecca. Situated in a desert oasis, it was a walled city until the oil boom of the 1950s led to the demolition of older structures to make way for commercial expansion.

litotes: A figure of speech consisting of an understatement in which an affirmative is expressed by negating its opposite, as in This is no small problem.

antechapel: An apartment, vestibule, porch, or the like, before the entrance to a chapel; the narthex of a chapel.

redyed: Simple past tense and past participle of redye.

unitasking: Doing a single thing at a time.

haphazard: Dependent upon or characterized by mere chance. synonym:chance.

Leanne: A female given name, a variant of Lee Ann.

chinche: A name of the common American skunk, Mephitis mephitica. Also cinche.

lexicology: The branch of linguistics that deals with the lexical component of language.

udder: A baglike organ containing the mammary glands, characteristic of certain female mammals, such as cows, sheep, and goats.

estoc: A sword used for thrusting, especially a second sword carried by knights in the middle ages.

al desko: At a desk (typically used of eating).

aahed: Simple past tense and past participle of aah.

jadish: Skittish; vicious: said of a horse.

brachistochrone: The curve upon which a body moves in the least possible time from one given point to another.

proprietor: One who has legal title to something; an owner.

barre: A handrail fixed to a wall, as in a dance studio, used by ballet dancers as a support in certain exercises.

opodeldoc: A plaster said to have been invented by Mindererus.

chaff: To make fun of in a good-natured way; tease.

ana: A general term for books recording miscellaneous sayings, anecdotes, and gossip about a particular person or subject; the sayings and anecdotes themselves. See -ana.

banjaxed: Simple past tense and past participle of banjax.

El Salvador: A country of Central America bordering on the Pacific Ocean. Conquered by Spain in 1524, the region gained its independence in 1821, joined (1825–1838) a federation of Central American states, and became a separate republic in 1839. The country was ruled by a series of military governments from 1931 to 1979 and was embroiled in a civil war from 1980 to 1992. San Salvador is the capital and the largest city.

bordereau: A detailed memorandum, especially one that lists documents or accounts.

cyathus: In Greek antiquity, a form of vase with a long handle, used especially for dipping, as for taking wine from the crater to pour into the oinochoë or directly into the cup. It was often made in the form of a ladle.

izote: In Mexico, Guatemala, and Honduras, a name of several species of Yucca and their allies, especially Y. Treculeana, which yields a fiber of commercial importance called ixtli de Coahuila; Y. Schottii Jaliscensis, the source of the fiber called ixtli de Jalisco; Samuela Carnerosana, yielding the ixtli de Carneros; and Y. baccata, which bears edible fruit often called datiles. In Guatemala and Honduras the name is applied to Y. elephantipes, a species cultivated in gardens and planted in hedges, which in Costa Rica is called itabo.

embellisher: One who or that which embellishes.

Honduras: A country of northern Central America. Originally inhabited by a Mayan civilization, Honduras was colonized by the Spanish in the early 1500s and gained its independence along with Mexico in 1821. Part of a short-lived confederation of Central American states, Honduras became a separate republic in 1838. Tegucigalpa is the capital and the largest city.

diiodide: In chem., a compound containing two atoms of iodine.

matinee: An entertainment, such as a dramatic performance or movie, presented in the daytime, usually in the afternoon.

euhemerism: A theory attributing the origin of the gods to the deification of historical heroes.

chiaroscurist: An artist who draws in chiaroscuro.

nuchal: In the trilobites, relating to the axial segment and groove at the base of the cephalon.

numen: A presiding divinity or spirit of a place.

marc: Brandy distilled from fermented grape or apple pomace.

glocalization: The adaptation of globally distributed goods, services, or publications in order to make them suitable for local needs.

epiblast: The outer layer of a blastula that gives rise to the ectoderm after gastrulation.

zaniness: The state or condition of being zany.

Martinique: An island and overseas department of France in the Windward Islands of the West Indies. Inhabited first by Arawaks and later by Caribs, the island was visited by Columbus in 1502. It was colonized by French settlers after 1635. Fort-de-France is the capital.

decentralise: same as decentralize. Opposite of centralize and concentrate

astray: Away from the correct path or direction.

adumbration: The act of adumbrating or making a shadow or faint resemblance.

palatableness: The character of being palatable or agreeable to the taste, literally or figuratively.

supraoptic: Above the optic tract or chiasma

lurid: Characterized by vivid description or explicit details that are meant to provoke or shock.

Madrid: The capital and largest city of Spain, on the central plateau north-northeast of Toledo. Built on the site of a Moorish fortress captured in the 11th century, it became the capital in 1561 during the reign of Philip II and grew in importance and magnificence under the Bourbons in the 18th century. Madrid was a Loyalist stronghold during the Spanish Civil War (1936–1939).

fisc: The treasury of a kingdom or state.

dupe: A person who is easily deceived or is used to carry out the designs of another.

cactaceous: Pertaining to or resembling the Cactaceæ.

paginated: Simple past tense and past participle of paginate.

periscii: The inhabitants of the polar circles: so called because in their summer-time their shadows describe an oval.

numnah: A pad, often of sheepskin, placed under a horse's saddle; a saddle blanket

sotto voce: In soft tones, so as not to be overheard; in an undertone.

grimthorpe: To treat in the manner of Lord Grimthorpe, that is, to ‘restore’ (an old piece of architecture) with the effect of spoiling it, as Lord Grimthorpe is said to have done when he undertook to restore the west front of St. Albans Abbey in England.

smorgasbord: A buffet meal featuring a varied number of dishes.

binge: A period of excessive or uncontrolled indulgence, especially in food or drink.

inalienable: That cannot be transferred to another or others.

pivotal: Of, relating to, or serving as a pivot.

sorites: An argument presenting a series of premises that can be analyzed as a chain of syllogisms, with each syllogism's major term forming the minor term of the next, until a final conclusion is attained. For example, a sorites might consist of the premises that some pets are snakes, that no snakes have fur, and that only furry things are cuddly, yielding the conclusion that not all pets are cuddly.

bacteriolytic: Pertaining to or of the nature of bacteriolysis; destructive to bacteria through the action of specific lysins.

nasalization: The act of nasalizing or uttering with a nasal sound.

murage: Money paid for keeping the walls of a town in repair.

actinide: Any of a series of chemically similar, radioactive elements with atomic numbers ranging from 89 (actinium) through 103 (lawrencium).

cymotrichous: In anthropology, characterized by having wavy hair.

intolerableness: The character of being intolerable or insufferable.

oones: A Middle English form of once.

nutrimental: Having the qualities of food; nutritious; nourishing; alimental.

ikat: A craft in which one tie-dyes and weaves yarn to create an intricately designed fabric.

dapple: Mottled or spotted marking, as on a horse's coat.

Saudi Arabia: A country occupying most of the Arabian Peninsula. Inhabited since ancient times by nomadic Semitic tribes, the region was consolidated under Muhammad, who established a theocratic state at Medina and gained control of all Arabia c. 630. After the caliphate was moved from Medina to Damascus in 661, the peninsula remained fragmented until most of it was united in the 1700s under the Saud family, who adopted the Wahhabi form of Islam. Crushed by Egyptian and Ottoman opposition in the 1800s, Saudi forces reconquered the peninsula in the early 1900s. The unified kingdom of Saudi Arabia was created in 1932 as an absolute monarchy under Wahhabi law. Oil was discovered in 1938 and soon became the mainstay of the economy. Riyadh is the capital and the largest city.

geoglyph: A large design or drawing created on the surface of the earth, as by positioning stones or removing earth or surface rock to create lines or spaces that contrast with the surrounding terrain.

honeymoon: A holiday or trip taken by a newly married couple.

majordomo: The head servant or official in a royal Spanish or Italian household; later, any head servant in a wealthy household in a foreign country; a leading servant or butler.

refusal: The act or an instance of refusing.

dismiss: To end the employment or service of; discharge.

scenic: Of or relating to the stage, stage scenery, or theatrical representation.

rap-full: Full of wind: applied to sails when on a wind every sail stands full without lifting.

pemmican: A food prepared by Native Americans from lean dried strips of meat pounded into paste, mixed with fat and berries, and pressed into small cakes.

plethora: An abundance or excess of something.

maypole: A pole, garlanded with streamers held by people who dance around it to celebrate May Day.

humdinger: One that is extraordinary or remarkable.

bank holiday: A day on which banks are legally closed.

ennead: A group or set of nine.

slate: A fine-grained metamorphic rock that splits into thin, smooth-surfaced layers.

nosegay: A small bunch of flowers; a bouquet.

germinable: Capable of germinating or proliferating; viable.

caviar: The roe of a large fish, especially sturgeon, that is salted, seasoned, and eaten as a delicacy or relish.

pock-pudding: A bag-pudding: sometimes applied to persons as a term of opprobrium.

exuviae: The cast-off skins or coverings of various organisms, such as the shells of crabs or the external coverings of the larvae and nymphs of insects.

tetrahydrobiopterin: A naturally-occurring nutrient and essential cofactor of the three aromatic amino acid hydroxylase enzymes, used in the biosynthesis of the neurotransmitters serotonin, melatonin, dopamine, norepinephrine, epinephrine, and nitric oxide.

roe: The eggs or spawn of a fish, contained within or separated from the ovary, especially when prepared as food.

musaceous: In botany, of or relating to the Musaceæ.
