dextromethorphan: An antitussive drug, C18H25NO, that is used in its hydrobromide form and is less addictive than codeine.

acetylcholine: A white crystalline derivative of choline, C7H17NO3, that is released at the ends of nerve fibers in the somatic and parasympathetic nervous systems and is involved in the transmission of nerve impulses in the body.

robitussin: trade name of an expectorant that loosens phlegm and makes it easier to cough up

brine: Water saturated with or containing large amounts of a salt, especially sodium chloride.

pedregal: A rough and rocky district, especially in a volcanic region.

plutonomy: The science of wealth or riches.

aljamiado: Text of non-Semitic language written in Arabic letters.

aporia: A figure of speech in which the speaker expresses or purports to be in doubt about a question.

offal: Waste parts, especially of a butchered animal.

robustious: Vigorous or energetic, especially in a rough or noisy way.

incunabula: The cradle or early abode; the place in which a thing had its earliest development, as a race, an art, etc.; hence, first trace; beginning; origin.

zenith: The point on the celestial sphere that is directly above the observer.

adscititious: Not inherent or essential; derived from something outside.

protozoa: Primordial or first-formed animals, or cell-animals; protozoans: a subkingdom of Animalia or prime division of animals, contrasted with Metazoa, or all other animals collectively.

expatiate: To speak or write at length.

uterine: Of, relating to, or in the region of the uterus.

pultaceous: Soft or semi-fluid, as the substance of a poultice; pulpy.

prepositor: A scholar appointed to oversee or superintend other scholars, or hold them in discipline; a monitor. Also prepostor, præpostor.

futurist: One who has regard to the future; one whose main interest lies in the future; an expectant.

nociceptive: Causing pain. Used of a stimulus.

jigged: Made in a jig; hence, accurately made. See jig, 6 .

yttria: A metallic oxid or earth, having the appearance of a white powder, which is insipid, insoluble in water, and infusible.

synesthesia: A condition in which one type of stimulation evokes the sensation of another, as when the hearing of a sound produces the visualization of a color.

pauperism: The quality or state of being a pauper.

chorizo: A spicy pork sausage seasoned especially with garlic.

sybaritic: Devoted to or marked by pleasure and luxury.

sackbut: A medieval instrument resembling the trombone.

mastaba: An ancient Egyptian tomb with a rectangular base, sloping sides, and a flat roof.

ufology: The study of unidentified flying objects.

extraneous: Not constituting an essential or vital element or part.

cohesive: Characterized by, causing, or concerned in cohesion or the quality of adhering together, literally or figuratively: as, cohesive force.

interminable: Being or seeming to be without an end; endless: synonym:continual.

pillar: A slender, freestanding, vertical support; a column.

totalitarian: Of, relating to, being, or imposing a form of government in which the political authority exercises absolute and centralized control over all aspects of life, the individual is subordinated to the state, and opposing political and cultural expression is suppressed.

bohea: A black Chinese tea, originally the choicest grade but later an inferior variety.

heelpost: The post to which a door or gate is hinged.

ecumenism: A movement promoting unity among Christian churches or denominations.

seiche: A wave that oscillates in lakes, bays, or gulfs from a few minutes to a few hours as a result of seismic or atmospheric disturbances.

circadian: Relating to or exhibiting approximately 24-hour periodicity.

knotgrass: A low-growing, weedy grass (Paspalum distichum) with spikelets arranged in two rows along the rachis.

dogfish: Any of various small sharks chiefly of the family Squalidae, often occurring in large schools.

amygdala: Either of two small, almond-shaped masses of gray matter that are part of the limbic system and are located in the temporal lobes of the cerebral hemispheres.

codling: A balk sawed into lengths for staves.

acquisitive: Characterized by a strong desire to gain and possess.

venison: The flesh of a deer used as food.

bigos: A traditional Polish stew containing cabbage and meat

wayzgoose: a holiday or party for the benefit of printers, traditionally held in August

verbatim: Using exactly the same words; corresponding word for word.

parlor: A room in a private home set apart for the entertainment of visitors.

Edda: A collection of Old Norse poems, called the Elder or Poetic Edda, assembled in the early 1200s.

scilla: Any of several bulbous Eurasian and African plants of the genus Scilla, having narrow leaves and cultivated for their bell-shaped blue, white, or pink flowers.

steeplechase: A horserace across open country or over an obstacle course.

beguiling: Alluring by guile; deluding; misleading; diverting.

diple: In paleography, a critical mark like a Υ or Λ laid on its side , used as a mark of a paragraph, the change from one speaker to another in a drama, different readings, rejection of a reading, etc.

douche: A stream of water, often containing medicinal or cleansing agents, that is applied to a body part or cavity for hygienic or therapeutic purposes.

guppy: A small live-bearing freshwater fish (Poecilia reticulata), native to northern South America and adjacent islands of the West Indies, bred in many colorful varieties and popular in home aquariums.

lieutenant: A commissioned rank in the US Navy or Coast Guard that is above lieutenant junior grade and below lieutenant commander.

consul: An official appointed by a government to reside in a foreign country and represent his or her government's commercial interests and assist its citizens there.

torticollis: A contracted state of the neck muscles that causes the neck to rotate and tilt sideways, forwards, or backwards.

autocracy: Government by a single person having unlimited power; despotism.

liberal: Favoring reform, open to new ideas, and tolerant of the ideas and behavior of others; not bound by traditional thinking; broad-minded. synonym:broad-minded.

domesticated: tame, tamed; -- of animals. Opposite of wild.

panting: The action of one who pants; hard and hurried breathing, with heaving of the breast or sides.

laced: Fastened with a lace or laces; decorated with narrow strips or braid. See lace, v. t.

asthenosphere: A zone of the earth's mantle that lies beneath the lithosphere and consists of several hundred kilometers of deformable rock.

ridge: A long narrow upper section or crest.

cornrow: To arrange or style (hair) by dividing into sections and braiding close to the scalp in rows.

porte-bonheur: A charm, an amulet, or a trinket carried after the fashion of an amulet, suspended to a bracelet or other article of personal adornment.

chivalrous: Having the qualities of gallantry and honor attributed to an ideal knight.

gri-gri: A charm or amulet; a fetish.

baroque: Of, relating to, or characteristic of a style in art and architecture developed in Europe from the early 17th to mid-18th century, emphasizing dramatic, often strained effect and typified by bold, curving forms, elaborate ornamentation, and overall balance of disparate parts.

alumna: A woman graduate or former student of a school, college, or university.

Saint Kitts: An island in the West Indies, the northern island of the federation of Saint Kitts and Nevis.

bulse: In the East Indies, a bag or purse to carry or measure valuables; hence, a certain quantity of diamonds or other valuables.

liver: Someone who lives (usually in a specified way).

cirrhosis: A chronic disease of the liver characterized by the replacement of normal tissue with fibrous tissue and the loss of functional liver cells. It can result from alcohol abuse, nutritional deprivation, or infection especially by the hepatitis virus.

pancreas: A long, irregularly shaped gland in vertebrates, lying behind the stomach, that secretes pancreatic juice into the duodenum and insulin, glucagon, and somatostatin into the bloodstream.

solatium: Compensation for injured feelings as distinct from financial loss or physical suffering.

superannuate: To retire (someone) on a pension because of age or infirmity.

transactional: Of, pertaining to or involving transactions

assuage: To make (something burdensome or painful) less intense or severe: synonym:relieve.

peruse: To read or examine, typically with great care.

salvageable: Capable of being salvaged, saved or repaired. Worth rescuing and keeping rather discarding or replacing.

bouilli: Meat boiled with vegetables, especially in making bouillon; boiled or stewed meat of any kind.

infringe: To transgress or exceed the limits of; violate.

darn: To mend (a garment, for example) by weaving thread or yarn across a gap or hole.

beret: A round, soft, brimless cap that fits snugly and is often worn angled to one side.

éclair: An elongated pastry filled with custard or whipped cream and usually iced with chocolate.

Montenegro: A country of the western Balkan Peninsula bordering on the Adriatic Sea. An ancient Balkan state, it was at various times under Ottoman Muslim and theocratic Christian rule before becoming an independent kingdom (1910–1918). Montenegro then joined the newly formed Kingdom of the Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes, which became Yugoslavia after 1929. In 1991, four of the six Yugoslav republics declared independence, leaving Montenegro and Serbia as the sole constituents of a reorganized federal republic. Yugoslavia changed its name to Serbia and Montenegro in 2003 and dissolved the union altogether in 2006. Podgorica is the capital and largest city.

crucifix: An image or figure of Jesus on the cross.

basilican: Pertaining to or resembling a basilica; basilic.

hyaline: Resembling glass, as in translucence or transparency; glassy.

bindi: An ornamental dot traditionally worn by Hindu women in the middle of the forehead or between the eyebrows, made of colored sandalwood paste, kohl, or other pigment and having varying religious and social significance, as in indicating marital status.

varicella: A specific contagious disease, usually of childhood, characterized by an eruption of vesicles of moderate size, filled with a clear, slightly yellowish fluid; chicken-pox: swine-pox.

dba: Doing business as; used to indicate the public alias of a business legally constituted under a different name

ginnel: A narrow passageway or alley often between terraced houses.

epiphany: A Christian feast celebrating the manifestation of the divine nature of Jesus to the Gentiles as represented by the Magi, traditionally observed on January 6.

amalgamate: To combine into a unified or integrated whole; unite. synonym:mix.

boondoggle: An unnecessary or wasteful project or activity.

recidivist: In French law, a relapsed criminal; one who falls back into the same criminal course for which he has already been condemned.

diaphanous: Sufficiently thin or airy as to be translucent.

Maundy Thursday: The Thursday before Easter, observed by Christians in commemoration of the Last Supper of Jesus.

helve: A handle of a tool, such as an ax, chisel, or hammer.

anvil: A heavy block of iron or steel with a smooth, flat top on which metals are shaped by hammering.

roughhewn: Hewn coarsely without smoothing; unfinished; not polished.

bajada: In the southwestern US, a slope, specifically part of a piedmont slope made of rocky detritus.

trousseau: The possessions, such as clothing and linens, that a bride assembles for her marriage.

oakum: Loose hemp or jute fiber, sometimes treated with tar, creosote, or asphalt, used chiefly for caulking seams in wooden ships and packing pipe joints.

potpie: A pie made by lining the inner surface of a pot or pan with pastry and filling it with meat, as beef, mutton, fowl, etc., seasoning it, and then baking.

nosology: The branch of medicine that deals with the classification of diseases.

pyrheliometer: Any of various devices that measure the intensity of solar radiation received at the earth.

placate: To allay the anger of, especially by making concessions; appease. synonym:pacify.

scissure: A split or opening in an organ or part.

accoutrement: An accessory item of equipment or dress.

mensch: A person of integrity and honor.

North Korea: A country of northeast Asia on the Korean Peninsula. Inhabited since ancient times, the region was occupied by Japan from 1910 until the end of World War II in 1945. After the war the peninsula was divided into a Soviet occupation zone in the north and an American zone in the south. The territory attained its present-day boundaries after the cease-fire ending the Korean War (1950–1953). Under Kim Il Sung (ruled 1948–1994) North Korea became increasingly isolated, especially after the breakup of the Soviet Union in 1991. Pyongyang is the capital and the largest city.

ameliorate: To make or become better; improve.

praline: A confection made of nut kernels, especially almonds or pecans, stirred in boiling sugar syrup until crisp and brown.

impugned: Simple past tense and past participle of impugn.

ornithology: The branch of zoology that deals with birds.

farouche: Unsociable or shy and socially awkward.

alectryon: In ornithology, a genus of birds, proposed by Cabanis in 1846 for a section of the Macartney pheasants, genus Euplocamus of Temminck. The type is A. erythrophthalmus of Malacca.

spam: Unsolicited e-mail, often of a commercial nature, sent indiscriminately to multiple mailing lists, individuals, or newsgroups; junk e-mail.

gunsel: A hoodlum or other criminal, especially one who carries a gun.

enthusiast: One who is filled with enthusiasm; one who is ardently absorbed in an interest or pursuit.

South Korea: A country of eastern Asia at the southern end of the Korean peninsula. Korea was divided into a northern Soviet zone and a southern American zone after World War II, and Soviet resistance to reunification led to the establishment in 1948 of two separate countries, with the Korean War (1950–1953) leaving the peninsula divided along much the same line as before. Ruled until 1993 by a series of authoritarian military leaders, South Korea developed a prosperous economy on the strength of trade ties with Japan and the United States. Seoul is the capital and the largest city.

atypical: Not conforming to type; unusual or irregular.

nougat: A confection made from a sugar or honey paste into which nuts are mixed.

saphie: A West African talisman or charm.

adularescence: The chatoyancy of the adularia variety of feldspar; the moon-like sheen of the moonstone, best visible when the stone is cut with a convex dome.

drongo: A name given by Le Vaillant, in the form drongeur, to a South African bird afterward known as the musical drongo, Dicrurus musicus; then extended to the numerous African, Asiatic, and East Indian fly-catching crow-like birds with long forked tails which compose the family Dicruridæ. They are also called drongo-shrikes. The Buchanga atra of India and the further East is an example.

carpaccio: Very thinly sliced raw meat or fish, especially beef or tuna, garnished with a sauce.

overcome: To defeat (another) in competition or conflict.

stonecrop: Any of various plants of the genus Sedum and other genera such as Hylotelephium that were formerly classified in Sedum, having fleshy leaves and variously colored flowers and frequently grown in rock gardens.

people: Humans considered as a group or in indefinite numbers. Often treated as a plural of person, especially in compounds.

dinky: Of small size or consequence; insignificant.

shagreen: The rough hide of a shark or ray with embedded denticles, used as an abrasive and as leather.

bilbo: Formerly, a sword or sword-blade, famous for extreme elasticity, made in Bilbao in Spain.

zoophagan: A carnivorous animal; a sarcophagan; especially, a member of the Zoöphaga, 2.

patrix: The reverse of matrix; in calico-printing, the steel roller, or molette, on which a design is formed in relief and then transferred by pressure to the printing-roller of a cylinder printing-machine.

talisman: An object marked with magic signs and believed to confer on its bearer supernatural powers or protection.

amadelphous: Living in society or in flocks; gregarious.

dysmorphology: The study of genetic defects, especially congenital malformations

internationalized: Simple past tense and past participle of internationalize.

misprision: An act of undervaluing or disdaining; scorn; contempt.

kenning: A figurative, usually compound expression used in place of a name or noun, especially in Old English and Old Norse poetry; for example, storm of swords is a kenning for battle.

fortuitous: Happening by accident or chance. synonym:accidental.

listless: Lacking energy or disinclined to exert effort; lethargic.

precipice: An overhanging or extremely steep mass of rock, such as a crag or the face of a cliff.

aurora: A luminous atmospheric phenomenon appearing as streamers or bands of light sometimes visible in the night sky in northern or southern regions of the earth. It is thought to be caused by charged particles from the sun entering the earth's magnetic field and stimulating molecules in the atmosphere.

gobstopper: A type of hard long-lasting candy, usually spherical in shape.

nonproliferation: Of, relating to, or calling for an end to the acquisition of nuclear weapons by additional nations.

irk: To be irritating, wearisome, or vexing to. synonym:annoy.

Saint Croix: An island of the US Virgin Islands in the West Indies east of Puerto Rico. Sighted and named by Columbus in 1493, it was controlled successively by Holland, England, Spain, France, and Denmark, which sold it to the United States in 1917.

ingle: An open fire in a fireplace.

curassow: Any of several long-tailed, crested South and Central American game birds of the family Cracidae, related to the pheasants and domestic fowl.

concierge: A staff member of a hotel or apartment complex who assists guests or residents, as by handling the storage of luggage, taking and delivering messages, and making reservations for tours.

proteinaceous: Resembling, containing, or consisting of protein. Also proteinous.

flaneur: An idle, gossiping saunterer; one who habitually strolls about idly.

lycaon: A name of the constellation Boötes (which see).

reskins: Third-person singular simple present indicative form of reskin.

Boötes: A constellation in the Northern Hemisphere near Virgo and Canes Venatici, containing the bright star Arcturus. Boötes is one of the earliest recorded constellations.

Crater: A constellation in the Southern Hemisphere near Hydra and Corvus.

southerner: A native or inhabitant of the south, especially the southern United States.

omnicide: The total extinction of the human species as a result of human action. Most commonly it refers to human extinction through nuclear warfare, but it can also refer to such extinction through other means such as global anthropogenic ecological catastrophe and Lethargica

complicit: Associated with or participating in a questionable act or a crime; having complicity.

carnivalesque: Pertaining to or resembling a carnival; suitable to or in keeping with a carnival.

addictionology: The study and treatment of addiction.

contemn: To view with contempt; despise. synonym:despise.

immortelle: Any of several coral trees, especially Erythrina fusca or E. poeppigiana.

dermatologist: One who is versed in dermatology.

petroleum: A thick, flammable, yellow-to-black mixture of gaseous, liquid, and solid hydrocarbons that occurs naturally beneath the earth's surface, can be separated into fractions including natural gas, gasoline, naphtha, kerosene, fuel and lubricating oils, paraffin wax, and asphalt and is used as raw material for a wide variety of derivative products.

anthropologist: One who studies or is versed in anthropology.

anthropology: The scientific study of the origin, the behavior, and the physical, social, and cultural development of humans.

emptiness: The state of being empty; the state of containing nothing, or nothing but air: as, the emptiness of a vessel.

idiolect: The speech of an individual, considered as a linguistic pattern unique among speakers of his or her language or dialect.

surveyor: A common name in Australia for a fish, Serranus geometricus.

hypotenuse: The side of a right triangle opposite the right angle.

adamantium: A fictional metal that is indestructible or nearly so.

Burkina Faso: A landlocked country of western Africa. It was a French protectorate from 1896 until 1960, when it gained its independence. The name of the country was officially changed in 1984. Ouagadougou is the capital and the largest city.

dun: An almost neutral brownish gray to dull grayish brown.

amaranthine: Of, relating to, or resembling an amaranth.

escapade: An adventurous, unconventional act or undertaking.

anthozoa: The flower-animals, or animal-flowers; a former class or large group of zoöphytes, inexactly equivalent to the modern class Actinozoa (which see).

orchestrion: A large mechanical instrument resembling a barrel organ that produces sound in imitation of an orchestra.

Monterrey: A city of northeast Mexico west of Matamoros. Founded in 1596, the city was captured (September 1846) by Zachary Taylor's forces during the Mexican War.

zinc: A bluish-white, lustrous metallic element that is brittle at room temperature but malleable with heating. It is used to form a wide variety of alloys including brass, bronze, various solders, and nickel silver, in galvanizing iron and other metals, for electric fuses, anodes, meter cases and batteries, and in roofing, gutters, and various household objects. US pennies minted after 1982 consist of a copper-clad zinc core. Atomic number 30; atomic weight 65.38; melting point 419.53°C; boiling point 907°C; specific gravity 7.134 (at 25°C); valence 2. cross-reference:Periodic Table.

chondrus: A rounded mass, or spherule, consisting of a single crystal of some mineral, or of an aggregate of several crystalline fragments of different minerals, often more or less mingled with a glassy base.

pashmina: Fine, downy wool growing beneath the outer hair of Himalayan goats.

cui bono: Utility, advantage, or self-interest considered as the determinant of value or motivation.

acephalous: Headless or lacking a clearly defined head.

simian: Relating to, characteristic of, or resembling a monkey or an ape.

spanakopita: A Greek spinach pie made with layers of phyllo and a filling of seasoned spinach, onions, feta, and sometimes eggs.

flokati: A woven, usually woolen area rug with a long, soft pile, traditionally of Greek origin.

fustian: A coarse sturdy cloth made of cotton and linen or flax.

wykehamist: A student, or one who has been a student, of Winchester College in England, founded by William of Wykeham (1324–1404), Bishop of Winchester and Chancellor of England, as a preparatory school for New College at Oxford, also founded by him. Also used attributively.

raven: Plunder; rapine; robbery; rapacity; furious violence.

titubate: To stumble; trip; stagger; reel; rock or roll.

shigellosis: Dysentery caused by any of various species of shigellae, occurring most frequently in areas where poor sanitation and malnutrition are prevalent and commonly affecting children and infants.

baccarat: A card game in which the winner is the player who holds two or three cards totaling closest to nine.

US Virgin Islands: A group of islands in the Caribbean that is a dependency of the United States. Official name: Virgin Islands of the United States.

morpheme: A meaningful linguistic unit that cannot be divided into smaller meaningful parts. The word man and the suffix -ed (as in walked) are morphemes.

oweth: Third-person singular simple present indicative form of owe.

simplism: The tendency to oversimplify an issue or a problem by ignoring complexities or complications.

jostle: To come in rough contact while moving; push and shove.

Lesser Antilles: An island group of the eastern West Indies extending in an arc from Aruba to the Virgin Islands.

corncrib: A structure for storing and drying ears of corn.

quiaquia: small fusiform fish of western Atlantic

Xe: A chemical symbol of xenon: less commonly used than X.

brute: An animal other than a human; a beast.

rapacious: Having or showing a strong or excessive desire to acquire money or possess things; greedy.

arbor: Literally, a tree: used in this sense chiefly in botanical names.

biographical: Containing, consisting of, or relating to the facts or events in a person's life.

camarasaurus: A genus of colossal dinosaurian reptiles, from the Cretaceous formation Of Dakota.

harpoon: A spearlike weapon with a barbed head used in hunting whales and large fish.

choon: A song or track, especially one that is catchy.

agglutinative: Tending or having power to agglutinate or unite; having power to cause adhesion: as, an agglutinative substance.

crottin: A pungent cheese made of goat's milk and formed into small disks.

Homo sapien: A member of the species Homo sapiens.

insomnia: Chronic inability to fall asleep or remain asleep for an adequate length of time.

unanimously: With one mind or voice; with unanimity.

idolum: Appearance or image; a phantasm; a spectral image; also, a mental image or idea.

ravelin: A detached triangular work in fortification, with two embankments which form a projecting angle.

steward: One who manages another's property, finances, or other affairs.

archbishop: A bishop of the highest rank, heading an archdiocese or province.

kiddingly: In a kidding manner; jestingly, jokingly.

squail: A disk or counter used in the game of squails.

ailurophilia: A fondness or love for cats or other felines.

furoshiki: A traditional Japanese wrapping-cloth, used for clothes, gifts etc.

netsuke: A small toggle, often in the form of a carved ivory or wood figure, used to secure a purse or container suspended on a cord from the sash of a kimono.

menopausal: Of, or pertaining to the menopause

microphthalmia: An abnormal smallness of the eye. Also microphthalmy.

hetaera: An ancient Greek courtesan or concubine, especially one who was highly educated or refined.

foundling: A deserted or abandoned child of unknown parentage.

scour: To search through or over thoroughly.

vendace: Either of two small whitefishes, Coregonus albula of northern Europe or C. vandesius of England and Scotland.

isogloss: A geographic boundary line delimiting the area in which a given linguistic feature occurs.

vigil: A watch kept during normal sleeping hours.

journeying: the act or process of traveling from one place to another.

equilibrist: A person who performs feats of balance, such as tightrope walking.

ayin: The 16th letter of the Hebrew alphabet.

quinine: A bitter, colorless, amorphous powder or crystalline alkaloid, C20H24N2O2·3H2O, derived from certain cinchona barks and used in medicine to treat malaria.

frenetic: Wildly excited or active; frantic; frenzied.

iota: The ninth letter of the Greek alphabet.

recidivism: The repeating of or returning to criminal behavior by the same offender or type of offender.

bout: A contest between antagonists; a match.

antidromic: flowing in the opposite direction from normal

impede: To retard or obstruct the progress of. synonym:hinder.

datum: A fact or proposition used to draw a conclusion or make a decision.

alumnus: A male graduate or former student of a school, college, or university.

opus: A creative work, especially a musical composition numbered to designate the order of a composer's works.

alloy: A metallic solid or liquid that is composed of a homogeneous mixture of two or more metals or of metals and nonmetal or metalloid elements, usually for the purpose of imparting or increasing specific characteristics or properties.

era: A period of time as reckoned from a specific date serving as the basis of its chronological system.

abidance: The act or condition of abiding; continuance.

posnet: A small basin or porringer; also, a small vessel of fanciful form.

pernicious: Tending to cause death or serious injury; deadly.

ninepin: A bowling game in which nine wooden pins are the target.

amici curiae: People/entities who have been allowed by the court to plead or make submissions but who, however, are not directly involved in the action.

heterological: Of an adjective, not describing itself.

existence: The fact or state of existing; being.

couponing: The use or distribution of money-saving coupons.

epoch: A particular period of history, especially one considered remarkable or noteworthy.

overvote: A ballot showing the selection of more candidates or choices than are allowed in a given race or referendum.

maritime: Of, relating to, or adjacent to the sea.

acromegaly: A chronic disease of adults marked by enlargement of the bones of the extremities, face, and jaw that is caused by overactivity of the pituitary gland.

peen: The end of a hammerhead opposite the flat striking surface, often wedge-shaped or ball-shaped and used for chipping, indenting, and metalworking.

affogato: A drink or dessert topped with espresso, and sometimes also with caramel sauce or chocolate sauce

charwoman: A woman hired to do cleaning or similar work, usually in a large building.

aesthetically: In an aesthetic manner; with a pleasing sensory effect.

chronological: Arranged in order of time of occurrence.

occult: Of, relating to, or dealing with supernatural or magical influences, agencies, or occurrences.

vallum: A name given, incorrectly, to a ditch with earthworks on either side, which follows the line of Hadrian's wall in northern England. See the extract.

interhemispheric: Situated between two hemispheres; specifically, between the two cerebral hemispheres.

figurine: A small molded or sculptured figure; a statuette.

insistent: Firm in asserting a demand or an opinion; unyielding.

cabecera: In the Philippine Islands, a provincial capital.

aparejo: A packsaddle made of a stuffed leather pad.

meringue: A topping for pastry or pies made of a mixture of egg whites and sugar beaten until stiff and often baked until brown.

thutter: To make a dull, vibrating sound. See the extract.

mosque: A building used as a place of Muslim worship.

adoxography: Good writing on a minor subject.

capuchin: A monk belonging to the Order of Friars Minor Capuchin, an independent order of Franciscans founded in Italy in 1525–1528 and dedicated to preaching and missionary work.

sajou: A South American monkey, or sai, one of several kinds also called sapajou. See sapajou, and synonyms under saguin.

alleviate: To make (pain, for example) less intense or more bearable: synonym:relieve.

uninominal: Relating to one name only. See the extract.

galingale: Any of various sedges of the genus Cyperus, especially C. longus of Europe, having rough-edged leaves, reddish spikelets, and aromatic roots.

acclimation: The process of acclimating or of becoming acclimated.

cryovolcanism: The activity, and associated phenomena, of a cryovolcano

electroporation: A process of applying a high-voltage electrical pulse to a living cell, causing temporary permeability of the cell membrane, through which a foreign material such as DNA may pass.

cellulase: Any of several enzymes produced chiefly by fungi, bacteria, and protozoans that catalyze the hydrolysis of cellulose.

technography: The description and study of arts and industries in their ethnic distribution and historic development.

ectodermal: Pertaining to the ectoderm; consisting of ectoderm: as, the ectodermal layer of a cœlenterate.

anoxygenic: That does not involve the production of oxygen

boustrophedon: An ancient method of writing in which the lines are inscribed alternately from right to left and from left to right.

panchayat: An elected village council in India.

altazimuth: A mounting for astronomical telescopes that permits pointing adjustments in both altitude and azimuth.

sympatric: Occupying the same or overlapping geographic areas. Used of organisms, especially populations of the same or closely related species.

stridulous: Characterized by or making a shrill grating sound or noise.

apteryx: A genus of ratite birds, constituting the family Apterygidœ.

coendoo: A name of the prehensile-tailed porcupine of Brazil, Synetheres or Cercolabes prchensilis.

impromptu: Prompted by the occasion rather than being planned in advance.

angwantibo: The slow lemur of Old Calabar, Arctocebus calabarensis, of the subfamily Nycticebinæ, related to the potto, and by some referred to the genus Perodicticus.

vernacular: The everyday language spoken by a people as distinguished from the literary language.

cloop: The sound made when a cork is pulled out of the neck of a bottle.

internationalism: The condition or quality of being international in character, principles, concern, or attitude.

antimony: A metallic element having two allotropic forms: a hard, extremely brittle, lustrous, bluish-white, crystalline material and a gray amorphous form. It is used in a wide variety of alloys, especially with lead in battery plates, and in the manufacture of flame-proofing compounds, paint, semiconductor devices, and ceramic products. Atomic number 51; atomic weight 121.76; melting point 630.63°C; boiling point 1,587°C; specific gravity 6.68; valence 3, 5. cross-reference:Periodic Table.

platitude: A trite or banal remark or statement, especially one expressed as if it were original or significant. synonym:cliché.

systemized: Simple past tense and past participle of systemize.

saleratus: Sodium or potassium bicarbonate used as a leavening agent; baking soda.

Acanthocephala: An order of worm-like internal parasites or entozoa, which have neither mouth nor alimentary canal, but have recurved hooks on a retractile proboscis at the anterior end of the body, by which they attach themselves to the tissues of animals.

Diophantine: Of or pertaining to Diophantus, the Greek mathematician.

scrutinize: To examine or observe with great care; inspect critically.

anomalogonatous: Abnormally kneed; having no ambiens muscle; specifically, pertaining to or resembling the Anomalogonatœ.

patella: A flat triangular bone located at the front of the knee joint.

orthopedic: Of, pertaining to, or employed in, orthopedics; relating to the prevention or cure of deformities of children, or, in general, of the human body at any age

albuminimeter: An instrument for measuring the quantity of albumin contained in any liquid.

atherosclerosis: A form of arteriosclerosis characterized by the deposition of atheromatous plaques containing cholesterol and lipids on the innermost layer of the walls of large and medium-sized arteries.

prose: Ordinary speech or writing, without metrical structure.

hone: A fine-grained whetstone for giving a keen edge to a cutting tool.

Utah: A state of the western United States. It was admitted as the 45th state in 1896. Explored by the Spanish in 1540, the region was settled in 1847 by Mormons led by Brigham Young. Salt Lake City is the capital and the largest city.

fernbird: An insectivorous bird native to New Zealand, with scientific name Bowdleria punctata.

gremolata: A mixture of chopped parsley, lemon rind, and garlic, used as a garnish for osso buco and other dishes.

killdeer: A New World plover (Charadrius vociferus) that has a distinctive noisy cry and two black bands across its breast.

spital: A hospital, especially one for patients with contagious diseases.

risoluto: In music, with resolution or firmness.

utahraptor: large (20-ft) and swift carnivorous dinosaur having an upright slashing claw 15 inches long on each hind foot; early Cretaceous

logorrhoea: An excessive and often uncontrollable flow of words.

foray: A sudden raid or military advance.

tattoo: In India, a native-bred pony or small horse. Also, by abbreviation, tat. See tat.

pidgin: A simplified form of speech that is usually a mixture of two or more languages, has a rudimentary grammar and vocabulary, is used for communication between groups speaking different languages, and is not spoken as a first or native language.

degreaser: An industrial solvent, often containing polyhalogenated hydrocarbons, used to remove grease from mechanical parts

socius: An associate; a member or fellow, as of a sodality, an academy, or an institution of learning.

ephebic: Of or pertaining to an ephebe, or to the ancient Greek system of public instruction of young men to fit them for the duties and privileges of citizenship.

baroqueness: The state or condition of being baroque.

adolesce: To commence or progress through adolescence.

newspeak: Deliberately ambiguous and contradictory language used to mislead and manipulate the public.

preclude: To make impossible, as by action taken in advance; prevent. synonym:prevent.

opportune: Suited or right for a particular purpose.

eponymous: Of, relating to, or constituting an eponym.

absorption: The act or process of absorbing or the condition of being absorbed.

sagamore: A subordinate chief among the Algonquians of North America.

abomasum: The fourth division of the stomach in ruminant animals, such as cows, sheep, and deer, in which digestion takes place.

lambie: A little lamb; a lambkin. Also lammie.

collision: An act of colliding; a crash.

androconia: Certain specialized scales oscurring in limited areas on the wings of the males of certain Lepidoptera.

bogong: An Australian noctuid moth, Agrotis spina, which occurs in enormous numbers in Victoria, where the hibernating adults were eaten by the aborigines.

perpetuity: The quality or condition of being perpetual.

Curaçao: An island territory of the Netherlands in the southern Caribbean Sea off the northwest coast of Venezuela. Originally inhabited by the Arawak, it was settled by the Spanish in 1527. The Dutch gained control in 1634, although the British held the island during the Napoleonic Wars (1807–1815). Oil refining and tourism are the major industries.

habeas corpus: A writ that a person may seek from a court to obtain immediate release from an unlawful confinement, as when the confinement has occurred through a means that violated the person's constitutional rights.

metalanguage: A language or vocabulary used to describe or analyze language.

siker: Middle English spellings of sicker, sickerly, sickerness.

olibanum: A gum-resin yielded by trees of the genus Boswellia in the Somali country.

middlescence: The period or condition of middle age, especially as a time of transition comparable to adolescence.

enigmatic: Of or resembling an enigma; puzzling: synonym:mysterious.

antepenultimate: Coming before the next to the last in a series.

catamount: The cat of the mountain; the European wildcat.

immigrant: A person who leaves one country to settle permanently in another.

embrocation: The act or process of moistening and rubbing a part of the body with a liniment or lotion.

contemporaneous: Originating, existing, or happening during the same period of time: synonym:contemporary.

Alcmene: Amphitryon's wife, who gave birth to Hercules after being seduced by Zeus.

integrity: Steadfast adherence to a strict moral or ethical code.

refute: To prove to be false or erroneous; overthrow by argument or proof.

barm: The yeasty foam that rises to the surface of fermenting malt liquors.

gibberish: Unintelligible or nonsensical talk or writing.

buffoonery: The art and practices of a buffoon; low jests; ridiculous pranks; vulgar tricks and postures.

Austenesque: Reminiscent of the works of Jane Austen (1775-1817), English novelist noted for realism and biting social commentary.

roulade: An embellishment consisting of a rapid run of several notes sung to one syllable.

myrtle: Any of several evergreen shrubs or trees of the genus Myrtus, especially M. communis, an aromatic shrub native to the Mediterranean region, having white flowers and blue-black berries and widely cultivated as a hedge plant.

ersatz: Being a usually inferior imitation or substitute; artificial.

isere: a river in southeastern France; a tributary of the Rhone

tiro: The more correct spelling of tyro.

triarch: In botany, having three centripetally developed xylem plates: said of vascular cylinders.

amphoteric: Having the characteristics of an acid and a base and capable of reacting chemically either as an acid or a base.

monoski: A type of snowboard in the form of a wide ski

Bahia: State in northeastern Brazil which has Salvador as its capital.

corvine: Of, resembling, or characteristic of crows.

tempo: The speed at which music is or ought to be played, often indicated on written compositions by a descriptive or metronomic direction to the performer.

gummi: A sugary, gelatinous material used to make candies.

frankfurter: A smoked sausage of beef or beef and pork made in long reddish links.

dachshund: A dog of a small breed developed in Germany for hunting badgers, having a long body, a brown or black-and-brown coat, drooping ears, and very short legs. Dachshunds are bred in long-haired, smooth-coat, wire-haired, and miniature varieties, sometimes considered separate breeds.

bough: A tree branch, especially a large or main branch.

theocracy: Government ruled by or subject to religious authority.

oligarchy: Government by a few, especially by a small faction of persons or families.

pomato: A fruit said to be the result of amalgamation of the potato and tomato, produced by Luther Burbank. It is a small tomato-like fruit, with white flesh, edible either raw or cooked.

hapkido: An eclectic Korean martial art founded by Young Sul Choi, a student of Daitō-ryū Aiki-jūjutsu.

tai chi: A Chinese martial art whose system of physical exercises is often practiced as a way of meditating or improving well-being.

presage: An indication or warning of a future occurrence; an omen.

crocodilian: Any of various reptiles of the order Crocodylia (or Crocodilia), which includes the alligators, the crocodiles, the caimans, and the gharial.

amorous: Full of or strongly disposed to romantic love.

brachypterous: Having short or rudimentary wings, as certain insects.

arbitrate: To judge or decide in or as in the manner of an arbitrator.

recusal: An act of recusing. To remove oneself from a decision/judgment because of a conflict of interest.

equator: The imaginary great circle around the earth's surface, equidistant from the poles and perpendicular to the earth's axis of rotation. It divides the earth into the Northern Hemisphere and the Southern Hemisphere.

unavowed: Not avowed or openly acknowledged: as, unavowed dislike.

cajole: To persuade by flattery, gentle pleading, or insincere language.

Tampico: A city of east-central Mexico near the Gulf of Mexico north-northeast of Mexico City. Settled by the Spanish in the 1530s, it is a major port, manufacturing center, and tourist resort.

effluvium: A usually invisible emanation or exhalation, as of vapor or gas.

cathect: To invest emotional energy in (a person, object, or idea).

Ash Wednesday: The seventh Wednesday before Easter and the first day of Lent, on which many Christians receive a mark of ashes on the forehead as a token of penitence and mortality.

tout: To promote or praise energetically; publicize.

palestra: A public place in ancient Greece for training and practice in wrestling and other athletics.

barrow-tram: The tram or shaft of a wheelbarrow; hence, jocularly, a raw-boned fellow.

Mardi Gras: Shrove Tuesday, celebrated as a holiday in many places with carnivals, masquerade balls, and parades of costumed merrymakers.

sophistication: The act or process of sophisticating.

consumer: One that consumes, especially one that acquires goods or services for direct use or ownership rather than for resale or use in production and manufacturing.

Desi: Of or pertaining to the culture, people, or products of India; Indian.

moonlight: The light reflected from the surface of the moon.

mezzeria: In Italy, a system of halving the produce of the soil between landowner and landholder: same as metayage. See the extract.

funk: A state of cowardly fright; a panic.

amor: Love; affection; friendship; especially, love toward one of the opposite sex: now only in the form amour (which see).

armor: A defensive covering, as of metal, wood, or leather, worn to protect the body against weapons.

shunpike: A side road taken to avoid the tolls or traffic of a turnpike.

fleecy: Of, resembling, or covered with fleece.

quintessence: The pure, highly concentrated essence of a thing.

offend: To cause displeasure, anger, resentment, or wounded feelings in.

astatki: The residuum from the distillation of Russian petroleum after the more volatile hydrocarbons, up to and including kerosene or illuminating oil, have been driven off.

laminitis: Inflammation of the sensitive laminae of the hoof, especially in horses.

inotropic: Affecting the contraction of muscle, especially heart muscle.

Panama: A country of southeast Central America. The region was inhabited by a variety of Indian peoples when Columbus landed on its Caribbean coast in 1502. In 1513 Balboa crossed the Isthmus of Panama to reach the Pacific Ocean. Controlled by Spain until 1821, the area then became part of Colombia. Eager for a canal across the isthmus, the United States supported a revolution leading to Panamanian independence in 1903. Panama is the capital.

coltish: Relating to or suggestive of a colt.

wimi: Sacred objects, supposed to possess magical powers, belonging to the various clans and religious societies among the Hopi. These objects are used in the construction of the ponya, or altar, and include tiponis, effigies of the gods, and other objects.

conjugal: Of or relating to marriage or the relationship of spouses.

excrescence: An outgrowth or enlargement, especially an abnormal one, such as a wart.

posada: A Christmas festival originating in Latin America that dramatizes the search of Joseph and Mary for lodging.

inanition: Exhaustion, as from lack of nourishment or vitality.

croustade: A molded or hollowed bowllike crust, as of pastry, rice, or bread, used as a serving container for another food.

buskin: A foot and leg covering reaching halfway to the knee, resembling a laced half boot.

aggravation: The act of aggravating or the state of being aggravated.

alimony: An allowance for support made under court order to a divorced person by the former spouse, usually the chief provider during the marriage. Alimony may also be granted without a divorce, as between legally separated persons.

culdoscopy: Endoscopy of the female pelvic organs by way of the vagina.

insertion: The act or process of inserting.

fool-hen: A grouse, especially the young bird. See the extract.

cabré: In heraldry, represented as rearing: said of a horse.

beastie: An animal, especially one regarded with jocular affection.

finesse: Refinement and delicacy of performance, execution, or artisanship.

spelunker: One who explores caves chiefly as a hobby; a caver.

monogamous: Practising or supporting the principle of monogamy.

quaigh: A shallow drinking-cup, made of small staves hooped together: it is usually of wood, but sometimes of silver.

monograph: A scholarly piece of writing of essay or book length on a specific, often limited subject.

eddish: The pasture or grass that comes after mowing or reaping.

bejewelled: Simple past tense and past participle of bejewel.

amoeba: Any of various one-celled free-living or parasitic protozoans having no definite form and moving by means of pseudopods.

pho: A soup of Vietnamese origin typically consisting of rice noodles, onions, herbs, seasonings, and thinly sliced beef or chicken in a clear broth.

acarophobia: An abnormal fear of mites, other small insects, or worms.

Dominican Republic: A country of the West Indies on the eastern part of the island of Hispaniola. Originally inhabited by Arawaks, it was claimed for Spain by Christopher Columbus in 1492 and remained a Spanish colony until 1795, when it was ceded to France. Ruled by Haiti after 1821, the country became independent in 1844 but has had a turbulent history, including many years of dictatorship under Rafael Trujillo Molina (1930–1961). Santo Domingo is the capital and the largest city.

zany: Comical or ludicrous because of incongruity or strangeness.

deployed: Simple past tense and past participle of deploy.

deploy: To position (troops) in readiness for combat, as along a front or line.

dudgeon: A feeling of offense; resentmont; sullen anger; ill will; discord.

Luddite: Any of a group of British workers who between 1811 and 1816 rioted and destroyed laborsaving textile machinery in the belief that such machinery would diminish employment.

excursive: Of, given to, characterized by, or having the nature of digression.

pederasty: Unnatural carnal union of males with males, especially boys.

psyche: In classical mythology, the personified and deified soul or spirit, the beloved of Eros, by whom she was alternately caressed and tormented.

anti-semitism: The agitation conducted by the Anti-Semites or its motives; antagonism to the Jews.

snotter: To breathe through an obstruction in the nostrils; blubber; sob; cry.

haggard: Exhausted or distraught and often gaunt in appearance.

electrode: A solid electric conductor through which an electric current enters or leaves an electrolytic cell or other medium.

dynasty: A succession of rulers from the same family or line.

Neckar: A river of southwest Germany rising in the Black Forest and flowing about 360 km (225 mi) generally north and west to the Rhine River at Mannheim.

stimulant: An agent, especially a chemical agent such as caffeine, that temporarily arouses or accelerates physiological or organic activity.

jalousie: A blind or shutter having adjustable horizontal slats for regulating the passage of air and light.

morphology: The branch of biology that deals with the form and structure of organisms without consideration of function.

tamarin: Any of various small, long-tailed, arboreal monkeys of the genera Leontopithecus and Saguinus of Central and South America, closely related to and resembling the marmosets but having a larger body, longer limbs, and lower canines that extend well beyond the incisors.

carpo: An element in certain compound words, meaning fruit.

rhea: Either of two large flightless South American birds, Rhea americana or R. pennata (syn. Pterocnemia pennata), having gray-brown plumage, a long neck and legs, and three-toed feet.

tachycardia: A rapid heart rate, especially one above 100 beats per minute in an adult.

leister: A three-pronged spear used in fishing.

iolite: A silicate of magnesium, aluminium, and iron, a mineral of a violet-blue color with a shade of purple or black.

stuporous: Characterized by stupor; having stupor as a conspicuous symptom.

locomote: To move from one place to another.

onomatopoeia: The formation or use of words such as buzz or murmur that imitate the sounds associated with the objects or actions they refer to.

kindergarchy: The state or phenomenon of children dominating, particularly in the context of children's needs, wishes, and preferences being accorded equal or greater status than those of adults.

fauxmance: A fake romance between celebrities, arranged for publicity.

trochilidine: Of or pertaining to the Trochilidæ or humming-birds: as, trochilidine literature.

zyzzyva: Any of several tropical American weevils of the genus Zyzzyva.

dervish: A member of any of various Muslim ascetic orders, some of which perform whirling dances and vigorous chanting as acts of ecstatic devotion.

anomie: Social instability caused by erosion of standards and values.

phreatophyte: A plant, often with deep roots, that is mostly or entirely dependent on water from a permanent ground supply.

ibex: Any of several wild goats of the genus Capra, especially C. ibex, native to mountainous regions of Eurasia and northern Africa, and having long, ridged, backward-curving horns.

cachet: A mark or quality, as of distinction, individuality, or authenticity.

Ojibwa: A member of a Native American people originally located north of Lake Huron before moving westward in the 1600s and 1700s into Michigan, Wisconsin, Minnesota, western Ontario, and Manitoba, with later migrations onto the northern Great Plains in North Dakota, Montana, and Saskatchewan.

hist: A sibilant utterance used to attract attention and command or suggest silence.

tarragon: An aromatic Eurasian herb (Artemisia dracunculus) in the composite family, having linear to lance-shaped leaves and small whitish-green flower heads arranged in loose spreading panicles.

jurat: A clause attached to an affidavit, in which a notary or legally authorized officer attests to the fact that the affidavit was made under oath.

ruse: A crafty stratagem; a subterfuge. synonym:wile.

pietà: An image or figure of the Virgin Mary holding and mourning over the dead body of Jesus.

neutral: Not aligned with, supporting, or favoring either side in a war, dispute, or contest.

estate: A landed property, usually of considerable size.

infantry: The branch of an army made up of units trained to fight on foot.

sine die: Without a day specified for a future meeting; indefinitely.

Byronesque: Reminiscent of the works of George Gordon Byron, typified by gloomy Romantic themes and passionate, arrogant and self-destructive heroes.

monogamy: The practice or condition of having a single sexual partner during a period of time.

isostasy: Equilibrium in the earth's crust such that the forces tending to elevate landmasses balance the forces tending to depress landmasses.

curmudgeon: An ill-tempered person full of resentment and stubborn notions.

mellifluous: Having a pleasant and fluid sound.

amaurosis: Total loss of vision, especially when occurring without pathological changes to the eye.

squirrel: Any of various arboreal rodents of the tribe Sciurini and especially of the genus Sciurus, characteristically having a long flexible bushy tail.

tomato: A widely cultivated plant (Solanum lycopersicum syn. Lycopersicon esculentum) in the nightshade family, having edible, fleshy, usually red fruit. Tomatoes are native to and were first domesticated in northern South America.

foodie: One who has an ardent or refined interest in food; a gourmet.

marmoreal: Resembling marble, as in smoothness, whiteness, or hardness.

domiciliation: The state of being domiciliated; inhabitancy.

nugget: A small, solid lump, especially of gold.

administrivia: The mundane details involved in running an organization or executing a process.

gynephobia: Hatred of women; repugnance to the society of women.

substrate: The material or substance on which an enzyme acts.

svelte: Slender or graceful in figure or outline; slim.

privilege: A special advantage, immunity, permission, right, or benefit granted to or enjoyed by an individual, class, or caste. synonym:right.

phototropic: Of, pertaining to, or exhibiting phototropism or phototropy.

hawfinch: A bird (Coccothraustes coccothraustes) of Eurasia and North Africa having a thick bill, a short white-tipped tail, and brown, white, and black plumage.

consociation: Friendly or cooperative association, as between groups or organizations.

agog: Full of keen anticipation or excitement; eager.

conversant: Familiar or knowledgeable, as by study or experience.

chastise: To punish, as for wrongdoing. synonym:punish.

escalate: To increase in intensity, extent, or amount.

bork: To defeat a judicial nomination through a concerted attack on the nominee's character, background and philosophy.

transpontine: Situated on the other side of a bridge.

pedagogy: The art or profession of teaching.

Dicksonia: A genus of ferns having large, much-divided fronds, and small sori placed close to the margin of the frond at the apex of a vein.

decennary: Of or relating to a ten-year period.

exhibition: The act or an instance of exhibiting.

propagation: Multiplication or increase, as by natural reproduction.

nervine: Of or pertaining to the nerves.

tune: A melody, especially a simple and easily remembered one.

scabrid: In botany, slightly rough to the touch: as, a scabrid leaf. Compare scabrous.

corroborate: To strengthen or support with other evidence; make more certain. synonym:confirm.

stearate: A salt or ester of stearic acid.

maenad: A woman member of the orgiastic cult of Dionysus.

epenthesis: The insertion of a sound in the middle of a word, as in Middle English thunder from Old English thunor.

kanzu: A long, usually white garment worn by men in Africa.

monera: Haeckel's name of a class of protozoans of the simplest possible characters.

protista: One of the kingdoms of animated nature, which Haeckel proposed (1868) to include the Protozoa and the Protophyta, or the lowest animals and plants as collectively distinguished from other organisms.

moss: Any of various green, usually small, nonvascular plants of the division Bryophyta, having leaflike structures arranged around the stem and spores borne in a capsule.

algae: A division of thallogenous chlorophyllous cryptogams found for the most part in the sea (seaweeds) or in fresh water.

diatom: Any of various microscopic one-celled or colonial heterokonts of the class Bacillariophyceae that are photosynthetic, have a silica cell wall made up of two interlocking parts, and form an important component of phytoplankton.

plantae: (botany) the taxonomic kingdom comprising all living or extinct plants

salutary: Effecting or designed to effect an improvement; remedial.

gargantua: A person of great size or stature and of voracious physical or intellectual appetites.

guisarme: A long-handled weapon resembling the pole-ax, or in some cases more nearly resembling the halberd, but having a long edge for cutting and a straight sharp point in the line of the handle. By some authors it is confounded with the pole-ax.

animalia: Animals as a grand division of nature; the animal kingdom (which see, under animal).

dracaena: Any of several tropical plants of the genera Dracaena and Cordyline cultivated as house plants for their sword-shaped sometimes variegated leaves.

edentata: In mammalogy, a Cuvierian order of mammals; the edentates.

sloth: Aversion to work or exertion; laziness; indolence.

appendage: Something added or attached to an entity of greater importance or size; an adjunct. synonym:attachment.

clasp: A fastening, such as a hook or buckle, used to hold two or more objects or parts together.

paravent: A wind-screen; a shelter from wind.

hyperbaton: A figure of speech that uses deviation from normal or logical word order for rhetorical effect, as in anastrophe or hysteron proteron.

unconstitutional: In violation of the requirements of the constitution of a nation or state.

disgorge: To bring up and expel from the throat or stomach; vomit.

Mrs. Grundy: An extremely conventional or priggish person.

troglodyte: A member of a fabulous or prehistoric race of people that lived in caves, dens, or holes.

protean: Readily taking on varied shapes, forms, or meanings.

chelydridae: a natural family comprising the snapping turtles.

gubbins: Assorted stuff, especially if of little value

bovarism: An imagined or unrealistic conception of oneself

sprezzatura: The art of performing a difficult task so gracefully, that it looks effortless.

scrubs: A protective plastic gown worn by a surgeon when performing surgery.

Narragansett: A member of an Algonquian Native American tribe that formerly inhabited the shores of Narragansett Bay.

grudge: To be reluctant to give or admit.

theremin: An electronic instrument played by moving the hands near its two antennas, often used for high tremolo effects.

cruse: A small earthenware container, such as a pot or jar, for holding liquids.

militate: To have force or influence; bring about an effect or a change.

mutiny: Open rebellion against constituted authority, especially rebellion of sailors against superior officers.

acetaminophen: A crystalline compound, C8H9NO2, used in medicine to relieve pain and reduce fever.

plagiarism: The act or behavior of plagiarizing.

malleable: Capable of being shaped or formed, as by hammering or pressure.

bioregionalism: The belief that social organization and environmental policies should be based on bioregions rather than on arbitrary political boundaries.

extremophile: Any of various organisms that require extreme conditions of temperature, pressure, or chemical concentration, as in very cold or salty environments, in order to thrive.

bloat: To cause to swell up or inflate, as with liquid or gas.

New England: A region of the northeast United States consisting of Maine, New Hampshire, Vermont, Massachusetts, Connecticut, and Rhode Island.

erosion: The group of natural processes, including weathering, dissolution, abrasion, corrosion, and transportation, by which material is worn away from the earth's surface.

cannoli: A fried pastry roll with a sweet creamy filling.

quetzal: Any of several tropical American birds of the genera Pharomachrus and Euptilotis having brilliant bronze-green and red plumage and, in the male, long flowing tail feathers, especially P. mocinno of Central America.

pistoleer: One who fires or uses a pistol; a soldier armed with a pistol, especially a German reiter.

willies: Feelings of uneasiness. Often used with the:

germinate: To cause to sprout or grow.

mahjong: A game of Chinese origin usually played by four persons with tiles resembling dominoes and bearing various designs, which are drawn and discarded until one player wins with a hand of four combinations of three tiles each and a pair of matching tiles.

hobble: To walk or move along haltingly or with difficulty; limp.

daube: a stew of braised meat, usually beef

ecotage: The commission of usually illegal acts of sabotage motivated by environmentalism.

accrue: To come to one as a gain, addition, or increment.

nandu: The South American ostrich, Rhea americana, and other species of that genus. Also spelled nandoo.

tourmaline: A complex crystalline silicate containing aluminum, boron, and other elements, used in electronic instrumentation and, especially in its green, clear, and blue varieties, as a gemstone.

lairage: Space where cattle may lie down and rest.

aerobiology: The study of the sources, dispersion, and effects of airborne biological materials, such as pollen, spores, and microorganisms.

futz: To waste time or effort on frivolities; fool. Often used with around.

elapsed: Simple past tense and past participle of elapse.

zinnia: Any of various plants of the genus Zinnia of the composite family, native to tropical America and widely cultivated for their showy, colorful flower heads.

conscientious: Guided by or in accordance with the dictates of conscience; principled.

dogmatic: Relating to, characteristic of, or resulting from dogma.

maté: An evergreen tree, Ilex paraguariensis, native to South America, cultivated for its leaves.

relatable: Possible to relate; able to be related to.

volost: A small administrative division in Russia.

bhaji: Any of various Indian dishes of fried vegetables

chafe: To wear away or irritate by rubbing or friction.

hyponym: A word whose meaning is included in the meaning of another more general word; for example, bus is a hyponym of vehicle.

persuasively: In a persuasive manner; so as to influence or win over; convincingly.

deja vu: A feeling of having previously experienced something, especially when that is not the case.

synteresis: In medicine, preservative or preventive treatment; prophylaxis.

dybbuk: In Jewish folklore, the wandering soul of a dead person that enters the body of a living person and controls his or her behavior.

chutzpadik: showing chutzpah; not showing due respect; impudent; impertinent; brazen

surreptitious: Obtained, done, or made by clandestine or stealthy means. synonym:secret.

tease: To make fun of (someone) playfully or taunt annoyingly.

telluric acid: A white, crystalline inorganic acid, Te(OH)6, used as a chemical reagent.

stammered: Of speech, that sounds irregular or halting.

cantrip: A magic spell; a witch's trick.

matrass: A chemical vessel with a round or oval body and a long neck open at the top, serving the purposes of digestion, evaporation, etc.; a cucurbit. Also called bolt-head.

Qing: A dynasty of Manchu emperors of China (1644–1912) during which increasing Western influence and trade led to the Opium War (1839–1842) with Britain and the Boxer Rebellion (1898–1900). The dynasty, China's last, was overthrown by nationalist revolutionaries.

shoestring: A small sum of money; capital that is barely adequate.

brunt: The main impact or force, as of an attack.

hyacinth: A bulbous Mediterranean plant (Hyacinthus orientalis) having narrow leaves and a terminal raceme of variously colored, usually fragrant flowers, with a funnel-shaped perianth.

antanaclasis: In rhetoric, a figure which consists in repeating the same word in a different sense: as, while we live, let us live; learn some craft when young, that when old you may live without craft.

kabuki: A form of Japanese theatre in which elaborately costumed male performers use stylized movements, dances, and songs in order to enact tragedies and comedies.

France: A country of western Europe. It was settled by the Franks after the retreat of the Romans, who had conquered Celtic Gaul in 58–51 BC. Though Charlemagne incorporated it into his Empire of the West after AD 800, France was eventually split into numerous fiefdoms and principalities, many of which were not incorporated into the royal domain until the time of Louis XI (reigned 1461–1483). Widespread poverty and discontent led to the French Revolution (1789) and the end of the monarchy. The First Republic (1792–1804) was followed by the First Empire (1804–1815) under Napoleon I, a period of constitutional monarchy (1814–1848), and a succession of republics broken by the Second Empire (1852–1870) under Napoleon III. Much of France was occupied by Germany in World War II. Paris is the capital and the largest city.

quango: An organization or agency that is financed by a government but that acts independently of it.

facile: Done or achieved with little effort or difficulty; easy.

heartened: Simple past tense and past participle of hearten.

animism: The belief in the existence of individual spirits that inhabit natural objects and phenomena.

polytheistic: Pertaining to, of the nature of, or characterized by polytheism : as, polytheistic belief or worship.

heteronomy: In biology, the state of divergent modification in parts that exhibit general homology or homonomy.

vicar: An Anglican parish priest in a parish where historically someone other than the priest was entitled to the tithes.

uvea: The vascular middle layer of the eye constituting the iris, ciliary body, and choroid.

hasidic: of or relating to the Jewish Hasidim or its members or their beliefs and practices

errorist: One who errs, or who encourages and propagates error.

bacchanalia: A wild, orgiastic party or celebration.

banal: Drearily commonplace and often predictable; trite.

covet: To feel strong or immoderate desire for (that which is another's).

churlish: Of, like, or befitting a churl; boorish or vulgar.

doggedly: In a dogged manner; with the pertinacity of a dog; persistently; unyieldingly.

manifest: Clearly apparent to the sight or understanding; obvious. synonym:apparent.

stony: Covered with or full of stones.

macaronic: Of or containing a mixture of vernacular words with Latin words or with vernacular words given Latinate endings.

connotation: The act or process of connoting.

cinematographer: A movie photographer, especially one who is in charge of the camera and lighting crews on a production.

empathy: The ability to identify with or understand another's situation or feelings: synonym:pity.

allocation: The act of allocating, allotting, or assigning; allotment; assignment; apportionment: as, the allocation of shares in a public company.

ransack: To search through (something) thoroughly and often roughly.

Cassandra: A daughter of Priam, the king of Troy, endowed with the gift of prophecy but fated by Apollo never to be believed.

Adonai: Lord. Used in Judaism as a spoken substitute for the ineffable name of God.

swathe: To wrap, as in layers of cloth.

soda jerk: One who works at a soda fountain.

blooter: A babbler, a bumbling idiot, a fool.

birling: A game of skill, especially among lumberjacks, in which two competitors try to balance on a floating log while spinning it with their feet.

Claudius: Roman decemvir (451–449) whose actions provoked a plebian revolt and the overthrow of the decemvirs.

courage: The state or quality of mind or spirit that enables one to face danger, fear, or vicissitudes with self-possession, confidence, and resolution; bravery.

barbican: A tower or other fortification on the approach to a castle or town, especially one at a gate or drawbridge.

dullard: A person regarded as mentally dull; a dolt.

sap: A leather-covered bludgeon with a short, flexible shaft or strap, used as a hand weapon.

desirable: Worth having or seeking, as by being useful, advantageous, or pleasing.

microphone: An instrument that converts sound waves into an electric current, usually fed into an amplifier, a recorder, or a broadcast transmitter.

photosynthesis: The process in green plants and certain other organisms by which carbohydrates are synthesized from carbon dioxide and a source of hydrogen (usually water), using light as an energy source. Most forms of photosynthesis release oxygen as a byproduct.

zek: An inmate of a Soviet labor camp.

ineffable: Incapable of being expressed; indescribable or unutterable.

totalitarianism: A system of government in which the people have virtually no authority and the state wields absolute control, for example, a dictatorship.

effectually: In an effectual manner; with complete effect; so as to produce or secure the end desired; thoroughly: as, the city is effectually guarded.

dolma: A fruit or vegetable, especially a grape leaf or cabbage leaf, cooked with a filling of ground meat, herbs, or rice.

araucaria: Any of several evergreen coniferous trees of the genus Araucaria native to South America, Australia, and islands of the southwest Pacific Ocean, having awl-shaped leaves and whorled branches and including Norfolk lsland pine.

virtuous: Having or showing virtue, especially moral excellence: synonym:moral.

contemplate: To look at attentively and thoughtfully.

bossism: The domination of a political organization by a boss.

melancholy: Sadness or depression of the spirits; gloom.

biquadratic: Of or relating to the fourth degree.

budget: An itemized summary of estimated or intended expenditures for a given period along with proposals for financing them.

articulate: Composed of distinct, meaningful syllables or words.

pyromania: The irresistible urge to start fires.

monokini: A women's topless swimsuit consisting of a brief, close-fitting bottom.

amphisbaena: A mythical serpent or winged creature having a head at each end of its body.

basenji: A dog of a breed originally from Africa, having a short, smooth, reddish-brown coat and characterized by the absence of a bark.

topi: In India, a hat or cap.

thalassic: Of or relating to seas or oceans, especially smaller or inland seas.

blaxploitation: A film genre of the 1970s featuring African-American actors and often having antiestablishment plots, sometimes criticized for stereotypical characterization and glorification of violence.

bridezilla: A woman who, in the course of planning her wedding, exercises or attempts to exercise a high degree of control over all or many minor details of the ceremony and reception.

bumf: Pamphlets, forms, memorandums, or similar printed matter, especially when considered uninteresting or unimportant.

ensue: To take place afterward or as a result. synonym:follow.

xylography: Wood engraving, especially of an early period.

orogen: The rock deformed by an orogeny

petitgrain: An essential oil that is extracted from the green twigs of the bitter orange plant.

williwaw: A violent gust of cold wind blowing seaward from a mountainous coast, especially in the Straits of Magellan.

prexy: A president, especially of a college or university.

abscond: To leave quickly and secretly and hide oneself, often to avoid arrest or prosecution.

Camorra: A Neapolitan secret society organized about 1820, notorious for practicing violence and blackmail.

asseverate: To declare seriously or positively; affirm.

tugged: Simple past tense and past participle of tug.

ritenuto: In music, at a slower tempo or pace.

luncheon: A lunch, especially a formal one.

mumpsimus: An error obstinately clung to; a prejudice.

governorate: In Arab countries, the territory ruled over by a governor; a province

ropen: A Middle English past participle of reap.

lunge: A sudden thrust or pass, as with a sword.

ecesis: The successful establishment of a plant or animal species in a habitat.

mahatma: A person venerated for spirituality and high-mindedness.

pronunciamento: An official or authoritarian declaration; a proclamation or edict.

chrematistics: The science of wealth: a name given by some writers to the science of political economy, or, in a more restricted sense, to that portion of the science which relates to the management and regulation of wealth and property.

Trinidad and Tobago: A country of the southeast West Indies in the Atlantic Ocean off northeast Venezuela. It comprises the islands of Trinidad and Tobago, which were formally united as a British colony in 1898 and became independent in 1962. Port of Spain, on Trinidad, is the capital.

jurisprudence: The philosophy or science of law.

demethylase: Any enzyme that catalyzes the removal of a methyl group from a compound

bioenergetics: The study of the flow and transformation of energy in and between living organisms and between living organisms and their environment.

diagnosis: The act or process of identifying or determining the nature and cause of a disease or injury through evaluation of patient history, examination, and review of laboratory data.

apropos: Fitting and to the point. synonym:relevant.

systole: The rhythmic contraction of the heart, especially of the ventricles, by which blood is driven through the aorta and pulmonary artery after each dilation or diastole.

expectoration: The act of discharging phlegm or mucus from the throat or lungs, by coughing or hawking and spitting; euphemistically, a spitting.

tribulation: Great affliction, trial, or distress; suffering: synonym:trial.

realia: Objects, such as coins, household items, or natural specimens, that are included in a collection primarily composed of documentary materials, as in a library.

decameron: A celebrated collection of tales, supposed to be related in ten days; -- written in the 14th century, by Boccaccio, an Italian.

Baroque: from the Baroque period in visual art and music.

fanfaron: A bully; a hector; a swaggerer; an empty boaster; a vain pretender.

anthropophagus: A person who eats human flesh; a cannibal.

raga: A traditional melodic type in Hindu music, consisting of a theme that expresses an aspect of religious feeling and sets forth a tonal system on which variations are improvised within a prescribed framework of typical progressions, melodic formulas, and rhythmic patterns.

safety: The condition of being safe; freedom from danger, risk, or injury.

kakistocracy: Government by the least qualified or most unprincipled citizens.

Aesculapius: The god of medicine and healing.

thimblerigger: One who practises the trick of thimblerig; a low trickster or sharper. Also thimbleman.

codicil: A supplement or appendix to a will.

benign: Having little or no detrimental effect; harmless.

sutler: An army camp follower who peddled provisions to the soldiers.

entelechy: In the philosophy of Aristotle, the condition of a thing whose essence is fully realized; actuality.

alpenglow: A rosy glow that suffuses snow-covered mountain peaks at dawn or dusk on a clear day.

laterigrade: Running sidewise, as a spider; pertaining to the Laterigradæ, or having their characters.

pansy: Any of various plants of the genus Viola, especially V. tricolor or its hybrids, widely cultivated for their flowers with velvety petals of various colors.

res judicata: The principle that a decision by a competent court in a case fully and fairly litigated is final and conclusive as to the claims and issues of the parties and cannot be relitigated.

pachisi: An ancient game of India similar to backgammon that uses cowrie shells instead of dice.

dehiscent: Opening, as the capsule of a plant.

ament: In botany, a kind of inflorescence consisting of unisexual apetalous flowers growing in the axils of scales or bracts ranged along a stalk or axis; a catkin. The true ament or catkin is articulated with the branch and is deciduous; it is well seen in the inflorescence of the birch, willow, and poplar, and in the staminate inflorescence of the oak, walnut, and hazel. Also written amentum.

pareidolia: The perception of a recognizable image or meaningful pattern where none exists or is intended, as the perception of a face in the surface features of the moon.

atmospheric: Of, relating to, or existing in the atmosphere.

braggardism: Boastfulness; vain ostentation: as, “what braggardism is this?” Also braggartism.

crambo: A word game in which a player or team must find and express a rhyme for a word or line presented by the opposing player or team.

patronize: To act as a patron to; support or sponsor.

arc-boutant: A buttress that stands apart from the main structure and connected to it by an arch; same as flying buttress.

ombre: A card game, played by three players with 40 cards, that was popular in Europe during the 1600s and 1700s.

vesical: Of or pertaining to a vesica; cystic; especially, pertaining to the urinary bladder: as, vesical arteries, veins, or nerves; vesical distention.

ophelimity: In political economics, a term suggested by Professor V. Pareto as a substitute for ‘utility,’ as used in political economy.

Rabelaisian: Of or relating to Rabelais or his works.

Saint Vincent and the Grenadines: An island country in the central Windward Islands of the West Indies. It comprises St. Vincent Island and the northern islets of the Grenadines. Part of the West Indies Federation from 1958 to 1962, the country gained self-governing status in 1969 and full independence in 1979. Kingstown, on St. Vincent, is the capital.

aesthetic: Relating to the philosophy or theories of aesthetics.

pathology: The scientific study of the nature of disease and its causes, processes, development, and consequences.

brusqueness: Quality of being brusque; roughness joined with promptness; bluntness.

cabalist: One versed in or engaged in the study of the cabala or mystic philosophy of the Jews.

cisco: Any of several North American freshwater fishes of the genus Coregonus whose upper and lower jaws are the same length, unlike other whitefishes.

darnel: Any of several ryegrasses, especially Lolium temulentum.

anergia: Lack of energy; passivity. Also anergy.

anarchist: Properly, one who advocates anarchy or the absence of government as a political ideal; a believer in an anarchic theory of society; especially, an adherent of the social theory of Proudhon. See anarchy, 2.
