Kyrgyzstan: A country of Central Asia bordering on Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, and northwest China. Inhabited since the 1200s by the Kyrgyz people, the region was annexed by Russia (1876), incorporated into the USSR after the Russian Revolution (1922), and established as the Kirghiz Soviet Socialist Republic in 1936. Kyrgyzstan, sometimes called Kirghizia, declared its independence in 1991 upon the dissolution of the USSR. Bishkek is the capital and the largest city.

bidet: A fixture similar in design to a toilet that is straddled for washing the genitals and the anal area.

dossier: A collection of papers giving detailed information about a particular person or subject.

rose: A member of the rose family.

bound morpheme: A morpheme that can only occur when bound to a root morpheme. For example, -ed, -ing, -ly.

hypernym: A word whose meaning includes the meaning of a more specific word; for example, animal is a hypernym of elephant.

British Virgin Islands: A British colony in the eastern Caribbean east of Puerto Rico and the US Virgin Islands. Road Town, on Tortola Island, is the capital.

autonomous: Not controlled by others or by outside forces; independent.

Netherlands Antilles: A former autonomous territory of the Netherlands consisting of Curaçao and Bonaire off the coast of Venezuela and Saba, St. Eustatius, and the southern portion of St. Martin in the northern Windward Islands.

calumet: A long-stemmed sacred or ceremonial tobacco pipe used by certain Native American peoples.

salacious: Appealing to or stimulating sexual desire.

Anacreontic: Of or in the manner of the poems of Anacreon, especially being convivial or amatory in subject.

dredge: Any of various machines equipped with scooping or suction devices and used to deepen harbors and waterways and in underwater mining.

parhelion: A bright spot sometimes appearing at either side of the sun, often on a luminous ring or halo, caused by the refraction and reflection of sunlight by ice crystals suspended in the earth's atmosphere.

Achaea: An ancient region of southern Greece occupying the northern part of the Peloponnesus on the Gulf of Corinth. The cities of the region banded together in the early third century BC to form the Achaean League, which defeated Sparta but was eventually beaten by the Romans, who annexed Achaea in 146 BC and later gave the name to a province that included all of Greece south of Thessaly.

Abydos: An ancient town of Asia Minor on the Hellespont in modern-day Turkey. It is the legendary home of Leander, who swam nightly across the strait to his lover Hero.

subside: To become less intense, active, or severe; abate.

moonbow: A meteorological phenomenon also known as a lunar rainbow or white rainbow, well documented at Cumberland Falls near Corbin, Kentucky, Victoria Falls in Africa as well as other places such as Yosemite National Park.

amaranth: Any of various annual plants of the genus Amaranthus having dense green or reddish clusters of tiny flowers and including weeds, ornamentals, and species cultivated for their edible leaves and seeds.

crepitate: To make a crackling or popping sound; crackle.

sassaby: The bastard hartbeest, Damalis or Alcelaphus lunatus, of South Africa.

flunky: A person of slavish or unquestioning obedience; a lackey.

grovel: To behave in a servile or obsequious manner.

flyway: A seasonal route followed by birds migrating to and from their breeding areas.

livery: A distinctive uniform worn by the male servants of a household.

knapsack: A bag made of sturdy material and furnished with shoulder straps, designed for carrying articles on the back.

marplot: An officious meddler whose interference compromises the success of an undertaking.

Aachen: A city of western Germany near the Belgian and Dutch borders. Charlemagne may have been born here in 742; he later made the city his northern capital.

grandeur: The quality or condition of being grand; magnificence.

antifogmatic: an alcoholic drink taken in the morning to brace oneself before going out into bad weather.

shebeen: An unlicensed drinking establishment, especially in Ireland, Scotland, and South Africa.

tangential: Of, relating to, or moving along or in the direction of a tangent.

frondescence: In bot.: The period or state of coming into leaf.

deliquescent: In botany, becoming liquid at maturity, as certain agarics.

aprosdoketon: A figure of speech where an expected word in an idiom is replaced unexpectedly by an unusual one, such as Rome wasn't built in a teacup; also, any surprising use or interpretation of language.

fadge: To suit; fit; come close, as the parts of things united; hence, to have one part consistent with another.

messianic: Of or relating to a messiah.

hath: Third person singular present indicative of have: now archaic or poetical.

Nerita: A genus of mollusks used with widely varying limits

fair: Of pleasing appearance, especially because of a pure or fresh quality; comely.

paneer: A soft unsalted and unripened cheese made from milk that is simmered, curdled using lemon juice, vinegar, yogurt, or a similarly acidic substance, and then drained and pressed in cheesecloth.

vibrissa: Any of the long stiff hairs that are located chiefly on the muzzle of most mammals and that function as tactile organs, as the whiskers of a cat.

prestidigitation: Performance of or skill in performing magic or conjuring tricks with the hands; sleight of hand.

lariat: A rope for picketing grazing horses or mules.

vie: To strive for victory or superiority; contend. synonym:rival.

Angelus: A devotional prayer at morning, noon, and night to commemorate the Annunciation.

isogamy: Reproduction by the fusion or conjugation of isogametes, as in certain algae and fungi.

freshet: A sudden overflow of a stream resulting from a heavy rain or a thaw.

ferret: An artificial albinotic variety of the fitch or polecat, Putorius vulgaris or fœtidus, said to be of African origin, about 14 inches long, of a whitish or pale-yellowish color, with red or pink eyes, bred in confinement in Europe and America to kill rats, rabbits, and other vermin or small game living in holes, into which its lithe, slender, and sinuous body readily enters.

disparagement: The matching of a man or a woman to one of inferior rank or condition, and against the rules of decency.

mankini: A kind of sling bikini worn by men

agglomerate: To form or collect into a rounded mass.

bête noire: One that is particularly disliked or that is to be avoided.

Gerbera: A genus of South African or Asiatic herbs having showy daisy-like flowers; it includes some of the African daisies.

hematemesis: In pathology, a vomiting of blood.

saturnine: Having the temperament of one born under the supposed astrological influence of Saturn.

hydronym: the name of a river, lake, sea or any other body of water

equivocal: Open to two or more interpretations and often intended to conceal the truth. synonym:ambiguous.

tussock: A clump or tuft, as of growing grass.

delay: To postpone until a later time; defer.

Macedonia: A region of southeast Europe on the Balkan Peninsula roughly coextensive with ancient Macedon and including parts of modern-day Greece, Bulgaria, and the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia. After the fall of the Alexandrian empire, it was held by Romans, Byzantines, Bulgars, Serbs, and Turks. The present division was largely determined after the Second Balkan War (1913).

annulus: A ringlike figure, part, structure, or marking, such as a growth ring on the scale of a fish.

dabbing: In stone-working, the process of covering the surface of a stone, after it has been made uniform, with small indentations, by means of a pick-shaped tool, or a hammer indented so as to form a series of points. Also called daubing and picking.

hypoglycemia: An abnormally low level of glucose in the blood.

cancer: Any of various malignant neoplasms characterized by the proliferation of anaplastic cells that tend to invade surrounding tissue and metastasize to new body sites.

carucate: Formerly, as much land as could be cultivated by one caruca: usually about 100 acres, but the quantity varied according to the nature of the soil and the practice of husbandry in different districts. Also carue.

Armenia: A region and former kingdom of western Asia that included present-day Armenia and parts of northeast Turkey and northwest Iran. Established c. 600 BC, it was probably the first state to adopt Christianity as a national religion (c. AD 303). In the fourth and fifth centuries Armenia was subsumed by the Roman and Persian empires.

Uzbekistan: A country of west-central Asia. Settled in ancient times, it was conquered by Alexander the Great, Genghis Khan, and Tamerlane and finally overrun by Uzbek peoples in the early 1500s. Russia conquered the area in the 1800s. Split into various administrative territories after 1917, it was consolidated as a constituent republic of the USSR in 1924. Uzbekistan declared its independence in 1991 after the collapse of the Soviet Union. Tashkent is the capital and the largest city.

idesia: deciduous roundheaded Asiatic tree widely grown in mild climates as an ornamental for its heart-shaped leaves and fragrant yellow-green flowers followed by hanging clusters of fleshy orange-red berries

augur: One of a group of ancient Roman religious officials who foretold events by observing and interpreting signs and omens.

paratha: an Indian bread with a texture somewhat resembling puff pastry; sometimes stuffed with vegetables etc.

spurn: To reject with disdain or contempt. synonym:refuse.

etesian: Occurring annually. Used of the prevailing northerly summer winds of the Mediterranean.

au fait: Up to the mark; fully skilled or accomplished; expert; possessing or showing the readiness or skill of an adept: followed by at or in: as, he is quite au fait at the game.

Mumbai: A city of west-central India, on a coastal island on the Arabian Sea. The capital of the state of Maharashtra, Mumbai is India's largest city and a major port and commercial center.

docile: Ready and willing to be taught; teachable.

regretting: Present participle of regret. Also form regreting is used, although it is not generally recognized by dictionaries.

cade: A bushy juniper (Juniperus oxycedrus) chiefly of the Mediterranean region that is used in horticulture and whose wood yields juniper tar.

feather: One of the light, flat growths forming the plumage of birds, consisting of numerous slender, closely arranged parallel barbs forming a vane on either side of a horny, tapering, partly hollow shaft.

brahmin: A Hindu priestly caste; one of the four varnas or social groups based on occupation in ancient Hindu society.

flamboyant: Given to or marked by elaborate, ostentatious, or audacious display or behavior. synonym:showy.

manzai: Strolling ballet-singers and -dancers who go about at the beginning of the new year.

arras: A tapestry, wall hanging, or curtain, especially one of Flemish origin.

Hogmanay: The eve of New Year's Day, on which children traditionally go from house to house asking for presents.

pongid: Any of various apes of the subfamily Ponginae, which includes only the orangutans and their extinct relatives.

penitentiary: A prison for those convicted of major crimes.

googolplex: The number 10 raised to the power googol, written out as the numeral 1 followed by 10100 zeros.

antepast: A foretaste; something taken before a meal to stimulate the appetite.

alien: Owing political allegiance to another country or government; foreign.

alienist: A physician who evaluates the competence of defendants to stand trial.

bangla: a Magadhan language spoken by the Bengali people; the official language of Bangladesh and Bengal

caracara: Any of several large carrion-eating or predatory birds in the family Falconidae, native to South and Central America and the southern United States.

mesa: A broad, flat-topped elevation with one or more clifflike sides, common in the southwest United States.

udometer: A pluviometer; a rain-gage. See cut under pluviometer.

browst: That which is brewed; as much liquor as is brewed at one time.

Mauritius: An island country in the southwest Indian Ocean comprising the island of Mauritius and several small dependencies in the Mascarene Islands. Originally uninhabited, the islands were probably known to Arab and Malay traders in the Middle Ages. Mauritius was controlled by the Dutch (1598–1710), the French (1715–1810), and the British (after 1814) before independence was achieved in 1968. It became a republic in 1992. Port Louis is the capital and the largest city.

alcarraza: A vessel made of porous unglazed pottery, used in hot climates for cooling water by the evaporation of the moisture oozing through the substance of the vessel.

bildungsroman: A novel whose principal subject is the moral, psychological, and intellectual development of a usually youthful main character.

carrageen: A marine alga very common on rocks and stones on the coasts of Great Britain and Ireland.

girandola: An ornate ornamental branched candlestick, often with a mirror at the back.

shama: A saxicoline singing bird (Kittacincla macroura) of India, noted for the sweetness and power of its song. In confinement it imitates the notes of other birds and various animals with accuracy. Its head, neck, back, breast, and tail are glossy black, the rump white, the under parts chestnut.

telomere: Either of the sections of DNA occurring at the ends of a chromosome.

shiitake: A mushroom (Lentinula edodes) native to East Asia, having an edible golden or dark brown cap.

vituperate: To rebuke or criticize harshly or angrily; berate. synonym:scold.

earthlight: Light reflected by the earth: same as earth-shine.

Central African Republic: A country of central Africa. Part of French Equatorial Africa after 1910, it became independent in 1960. In 1966 Col. Jean-Bédel Bokassa overthrew the government and in 1976 declared himself emperor, renaming the country the Central African Empire. After Bokassa's ouster in 1979, political upheavals alternated with periods of peace and the reestablishment of democratic institutions. Bangui is the capital and the largest city.

emperor: The male ruler of an empire.

algolagnia: Sexual gratification derived from inflicting or experiencing pain.

gambit: An opening in chess in which the player risks one or more minor pieces, usually a pawn, in order to gain a favorable position.

iftar: The evening meal that breaks the daily fast during Ramadan, traditionally featuring the fruit of the date palm as a first course.

psychasthenia: A group of psychiatric symptoms, including phobias, obsessions, and compulsions. These symptoms are currently attributed to other disorders, including obsessive-compulsive disorder and anxiety disorders.

armoured: provided with protective covering; -- used of animals. Opposite of unarmored.

landscape: An expanse of scenery that can be seen in a single view.

nescient: Destitute of knowledge; ignorant; characterized by or exhibiting nescience.

regal: Of or relating to a monarch; royal.

shashlik: A dish consisting of marinated cubes of lamb or beef grilled or roasted on a spit, often with slices of eggplant, onion, and tomato; shish kebab.

duxelles: A finely chopped mixture of mushrooms, onions, shallots and herbs sautéed in butter and reduced to a paste, used in stuffings and sauces (as in beef Wellington) or as a garnish.

kerygma: The proclamation of religious truths, especially as taught in the Gospels.

frumenty: Hulled wheat boiled in milk and flavored with sugar and spices.

Yule: Christmas or the Christmas season, especially as traditionally celebrated in Northern Europe and North America with customs stemming in part from pagan celebrations of the winter solstice.

piquant: Pleasantly pungent or tart in taste; spicy.

Hanukkah: An eight-day festival beginning on the 25th day of Kislev, commemorating the victory in 165 BC of the Maccabees over Antiochus Epiphanes (c. 215–164 BC) and the rededication of the Temple at Jerusalem.

affinity: A natural attraction, liking, or feeling of kinship.

choir: An organized company of singers, especially one performing church music or singing in a church.

pyrrhic: A metrical foot having two short or unaccented syllables.

carnal: Relating to the physical and especially sexual appetites.

Barsac: A general name for the white wines made in Barsac, department of Gironde, France.

disjecta membra: Scattered members; disjointed portious or parts.

bharal: The blue sheep of northern India, Ovis nahura or O. burhel.

golgotha: A place or occasion of great suffering.

exostosis: A bony growth on the surface of a bone or tooth.

Suzhou: A city of eastern China west of Shanghai. The capital (6th–5th century BC) of an ancient feudal kingdom, Suzhou is famous for its beautiful bridges and pagodas and for its silk industry.

listicle: An article based around a list.

toxophily: The love of, or an addiction to, archery

kulfi: A dense ice cream of South Asian origin, typically made with boiled milk, sugar, cardamom, pistachios, and other ingredients.

accost: To approach and speak to, especially aggressively or insistently, as with a demand or request.

ablation: Surgical excision or amputation of a body part or tissue.

eosin: A yellowish-red crystalline powder, C20H8 Br4O5, used in textile dyeing and ink manufacturing, as a biological stain, and in coloring gasoline.

aposematic: Of a nature to warn or alarm; serving to warn or alarm enemies: noting characteristics of organisms which, when displayed, effect this.

abaya: A loose, usually black robe worn by Muslim women, especially in Arabic-speaking regions, covering the body from head to toe or the neck down and often worn with a headscarf and veil.

vagrant: One who wanders from place to place without a permanent home or a means of livelihood.

Zurich: A city of northeast Switzerland at the northern tip of the Lake of Zurich. Founded before Roman times, Zurich was chartered in 1218 and joined the Swiss Confederation in 1351. In the 1500s, it was a center of the Swiss Reformation under the leadership of Ulrich Zwingli. Today it is the largest city in the country. Zurich is known for its international banking and financial institutions.

aegrotat: In English universities, a medical certificate given to a student showing that he has been prevented by sickness from attending to his duties. Also called æger.

reversi: A board game played by two players on a board of 64 squares arranged in an eight-by-eight grid, with 64 playing pieces that are black on one side and white on the other. Each player alternates laying a piece on the board, and if a player places a piece so that one or more of an opponent's pieces lie between that piece and another of that player's pieces, that player flips the opponent's piece or pieces to that player's color. After all pieces have been laid, the player with the most pieces showing his or her color wins.

nocturia: A frequent need to arise during the night in order to urinate.

guenon: Any of various small- to medium-sized African monkeys primarily of the tribe Cercopithecini, being chiefly arboreal and having long hind legs, a long tail, and often a brightly colored face.

nosocomial: Of or relating to a hospital.

mythopoeic: Of or relating to the making of myths.

anomalous: Deviating from the normal or common order, form, or rule.

Idaho: A state of the United States of America. Capital: Boise.

ophicleide: A keyed brass instrument of the bugle family with a baritone range that was the structural precursor of the bass saxophone and was replaced by the tuba in orchestras.

blackcap: A small warbler (Sylvia atricapilla) of Eurasia and Africa, the male of which is gray with a black crown.

artisanal: Relating to or made by an artisan.

sedulously: In a sedulous manner; diligently; industriously; assiduously.

decadence: A process, condition, or period of deterioration or decline, as in morals or art; decay.

flexecutive: An executive or other professional who works flexible hours, sometimes from home via the Internet

embed: To fix firmly in a surrounding mass.

deprivation: The act or an instance of depriving; loss.

clamor: A loud noise or outcry; a hubbub. synonym:noise.

tithing: An administrative division consisting of ten householders in the old English system of frankpledge.

scudo: A unit of currency and coin formerly used in Italy and Sicily.

pinfeather: A growing feather still enclosed in its horny sheath, especially one just emerging through the skin.

isoseismal: A curve or line connecting points at which an earthquake-shock is felt with equal intensity, or at which there is an “equal overthrow” (Mallet). See homoseismal.

embolus: A mass, such as an air bubble, a detached blood clot, or a foreign body, that travels through the bloodstream and lodges so as to obstruct or occlude a blood vessel.

cicatrix: A scar left by the formation of new connective tissue over a healing sore or wound.

New Zealand: An island country in the southern Pacific Ocean southeast of Australia. Maori groups probably migrated to New Zealand from Polynesia by the late 1200s. Visited by Abel Tasman in 1642, the islands were more thoroughly explored by Capt. James Cook in three voyages between 1769 and 1777. The British established their first permanent settlement in 1840 and claimed the region as a crown colony. New Zealand received dominion status in 1907 and became fully independent in 1931. Wellington is the capital and Auckland the largest city.

atole: A thick drink of Mexican origin that is made with cornmeal, water, raw sugar, cinnamon, and vanilla and is served warm.

impetuous: Acting or done quickly with little or inadequate thought.

disarm: To divest of a weapon or weapons.

modiste: One that produces, designs, or deals in women's fashions.

transfer: To convey or cause to pass from one place, person, or thing to another.

robusta: A hardy species of coffee, Coffea canephora, of western Africa, widely cultivated for its commercially valuable seeds, often considered inferior to arabica seeds.

tunicle: A sleeved outer vestment reaching to the knees, worn over the alb by a subdeacon or sometimes under the dalmatic by a bishop or cardinal.

circumzenithal: About or near the zenith; relating to objects or observations near the zenith.

trading post: A station or store in a sparsely settled area established by traders to barter supplies for local products.

perjury: The crime of willfully and knowingly making a false statement about a material fact while under oath.

bodega: A small grocery store that specializes in products from the Caribbean and Latin America.

ihram: The sacred dress of Muslim pilgrims, consisting of two lengths of white cotton, one wrapped around the loins, the other thrown over the left shoulder.

carpus: The group of eight bones forming the joint between the forearm and the hand.

mononym: A name consisting of a single term; a mononomial name in zoölogy.

aquaplane: A board pulled over the water by a motorboat and ridden by a person standing up.

dura mater: The tough fibrous membrane covering the brain and the spinal cord and lining the inner surface of the skull. It is the outermost of the three meninges that surround the brain and spinal cord.

purl: To flow or ripple with a murmuring sound.

sodality: A society or an association, especially a devotional or charitable society for the laity in the Roman Catholic Church.

colonoscopy: Examination of the colon with a colonoscope.

acclaim: To praise enthusiastically and often publicly. synonym:praise.

donzel: A young attendant; a page; a youth of good quality not yet knighted.

supremacist: One who believes that a certain group is or should be supreme.

ineluctable: Not to be avoided or escaped; inevitable.

noisome: Offensive to the point of arousing disgust; foul.

lackadaisical: Lacking spirit, liveliness, or interest; languid.

autocrat: A ruler having unlimited power; a despot.

dictation: The act or process of dictating material to another for transcription.

ale: A fermented alcoholic beverage containing malt and hops, similar to but heavier than beer.

equid: Any of various mammals of the family Equidae, having a single hoofed digit on each foot, and including the horses, asses, and zebras.

dev: In Persian myth., an evil spirit; a ministering demon of Ahriman. Sometimes written deev (Pers. dīv). See deva.

oocyte: A diploid cell from which an egg or ovum develops by meiosis. A primary oocyte divides to produce a polar body and a secondary oocyte, which divides again to produce the ovum and another polar body.

schipperke: A small stocky dog of a breed developed in Belgium, having dense long black fur and small pointed ears.

stichomancy: Divination by lines or passages in books taken at hazard; bibliomancy.

fillip: A snap or light blow made by pressing a fingertip against the thumb and suddenly releasing it.

thali: An Indian meal comprising a selection of different dishes, usually served in small bowls on a round tray.

mangabey: Any of various large forest-dwelling African monkeys of two genera, one (Cercocebus) consisting of chiefly terrestrial species, and the other (Lophocebus) consisting of chiefly arboreal species.

spectroheliokinematograph: A scientific apparatus of the 1930s consisting of a spectrohelioscope and early video camera, used to monitor events on the surface of the Sun.

amphiuma: Any of several long slender salamanders of the genus Amphiuma of the southeast United States that in their adult stage have two pairs of very small nonfunctioning legs and breathe with lungs although they are aquatic.

metronymy: The system of tracing name and kinship in the female line.

biosemiotics: A growing field that studies the production, action and interpretation of signs in the biological realm.

yogh: The Middle English letter ȝ, used to represent the sound (y) and some velar consonants similar to the ch in German Bach and the r in French France.

tropology: The use of tropes in speech or writing.

requiescat: A prayer for the repose of the souls of the dead.

clef: A symbol indicating the pitch represented by one line of a staff, in relation to which the other pitches of the staff can be determined.

ictus: A sudden attack, blow, stroke, or seizure.

chalazion: A cyst of a tarsal gland.

heave: To raise or lift, especially with great effort or force: synonym:lift.

module: A standardized, often interchangeable component of a system or construction that is designed for easy assembly or flexible use.

curia: One of the ten primitive subdivisions of a tribe in early Rome, consisting of ten gentes.

retrieve: To get back into one's grasp, possession, or control, especially from a known place or a place of storage.

axiomatical: Of the nature of an axiom; axiomatic.

disheveled: Being in loose disarray; unkempt, as hair or clothing.

astucious: Astute; subtle; designing. Also spelled astutious.

contradictory: Involving, of the nature of, or being a contradiction: synonym:opposite.

aura: An invisible emanation or field of energy believed to radiate from a person or object.

adherence: The process or condition of adhering.

jumble: To mix in a confused way; throw together carelessly.

mere: Being nothing more than what is specified.

sacred: Dedicated to or set apart for the worship of a deity.

perimeter: A closed line bounding a plane area.

tristesse: Sadness; melancholy: in modern use as a French word.

shpadoinkle: An exclamation meaning "great" or denoting surprise.

ignitron: A single-anode, mercury-vapor rectifier in which current passes as an arc between the anode and a mercury-pool cathode, used in power rectification.

enervation: The act of enervating, or the state of being enervated; reduction or weakening of strength; effeminacy.

pastern: The part of a horse's foot between the fetlock and hoof.

smuggle: To bring into a country (a prohibited item) secretively and intentionally, in violation of the law.

spline: Any of a series of projections on a shaft that fit into slots on a corresponding shaft, enabling both to rotate together.

assertive: Inclined to bold or confident assertion; aggressively self-assured.

Addis Ababa: The capital and largest city of Ethiopia, in the center of the country on a plateau more than 2,440 m (8,000 ft) above sea level. Captured by the Italians in 1936 and made the capital of Italian East Africa, it was retaken by the Allies in 1941 and returned to Ethiopian sovereignty.

basil: An aromatic annual herb (Ocimum basilicum) in the mint family, native to Asia and Africa and widely cultivated for its leaves.

fautor: A favorer; a patron; one who gives countenance or support.

ardor: Intensity of emotion, especially strong desire, enthusiasm, or devotion. synonym:passion.

cylinder: The surface generated by a straight line intersecting and moving along a closed plane curve, the directrix, while remaining parallel to a fixed straight line that is not on or parallel to the plane of the directrix.

buffer: A person who killed sound horses in order to sell their hides.

caper: A leap; a skip or spring, as in dancing or mirth, or in the frolic of a kid or lamb, or a child; hence, a sportive or capricious action; a prank.

heterodoxy: The condition or quality of being heterodox.

graffiti: Drawings or inscriptions made on a wall or other surface, usually so as to be seen by the public.

speleologist: One who is concerned in the exploration and study of caves; a student of speleology.

burro: A small donkey, especially one used as a pack animal.

Karachi: A city of southern Pakistan on the Arabian Sea. Developed as a trading center in the early 1700s, it passed to the British in 1843 and was the capital of newly independent Pakistan from 1947 until 1959.

paraphrenia: In pathology, disorder of the mind.

fortress: A fortified place, especially a large, permanent military stronghold that often includes a town.

exemplar: One that is worthy of imitation; a perfect example or model. synonym:ideal.

epitome: A representative or perfect example of a class or type.

succulent: Full of juice or sap; juicy.

campanology: The art or study of bell casting and ringing.

draw: To cause to move after or toward one by applying continuous force; drag: synonym:pull.

dubious: Fraught with uncertainty or doubt; undecided.

woodbine: Any of various climbing vines, especially a European honeysuckle (Lonicera periclymenum) having yellowish flowers.

biopsy: The removal and examination of a sample of tissue from a living body for diagnostic purposes.

muckrake: To search for and expose misconduct in public life.

centerboard: A movable keel in a sailboat that can be pivoted upward to reduce the boat's draft in shallow water.

graceful: Showing grace of movement, form, or proportion.

Rio de Janeiro: A city of southeast Brazil on Guanabara Bay, an arm of the Atlantic Ocean. The city's name, Portuguese for “River of January,” reflects the fact that the first European explorers to visit the bay, in January 1502, believed it was the mouth of a river. The city, founded in 1565, was the capital of Brazil from 1763 until 1960, when the government was transferred to Brasília.

undertone: An underlying or implied tendency or meaning; an undercurrent.

soutache: A narrow flat braid in a herringbone pattern, used for trimming and embroidery.

lipogrammatic: Pertaining to the writing of lipograms; also, of the nature of a lipogram.

bobbery: A squabble; a row; a disturbance: as, to kick up a bobbery.

abeyance: The condition of being temporarily set aside; suspension.

hierarchy: A group of persons or things organized into successive ranks or grades with each level subordinate to the one above.

tactician: One who is skilled in the planning and execution of military tactics.

pastorate: The office, rank, or jurisdiction of a pastor.

smew: A small Eurasian diving duck (Mergellus albellus), the male of which has white and black plumage and a white crest.

isallobar: A line on a weather map connecting places having equal changes in atmospheric pressure within a given period of time.

prelapsarian: Of or relating to the period before the fall of Adam and Eve.

strategist: One who is skilled in strategy.

sclaff: To scrape or strike the ground with a golf club behind the ball before hitting it.

elevon: A control surface on an airplane that combines the functions of an elevator and an aileron.

trudge: To walk in a laborious, heavy-footed way; plod.

pillory: A wooden framework on a post, with holes for the head and hands, in which offenders were formerly locked to be exposed to public scorn as punishment.

Faustian: Of or pertaining to Faust, especially his abandonment of values in order to pursue knowledge.

wane: To decrease gradually in size, number, strength, or intensity.

carious: Having caries, especially of the teeth; decayed.

allotrope: A structurally differentiated form of an element that exhibits allotropy.

nisei: an American whose parents were Japanese immigrants

-ize: A suffix of Greek origin, forming, from nouns or adjectives, verbs meaning to be or do the thing denoted by the noun or adjective.

coinage: The right or process of making coins.

cove: A small sheltered bay in the shoreline of a sea, river, or lake.

aboulomania: Paralysis of the will; pathological indecisiveness.

quinquagenarian: A person 50 years old, or in his or her fifties.

nutraceutical: A food or naturally occurring food supplement thought to prevent disease or have other beneficial effects on human health.

syncope: The shortening of a word by omission of a sound, letter, or syllable from the middle of the word; for example, bos'n for boatswain.

ichneumon: Any of numerous parasitic wasps of the family Ichneumonidae, with larvae that are parasitoids of other insects and females that have long ovipositors.

patent: A grant made by a government that confers upon the creator of an invention the sole right to make, use, and sell that invention for a set period of time.

kakapo: A nocturnal, flightless New Zealand parrot (Strigops habroptila) with greenish plumage.

beech: Any of various deciduous trees of the genus Fagus having smooth gray bark, alternate simple leaves, and three-sided nuts enclosed in prickly burs, including F. sylvatica of Europe and its many cultivated forms, and F. grandifolia of eastern North America.

Angel Falls: A waterfall in the Canaima National Park, Venezuela; the highest waterfall in the world.

misoneism: Hatred or fear of change or innovation.

remunerate: To pay (a person) a suitable equivalent in return for goods provided, services rendered, or losses incurred; recompense.

ingratiate: To bring (oneself, for example) into the favor or good graces of another, especially by deliberate effort.

octastyle: Having eight frontal columns in the portico, as in some Greek temples.

Cuba: An island country in the Caribbean Sea south of Florida. Originally settled by Arawak Indians, it was claimed for Spain by Columbus in 1492 and was colonized beginning in 1511. Spain relinquished its control of Cuba in 1898 as a result of the Spanish-American War, and following a three-year occupation by US forces, the island became self-governing in 1902. Fulgencio Batista dominated the government of Cuba from 1933 until 1959, when a revolution led by Fidel Castro established a Marxist-Leninist state. Havana is the capital and the largest city.

siciliano: A dance of the peasants of Sicily in rather slow movement, accompanied with singing.

parasite: An organism that lives and feeds on or in an organism of a different species and causes harm to its host.

sovereignty: Supremacy of authority or rule as exercised by a sovereign or sovereign state.

despotism: Rule by or as if by a despot; absolute power or authority.

despotic: Pertaining to or of the nature of a despot or despotism; unlimited; arbitrary; tyrannical: as, a despotic ruler; despotic government or power; a despotic will.

ragstone: The weathered first bed or upper layer of a quarry in England. Also raggstone.

soliloquize: To utter or put into the form of a soliloquy.

histrionic: Of or relating to actors or acting.

hoary: Gray or white with or as if with age.

comparative: Relating to, based on, or involving comparison.

clothing: Clothes considered as a group; wearing apparel.

terreplein: A platform or level ground surface on which heavy guns are mounted.

vervet: Any of several African monkeys of the genus Chlorocebus, having a black face with white cheek tufts, a yellowish-brown or greenish coat, and a long tail.

salsify: A European plant (Tragopogon porrifolius) in the composite family, having grasslike leaves, purple flower heads, and an edible taproot.

intercalate: To insert (a day or month) in a calendar.

Tobago: An island of Trinidad and Tobago in the southeast West Indies northeast of Trinidad. Originally inhabited by Caribs, the island was held as a colony at various times by the Dutch, Spanish, British, and French before being finally ceded to Britain in 1814. Tobago was united (1898) with Trinidad to form the colony of Trinidad and Tobago, which gained independence in 1962.

adversaria: A miscellaneous collection of notes, remarks, or selections; a commonplace-book; memoranda or annotations.

schlockmeister: One who produces or deals in inferior or shoddy goods or material.

foramen: An opening or orifice, as in a bone or in the covering of the ovule of a plant.

phalanger: Any of various small arboreal marsupials of the family Phalangeridae of New Guinea, Australia, and adjacent islands, having a long tail and dense woolly fur.

eolith: A crude stone artifact, such as a flake.

Irish bull: A statement containing an incongruity or a logical absurdity, usually unbeknown to the speaker. “With a pistol in each hand and a sword in the other” is an Irish bull.

weigela: Any of various deciduous shrubs of the genus Weigela of Asia, especially W. florida, widely cultivated for its pink, white, or red flowers.

Saudi: A person from Saudi Arabia or of Saudi Arabian descent.

mimesis: The imitation or representation of aspects of the sensible world, especially human actions, in literature and art.

devolve: To pass on or delegate to another.

peripeteia: A sudden change of events or reversal of circumstances, especially in a literary work.

sloven: One who is habitually careless in personal appearance or work.

vassal: A person who held land from a feudal lord and received protection in return for homage and allegiance.

obtuse: Lacking quickness of perception or intellect.

vapor: The gaseous state of a substance that is liquid or solid at room temperature.

shrew: Any of various small, chiefly insectivorous mammals of the family Soricidae, resembling a mouse but having a long pointed snout and small eyes and ears.

cosmorama: A view or series of views of the world; specifically, an exhibition of a number of drawings, paintings, or photographs of cities, buildings, landscapes, and the like, in different parts of the world, so arranged that they are reflected from mirrors, the reflections being seen through a lens.

expedient: Suitable or efficient for accomplishing a purpose.

regale: To provide with great enjoyment; entertain. synonym:amuse.

immolation: The title of the eucharistic preface in the Gallican liturgy: so called because it is an introduction to the sacrifice of the mass. See preface, 2.

factious: Given to, characterized by, or promoting internal dissension. synonym:insubordinate.

changeling: A child secretly exchanged for another.

deface: To mar or spoil the appearance or surface of; disfigure.

hoki: A marine fish (Macruronus novaezelandiae) of southwest Pacific waters, having a silvery-blue body with a tapering tail and often used for manufactured food products.

harvest-home: The time of gathering the harvest; the bringing home of the harvest; hence, any opportunity for making advantage or gain.

Bihari: A native or inhabitant of Bihar.

bankshall: In the East Indies: A warehouse.

rouleau: A small roll, especially of coins wrapped in paper.

prefigure: To suggest, indicate, or represent by an antecedent form or model; presage or foreshadow.

plenipotentiary: Invested with or conferring full powers.

basilisk: A legendary serpent or dragon with lethal breath and glance.

forage: Plant material that livestock graze or that is cut and fed to them.

floruit: Used to indicate the period during which a person lived or a school or movement was most active or flourishing.

banhammer: The power of a sysop to block a user or potential user from participating at a website.

Niger: A country of west-central Africa. The Tuareg and Hausa established states in the late Middle Ages, and the region was dominated by the Songhai and Bornu empires in the 1500s. Niger came under the French sphere of influence after the Conference of Berlin (1884–1885) and was made a separate colony within French West Africa in 1922. It achieved independence in 1960. Niamey is the capital and the largest city.

balsa: A tropical American tree (Ochroma pyramidale) having soft wood that is very light in weight and is used as a substitute for cork in insulation, floats, and crafts such as model airplanes.

savoir-faire: The ability to say or do the appropriate or graceful thing in social situations.

intrinsic: Of or relating to the essential nature of a thing; inherent.

trajectory: The path of a projectile or other moving body through space.

uncle: The brother of one's mother or father.

niece: The daughter of one's brother or sister or of the brother or sister of one's spouse.

spoon-meat: Food that is or has to be taken with a spoon; liquid food; figuratively, food for babes or weaklings.

resort: To turn to or make use of a person, strategy, or course of action for help or as a means of achieving something.

Quincy: A city of western Illinois on a bluff above the Mississippi River.

condemn: To express strong disapproval of: synonym:criticize.

chyron: Graphics or words at the bottom of a TV screen usually unrelated to the current viewing content.

durra: A variety of sorghum widely cultivated in dry regions of Africa and Asia for its grain.

aspinwall: a port city at the Caribbean entrance to the Panama Canal

rahu: In Hindu mythology, the demon that is supposed to be the cause of the eclipses of the sun and moon.

eschar: A dry scab or slough formed on the skin as a result of a burn or by the action of a corrosive or caustic substance.

incommunicado: Without the means or right of communicating with others.

perorate: To conclude a speech with a formal recapitulation.

happy: Enjoying, showing, or marked by pleasure, satisfaction, or joy. synonym:glad.

supplement: Something added to complete a thing, make up for a deficiency, or extend or strengthen the whole.

benevolent: Characterized by or given to doing good.

lordship: Used with Your, His, or Their as a title and form of address for a man or men holding the rank of lord.

tocher: The dowry which a wife brings to her husband by marriage.

cohort: A group or band of people.

dandle: To move (a small child) up and down on the knees or in the arms in a playful way.

sundog: A small halo, sometimes resembling part of a rainbow, near the horizon just off the parhelic circle.

galumph: To move or run clumsily or heavily.

tilt: A canopy or an awning for a boat, wagon, or cart.

isomorph: An object, organism, or substance exhibiting isomorphism.

distinctive: Serving to identify; distinguishing or characteristic.

cates: Provisions; food; viands; especially, luxurious food; delicacies; dainties.

azimuth: The horizontal angular distance from a reference direction, usually the northern point of the horizon, to the point where a vertical circle through a celestial body intersects the horizon, usually measured clockwise. Sometimes the southern point is used as the reference direction, and the measurement is made clockwise through 360°.

stretto: A close succession or overlapping of statements of the subject in a fugue, especially in the final section.

kapellmeister: A leader or conductor of a musical group such as an orchestra.

repudiation: The act of repudiating or the state of being repudiated.

demimonde: A class of women supported by wealthy lovers and considered to be promiscuous or otherwise unrespectable.

juvenilia: Works, particularly written or artistic works, produced in an author's or artist's youth.

pastoral: Of or relating to shepherds or herders.

diffusion: The process of diffusing or the condition of being diffused.

deregulate: To free from regulation, especially to remove government regulations from.

bureaucracy: Administration of a government chiefly through bureaus or departments staffed with nonelected officials.

stromuhr: An instrument for measuring the velocity of blood flow.

cytolysis: The dissolution or destruction of a cell.

hermitage: The habitation of a hermit or group of hermits.

cyclothymia: A mood disorder characterized by alternating periods of elevated and depressed mood.

tokonoma: A niche or an alcove in a Japanese home for displaying a flower arrangement, kakemono, or other piece of art.

inviscate: To daub or smear with glutinous matter.

iridocyclitis: Inflammation of the iris and the ciliary body of the eye.

kabaragoya: The water monitor, a reptile with scientific name Varanus slavator

allusive: Containing or characterized by indirect references.

overindulgence: The gratification of one's appetite or desires to an intemperate degree.

scientism: The collection of attitudes and practices considered typical of scientists.

glottogonic: Relating to the origin of language or of languages.

ne plus ultra: The highest point, as of excellence or achievement; the ultimate.

Damocles: Greek courtier to Dionysius the Elder, tyrant of Syracuse, who according to legend was forced to sit at a banquet table under a sword suspended by a single hair to demonstrate the precariousness of a king's fortunes.

obiter: In passing; by the way; by the by; incidentally.

decorous: Characterized by or exhibiting decorum; proper.

reticent: Inclined to keep one's thoughts, feelings, and personal affairs to oneself. synonym:laconic.

acrimony: Bitter, sharp animosity, especially as exhibited in speech or behavior.

yew: Any of several poisonous evergreen coniferous trees or shrubs of the genus Taxus, having scarlet cup-shaped arils and flat needles that are dark green above and yellowish below. Yews contain compounds used in medicine and are often grown as ornamentals.

defame: To damage the reputation, character, or good name of (someone) by slander or libel. synonym:malign.

populism: A political philosophy supporting the rights and power of the people in their struggle against the privileged elite.

safe: Free from danger or injury; undamaged or unhurt.

since: From then until now or between then and now.

posse: A group of civilians called upon by a sheriff or other law enforcement official to assist temporarily in preserving the peace or pursuing and arresting a fugitive.

kantele: A stringed instrument of the zither family, used in the traditional music of Finland.

anathema: A formal ecclesiastical ban, curse, or excommunication.

embark: To cause to board a vessel or aircraft.

genuflect: To bend the knee or touch one knee to the floor or ground, as in worship.

mephitic: Pertaining to mephitis; foul; noxious; pestilential; poisonous; stifling.

yurt: A circular, domed, portable tent used by nomadic peoples of central Asia.

hoke: To give an impressive but artificial, false, or deceptive quality to.

loom: To come into view as a massive, distorted, or indistinct image: synonym:appear.

pseudoplastic: Whose viscosity decreases as shear stress increases (as with paint and ketchup, for example).

agriology: The comparative study of the customs of man in his uncivilized state.

newel: A vertical support at the center of a circular staircase.

arborvitae: Any of several North American or eastern Asian evergreen trees or shrubs of the genus Thuja, having flattened branchlets with opposite, scalelike leaves and small cones. They are grown as ornamentals and for timber.

mongoose: Any of various carnivorous mammals of the family Herpestidae, native to Asia, Africa, and southern Europe and introduced elsewhere, having a slender agile body and a long tail, and noted for the ability to seize and kill venomous snakes.

birch: Any of various deciduous trees or shrubs of the genus Betula, native to the Northern Hemisphere and having unisexual flowers in catkins, alternate, simple, toothed leaves, and bark that often peels in thin papery layers.

parfait: A dessert made of cream, eggs, sugar, and flavoring frozen together and served in a tall glass.

arthroscopy: Examination of the interior of a joint, such as the knee, using a type of endoscope that is inserted into the joint through a small incision.

chase: A rectangular steel or iron frame into which pages or columns of type are locked for printing or plate making.

The Gambia: a narrow republic surrounded by Senegal in West Africa

prehensile: Able to seize, grasp, or hold, especially by wrapping around an object.

caconym: A taxonomic name that is unacceptable for linguistic reasons.

apparatchik: A member of a Communist apparat.

argyle: A knitting pattern of varicolored, diamond-shaped areas on a solid background.

maintop: A platform at the head of the mainmast on a square-rigged vessel.

pelycosaur: Any of various extinct, chiefly carnivorous synapsids of the Carboniferous and Permian Periods, including the dimetrodon and other species with saillike structures along the back.

saltigrade: Moving by leaping; saltatorial, as a spider; specifically, of or pertaining to the Saltigradæ.

stitchwort: Any of several low-growing plants of the genus Stellaria of the pink family, having small white flowers with five deeply notched petals.

deuteron: The nucleus of a deuterium isotope of hydrogen, composed of a proton and a neutron, regarded as a subatomic particle with unit positive charge.

daybed: A bed used for rest during the day; a lounge or sofa.

cosmos: The universe regarded as an orderly, harmonious whole.

plout: To wade or flounder through water or mire.

anachronism: The representation of someone as existing or something as happening in other than chronological, proper, or historical order.

fawn: To exhibit affection or attempt to please, as a dog does by wagging its tail, whining, or cringing.

touché: Used to acknowledge a hit in fencing or a successful criticism or an effective point in argument.

elicit: To call forth, draw out, or provoke (a response or reaction, for example): synonym:evoke.

impetuosity: The quality or condition of being impetuous.

misogynist: One who hates or mistrusts women.

facially: In a facial manner; with reference to the face.

alexipharmic: Acting as a means of warding off disease; acting as a remedy; prophylactic.

precinct: A subdivision or district of a city or town under the jurisdiction of or patrolled by a specific unit of its police force.

syncretism: Reconciliation or fusion of differing systems of belief, as in philosophy or religion, especially when success is partial or the result is heterogeneous.

triptych: A work, such as an altarpiece, consisting of three painted or carved panels that are hinged together.

exempt: To free from an obligation, duty, or liability to which others are subject.

whitelash: backlash by white racists against black civil rights advances

Trump: A surname, a metonymic occupational name for a trumpeter

concede: To acknowledge, often reluctantly, as being true, just, or proper; admit: synonym:acknowledge.

frangible: Capable of being broken; breakable. synonym:fragile.

colossal: Of great size, extent, or amount; immense. synonym:enormous.

bate: To flap the wings wildly or frantically. Used of a falcon.

Democratic Party: One of the two major political parties in the United States, owing its origin to a split in the Democratic-Republican Party under Andrew Jackson in 1828.

Republican: Of or pertaining to the Republican Party of the United States.

role: A character or part played by a performer.

doth: The third person singular indicative present of do.

manufactroversy: The deliberate presentation of a largely uncontroversial matter as subject to substantive dispute in order to further a particular ideological or political agenda.

qoph: The 19th letter of the Hebrew alphabet.

sheqel: A currency unit of both ancient and modern Israel.

MP3: An MPEG standard used especially for digitally transmitting music over the Internet.

ceviche: Raw fish marinated in lime or lemon juice with olive oil and spices and served as an appetizer.

carr: A bog or marsh; marshy ground, swampland.

circumduce: In Scots law, same as circumduct, 4.

mollify: To calm the anger of; soothe or appease. synonym:pacify.

cavort: To bound or prance about in a sprightly manner; caper.

ballot: A sheet of paper or a card used to cast or register a vote, especially a secret one.

gaur: A large, dark brown wild ox (Bos gaurus) of tropical woodlands of South and Southeast Asia.

Cher: A short form of the female given name Cherilyn.

bleacher: One that bleaches or is used in bleaching.

recommend: To praise or commend to another as being worthy or desirable; endorse.

bioprocess: A technique that produces a biological material, such as a genetically engineered microbial strain, for commercial use.

Querétaro: A city of central Mexico northwest of Mexico City. An ancient pre-Aztec settlement, it was conquered by the Spanish in 1531. Emperor Maximilian was executed nearby in 1867.

maieutic: Of or relating to the aspect of the Socratic method that induces a respondent to formulate latent concepts through a dialectic or logical sequence of questions.

streusel: A crumblike topping for coffee cakes and rich breads, consisting of flour, sugar, butter, cinnamon, and sometimes chopped nutmeats.

vetch: Any of various herbs of the genus Vicia of the pea family, having pinnately compound leaves that terminate in tendrils and small, variously colored flowers.

potometer: An instrument for measuring the amount of water absorbed by a transpiring plant in a given time.

boletus: Any of various boletes of the genus Boletus, including both poisonous species and edible species such as the porcini mushroom.

quietist: One who believes in or practises quietism: applied especially [capitalized] to a body of mystics (followers of Molinos, a Spanish priest) in the latter part of the seventeenth century.

levity: Humor, merriment, or a lack of seriousness, especially when inappropriate.

feretory: A receptacle to hold the relics of saints; a reliquary.

nihilist: One who believes in nothing; one who advocates the metaphysical doctrine of nihilism.

Ecatepec de Morelos: A city of central Mexico near Mexico City. It occupies the site of an Aztec kingdom established in the 1100s.

freemason: A member of the Free and Accepted Masons, an international fraternal and charitable organization with secret rites and signs.

latitudinarian: Holding or expressing broad or tolerant views, especially in religious matters.

infer: To conclude from evidence or by reasoning.

indri: A large arboreal lemur (Indri indri) of eastern Madagascar, having very long legs and a rudimentary tail.

tweenager: A young human being that is not yet technically a teenager (being less than thirteen years old), but starting to act like one—generally eight to twelve years old.

indictment: A set of written criminal charges issued against a party, where a grand jury, under the guidance of a prosecutor, has found that sufficient evidence exists to justify trying the party for that crime.

epidiascope: A machine for projecting the images of opaque objects or transparencies on a screen.

wholesome: Conducive to or indicative of good health or well-being; salutary: synonym:healthy.

breadth: The measure or dimension from side to side; width.

Guadalajara: A city of west-central Mexico west-northwest of Mexico City. A major commercial center, it is Mexico's second largest city.

cost: An amount paid or required in payment for a purchase; a price.

stuff: The material out of which something is made or formed; substance.

noumenon: In the philosophy of Kant, an object as it is in itself independent of the mind, as opposed to a phenomenon.

soul-cake: A cake of sweetened bread formerly distributed at church doors on All Souls' day. See soul-paper.

concinnity: Harmony in the arrangement or interarrangement of parts with respect to a whole.

temerarious: Presumptuously or recklessly bold; rash or reckless: synonym:reckless.

maxixe: A Brazilian dance in a rapid 2/4 time, influenced by the tango and polka.

innuendo: An indirect or subtle, usually derogatory implication in expression; an insinuation.

traction: The act of drawing or pulling, especially the drawing of a vehicle or load over a surface by motor power.

ghastly: Causing shock, revulsion, or horror; terrifying.

pantywaist: A child's undergarment consisting of a shirt and pants buttoned together at the waist.

partridge: Any of various plump-bodied game birds of several genera in the family Phasianidae, native to Eurasia and Africa and introduced elsewhere.

Lithuania: A country of north-central Europe on the Baltic Sea. Settled perhaps as early as 1500 BC, the area was unified in the 1200s and became one of the largest states of medieval Europe. Lithuania merged with Poland in 1569 but was absorbed into Russia by three partitions of Poland (1772, 1793, and 1795). The independent country of Lithuania existed from 1918 to 1940, when it became a constituent republic of the USSR. Occupied by Germany from 1941 to 1944, it reverted to Soviet rule after World War II and was known as the Lithuanian Soviet Socialist Republic before achieving independence in 1991. Vilnius is the capital and the largest city.

rood screen: In medieval churches, an often openwork wall-like screen separating the choir from the nave and extending upward to the rood beam.

forsake: To give up (something formerly held dear); renounce.

vortex: A whirling mass of water or air that sucks everything near it toward its center.

holler: A common vulgar form of hollo.

estranged: Simple past tense and past participle of estrange.

séance: A meeting of people to receive spiritualistic messages.

barghest: A goblin in English folklore, often appearing in the shape of a large dog and believed to portend imminent death or misfortune.

spackle: Any powder that when mixed with water forms a plastic paste used to fill cracks and holes in plaster.

shellac: A purified lac in the form of thin yellow or orange flakes, often bleached white and widely used in varnishes, paints, inks, sealants, and formerly in phonograph records.

logophobia: fear of words or of talking

impute: To relate (something, usually something bad) to a particular cause or source; place the fault or responsibility for: synonym:attribute.

motherlode: The main, central lode of a natural resource, near which smaller deposits of the same ore etc. exist.

Halloween: October 31, celebrated in the United States, Canada, and the British Isles by children going door to door while wearing costumes and asking for treats and playing pranks.

heart-scald: Heartburn; figuratively, a feeling of shame or aversion.

Wallis and Futuna: An overseas territory of France in Oceania. Official name: Territory of the Wallis and Futuna Islands.

Wallis: An alternative name (the German name) for Valais (the French name).

Holocaust: The systematic mass murder (genocide) of 6 million Jews perpetrated by Nazi Germany shortly before and during World War II.

basho: a sumo tournament of any kind

ephedra: Any of various usually shrubby gymnosperms of the genus Ephedra, having jointed green stems and small scalelike leaves, some species of which are used as a source of ephedrine.

allopathist: One who practises medicine according to the principles and rules of allopathy; an allopath.

amygdalin: A glycoside, C20H27NO11, commonly found in seeds and other plant parts of many members of the rose family, such as kernels of the apricot, peach, and bitter almond, which breaks down into hydrocyanic acid, benzaldehyde, and glucose.

quale: A property, such as whiteness, considered independently from things having the property.

guidon: A small flag or pennant carried as a standard by a military unit.

aigrette: An ornamental tuft of upright plumes, especially the tail feathers of an egret.

epos: A number of poems, not formally united, that treat an epic theme.

anuran: An amphibian of the order Anura; a frog or toad.

dysmorphia: Any of various psychological disorders whose sufferers believe that their body is wrong or inadequate, such as anorexia, bulimia, and muscle dysmorphia ("bigorexia").

axon: The usually long process of a nerve fiber that generally conducts impulses away from the body of the nerve cell.

statice: A genus of gamopetalous plants, of the order Plambagineæ, type of the tribe Staticeæ.

textuary: Of, relating to, or contained in a text; textual.

rhetoric: The art or study of using language effectively and persuasively.

epithalamium: A lyric ode in honor of a bride and bridegroom.

epitomize: To make an epitome of; sum up.

disempower: To deprive of power or influence.

orchestrate: To compose or arrange (music) for performance by an orchestra.

prime minister: A chief minister appointed by a ruler.

chauffer: In chem., a small furnace, a cylindrical box of sheet-iron, open at the top, with a grating near the bottom. See chafer, 4.

red-tapist: A clerk in a public office.

secessionist: One who maintains the principle of secessionism; specifically, in United States history, one who took part in or sympathized with the attempt of the Southern States, in 1860–65, to withdraw from the Union; an inhabitant of a Southern State who aided or sympathized with the secession movement.

avo: A current subsidiary coin of Macao, Timor, equivalent to .42 of a cent.

Nagorno-Karabakh: A mountainous region of western Azerbaijan. It was ceded to Russia by Persia in the early 1800s and organized as an autonomous region within Azerbaijan by the Soviets (1923). Conflict between Azeris and the majority ethnic-Armenian population in the 1980s resulted in Nagorno-Karabakh's unilateral declaration of independence in 1991. A ceasefire was declared in 1994.

grosgrain: A closely woven silk or rayon fabric with narrow horizontal ribs.

phlegm: Thick, sticky, stringy mucus secreted by the mucous membrane of the respiratory tract, as during a cold or other respiratory infection.

sheikh: A man respected for his piety or religious learning.

alewife: A North American fish, Clupea vernalis, from 8 to 10 inches long, resembling a small shad, but much inferior to it as food. It is taken in large numbers with that fish.

pygostyle: In ornithology, the vomer or plowshare bone of a bird's tail, consisting of a number of caudal vertebraæ ankylosed together for the support of the tail-feathers, and possessed by nearly all birds.

millennium: A span of one thousand years.

Saint Pierre and Miquelon: A French island group and overseas territory in the northern Atlantic Ocean south of Newfoundland, Canada. The two main islands include Saint Pierre, site of the capital, also named Saint Pierre, and Miquelon, the largest of the islands. Settled by Basque and Norman fishermen in 1604, the islands were taken by the British three times and finally awarded to France in 1814. They are the sole remnants of the once vast French territory in North America.

alphanumerically: In an alphanumeric manner; using alphanumeric characters.

collectivity: The quality or condition of being collective.

eminent: Well-known and respected, especially for achievement in a particular field: synonym:famous.

purpose: The object toward which one strives or for which something exists; an aim or goal: synonym:intention.

grogram: A coarse, often stiffened fabric made of silk, mohair, wool, or a blend of them.

frontless: Without a face or front; figuratively, without shame or modesty; not diffident; shameless.

iguazu: a large waterfall on the border between Argentina and Brazil

gab: To talk idly or incessantly, as about trivial matters.

prerequisite: Required or necessary as a prior condition.

kingdom: A political or territorial unit ruled by a sovereign.

lustrum: A ceremonial purification of the entire ancient Roman population after the census every five years.

craquelure: The distinctive pattern of hairline cracks in the surface of an old painting

gallinipper: A large biting mosquito, especially Psorophora ciliata of the Americas.

bete noire: Something especially hated or dreaded; a bugbear.

boulevardier: A sophisticated, socially active man who frequents fashionable places.

grandiloquent: Speaking or expressed in a lofty style; bombastic; pompous.

woebegone: Feeling, showing, or expressing deep sorrow, grief, or wretchedness: synonym:sad.

peoplehood: The condition of being a people or one of a people.

captivity: The state or period of being imprisoned, confined, or enslaved.

meal-pock: A meal-bag; a bag carried by beggars to hold the meal received in charity.

United Arab Emirates: A country of eastern Arabia, a federation of seven sheikhdoms on the Persian Gulf and the Gulf of Oman. Converted to Islam in the 7th century, the area later became a base for pirates and was known as the Pirate Coast into the 19th century. The British signed a series of truces with the ruling sheikhs between 1820 and 1892, and the area became known as the Trucial States or Trucial Oman. After World War II Britain granted internal autonomy to the sheikhdoms or emirates, with the United Arab Emirates being formed in 1971 after Britain withdrew from the area completely. Abu Dhabi is the capital.

vichyssoise: A thick creamy potato soup flavored with leeks or onions, usually served cold.

krait: Any of several highly venomous snakes of the genus Bungarus of South and Southeast Asia, having a generally black body with brightly colored bands.

marauder: One who marauds; a rover in quest of booty or plunder; a plunderer; especially, one of a number of soldiers or of an organized band engaged in spoliation.

shaw: A thicket; a small wood or grove.

palingenesis: The doctrine of transmigration of souls; metempsychosis.

wraith: An apparition of someone that is believed to appear as a portent just before that person's death.

banshee: A female spirit in Gaelic folklore believed to presage, by wailing, a death in a family.

barefaced: Having no covering over the face.

dyad: Two individuals or units regarded as a pair.

cryptogam: A member of a formerly recognized taxonomic group that included all seedless plants and plantlike organisms, such as mosses, algae, ferns, lichens, and fungi.

scrofula: A form of tuberculosis affecting the lymph nodes, especially of the neck, that is most common in children and is usually spread by unpasteurized milk from infected cows.

etagere: A piece of furniture with open shelves for displaying ornaments

levet: A musical call or strain intended to arouse or excite; a blast of a trumpet to awaken soldiers in the morning.

glossary: A list of often difficult or specialized words with their definitions, often placed at the back of a book.

dose: A specified quantity of a therapeutic agent, such as medicine, prescribed to be taken at one time or at stated intervals.

genial: In anatomy, pertaining to the chin; situated on the chin; mental.

inexorable: Impossible to stop, alter, or resist; inevitable.

elutriate: To purify, separate, or remove (ore, for example) by washing, decanting, and settling.

prosody: The study of the metrical structure of verse.

Indonesia: A country of southeast Asia in the Malay Archipelago including Sumatra, Java, Sulawesi, the Moluccas, parts of Borneo, New Guinea, and Timor, and many smaller islands. First settled by Austronesian-speaking peoples from the Asian mainland, the islands were the site of kingdoms allied with India before the arrival of Arab traders who introduced Islam, which became the dominant religion after the 1300s. The Dutch East Indies Company controlled the territory from 1602 to 1799, when authority was turned over to the government of the Netherlands. In 1945 Indonesia declared its independence, which was finally achieved in 1949. Jakarta, on Java, is the capital and the largest city.

espadrille: A shoe usually having a fabric upper part and a sole made of a flexible material, such as rope or rubber.

prestidigitator: One who practises prestidigitation; a prestigiator; a juggler.

hoik: a wild hook shot played without style

quorum: The minimal number of officers and members of a committee or organization, usually a majority, who must be present for valid transaction of business.

xyster: A surgical instrument for scraping bones.

nugae: Trifles; things of little value; trivial verses.

squamous: Covered with or formed of scales; scaly.

calypso: A terrestrial orchid (Calypso bulbosa) native to northern temperate regions, having a rose-pink flower with an inflated pouchlike lip usually marked with white, purple, and yellow.

colubrine: Of, relating to, or resembling a snake.

harum-scarum: Lacking a sense of responsibility; reckless.

queso: Melted cheese, used for instance as a dipping sauce.

sullied: defiled or tainted, soiled or stained.

prolific: Producing offspring or fruit in great abundance; fertile.

bootless: Being without advantage or benefit; useless. synonym:futile.

aqueduct: A pipe or channel designed to transport water from a remote source, usually by gravity.

clerisy: Educated people considered as a group; the literati.

chintzy: Of, relating to, or decorated with chintz.

porous: Admitting the passage of gas or liquid through pores or interstices.

odder: comparative form of odd: more odd

quid pro quo: Something that is given in return for something else or accepted as a reciprocal part of an exchange.

transpare: To appear through something else; be visible through something.

curvature: The act of curving or the state of being curved.

peristalsis: The wavelike muscular contractions of the digestive tract or other tubular structures by which contents are forced onward toward the opening.

cellblock: A group of cells that make up a section of a prison.

nebbish: A person regarded as weak-willed or timid.

quantitative: Expressed or expressible as a quantity.

stool: A backless and armless single seat supported on legs or a pedestal.

Dravidian: A large family of languages spoken especially in southern India and northern Sri Lanka that includes Tamil, Telugu, Malayalam, and Kannada.

volery: A large bird-cage or inclosure in which the birds have room to fly.

sibylline: Coming from, characteristic of, or relating to a sibyl.

agnomen: An additional cognomen given to a Roman citizen, often in honor of military victories.

blasphemous: Committing or tending to commit blasphemy.

forbearance: Tolerance and restraint in the face of provocation; patience.

fougasse: A flat, often leaf-shaped bread from Provence flavored with olive oil and topped with herbs, onions, or other items.

rattlebrain: A giddy, chattering person; a rattlepate.

hemolymph: The circulatory fluid of arthropods and some mollusks, analogous to blood and lymph in vertebrates.

incorrigible: Incapable of being corrected or reformed.

homochromatic: Of or characterized by one color; monochromatic.

pip pip: general greeting, mostly used by the upper classes.

gustatory: Of or relating to the sense of taste.

tome: One of the books in a work of several volumes.

ephapse: A point of contact or significant electrical influence between neurons, other than at a synapse.

ejido: In Spanish and Mexican law, a common; a public inclosed space of land.

femtobarn: A unit of area equal to a billionth of a millionth (10-15) of a barn

dubiety: The condition of being doubtful or uncertain. synonym:uncertainty.

flagitious: Characterized by extremely brutal or cruel crimes; vicious.

sich: A variant of such, formerly in good use, but now only dialectal.

thereof: Of or concerning this, that, or it.

overt: Open and observable; not hidden, concealed, or secret.

pediment: A wide, low-pitched gable surmounting the façade of a building in the Grecian style.

spur: A short spike or spiked wheel that attaches to the heel of a rider's boot and is used to urge a horse forward.

scapulimancy: Divination by means of a shoulder-blade: same as omoplatoscopy.

chrysography: The art of writing in letters of gold, practised by the writers of manuscripts in the early middle ages.

Demiurge: The subordinate being that fashions the perceptible world in the light of eternal ideas.

akathisia: a sensation of restlessness characterized by an inability to sit still or remain motionless, often as a side effect of psychiatric medications

just: Honorable and fair in one's dealings and actions: synonym:fair.

charily: In a chary manner; carefully; warily; sparingly; frugally.

theorbo: A large lute with a long neck having two sets of pegs, one set above and somewhat to the side of the other to accommodate a set of bass strings, used in the 1600s and early 1700s.

bioswale: A type of biofilter designed to remove silt and pollution from surface runoff, consisting of a swaled drainage course with gently sloped sides and filled with vegetation, compost and/or riprap.

masa: Dough made of dried corn that has been soaked in limewater then rinsed and ground, used especially in tortillas and tamales.

Bophuthatswana: A former autonomous black homeland of northern South Africa. It was granted nominal independence in December 1977 and was dissolved and reintegrated into South Africa under the 1994 constitution.

Tijuana: A city of extreme northwest Mexico on the US border south of San Diego. It is a popular tourist center.

gorge: A deep narrow passage with steep rocky sides; a ravine.

resign: To submit (oneself) passively; accept as inevitable.

retire: To withdraw from one's occupation or position, especially upon reaching a certain age; stop working.

granita: A granular dessert ice with a sugar-syrup base, usually flavored with fruit purée, coffee, or wine.

notice: The act of noting or observing; perception or attention.

gossamer: A fine film of cobwebs that is often seen floating in the air or is caught on bushes or grass.

docility: The quality of being docile; teachableness; readiness or aptness to learn; tractableness.

solutionism: The belief that all difficulties have benign solutions, often of a technocratic nature.

nexus: A means of connection; a link or tie.

paranoia: A psychotic disorder characterized by delusions of persecution with or without grandeur, often strenuously defended with apparent logic and reason.

succinctly: In a succinct manner; briefly; concisely; tersely: as, the facts were succinctly stated.

atrocity: Appalling or atrocious condition, quality, or behavior; monstrousness.

malevolence: The quality or state of being malevolent.

perverseness: The state or character of being perverse; disposition to be contrary, or to thwart or cross; corruption; wickedness.

pestilence: A usually fatal epidemic disease, especially bubonic plague.

agio: A commercial term in use, principally on the continent of Europe, to denote—

tawdry: Gaudy and cheap in nature or appearance. synonym:garish.

kincob: A rich stuff made in India with silk or silk and cotton and a free use of gold thread, silver thread, or both. Also kinkhab.

pinion: A small wheel with cogs or teeth which engage the teeth of a larger wheel with cogs or teeth, or sometimes only an arbor or spindle having notches or leaves, which are caught successively by the teeth of the wheel, and the motion thereby communicated. See also cut under pawl-press.

client: The party for which professional services are rendered, as by an attorney.

England: A division of the United Kingdom, in the southern part of the island of Great Britain. Inhabited in prehistoric times by Celtic peoples, it was subsequently invaded by Romans, Angles, Saxons, Jutes, Danes, and Normans. Acts of union joined England with Wales in 1536, with Scotland in 1707 to create the political entity of Great Britain, and with Ireland in 1801 to form the United Kingdom. London is the historic capital and the largest city.

lull: To cause to sleep or rest; soothe or calm.

buyer: One that buys, especially a purchasing agent for a retail store.

Tortola: An island of the West Indies east of Puerto Rico. It is the largest of the British Virgin Islands.

headrace: A watercourse that feeds water into a mill, water wheel, or turbine.

mass: A unified body of matter with no specific shape.

spleuchan: A pouch or pocket; especially, a tobacco-pouch.

cloy: To cause distaste or disgust by supplying with too much of something originally pleasant, especially something rich or sweet; surfeit.

décolletage: A low neckline on a woman's garment, especially a dress.

falter: To be unsteady in purpose or action, as from loss of courage or confidence; waver.

facelift: Plastic surgery to the face to remove wrinkles, fat or various signs of aging.

grope: To reach about uncertainly; feel one's way.

rigorism: Harshness or strictness in conduct, judgment, or practice.

fruitloopery: The use of scientific language inappropriately and without comprehension in order to increase believability of a concept.

anthophilous: Frequenting flowers, especially to feed on nectar or pollen.

ochlocracy: Government by the masses; mob rule.

flummadiddle: A baked main course pudding consisting of stale bread, pork fat, molasses, and spices including cinnamon and allspice. It was a part of early American cuisine, especially in New England.

argentite: A valuable silver ore, Ag2S, with a lead-gray color and metallic luster that is often tarnished a dull black.

anosmia: Loss of the sense of smell.

lewd: Preoccupied with sex and sexual desire; lustful.

anthozoan: Any of numerous cnidarians of the class Anthozoa, including the corals and sea anemones, that grow singly or in colonies and live as polyps, without a medusa stage.

effete: Characterized by extreme refinement or self-indulgence, often to the point of unworldiness or decadence:

vellicate: To twitch; cause to twitch convulsively, as the muscles and nerves of animals.

garish: Overly bright or ornamented, especially in a vulgar or tasteless way; gaudy.

afoul of: In or into collision, entanglement, or conflict with.

sect: A group of people forming a distinct unit within a larger group by virtue of certain refinements or distinctions of belief or practice.

blasphemy: Contemptuous or profane speech or action concerning God or a sacred entity.

plaintiff: The party that institutes a suit in a court.

swarming: The act of moving in a swarm, as bees from a hive.

toll: To sound (a large bell) slowly at regular intervals.

slathered: Simple past tense and past participle of slather.

life-car: A water-tight chamber used for conveying people ashore from a wreck.

Bahamas: An island country in the Atlantic Ocean east of Florida and Cuba comprising some 700 islands and islets and numerous cays. The country gained its independence from Great Britain in 1973. Nassau, on New Providence Island, is the capital and the largest city.

lasciviousness: Lascivious desires or conduct; lewdness; wantonness; lustfulness; looseness of behavior.
