sesquipedalianism: The condition of being sesquipedalian; the practice of using, or fondness for using, long words; also, a long word, or a style abounding in long words.

moderate: Being within reasonable limits; not excessive or extreme.

trend line: A line on a graph, drawn through points that vary widely, that shows the general trend of a real-world function; often generated using linear regression

benchmark: A standard by which something can be measured or judged.

posthumous: Occurring or continuing after one's death.

sheath: A usually close-fitting case or covering for a blade, as of a sword.

inflatus: A blowing or breathing into; hence, inspiration; afflatus: as, “ineffable inflatus,” Mrs. Browning.

drysalter: A dealer in salted or dried meats, pickles, sauces, etc.

astuteness: The quality of being astute; cunning; shrewdness.

organelle: A differentiated structure within a cell, such as a mitochondrion, vacuole, or chloroplast, that performs a specific function.

farceur: One who acts in or writes a farce.

providence: Care or preparation in advance; foresight.

hubbly: Full of hubbles; rough: as, hubbly ice; a hubbly road; hubbly skating or sleighing. The Advance, Feb. 18, 1886.

verisimilitude: The quality of appearing to be true or real. synonym:truth.

sunstone: A variety either of oligoclase or of orthoclase, or when green a microcline feldspar, showing red or golden-yellow colored reflections produced by included minute crystals of mica, göthite, or hematite.

assiduity: Persistent application or diligence; unflagging effort.

survivor: One who or that which survives after the death of another.

dislocation: The act or process of dislocating or the state of having been dislocated.

interstate: Involving, existing between, or connecting two or more states.

lordosis: An abnormal forward curvature of the spine in the lumbar region.

learning: The act, process, or experience of gaining knowledge or skill.

autophagy: The process of self-digestion by a cell through the action of enzymes originating within the same cell.

inpatient: A patient who is admitted to a hospital or clinic for treatment that requires at least one overnight stay.

Abernethy: A village in Perth and Kinross, Scotland

profligate: Given to or characterized by licentiousness or dissipation.

fusee: A usually cone-shaped pulley with a spiral groove, used in a cord- or chain-winding clock to maintain even travel in the timekeeping mechanism as the force of the mainspring lessens in unwinding.

federal: Of, relating to, or being a form of government in which a union of states recognizes the sovereignty of a central authority while retaining certain residual powers of government.

confederation: The act of forming into or becoming part of a confederacy.

consolidation: The act or process of consolidating.

castellated: Furnished with turrets and battlements in the style of a castle.

blandishment: Speech or action expressive of affection or kindness, and tending to win the heart; an artful caress; flattering attention; cajolery; endearment.

misspense: Wrong or useless expenditure; waste; ill employment.

pettifogger: A lawyer whose practice involves petty matters or who lacks sound legal judgment or skills.

apiarist: One who keeps bees, specifically one who cares for and raises bees for commercial or agricultural purposes.

prodigy: A person with exceptional talents or powers.

shoal: A large school of fish or other aquatic animals.

beurre blanc: A sauce made with butter, shallots, and vinegar, white wine, or lemon juice.

moki: The native name of two New Zealand fishes, the blue cod, Percis colias, and the bastard trumpeter, Latris ciliaris.

latescent: Becoming latent or obscure; not obvious to perception or cognizance.

latitudinarianism: The doctrine of a latitudinarian or of the latitudinarians; freedom or liberality of opinion in religion, philosophy, politics, etc.; laxity or indifference in regard to doctrines and forms.

eristic: Given to or characterized by disputatious, often specious argument.

testudinal: Pertaining to or resembling a tortoise.

centromere: The most condensed and constricted region of a chromosome, to which the spindle fiber is attached during mitosis.

viaticum: The Eucharist given to a dying person or one in danger of death.

hyleg: In astrology, the planet which rules the particular sign of the zodiac which happens at the instant of a nativity to be in the ascendant, or first twelfth part of the heavens above the eastern horizon; the apheta, prorogator, significator, or giver of life. Also spelled hileg.

alchemy: A medieval chemical philosophy having as its asserted aims the transmutation of base metals into gold, the discovery of the panacea, and the preparation of the elixir of longevity.

bunsen: same as bunsen burner; a gas burner used in laboratories; has an air valve to regulate the mixture of gas and air.

venerable: Commanding respect by virtue of age, dignity, character, or position.

magsman: A street swindler who preys on countrymen and simple persons.

brandish: To wave or flourish (something, often a weapon) in a menacing, defiant, or excited way. synonym:flourish.

precipitous: Resembling a precipice; extremely steep. synonym:steep.

magnate: A powerful or influential person, especially in business or industry.

fecundity: The quality or power of producing abundantly; fruitfulness or fertility.

honcho: A person who is in charge; a manager or leader.

investigate: To observe or inquire into in detail; examine systematically.

strophe: The first of a pair of stanzas of alternating form on which the structure of a given poem is based.

magpie: Any of various birds of the family Corvidae having a long tail and black, blue, or green plumage with white markings, and noted for their chattering call, especially Pica hudsonia, of western North America, and P. pica, of Eurasia and Africa.

excogitate: To consider or think (something) out carefully and thoroughly.

tracheophyte: : Any plant possessing vascular tissue (xylem and phloem), including ferns, conifers, and flowering plants.

herbaceous plant: a plant lacking a permanent woody stem; many are flowering garden plants or potherbs; some having medicinal properties; some are pests

ayapana: The native name of Eupatorium triplinerve, a Brazilian plant, natural order Compositæ, at one time believed to be a panacea. It is still considered to have some valuable medicinal properties.

galega: A genus of tall perennial leguminous herbs, with racemes of blue or white flowers and linear cylindrical pods.

sparse: Occurring, growing, or settled at widely spaced intervals; not thick or dense.

dynam: A unit of work, equal to a weight of one pound raised through one foot; a foot-pound.

stability: The state or quality of being stable, especially.

wretched: In a deplorable state of distress or misfortune; miserable.

force: The capacity to do work or cause physical change; energy, strength, or active power.

aquacade: An entertainment spectacle of swimmers and divers, often performing in unison to the accompaniment of music.

detente: the easing of tensions or strained relations (especially between nations), as by agreement, negotiation, or tacit understandings.

pablum: Trite, insipid, or simplistic writing, speech, or conceptualization.

nonplus: To put at a loss as to what to think, say, or do; bewilder.

ambigu: An entertainment or feast consisting, not of regular courses, but of a medley of dishes set on the table together.

ayahuasca: A hallucinogenic brew made from the bark and stems of a tropical South American vine of the genus Banisteriopsis, especially B. caapi, mixed with other psychotropic plants, used especially in shamanistic rituals by certain Amazonian Indian peoples.

Qom: A city of west-central Iran south-southwest of Tehran. It has been a Shiite Muslim center since early Islamic times and a pilgrimage site since the 1600s.

bigly: In a tumid, swelling, blustering manner; haughtily; arrogantly.

camp: Deliberate affectation or exaggeration of style, especially of popular or outdated style, for ironic or humorous effect.

boot: To be of help or advantage; avail.

assimilate: To consume and incorporate (nutrients) into the body after digestion.

persecution: The act or practice of persecuting on the basis of race, religion, gender, sexual orientation, or beliefs that differ from those of the persecutor.

temperament: The manner of thinking, behaving, or reacting characteristic of a specific person: synonym:disposition.

travertin: The calcareous deposit from springs which occurs in many localities in Italy, and is extensively quarried for use in building.

stamina: Latin plural of stamen, sometimes used as a singular (see stamen, 3).

Eumenides: A group of usually three goddesses, often described as benevolent fertility deities but identified in some traditions with the Furies.

rockfish: Any of various fishes living among rocks.

Platonism: The philosophy of Plato, especially insofar as it asserts ideal forms as an absolute and eternal reality of which the phenomena of the world are an imperfect and transitory reflection.

xylan: A yellow, water-soluble, gummy polysaccharide found in plant cell walls and yielding xylose upon hydrolysis.

wannigan: A box, usually made of wood, used to store food on canoe or sledding trips.

varia: A miscellany, especially of literary works.

intertrigo: A slight inflammation of the skin, occurring in creases or folds where one part of skin rubs on another.

synapse: The junction across which a nerve impulse passes from an axon terminal to a neuron, muscle cell, or gland cell.

pyxie: Either of two creeping prostrate evergreen plants (Pyxidanthera barbulata or P. brevifolia) having small white or pinkish flowers, native to the eastern United States.

lymphoid: Of or relating to lymph or the lymphatic tissue where lymphocytes are formed.

metate: A stone block with a shallow concave surface, used with a mano for grinding corn or other grains.

jink: To make a quick, evasive turn.

hydrocortisone: A steroid hormone, C21H30O5, produced by the adrenal cortex, that regulates carbohydrate metabolism and maintains blood pressure.

cabala: The theosophy or mystic philosophy of the Hebrew religion, which grew up mainly after the beginning of the tenth century, and flourished for many generations.

baba: A leavened rum cake, usually made with raisins.

emargination: The act of taking away the margin, or the state or condition of having the margin taken away.

jehu: A coachman; a driver; especially, one who drives furiously.

Yakima: A city of south-central Washington in the eastern foothills of the Cascade Range southeast of Seattle. It grew as a processing center for the fertile valley of the Yakima River, which flows about 340 km (210 mi) generally southeast to the Columbia River near Richland.

macronucleus: The larger of two nuclei present in ciliate protozoans, which controls nonreproductive functions of the cell, such as metabolism.

curry: To flavor or prepare with curry.

frisk: To search (a person) for something concealed, especially a weapon, by passing the hands quickly over clothes or through pockets.

zymogen: A substance from which an enzym may be formed by internal change. Also zymogene.

abbey: A monastery supervised by an abbot.

quadriplegic: Of, related to, or suffering from quadriplegia.

catena: A closely linked series, as of writings or geological features.

hardship: The condition of lacking necessities or comforts; privation or suffering.

polygon: A closed plane figure bounded by three or more line segments.

morals: motivation based on ideas of right and wrong.

parabola: A plane curve formed by the intersection of a right circular cone and a plane parallel to an element of the cone or by the locus of points equidistant from a fixed line and a fixed point not on the line.

pelagic: Of, relating to, or living in open oceans or seas rather than waters adjacent to land or inland waters.

digraph: A pair of letters representing a single speech sound, such as the ph in pheasant or the ea in beat.

dovecote: A compartmental structure, often raised on a pole, for housing domesticated pigeons.

trapezoid: A quadrilateral having two parallel sides.

sabretasche: A leather case or pocket worn by cavalry at the left side, suspended from the sword belt.

payee: One to whom money is paid.

slot: A narrow opening; a groove or slit.

endocarp: The inner layer of the pericarp of a fruit, which can be soft, such as the pulp of an orange, or hard, such as the stone of a peach.

mitigate: To make less severe or intense; moderate or alleviate. synonym:relieve.

pueblo: A communal building erected by certain Indian tribes of Arizona and New Mexico. It is often of large size and is usually built either of stone or adobe.

intently: In an intent manner; with close attention or application; with eagerness or earnestness; fixedly.

skittle: A British form of ninepins, in which a wooden disk or ball is thrown to knock down the pins.

list: A narrow strip, especially of wood.

potoroo: Any of several rat kangaroos of the genus Potorous of Australia, feeding primarily on plants and fungi.

fame: The state of being widely known, recognized, or of great popular interest.

luminous: Emitting light, especially in the dark; shining.

piebald: Spotted or patched, especially in black and white.

gluten: The mixture of proteins, including gliadins and glutelins, found in wheat grains, which are not soluble in water and which give wheat dough its elastic texture.

sage: One venerated for experience, judgment, and wisdom.

caffa: A rich stuff, probably of silk, in use in the sixteenth century.

longanimity: Calmness in the face of suffering and adversity; forbearance.

assumption: The act of taking to or upon oneself.

waney: Having a natural bevel (compare wane, n., 3); hence, making poor lumber from irregular ities of the surface, as a log.

Taino: A group of pre-Columbian indigenous inhabitants of the Bahamas, Greater Antilles, and some of the Lesser Antilles.

monadnock: A mountain or rocky mass that has resisted erosion and stands isolated in an essentially level area.

ferrotype: A positive photograph made directly on an iron plate varnished with a thin sensitized film.

silviculture: The care and cultivation of forest trees; forestry.

Big Brother: The nominal leader of Oceania in George Orwell's novel Nineteen Eighty-Four.

margent: To note or enter on the margin; margin.

entropy: For a closed thermodynamic system, a quantitative measure of the amount of thermal energy not available to do work.

Illyria: An ancient region of the Balkan Peninsula on the Adriatic coast. Occupied in prehistoric times by an Indo-European-speaking people, the area became the Roman province of Illyricum after the final conquest of the Illyrians in 35–33 BC. The name was revived by Napoleon for the provinces of Illyria (1809–1815) and retained for the kingdom of Illyria, a division of Austria from 1816 to 1849.

stoa: An ancient Greek covered walk or colonnade, usually having columns on one side and a wall on the other.

loge: A small compartment, especially a box in a theater.

precordium: The region of the body over the heart and thorax.

abysmal: Resembling an abyss in depth; unfathomable.

wharfage: The use of wharves or a wharf.

loof: The palm of the hand; also, the hand itself.

birther: A person who denies that Barack Obama was born in the United States and asserts that he therefore became president in violation of the requirements of the US Constitution.

squawk: To utter a harsh scream; screech.

unfathomable: Difficult or impossible to understand; incomprehensible.

pouch: A small bag often closing with a drawstring and used especially for carrying loose items in one's pocket.

catastrophic: Of, relating to, or involving a catastrophe.

stover: The dried stalks and leaves of a cereal crop, used as fodder after the grain has been harvested.

glutton: A person who eats or consumes immoderate amounts of food and drink.

sourly: In a sour manner, in any sense of the word sour.

stealthily: In a stealthy manner; by stealth.

cunning: Marked by or given to artful subtlety and deceptiveness.

stemma: A scroll recording the genealogy of an ancient Roman family; a family tree.

immutable: Not subject or susceptible to change.

truce: A temporary cessation or suspension of hostilities by agreement of the opposing sides; an armistice.

dichotic: Involving the use of both ears for the simultaneous hearing of tones of different pitch: opposed to diotic: as, dichotic audition; a dichotic experiment.

divine: Having the nature of or being a deity.

langur: Any of various leaf-eating Asian monkeys of the genera Presbytis, Semnopithecus, and Trachypithecus, having a slender body and a long tail.

surmise: To make a judgment about (something) without sufficient evidence; guess.

hadith: A report of the sayings or actions of Muhammad or his companions, together with the tradition of its chain of transmission.

costrel: A flat, pear-shaped drinking vessel with loops for attachment to the belt of the user.

ontology: The branch of metaphysics that deals with the nature of being.

livid: Discolored, as from a bruise; black-and-blue.

hullabaloo: A loud noise or a condition of noisy confusion. synonym:noise.

appetizing: Appealing to or stimulating the appetite.

Schnabel: United States composer (born in Austria) and pianist noted for his interpretations of the works of Mozart and Beethoven and Schubert (1882-1951)

Tenebrae: The office of matins and lauds sung on the last three days of Holy Week, with a ceremony of candles.

superfluous: Being beyond what is required or sufficient.

arboreal: Relating to or resembling a tree.

ideology: A set of doctrines or beliefs that are shared by the members of a social group or that form the basis of a political, economic, or other system.

dyspnea: Difficulty in breathing, often associated with lung or heart disease and resulting in shortness of breath.

chose: An item of personal property; a chattel.

choose: To select from a number of possible alternatives; decide on and pick out.

mandrake: A southern European plant (Mandragora officinarum) in the nightshade family, having greenish-yellow flowers and a branched root. This plant was once believed to have magical powers because its root resembles the human body.

screamer: One that screams, especially one that sings harshly or stridently.

oner: One indeed; one of the best; a person possessing some unique characteristic, particularly some special skill, or indefatigable in some occupation or pursuit; a good hand; an adept or expert.

lascivious: Given to or expressing lust; lecherous.

lackey: A liveried male servant; a footman.

calico: A tightly woven cotton cloth having a repeating, often floral design.

migrant: An organism, especially an animal, that moves from one region to another (as for breeding) or that has established itself in an area where it previously did not exist.

tump: To overturn. Often used with over.

pulverulent: Made of, covered with, or crumbling to fine powder or dust.

myrmidon: A soldier or a subordinate civil officer who executes orders of a superior without protest or pity; -- sometimes applied to bailiffs, constables, etc.

plenary: Complete in all respects; unlimited or full.

zoril: An African animal of the genus Zorilla.

deplorable: Worthy of severe condemnation or reproach.

atelier: A workshop or studio, especially for an artist or designer.

parlance: A particular manner of speaking; idiom.

expurgate: To remove erroneous, vulgar, obscene, or otherwise objectionable material from (a book, for example) before publication.

argot: A specialized vocabulary or set of idioms used by a particular group.

commissariat: A department of an army in charge of providing food and other supplies for the troops.

sectarian: Of, relating to, or characteristic of a sect.

shako: A stiff, cylindrical military dress hat with a metal plate or badge in front, a short visor, and a plume or pompom.

midinette: A female salesperson, a shopgirl, especially in Paris; a vacuous but fashionable young woman.

naseberry: The tree Achras Sapota, or its fruit. See Achras, bully-tree, chicle-gum, and sapodilla.

autotroph: An organism capable of synthesizing its own food from inorganic substances, using light or chemical energy. Green plants, algae, and certain bacteria are autotrophs.

metatarsal: Of or relating to the metatarsus.

camouflage: The concealing of personnel or equipment from an enemy by making them appear to be part of the natural surroundings.

sullen: Showing a brooding ill humor or silent resentment; morose or sulky.

geniality: The state or quality of being genial; especially, sympathetic cheerfulness or cordiality.

curt: Rudely brief or abrupt, as in speech or manner: synonym:gruff.

fire: A rapid, persistent chemical change that releases heat and light and is accompanied by flame, especially the exothermic oxidation of a combustible substance.

poll: The casting and registering of votes in an election.

portico: A porch or walkway with a roof supported by columns, often leading to the entrance of a building.

superiority: The state or character of being superior, in any sense.

toil: Something that binds, snares, or entangles one; an entrapment.

mock: To treat with ridicule or contempt; deride: synonym:ridicule.

ashram: A usually secluded residence of a religious community and its guru.

precept: A rule or principle prescribing a particular course of action or conduct.

chav: Used as a disparaging term for a poor or uneducated young person, especially one who behaves in a brash or vulgar manner and wears ostentatious clothing and jewelry.

zeroth: Of or relating to the ordinal number matching the number 0 in a series.

balaclava: A knitted cap covering the head and neck with an opening for the eyes or face, used as cold-weather gear especially by soldiers, mountain climbers, and skiers.

impatiens: Any of various plants of the genus Impatiens, especially several species that are widely cultivated for their colorful flowers and attractive foliage.

grackle: Any of several blackbirds of the family Icteridae found throughout the Americas, especially those of the genus Quiscalus, having iridescent blackish plumage.

flagon: A large vessel, usually of metal or pottery, with a handle and spout and often a lid, used for holding wine or other liquors.

hogan: A one-room Navajo structure traditionally built with the entrance facing east, used as a dwelling or for ceremonial purposes. Early hogans were made of earth-covered poles, with later models often built of logs, stones, and other materials.

spirit: A force or principle believed to animate living beings.

epidemic: Spreading rapidly and extensively by infection and affecting many individuals in an area or a population at the same time.

reality: The quality or state of being actual or true.

snub: To ignore or behave coldly toward; slight.

sentinel: One that keeps guard; a sentry.

nebulium: A supposed gaseous element assumed to account for the brilliant green lines in the spectrum of the nebulæ. Thus far it has not been detected on the earth, or in any of the heavenly bodies except the nebulæ.

babushka: A woman's headscarf, folded triangularly and worn tied under the chin.

duvet: A quilt, usually with a washable cover, that may be used in place of a bedspread and top sheet.

legume: A plant of the pea family.

spot: A mark on a surface differing sharply in color from its surroundings.

sullenly: In a sullen manner; gloomily; with moroseness.

agar: A gelatinous material derived from certain marine algae. It is used as a base for bacterial culture media and as a stabilizer and thickener in many food products.

reluctantly: In a reluctant manner: with opposition; unwillingly.

sistrum: A percussion instrument of ancient Egypt, Sumeria, and Rome consisting of metal rods or loops attached to a metal frame.

lout: An awkward and stupid person; an oaf.

countenance: Appearance, especially the expression of the face.

subspecies: A taxonomic subdivision of a species consisting of an interbreeding, usually geographically isolated population of organisms.

creperie: A crêperie; a restaurant that specializes in crêpes.

penetration: The act or process of piercing or penetrating something, especially.

polyptoton: In rhetoric, a figure consisting in the use of different cases or inflections of the same word, or of words of the same immediate derivation, in the same context.

surplice: A loose-fitting, white ecclesiastical gown with wide sleeves, worn over a cassock.

agnostic: One who believes that it is impossible to know whether there is a God.

classics: the branch of learning concerned with study of the literary works of ancient Greece and Rome.

Tuvalu: An island country of the western Pacific Ocean north of Fiji. Organized as a British protectorate in 1892, the islands became part of the Gilbert and Ellice Islands Colony in 1916 and achieved independence in 1978. Funafuti is the capital.

patchouli: A small southeast Asian shrub (Pogostemon cablin) in the mint family, having leaves that yield a fragrant oil used in the manufacture of perfumes.

oculist: A physician who treats diseases of the eyes; an ophthalmologist.

fugu: Any of various pufferfishes that are used as food, especially in Japan, after the poisonous skin and organs have been removed.

shtetl: A small Jewish town or village in Eastern Europe, especially before World War II.

sirvente: A form of lyric verse of the Provençal troubadours satirizing political figures, personal rivals, or social morals.

stipple: To draw, engrave, or paint in dots or short strokes.

jalopy: An old, dilapidated motor vehicle, especially an automobile.

coruscate: To give forth flashes of light; sparkle and glitter.

bonce: A large marble for playing with.

imido: Pertaining to, containing, or combined with, the radical NH, which is called the imido group.

ruckle: To make a rattling noise; rattle.

Chile: A country of southwest South America with a long Pacific coastline. Originally inhabited by Araucanian Indian peoples, it was colonized by Spain in 1541 and declared its independence in 1818. Chile annexed mineral-rich territory from Bolivia and Peru following the War of the Pacific (1879–1884). After numerous coups d'état and periods of military rule in the 20th century, Chile reestablished democratic rule in 1990. Santiago is the capital and the largest city.

sousveillance: The recording of an activity from the perspective of a participant in the activity.

cankle: An obese or otherwise swollen ankle that blends into the calf without clear demarcation.

tentacular: Of or pertaining to a tentacle, in any sense; of the nature, structure, function, or appearance of a tentacle; adapted or used as a tactile organ; tentaculiform: as, tentacular character, movements, or formation.

forehead: The part of the face between the eyebrows, the normal hairline, and the temples.

shroud: A cloth used to wrap a body for burial; a winding sheet.

crotaline: Having a rattle, as a rattlesnake; specifically, pertaining to or having the characters of the Crotalinæ or Crotalidæ.

Bogotá: The capital and largest city of Colombia, in the central part of the country on a high plain in the eastern Andes. It was a center of Chibcha culture before the Spanish established a settlement in 1538.

naycation: A vacation period during which no travel or paid leisure activities are done.

gehenna: one of various hells in Abrahamic religions, being the hell into which sinners are cast after judgment for eternal suffering

hilt: The handle of a weapon or tool.

premonition: A presentiment of the future; a foreboding.

parietal: Relating to or forming the wall of a body part, organ, or cavity.

bilocation: Existence or the ability to exist simultaneously in two places.

Sweden: A country of northern Europe on the eastern Scandinavian Peninsula. The region was settled by Germanic tribes probably in Neolithic times, and by the 10th century AD the Swedes had extended their influence as far as the Black Sea. During the 14th century Sweden and Norway, and for a while Denmark, formed a union, but in the 16th century the Swedes revolted and established a separate state. By the 17th century Sweden was a major European power, controlling most of the Baltic coast. It lost much of its territory in the Great Northern War (1700–1721) but acquired Norway (1814) in the Napoleonic Wars, ruling it until 1905. Stockholm is the capital and the largest city.

malpractice: Performance, as by a physician or lawyer, that falls below the professional minimum standard of care or service for a patient or client, especially when legally actionable because an injury or loss has been suffered by the patient or client.

blurb: A brief publicity notice, as on a book jacket.

adage: A saying that sets forth a general truth and that has gained credit through long use. synonym:saying.

anecdotally: In an anecdotal manner; by means of a recounted incident.

apparitional: Kesembling an apparition; having the nature of a phantom: spectral.

iatroepidemic: A large-scale problem caused by a medical procedure or drug.

scowl: To wrinkle or contract the brow as an expression of anger or disapproval. synonym:frown.

madras: A lightweight, often plain-woven cotton cloth, usually with a plaid, striped, or checked pattern.

prognosis: A prediction of the probable course and outcome of a disease.

comply: To act in accordance with another's command, request, rule, or wish.

manichean: Of or pertaining to the Manicheans.

geekerati: An elite community of computer geeks.

strollerobics: An exercise routine for new mothers which incorporates their babies' strollers.

yottabyte: A unit of computer memory or data storage capacity equal to 1,024 zettabytes (280 bytes).

slug: Any of various terrestrial gastropod mollusks having a slow-moving slimy elongated body with no shell or with a flat rudimentary shell on or under the skin, usually found in moist habitats.

celesbian: A celebrity who is also famous for being a lesbian.

rubella: A mild contagious eruptive disease caused by a virus and capable of producing congenital defects in infants born to mothers infected during the first three months of pregnancy.

senility: The state of being senile; old age; especially, the weakness or imbecility of old age.

lesion: Any of various pathological or traumatic changes in a bodily organ or tissue, including tumors, ulcers, sores, and wounds.

myopia: A visual defect in which distant objects appear blurred because their images are focused in front of the retina rather than on it.

expediency: Appropriateness to the purpose at hand.

presentiment: A sense that something is about to occur; a premonition.

wormwood: Any of several aromatic plants of the genus Artemisia.

annotate: To furnish (a literary work) with critical commentary or explanatory notes; gloss.

corpuscle: An unattached body cell, such as a blood or lymph cell.

knaidel: A type of dumpling eaten by Jews during Passover

exedra: A usually curved outdoor bench with a high back.

recursive: Of or relating to a repeating process whose output at each stage is applied as input in the succeeding stage.

whim: A sudden or capricious idea; a fancy.

buccellation: The act of breaking into small pieces.

heebie-jeebies: A feeling of uneasiness or nervousness; the jitters.

litre: A small tree of Chili, Rhus caustica, with very hard wood, used for axletrees, cogs, and furniture.

mausoleum: A large stately tomb or a building housing such a tomb or several tombs.

einkorn: A type of wheat (Triticum monococcum syn. T. monococcum subsp. monococcum) typically having one grain per spikelet, grown in semiarid regions. It was domesticated by Neolithic peoples in the Near East and is now cultivated in Europe and southwest Asia.

septum: A thin partition or membrane that divides two cavities or soft masses of tissue in an organism.

praxis: Practical application or exercise of a branch of learning.

tenson: A contention in verse between rival troubadours, before a tribunal of love or gallantry; hence, a subdivision of a chanson composed by one of the contestants or competitors; also, one of the pieces of verse sung by the competitors, for which a peculiar meter was thought appropriate.

autological: Of a phrase (especially an adjective), possessing the property it describes.

permalancer: An employee who was originally hired on a freelance basis (on a fixed-term contract) but has become permanent (but not necessarily with the same benefits as a full-time employee)

okra: A tall tropical African annual plant (Abelmoschus esculentus) in the mallow family, widely cultivated in warm regions for its edible, mucilaginous green pods.

hepcat: A performer or devotee of swing and jazz, especially during the 1940s.

erumpent: Bursting through a surface or covering.

effervescent: Effervescing; having the property of effervescence; of a nature to effervesce.

rampart: A fortification consisting of an embankment, often with a parapet built on top.

throb: To beat rapidly or violently, as the heart; pound.

splenius: Either of two muscles of the back of the neck, extending from the upper vertebrae to the base of the skull, that rotate and extend the head and neck.

kama: A sickle-like weapon, originally used as a tool for cutting weeds.

Great Britain: An island off the western coast of Europe comprising England, Scotland, and Wales, and constituting the largest part of the United Kingdom. It is separated from the mainland by the English Channel and from Ireland by the Irish Sea.

caret: A proofreading symbol (⁁) used to indicate where something is to be inserted in a line of printed or written matter.

craniometry: Measurement of the skull to determine its characteristics as related to sex, race, or body type.

satsuma: A seedless mandarin orange originally cultivated in Japan.

pyx: A container in which wafers for the Eucharist are kept.

extend: To cause (something) to be longer, wider, or cover more area.

fabliau: A medieval verse tale characterized by comic, ribald treatment of themes drawn from life.

pily: In heraldry, divided into a number of piles set side by side.

pious: Earnestly compliant in the observance of religion; reverent or devout.

ious: A termination consisting of the suffix -ous with a preceding original or euphonic vowel i. It formerly alternated with -eous. See -eous and -ous.

gamin: An often homeless boy who roams about the streets; an urchin.

care: A concerned or troubled state of mind, as that arising from serious responsibility; worry.

pimento: Allspice, the berry of Pimenta officinalis (Eugenia Pimenta), a tree, native of the West Indies, but cultivated almost exclusively in Jamaica, whence called Jamaica pepper.

chamfer: To cut off the edge or corner of; bevel.

swash: A splash of water or other liquid hitting a solid surface.

monosyllable: A word or an utterance of one syllable.

baccalaureate: A farewell address in the form of a sermon delivered to a graduating class.

curator: One who manages or oversees, as the administrative director of a museum collection or a library.

ferment: Something, such as a yeast, bacterium, mold, or enzyme, that causes fermentation.

lend: To give or allow the use of temporarily on the condition that the same or its equivalent will be returned.

Ionia: An ancient region of western Asia Minor along the coast of the Aegean Sea. Greek settlers established colonies here before 1000 BC. The seaports of Ionia flourished from c. 8th century BC until the Turkish conquest of the 15th century AD.

epistemology: The branch of philosophy that examines the nature of knowledge, its presuppositions and foundations, and its extent and validity.

karaoke: A music entertainment system providing prerecorded accompaniment to popular songs that a performer sings live, usually by following the words on a video screen.

opuntia: Any of various cacti of the genus Opuntia of the Americas, having stems with flat or cylindrical jointed segments and small easily detached spines, and including the chollas and the prickly pears.

pith: The soft, spongy tissue in the center of the stems of most vascular plants, consisting mainly of parenchyma.

supra: A prefix of Latin origin, meaning ‘above,’ ‘beyond.’

baconer: A pig raised to produce bacon.

pleochroism: The property possessed by some crystals of exhibiting different colors, especially three different colors, when viewed along different axes.

swastika: An ancient cosmic or religious symbol formed by a Greek cross with the ends of the arms bent at right angles in either a clockwise or a counterclockwise direction.

makimono: A horizontal Japanese decorative scroll featuring pictures or calligraphy.

dojo: A school for training in Japanese arts of self-defense, such as judo and karate.

echelon: A formation of troops in which each unit is positioned successively to the left or right of the rear unit to form an oblique or steplike line.

leporine: Of or characteristic of rabbits or hares.

crazy quilt: A patchwork quilt of pieces of cloth of various shapes, colors, and sizes, sewn together in an irregular pattern.

cisgender: Identifying as having a gender that corresponds to the sex one has been assigned at birth; not transgender.

anticipate: To see as a probable occurrence; expect.

hispid: Covered with stiff or rough hairs; bristly.

hallelujah: Used to express praise or joy.

bougainvillea: Any of several woody shrubs or vines of the genus Bougainvillea of Central and South America, having small flowers surrounded by large usually bright red or purple bracts.

obelus: A mark (— or ÷) used in ancient manuscripts to indicate a doubtful or spurious passage.

ravish: To force (another) to have sexual intercourse; rape.

remissory: Pertaining to remission; serving or tending to remit; obtaining remission.

prescript: Something prescribed, especially a rule or regulation of conduct.

geck: To toss the head in derision or scorn, or from vanity or folly; deride; mock.

raffish: Cheaply or showily vulgar in appearance or nature; tawdry.

zeugmatography: A former proposed term for magnetic resonance imaging.

brachiopod: Any of numerous marine invertebrates of the phylum Brachiopoda, having a shell with two valves of unequal size enclosing an armlike lophophore used for feeding, and including many extinct species commonly found as fossils.

abbozzo: The dead or first coloring laid on a picture after the sketch has been blocked in.

ngaio: In New Zealand, Myoporum lætum, a shrub or small tree closely allied to the bastard sandalwood of Hawaii (M. Sandwicense) and the Australian blueberry-tree (M. serratum). It bears small edible drupes and its light, tough white wood is used for making gunstocks. In the South Island the name is generally corrupted to kaio.

comus: In late classical myth., a god of festive mirth.

disaffected: Resentful and rebellious, especially against authority.

moralist: A teacher or student of morals and moral problems.

withers: The high part of the back of a horse or other quadruped, located between the shoulder blades.

breech: The lower rear portion of the human trunk; the buttocks.

overhaul: To examine or go over carefully for needed repairs.

polytheism: The worship of or belief in more than one god.

simaruba: A genus of polypetalous trees, type of the order Simarubaceæ and tribe Simarubeæ.

vespertine: Of, relating to, or occurring in the evening.

pinafore: A sleeveless garment similar to an apron, worn especially by small girls as a dress or an overdress.

erratum: An error in printing or writing, especially such an error noted in a list of corrections and bound into a book.

sturdy: Having or showing rugged physical strength or robust health.

lazy susan: a revolving tray placed on a dining table

contumacy: Obstinate or contemptuous resistance to authority; stubborn rebelliousness.

skin-game: A game, as of cards, in which one player has no chance against another, as when the cards are stocked or other tricks are played to cheat or fleece; any confidence-game.

orthogonal: Relating to or composed of right angles.

maven: A person who has special knowledge or experience; an expert.

dissipated: Intemperate in the pursuit of pleasure; dissolute.

tremulous: Marked by trembling, quivering, or shaking.

Jamaica: An island country in the Caribbean Sea south of Cuba. Originally inhabited by Arawaks, it was visited by Columbus in 1494 and settled by the Spanish in 1509. The British captured the island in 1655, and it was formally ceded to Great Britain in 1670, becoming a crown colony in 1866. Jamaica became independent in 1962. Kingston is the capital and the largest city.

pelf: Wealth or riches, especially when dishonestly acquired.

bobber: One who or that which bobs.

serac: a sharp ridge of ice between crevasses of a glacier

hypermetropic: Pertaining to or affected with hypermetropia; far-sighted.

knell: To ring slowly and solemnly, especially for a funeral; toll.

eccentric: Departing from a recognized, conventional, or established norm or pattern. synonym:strange.

interment: The act or ritual of interring or burying.

generality: The state or quality of being general.

tronc: A monetary pool, in which tips are collected and later shared out between all staff, e.g. in a restaurant.

animalcule: A microscopic or minute organism, such as an amoeba or paramecium, usually considered to be an animal.

limbate: Having a distinct edge or margin, especially of a different color.

epergne: A large table centerpiece consisting of a frame with extended arms or branches supporting holders, as for flowers, fruit, or sweetmeats.

bugaboo: An object of often obsessive fear, anxiety, or irritation.

dexterous: Skillful in the use of the hands.

foppish: Of, relating to, or characteristic of a fop; dandified.

presumption: Behavior or attitude that is boldly arrogant or offensive; effrontery.

uptalk: A manner of speaking in which declarative sentences are uttered with a rising intonation as though they were questions.

paronymous: Allied by derivation from the same root; having the same stem; for example, beautiful and beauteous.

trolleyology: An area of philosophy dealing with the kind of moral dilemma typified by the trolley problem.

diabulimia: The manipulation of insulin dosage by a diabetic person in order to effect loss of weight

biopharming: The field of growing (usually genetically) altered plants for medicinal uses.

welfariat: The class of people who live on welfare payments.

cant: Angular deviation from a vertical or horizontal plane or surface; an inclination or slope.

Turin: A city of northwest Italy on the Po River west-southwest of Milan. An important Roman town, it was later a Lombard duchy and the capital of the kingdom of Sardinia (1720–1861). It was also the first capital of the new kingdom of Italy.

interrobang: A punctuation mark (‽) in the form of a question mark superimposed on an exclamation point, used to end a simultaneous question and exclamation.

nopal: Any of various cacti having edible stems, especially the prickly pears.

archaeoastronomy: The study of the knowledge, interpretations, and practices of ancient cultures regarding celestial objects or phenomena.

menopot: Abdominal fat present in post-menopausal women, forming a pot belly.

himbo: A physically attractive man who lacks intelligence; the male equivalent of a bimbo.

late: Coming, occurring, continuing, or remaining after the correct, usual, or expected time; delayed: synonym:tardy.

meme: A unit of cultural information, such as a cultural practice or idea, that is transmitted verbally or by repeated action from one mind to another.

decapitated: having had the head cut off.

coeducational: Relating or pertaining to coeducation: as, coeducational problems.

inexorably: In an inexorable manner; so as to be immovable by entreaty.

asperity: Roughness or harshness, as of surface, sound, or climate.

ladrone: In the Philippine Islands, among American soldiers, a hostile Filipino soldier or ‘insurgent.’

Gothic: Of or relating to the Goths or their language.

abridgment: The act of abridging or the state of being abridged.

strut: To walk with pompous bearing; swagger.

secret: Kept hidden from knowledge or view; concealed.

elastomer: Any of various polymers having the elastic properties of natural rubber.

masseter: A thick muscle in the cheek that closes the jaws during chewing.

collogue: To be on friendly or intimate terms with someone.

paparazzification: The process of making or becoming characteristic of the paparazzi.

satellite: An object launched to orbit Earth or another celestial body, as a device for reflecting or relaying radio signals or for capturing images.

afterdamp: An asphyxiating mixture of gases, primarily nitrogen and carbon dioxide, left in a mine after a fire or an explosion.

magnify: To increase the apparent size of (an object), especially by means of a lens, instrument, or device.

nutation: The act or an instance of nodding the head.

figment: Something invented, made up, or fabricated.

torta: The flat circular heap of ore spread out on the floor of the patio in a cake about 50 feet in diameter and a few inches in thickness, ready for amalgamation in the so-called patio process (which see, under process).

butea: A genus of leguminous plants, natives of the East Indies, containing three or four species, small trees or climbing shrubs, yielding a kind of kino known as butea gum or Bengal kino.

Tonga: A country in the southwest Pacific Ocean east of Fiji comprising about 150 islands, some 36 of which are inhabited. Long inhabited by Polynesians, the islands were sighted by the Dutch in 1616 and visited by the British navigator Capt. James Cook, who named them “The Friendly Islands” in the late 1700s. It became a British protectorate in 1900 and gained independence as a constitutional monarchy in 1970. Nuku'alofa is the capital and the largest city.

inveighed: Simple past tense and past participle of inveigh.

event: Something that takes place, especially a significant occurrence. synonym:occurrence.

trismus: A tonic spasm of the muscles of mastication, causing closure of the lower jaw, occurring as a manifestation of tetanus, either alone or in conjunction with other tonic muscular spasms; lockjaw.

limmer: A limehound; in general, a hound; in a later use, a mongrel hound.

inertia: The tendency of a body at rest to remain at rest or of a body in straight line motion to stay in motion in a straight line unless acted on by an outside force; the resistance of a body to changes in momentum.

glissando: A rapid slide through a series of consecutive tones in a scalelike passage.

schist: Any of various medium-grained to coarse-grained metamorphic rocks composed of laminated, often flaky parallel layers of chiefly micaceous minerals.

abjured: Simple past tense and past participle of abjure.

jeremiad: A literary work or speech expressing a bitter lament or a righteous prophecy of doom.

Vietnam: A country of southeast Asia in eastern Indochina on the South China Sea. It comprises the historical regions of Tonkin, Annam, and Cochin China, much of which was under Chinese control from the 3rd century BC to the 15th century AD. Portuguese traders arrived in 1535, and the area came under French influence in the mid-19th century as part of French Indochina. After the fall of the French garrison at Dien Bien Phu in 1954, it was partitioned into North Vietnam and South Vietnam. The Vietnam War (1959–1975) grew out of the attempt by Communist Vietcong guerrillas backed by North Vietnam to overthrow the US-supported regime in the south. The South Vietnamese government collapsed in 1975, and the country was reunited in 1976. Hanoi is the capital and Ho Chi Minh City the largest city.

effigy: A crude figure or dummy representing a hated person or group.

inherited: tending to occur among members of a family usually by heredity.

scroyle: A fellow; especially, a mean fellow; a wretch.

Equatorial Guinea: A country of west-central Africa including islands in the Gulf of Guinea. Originally inhabited by Pygmy and Bantu peoples, it was settled by the Portuguese after 1472. Portugal ceded the largest island (Bioko) to Spain in 1778, and the mainland territory (Río Muni) came under Spanish rule in 1885. This colony, known as Spanish Guinea, gained independence in 1968. Malabo is the capital and the largest city.

jurymast: A temporary mast constructed when a vessel has been dismasted, usually in heavy weather.

en prise: Exposed to possible capture. Used of a chess piece.

cosmopolis: A large city inhabited by people from many different countries.

croquembouche: A French dessert made by piling profiteroles and other sweets in a tall shape, then pouring caramel over them to hold them in place.

misanthrope: One who hates or mistrusts humankind.

husbandman: One whose occupation is husbandry; a farmer.

blight: Any of numerous plant diseases resulting in sudden conspicuous wilting and dying of affected parts, especially young, growing tissues.

estovers: In law: So much of the wood and timber of the premises held by a tenant as may be necessary for fuel, for the use of the tenant and his family, while in possession of the premises, and so much as may be necessary for keeping the buildings and fences thereon in suitable repair. Bingham. See bote, 2 .

synchronized: Having attained synchronization, together, coordinated, combined.

BMX: A bicycle race on a dirt track with steep hills and sharp curves.

analog: Something that bears an analogy to something else; something that is comparable.

zooplasty: Surgical transfer of tissue from an animal to a human.

wave: To move freely back and forth or up and down in the air, as branches in the wind.

king post: A supporting post extending vertically from a crossbeam to the apex of a triangular truss.

tawse: A whip or leather thong used to drive a spinning top.

maquette: A usually scaled-down version or model of an intended work such as a sculpture or mural.

rugby: A sport where players can hold or kick an ovoid ball. The ball cannot be handled forwards and points are scored by touching the ball to the ground in the area past their opponent’s territory or kicking the ball between goalposts and over a crossbar.

adversity: A state of hardship or affliction; misfortune.

receptionist: An office worker employed chiefly to receive visitors and answer the telephone.

interested: Having or showing curiosity, fascination, or concern.

para: A prefix of Greek origin, meaning ‘from beside,’ ‘beside,’ ‘near,’ ‘by,’ etc. See etymology.

malleolus: Either of the two rounded protuberances on each side of the ankle, the inner formed by a projection of the tibia and the outer by a projection of the fibula.

apoplectic: Of, resembling, or produced by apoplexy.

auteur: A filmmaker, usually a director, who exercises creative control over his or her works and has a strong personal style.

subsume: To classify or include in a more comprehensive category or under a general principle.

lissome: Moving or able to move with grace and ease; lithe and graceful.

stratosphere: The region of the atmosphere above the troposphere and below the mesosphere.

fedora: A soft felt hat with a fairly low crown creased lengthwise and a brim that can be turned up or down.

torrid: Parched with the heat of the sun; intensely hot.

misandrist: one who hates men. Contrast misogynist and cf. misandry.

pickthank: To obtain by the methods of a pickthank.

cenotaph: A monument erected in honor of a dead person whose remains lie elsewhere.

insidious: Working or spreading harmfully in a subtle or stealthy manner.

asthenopia: Weakness or fatigue of the eyes, usually accompanied by headache and dimming of vision.

conceit: Unduly favorable estimation of one's own abilities or worth; overly positive self-regard.

illustrate: To clarify or explain, as by the use of examples or comparisons.

meridian: An imaginary great circle on the earth's surface passing through the North and South geographic poles.

extremity: The outermost or farthest point or portion.

paysagist: An artist or draftsman who works in landscape; a landscape-painter.

birkie: A man, especially one who is spirited and energetic.

preacher: One who preaches, especially one who publicly proclaims the gospel for an occupation.

antiquity: Ancient times, especially the times preceding the Middle Ages.

philosophy: The study of the nature, causes, or principles of reality, knowledge, or values, based on logical reasoning.

attain: To gain as an objective; achieve.

tactics: The study of the most effective ways of securing objectives set by strategy, as in deploying and directing troops, ships, and aircraft against an enemy.

conspire: To plan together secretly to commit an illegal or wrongful act or accomplish a legal purpose through illegal action.

potent: Possessing inner or physical strength; powerful.

acquainted: Known by or familiar with another.

eloquent: Capable of or characterized by eloquence.

abolition: The act of doing away with or the state of being done away with; annulment.

Slovakia: A landlocked country of central Europe. Settled by Slavic peoples c. 6th century AD, the region was conquered by Magyars in the early 10th century and was generally under Hungarian rule until 1918, when it became part of Czechoslovakia. Slovakia became a German puppet state during World War II. It was taken by the Soviets in 1945 and again made part of Czechoslovakia, which came under Communist rule in 1948. After the end of Communist rule in 1989, government leaders reached an agreement to separate the country into two fully independent republics. The Republic of Slovakia came into existence on January 1, 1993. Bratislava is the capital and largest city.

kryptonite: The one weakness of something or someone that is otherwise invulnerable, an Achilles' heel.

cryptology: The study of cryptanalysis or cryptography.

tartuffe: A hypocrite, especially one who affects religious piety.

post chaise: A closed, four-wheeled, horse-drawn carriage, formerly used to transport mail and passengers.

tostada: A tortilla or tortilla chip deep-fried until crisp.

hamshackle: To shackle, as a horse or a cow, by a rope or strap attached to the head and to one of the legs, to prevent it from running away or wandering too far; hence, to curb; restrain.

fastidious: Showing or acting with careful attention to detail.

descry: To catch sight of (something difficult to discern). synonym:see.

pennon: A long narrow banner or streamer borne upon a lance.

garth: A grassy quadrangle surrounded by cloisters.

prairie schooner: A covered wagon, drawn by horses or oxen, that was used by pioneers in crossing the North American prairies and plains.

orcein: A nitrogenous compound (C7H7NO3) formed from orcine and ammonia.

clique: A small exclusive group of friends or associates.

catalyst: A substance, usually used in small amounts relative to the reactants, that modifies and increases the rate of a reaction without being consumed in the process.

china: High-quality porcelain or other ceramic ware, originally made in China.

fret: One of several ridges set across the fingerboard of certain stringed instruments, such as guitars.

lantana: Any of various chiefly tropical shrubs or herbs of the genus Lantana, widely cultivated for their dense clusters of small colorful flowers.

infatuation: The act of infatuating, or the state of being infatuated; extravagant folly; fatuous devotion or passion: as, infatuation for an unworthy object.

bluebonnet: Any of several annual North American lupines having palmately compound leaves and blue flowers, especially Lupinus texensis, chiefly found in Texas.

avocado: A tropical American tree (Persea americana) having oval or pear-shaped fruit with leathery skin, yellowish-green flesh, and a large seed.

Houston: A city of southeast Texas near Galveston Bay. Founded in 1836 and named for Sam Houston, the city developed as a cotton market in the 1800s. It is now a major port and commercial center known for its aerospace and petroleum industries.

anodyne: Capable of soothing or eliminating pain.

malarkey: Exaggerated or foolish talk, usually intended to deceive.

piñata: A decorated container filled with candy and toys suspended from a height, intended to be broken by blindfolded children with sticks, and used as part of Christmas and birthday celebrations in certain Latin-American countries or at children's parties.

constitute: To be the elements or parts of; compose.

panada: A paste or gruel of bread crumbs, toast, or flour combined with milk, stock, or water and used for making soups, binding forcemeats, or thickening sauces.

intuitive: Of, relating to, or arising from intuition: synonym:instinctive.

edification: Intellectual, moral, or spiritual improvement; enlightenment.

disabuse: To free from a falsehood or misconception.

determined: Marked by or showing determination; resolute.

blue: The hue of that portion of the visible spectrum lying between green and indigo, evoked in the human observer by radiant energy with wavelengths of approximately 420 to 490 nanometers; any of a group of colors that may vary in lightness and saturation, whose hue is that of a clear daytime sky; one of the additive or light primaries; one of the psychological primary hues.

acclamation: A shout or salute of enthusiastic approval.

karoo: An arid plateau of southern Africa.

inculcate: To impress (something) upon the mind of another by frequent instruction or repetition; instill.

brigand: A robber or bandit, especially one of an outlaw band.

arraignment: In law, the act of arraigning; the act of calling and setting a prisoner before a court to answer to an accusation.

tights: A snug stretchable garment covering the body from the waist down, designed for general wear by women and girls.

fertilize: To cause the fertilization of (an ovum, for example).

pahoehoe: Lava with a smooth ropy surface.

orra: Odd; not matched; not appropriated; left over; occasional; incidental: as, an orra thing; an orra time.

Philadelphia: An ancient city northeast of the Dead Sea in modern-day Jordan. The chief city of the Ammonites, it was enlarged and embellished by Ptolemy II Philadelphus (285–246 BC) and named in honor of him. Amman, the capital of Jordan, is now on the site.

epistolary: Of or associated with letters or the writing of letters.

floorshow: A set of performances held in a nightclub during the course of an evening.

dotage: A deterioration of mental faculties associated with aging.

genealogy: A record or table of the descent of a person, family, or group from an ancestor or ancestors; a family tree.

ambo: A raised speaking stand in a church, especially such a stand in early Christian churches serving as a lectern or pulpit.

gavel: A sheaf of corn before it is tied up; a small heap of unbound wheat or other grain.

balneal: Of or relating to baths or bathing.

stultify: To cause to lose interest or feel dull and not alert.

investiture: The act or formal ceremony of conferring the authority and symbols of a high office.

puissant: Powerful; mighty; strong; vigorous; forcible: as, a puissant prince or empire.

chiaroscuro: The technique of using light and shade in pictorial representation.

aphasia: Partial or total loss of the ability to articulate ideas or comprehend spoken or written language, resulting from damage to the brain from injury or disease.

molly maguire: A member of a lawless secret association in Ireland, organized with the object of defeating and terrorizing agents and process-servers, and others engaged in the business of evicting tenants.

circuitous: Being or taking a roundabout, lengthy course.

accompaniment: A vocal or instrumental part that supports another, often solo, part.

compendium: A short but complete summary of something.

mendicant: Depending on alms for a living; practicing begging.

empyrean: The highest reaches of heaven, believed by the ancients to be a realm of pure fire or light.

wickiup: A frame hut covered with matting, as of bark or brush, used by nomadic Native Americans of North America.

tau cross: A cross in the form of a T.

radicle: The part of a plant embryo that develops into a root.

habilatory: Pertaining or relating to habiliments or clothing.

ghazwa: The battles in which the Islamic prophet Muhammad personally participated.

baa: To make a bleating sound, as a sheep or goat.

parauque: A bird (Nyctidromus albicollis) ranging from Texas to South America. It is allied to the night hawk and goatsucker.

gazpacho: A chilled soup made with chopped tomatoes, cucumbers, onions, peppers, and herbs.

carry: To hold or support while moving; bear.

mohs scale: a scale of hardness of solids; talc is 0 and diamond is 10; ordering is determined by which substance can scratch another substance

telos: The end of a goal-oriented process.

lampadrome: A race run by young men with lighted torches in their hands. He who reached the goal first, with his torch unextinguished, gained the prize.

excerpt: A passage or segment taken from a longer work, such as a literary or musical composition, a document, or a film.

abrogate: To abolish, do away with, or annul, especially by authority.

lift: To direct or carry from a lower to a higher position; raise.

quash: To put down or suppress forcibly and completely.

quandary: A state of uncertainty or perplexity. synonym:predicament.

view: An examination using the eyes; a look.

methylation: An alkylation process involving addition of, or substitution by, a methyl group.

idolothytic: Permitting the eating of meats sacrificed to idols.

snort: A rough, noisy sound made by breathing forcefully through the nostrils, as a horse or pig does.

ring: A circular object, form, line, or arrangement.

hiss: A sharp sibilant sound similar to a sustained s.

plagiarize: To reproduce or otherwise use (the words, ideas, or other work of another) as one's own or without attribution.

patois: A regional dialect, especially one without a literary tradition.

idealism: The act or practice of envisioning things in an ideal and often impractical form.

wisest: superlative form of wise: most wise. Most wise.

coerce: To pressure, intimidate, or force (someone) into doing something. synonym:force.

rancorous: Full of rancor; implacably spiteful or malicious; intensely virulent.

systematic: Characterized by, based on, or constituting a system.

pall: To become insipid, boring, or wearisome.

civilization: An advanced state of intellectual, cultural, and material development in human society, marked by progress in the arts and sciences, the extensive use of record-keeping, including writing, and the appearance of complex political and social institutions.

body: The entire material or physical structure of an organism, especially of a human or animal.

ginkgo: A deciduous, dioecious tree (Ginkgo biloba) native to China and having fan-shaped leaves used in herbal medicine. The female plants bear foul-smelling fleshy fruitlike structures containing edible seeds used in East Asian cuisine, while the male plants are often grown as ornamental street trees.

coup: A brilliantly executed stratagem; a triumph.

ambush: A sudden attack made from a concealed position.

epochal: Of or characteristic of an epoch.

punctilious: Strictly attentive to minute details of form in action or conduct. synonym:meticulous.

perspicuous: Clearly expressed or presented; easy to understand.

fulvescent: Somewhat tawny or fulvous in color; approaching or becoming tawny.

inveigle: To win over by coaxing, flattery, or artful talk.

rorqual: Any of several baleen whales of the family Balaenopteridae having longitudinal grooves on the throat and a small, pointed dorsal fin, and including the blue whale and the humpback whale.

kakemono: A Japanese scroll that displays painting or calligraphy, hung vertically on a wall.

Holocene: Of, relating to, or being the epoch of geologic time from about 10,000 years ago to the present, the more recent of the two epochs of the Quaternary Period. It began at the end of the last Ice Age and is characterized by the development of human civilizations.

voracity: The character of being voracious; greediness of appetite; voraciousness.

discalced: Barefoot or wearing sandals. Used of certain religious orders.

tonsure: The act of shaving the head or part of the head, especially as a preliminary to becoming a priest or a member of a monastic order.

holiday: A day free from work that one may spend at leisure, especially a day on which custom or the law dictates a halting of general business activity to commemorate or celebrate a particular event.

balladmonger: A seller or composer of ballads.

isohel: A line drawn on a map connecting points that receive equal amounts of sunlight.

lactometer: A device used to measure the specific gravity, and therefore the richness, of milk.

repugnant: Arousing disgust or aversion; offensive or repulsive.

martial law: Temporary rule by military authorities, imposed on a civilian population especially in time of war or when civil authority has broken down.

treason: The betrayal of allegiance toward one's own country, especially by committing hostile acts against it or aiding its enemies in committing such acts.

nimbus: A cloudy radiance said to surround a classical deity when on earth.

venality: The condition of being susceptible to bribery or corruption.

sinuous: Characterized by many curves or turns; winding.

empiricism: The view that experience, especially of the senses, is the only source of knowledge.

autodefenestration: The act of hurling oneself from a window.

intrados: The inner curve of an arch.

amice: A liturgical vestment consisting of an oblong piece of white linen worn around the neck and shoulders and partly under the alb.

narthex: A portico or lobby of an early Christian or Byzantine church or basilica, originally separated from the nave by a railing or screen.

palaeoclimatology: The scientific study of prehistoric climate of the Earth.

calafate: A Cuban name of the black oldwife, Melichthys piceus, a fish of the family Balistidæ.

auslese: A subcategory in the German wine labeling system; Auslese (literal meaning: "selected harvest") is the term for a late harvest wine and is a riper category than Spätlese in the Prädikatswein category of the Austrian and German wine classification. For more see Auslese

peso: A silver coin that was formerly used in Spain and Spanish America; a piece of eight.

enervating: causing the loss of strength or vigor.

peter: A kind of wine otherwise called peter-sec-me and peter-sameene.

tempestuous: Characterized by violent emotions or actions; tumultuous.

sterilize: To make free from live bacteria or other microorganisms.

pachydermia: A chronic disease marked by repeated attacks of dermatitis of erysipelatous form, with more or less phlebitis, lymphangitis, and lymphadenitis, accompanied and followed by hypertrophy and infiltration of the skin and subjacent tissues.

quench: To put out (a fire, for example); extinguish.

Thailand: A country of southeast Asia on the Gulf of Thailand (formerly the Gulf of Siam), an arm of the South China Sea. Various Thai kingdoms were founded from the 13th century on, frequently coming into conflict with neighboring Burmese and Cambodian powers. Siam remained an absolute monarchy until 1932, when the king was compelled to accept a constitution, and the country was renamed Thailand in 1939. Thailand was occupied by the Japanese in World War II, and most of its numerous postwar governments were controlled by the military. Bangkok is the capital and the largest city.

bourgeois: A person belonging to the middle class.

apothecary: One that prepares and sells drugs and other medicines; a pharmacist.

baneful: Causing harm, ruin, or death; harmful.

avulsion: The forcible tearing away of a body part by trauma or surgery.

apologetic: Offering or expressing an apology or excuse.

quirky: Abounding in quirks or twists; irregular; zigzag; quirkish.

fjord: A long, narrow, deep inlet of the sea between steep slopes.

invertase: An enzyme that catalyzes the hydrolysis of sucrose into glucose and fructose.

avulse: To separate, cut, or tear off by avulsion.

bailiff: A court attendant entrusted with duties such as the maintenance of order in a courtroom during a trial.

flacket: To flap about, as women's skirts; have the skirts flap about.

embellish: To make beautiful, as by ornamentation; decorate.

carapace: A hard bony or chitinous outer covering, such as the fused dorsal plates of a turtle or the portion of the exoskeleton covering the head and thorax of a crustacean.

score: A usually numerical record of a competitive event.

temporary: Lasting, used, serving, or enjoyed for a limited time.

beaten: Formed or made thin by hammering.

gerbil: Any of various small, mouselike rodents of the genus Gerbillus and other genera of the subfamily Gerbillinae, having long hind legs and a long tail and inhabiting arid regions of Africa and Asia.

gentrification: The restoration and upgrading of deteriorated urban property by middle-class or affluent people, often resulting in displacement of lower-income people.

diverb: A saying in which the two members of a sentence are contrasted; an antithetical proverb.

referent: A person or thing to which a linguistic expression refers.

exosphere: The outermost region of a planet's atmosphere.

mugwump: A person who acts independently or remains neutral, especially in politics.

analogous: Similar or alike in such a way as to permit the drawing of an analogy.

officious: Marked by excessive eagerness in offering unwanted services or advice to others.

ippon: a throw in judo in which the opponent is held on the back for 25 seconds

accretion: Growth or increase in size by gradual external addition, fusion, or inclusion.

gneiss: A banded or foliated metamorphic rock, usually of the same composition as granite.

alliaceous: Of or resembling onion, garlic, or similar plants of the genus Allium, particularly in taste and smell.

colloquy: A conversation, especially a formal one.

manumit: To free from slavery or bondage; emancipate.

debunk: To expose or ridicule the falseness, sham, or exaggerated claims of.

antonomasia: The substitution of a title or epithet for a proper name, as in calling a sovereign “Your Majesty.”

sonde: Any of various instruments, such as a radiosonde, used for measuring or testing physical conditions.

nerine: A genus of ornamental flowering bulbs of the monocotyledonous order Amaryllideæ and the tribe Amarylleæ, known by the versatile anthers, many biseriate ovules in each cell, filaments dilated at the base, and thong-like leaves.

tutelary: Being or serving as a guardian or protector.

Portugal: A country of southwest Europe on the western Iberian Peninsula and the Madeira Islands and the Azores in the northern Atlantic Ocean. Originally inhabited by the Lusitanians, a Celtiberian people, the mainland area was subsequently held by the Romans, the Visigoths, and the Moors before the establishment of an independent Christian kingdom in the 1100s. Portugal flourished as a maritime and colonial power in the 1400s and 1500s with holdings in Africa, India, Southeast Asia, and Brazil. Much of its empire was lost to the British and the Dutch in the 1600s and 1700s, and the remaining colonies became independent in the 1800s and 1900s. Lisbon is the capital and the largest city.

despicable: Deserving of contempt or scorn; vile.

sniper: A skilled military shooter detailed to spot and pick off enemy soldiers from a concealed place.

prevalent: Widely or commonly occurring, existing, accepted, or practiced. synonym:prevailing.

baisemain: A kissing of the hands; in the plural, compliments; respects.

subversive: Intending or intended to subvert an established order, especially to undermine or overthrow an established government.

nicety: The quality of showing or requiring careful, precise treatment.

nystagmus: A rapid, involuntary, oscillatory motion of the eyeball.

eviscerate: To remove the entrails of; disembowel.

summa: A comprehensive treatise, especially in philosophy or theology.

centesimate: To pick out one in a hundred of; inflict the punishment of centesimation upon.

precedent: An act or instance that may be used as an example in dealing with subsequent similar instances.

transitive: Expressing an action carried from the subject to the object; requiring a direct object to complete meaning. Used of a verb or verb construction.

thread: Fine cord of a fibrous material, such as cotton or flax, made of two or more filaments twisted together and used in needlework and the weaving of cloth.

Atalanta: A hunter who agreed to marry any man who could defeat her in a footrace. She was outrun by Hippomenes, who won by dropping along the course three golden apples, which she paused to pick up.

fellmonger: A dealer in fells or hides. Also felmonger.

sibilant: Of, characterized by, or producing a hissing sound like that of (s) or (sh).

interpolate: To insert or introduce between other elements or parts.

belated: Having been delayed; done or sent too late.

nepotism: Favoritism shown or patronage granted to relatives, as in business.

predominant: Having the most importance, influence, or force.

allied: Joined or united in a close relationship.

pyrotechny: The management and mechanical application of fire.

prove: To establish the truth or validity of (something) by the presentation of argument or evidence.

stannic: Relating to or containing tin, especially with valence 4.

gourami: Any of various freshwater fishes of Southeast Asia of the families Osphronemidae and sometimes Belontiidae, capable of breathing air and popular in home aquariums.

saltbox: A frame house with two stories in front and one in back, having a pitched roof with unequal sides, being short and high in front and long and low in back.

ambivalence: The coexistence of opposing attitudes or feelings, such as love and hate, toward a person, object, or idea.

guidepost: A post with a sign giving directions for travelers, usually placed at a crossroad.

maraud: To rove and raid in search of plunder.

problem: A question to be considered, solved, or answered.

apophantic: Containing or consisting of a declaration, statement, or proposition; declaratory.

ossify: To change into bone; become bony.

Cayman Islands: A British-administered island group in the Caribbean Sea northwest of Jamaica, including Grand Cayman, Little Cayman, and Cayman Brac. The islands were discovered by Columbus in 1503. Georgetown, on Grand Cayman, is the capital.

upgrade: To raise to a higher grade or standard.

diglot: Using, speaking, or written in two languages.

chewet: A kind of pie made from chopped substances.

guillemot: Any of several auks of the genus Cepphus of the northern Atlantic and Pacific Oceans, having black plumage with white markings.

spectrophotometer: An instrument used to determine the relative intensity of various wavelengths in a spectrum of light.

electrophorus: An apparatus for generating static electricity, consisting of a hard rubber disk that is given a negative charge by friction and a metal plate that is given a net positive charge by induction when in contact with the disk.

placed: Simple past tense and past participle of place.

repeal: To revoke or rescind, especially by the action of a legislature.

recuse: To disqualify or seek to disqualify (a judge or juror) from participation in the decision in a case, as for personal prejudice against a party or for personal interest in the outcome.

brocatel: A variety of ornamental marble, the most famous localities of which are in Italy and Spain.

negus: A beverage of wine, hot water, lemon juice, sugar, and nutmeg.

babied: Simple past tense and past participle of baby.

ecclesiastical: Of or relating to a church, especially as an organized institution.

beatification: The act of beatifying or of rendering or pronouncing happy; the state of being blessed; blessedness.

eureka: Used to express triumph upon finding or discovering something.

hunker: To squat close to the ground; crouch. Usually used with down:

tampered: Simple past tense and past participle of tamper.

aeolian: of, or relating to the wind.

rubato: Rhythmic flexibility within a phrase or measure; a relaxation of strict time.

New Orleans: A city of southeast Louisiana between the Mississippi River and Lake Pontchartrain. Founded in 1718, it became the capital of a French colony in 1722 and passed to the United States as part of the Louisiana Purchase of 1803. The city is known for its annual Mardi Gras celebrations and as the birthplace of jazz music. In 2005, New Orleans was devastated by Hurricane Katrina, which caused breaches in the protective levee system that resulted in widespread flooding and the evacuation of much of the city.

Towser: A given name for a dog.

mumblecore: An American independent film movement of the early twenty-first century, characterised by low-budget production, focus on personal relationships between twentysomethings, improvised scripts, and non-professional actors.

disdainful: Expressive of disdain; scornful and contemptuous. synonym:arrogant.

perplexed: Filled with confusion or bewilderment; puzzled.

pessimistic: Pertaining to, characterized by, or of the nature of pessimism, in any sense.

chiding: The act of reproving, rebuking, berating, or scolding; utterance of reproof or reproach.

trilith: A monument, or part of a monument, consisting of three large stones; especially, in prehistoric or megalithic antiquities, a group consisting of two upright stones with a lintel-stone resting upon them. Also trilithon.

regulate: To control or direct according to rule, principle, or law.

supererogatory: Performed or observed beyond the required or expected degree.

teapoy: A small table incorporating a tea chest.

hypermetric: Having one or more syllables in addition to those found in a standard metrical unit or line of verse.

attaint: To impart a stigma to; disgrace.

teal: Any of several small dabbling ducks, chiefly of the genus Anas, often having brightly marked plumage.

automagical: Automatic, but with an apparent element of magic. Commonly used in computer and other technology fields, referring to complex technical processes hidden from the view of users or operators. Includes a connotation of specialness and often implies pride on the part of the process creator (especially when the person using the word is the process creator). Sometimes, also used in sarcastic way, ironically implying an impossible process. A one-size-fits-all approach to automatic controls that replaces rather than supplements manual control, resulting in a product that is less flexible and more difficult to use.

desuetude: A state of disuse or inactivity.

synderesis: A technical term of the scholastic philosophy, signifying the innate principle in the moral consciousness of every man, which directs him to good and restrains him from evil.

cote-hardie: A garment worn by both sexes throughout the fourteenth century.

jitter: To be nervous or uneasy; fidget.

transmogrify: To change thoroughly, as into a different shape or form. synonym:convert.

ignominious: Characterized by or deserving shame or disgrace.

resile: To spring back, especially to resume a former position or structure after being stretched or compressed.
