Ohio: A state of the north-central United States south of Lake Erie. It was admitted as the 17th state in 1803. In prehistoric times Mound Builders inhabited the region, which was explored by La Salle in 1669. The French-British rivalry for control of the area led to the last of the French and Indian Wars (1754–1763), in which the French were defeated. Ohio was part of the vast area ceded to the United States by the Treaty of Paris in 1783 and became part of the Northwest Territory by the Ordinance of 1787. It became a separate territory in 1799. Columbus is the capital.

automation: The automatic operation or control of equipment, a process, or a system.

bawbee: A Scotch billon coin, weighing about 29 grains troy, first issued in 1542 by James V. of Scotland, and worth at that time 1½d. Scotch.

centime: A unit of currency that is equal to1/100of the primary unit of currency in many countries where French is spoken as an official language, including Algeria, Morocco, and Switzerland.

Burundi: A country of east-central Africa with a coastline on Lake Tanganyika. It was inhabited originally by the Twa, a Pygmy people, and later also by Hutus and Tutsis, the latter gaining political and economic dominance in the 19th century. The area formed part of German East Africa and later of Belgian-ruled Ruanda-Urundi before it became an independent kingdom in 1962 and was declared a republic in 1966. In the 1970s and again in the 1990s tens of thousands of people were killed in ethnic clashes between Hutus and Tutsis. Bujumbura is the capital and the largest city.

abased: In heraldry, the same as abaissé.

oxlip: A Eurasian primrose (Primula elatior) having yellow flowers clustered in a one-sided umbel.

acetaldehyde: A colorless, flammable liquid, C2H4O, used to manufacture acetic acid, perfumes, and drugs.

biofuel: A fuel, such as biogas or biodiesel, that is produced from renewable resources, especially plant biomass, vegetable oils, or treated municipal and industrial wastes.

United Kingdom: A country of western Europe comprising England, Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland. Beginning with the kingdom of England, it was created by three acts of union: with Wales (1536), Scotland (1707), and Ireland (1801). At the height of its power in the 1800s, it ruled an empire that spanned the globe. London is the capital and the largest city.

majolica: Tin-glazed earthenware that is often richly colored and decorated, especially an earthenware of this type produced in Italy.

posset: A spiced drink of hot sweetened milk curdled with wine or ale.

panmixia: Random mating within a breeding population.

diazepam: A drug, C16H13ClN2O, used to treat anxiety and as a sedative, skeletal muscle relaxant, and anticonvulsant.

accelerograph: An accelerometer equipped to measure and record ground motion during an earthquake.

San Francisco: A city of northern California on a peninsula between the Pacific Ocean and San Francisco Bay. It was founded as Yerba Buena in 1835 near the site of a Spanish presidio and mission built in 1776. The city grew into a major port during the gold rush of 1848, and survived a devastating earthquake and fire in 1906. Today it is the center of a large metropolitan area around San Francisco Bay.

vagrancy: The state of being a vagrant.

catchpenny: Designed and made to sell without concern for quality; cheap.

conga: A dance of Latin-American origin in which the dancers form a long winding line.

desideratum: Something considered necessary or highly desirable.

euthenics: The study of the improvement of human functioning and well-being by improvement of living conditions.

penguin: Any of various stout, flightless aquatic birds of the family Spheniscidae, of the Southern Hemisphere, having flipperlike wings and webbed feet adapted for swimming and diving, short scalelike feathers, and white underparts with a dark back.

Jotun: One of a race of giants who were adversaries of the gods.

BMW: Bayerische Motoren-Werke (Bavarian Motor Works), a manufacturer of motor vehicles.

celestial: Of or relating to the sky or physical universe as understood in astronomy.

decry: To condemn as wrong or reprehensible.

San Jose: A city of northern California south of San Francisco Bay. Founded in 1777, it served as state capital from 1850 to 1851 and is today the largest of the Silicon Valley cities.

account: A narrative or record of events.

USB: A serial bus standard used for transferring data to and from digital devices. USB devices such as mice and flash drives are often powered by their USB connection.

anti-imperialist: Pertaining to the ideas of the anti-imperialists.

diametrically: In a diametrical direction; directly; in an extreme degree.

Malibu: A district of Los Angeles, California, on Santa Monica Bay. It is a fashionable resort and residential area.

swarthy: Having a dark complexion or color.

kodachrome: A brand of photographic transparency bearing a positive color image.

brand: A trademark or distinctive name identifying a product, service, or organization.

telluric: Of or relating to Earth; terrestrial.

plebiscite: A direct vote in which the entire electorate is invited to accept or refuse a proposal.

aitiology: Another spelling, nearer the Greek, of ætiology.

funemployment: A period of unemployment spent pursuing recreational activities or hobbies.

manque: In roulette, one of the numbers from 1 to 18.

carceral: Of or belonging to a prison: as, “carceral endurance,”

redact: To draw up or frame (a proclamation, for example).

obtrude: To impose (oneself or one's ideas) on others with undue insistence or without invitation.

neutrality: The state or policy of being neutral, especially nonparticipation in war.

peal: A ringing of a set of bells, especially a change or set of changes rung on bells.

wraprascal: A loose greatcoat worn by people of elegance about 1740, in supposed imitation of the coarse coats of the poorer people; hence, any surtout or long outer garment.

eroticism: The quality of being erotic or being represented as erotic.

haute couture: The leading establishments or designers for the creation of exclusive fashions.

shivery: Easily falling into shivers or small fragments; not firmly cohering; brittle.

leeboard: One of a pair of movable boards or plates attached to the hull of a sailing vessel and lowered on the leeward side to reduce downwind drift.

rudas: A foul-mouthed old woman; a randy; a beldam; a hag.

swive: To perform the act of copulation with; have sexual intercourse.

louvre: An alternative spelling of louver in US English; the only spelling of this word in UK English.

loot: Valuables pillaged in time of war; spoils.

poke bonnet: A woman's bonnet in the shape of a hood, featuring a projecting rim on the front side for the purpose of shading the face.

dealfish: Any of several ribbonfishes of the genus Trachipterus, especially T. arcticus of the Atlantic Ocean, which can attain a length of 3 meters (9.8 feet).

campion: Any of several plants of the genera Lychnis and Silene native chiefly to the Northern Hemisphere and having variously colored flowers with notched or fringed petals.

tignon: an article of woman's headgear consisting of a piece of material tied in individual ways

boxiana: The annals of prize-fighting; the literature of, or gossip or anecdotes concerning, pugilism.

parsimony: Unusual or excessive frugality; extreme economy or stinginess.

kenspeckle: Same as kenspeck, and the more common form.

Yemen: A country of southwest Asia at the southern tip of the Arabian peninsula. It was ruled by various peoples, such as the Sabaeans, Himyarites, Romans, Ethiopians, and Persians, in ancient times. It was conquered in the 7th century AD by Muslim Arabs and became part of the Ottoman Empire in the 16th century. The northern part (known as Yemen or North Yemen) was established as an independent kingdom in 1918 and made a republic in 1962. The southern part consisted of several British protectorates in the late 1800s and early 1900s. Britain withdrew from the area in 1967, and South Yemen became independent soon after. The two united in May 1990. San‘a is the capital and the largest city.

ulna: The bone extending from the elbow to the wrist on the side opposite to the thumb in humans.

roquet: To hit (another player's ball) in croquet.

kvell: To feel or express pride about something or someone.

skilts: A sort of coarse, loose short trousers formerly worn in New England.

syntax: The study of the rules whereby words or other elements of sentence structure are combined to form grammatical sentences.

404: Not found, especially of a web page on the internet.

heredity: The genetic transmission of characteristics from parent to offspring.

monastery: A community of persons, especially monks, bound by vows to a religious life and often living in partial or complete seclusion.

nesh: To make soft, tender, or weak.

patriarchy: A social system in which the father is the head of the family.

workspace: An area used or allocated for one's work, as in an office.

yesteryear: The year before the present year.

filibuster: The obstructing or delaying of legislative action, especially by prolonged speechmaking.

molly: Any of several tropical and subtropical live-bearing fishes of the genus Poecilia of the Americas, often kept in home aquariums.

career: A chosen pursuit; a profession or occupation.

terrene: Of or relating to the earth; earthly.

grandiloquence: Pompous or bombastic speech or expression.

Iceland: An island country in the North Atlantic near the Arctic Circle. Norse settlers arrived c. 850–875, and Christianity was introduced c. 1000. Iceland passed to Norway in 1262 and, with Norway, to Denmark in 1380. In 1918 it became a sovereign state still nominally under the Danish king, until Icelanders voted for full independence in 1944. Reykjavík is the capital and the largest city.

Ababda: A nomadic Beja people of upper Egypt.

luthier: One that makes or repairs stringed instruments, such as violins.

scena: A subdivision or scene of an opera.

saithe: The pollock, or coalfish; -- called also sillock.

manqué: Unfulfilled or frustrated in the realization of one's ambitions or capabilities.

kif: A loose or powdered form of cannabis resin used especially for smoking.

revilement: The act of reviling; abuse; contemptuous or insulting language; a reproach.

sartorial: Of or relating to a tailor, tailoring, or tailored clothing.

ontogenesis: In biology, the history of the individual development of an organized being, as distinguished from phylogenesis, or the history of genealogical development, and from biogenesis, or life-development generally. Also ontogeny.

romanization: A making Roman; the act or system of causing to conform to Roman standards and institutions. Also spelled Romanisation.

against: In a direction or course opposite to.

convert: To change (something) into another form, substance, state, or product; transform.

Ecuador: A country of northwest South America on the Pacific Ocean. Once part of the Inca Empire, it was conquered by the Spanish in 1534 and later became subject to Peru and New Granada. The area achieved independence from Spain in 1822 but formed a part of Greater Colombia until 1830, when it became a separate country. Quito is the capital and Guayaquil the largest city.

enduro: A race, as of motorcycles, that tests endurance.

sample: A portion, piece, or segment that is representative of a whole.

gyve: A shackle or fetter, especially for the leg.

quassia: A tropical American shrub or small tree (Quassia amara) having bright scarlet flowers and yielding a fine-grained, yellowish-white wood.

megohm: A unit equal to one million ohms.

esbat: A Wiccan coven gathering other than one of the Sabbats. While a full moon ritual may be held during an esbat, esbats encompass coven business meetings, social occasions, and opportunities for merriment.

Peru: A country of western South America on the Pacific Ocean. Inhabited since at least the 9th millennium BC, it was the center of the Inca Empire after the 12th century AD. Francisco Pizarro's conquest of the Inca in 1533 led to the establishment in 1542 of the Spanish viceroyalty of Peru, which in time included Panama and all of Spanish South America except Venezuela. Peru achieved full independence from Spain in 1824. Lima is the capital and the largest city.

coquettish: Like a coquette; of or pertaining to or characterized by or practising coquetry.

greensward: Ground that is green with grass; turf.

impart: To grant a share of; bestow.

goatsucker: The European night-jar, Caprimulgus europœus: so called from tho vulgar notion that it sucks goats; by extension, any bird of the same genus, or of the family Caprimulgidœ.

monte: A card game in which two cards are chosen from four laid out face-up and a player bets that one of the two will be matched in suit by the dealer before the other one.

forint: The basic unit of currency of Hungary; subdivided into 100 fillér.

alpargata: In Spanish-speaking countries, a kind of sandal or low shoe with a hemp or rush sole and cloth upper.

tisane: An herbal infusion or similar preparation drunk as a beverage or for its mildly medicinal effect.

realm: A community or territory over which a sovereign rules; a kingdom.

cited: Simple past tense and past participle of cite.

sheik: In Arabia and other Mohammedan countries, an old man; an elder.

noisette: A small round piece of meat, especially a loin or fillet of lamb, veal, or pork.

arbitral: Of or relating to arbiters or arbitration.

procrustean: Producing or designed to produce strict conformity by ruthless or arbitrary means.

United States: A country of central and northwest North America with coastlines on the Atlantic and Pacific Oceans. It includes the noncontiguous states of Alaska and Hawaii and various island territories in the Caribbean Sea and Pacific Ocean. The area now occupied by the contiguous 48 states was originally inhabited by numerous Native American peoples and was colonized beginning in the 1500s by Spain, France, the Netherlands, and England. Great Britain eventually controlled most of the Atlantic coast and, after the French and Indian Wars (1754–1763), the Northwest Territory and Canada. The original Thirteen Colonies declared their independence from Great Britain in 1776 and formed a government under the Articles of Confederation in 1781, adopting (1787) a new constitution that went into effect after 1789. The nation soon began to expand westward. Growing tensions over the issue of black slavery divided the country along geographic lines, sparking the secession of the South and the Civil War (1861–1865). The remainder of the 1800s was marked by increased westward expansion, industrialization, and the influx of millions of immigrants. The United States entered World War II after the Japanese attack (1941) on Pearl Harbor and emerged after the war as a world power. Washington, DC, is the capital and New York the largest city.

cellaret: A case for holding bottles or decanters, as of wine, cordials, etc., sometimes also several liqueur-glasses.

cordially: With cordiality; heartily; earnestly; with real feeling or affection.

wayfarer: One who travels, especially on foot.

chavicha: An Alaskan Indian name of the Californian salmon or quinnat, Oncorhynchus chavicha. Also tchawytcha, chaoucha, choweecha, and chouicha.

anadromous: Migrating up rivers from the sea to breed in fresh water. Used of fish.

spectator: An observer of an event, especially a sports contest.

Haiti: A country of the West Indies comprising western Hispaniola and two offshore islands. Originally inhabited by Arawak Indians, the region became a French colony in 1697. Following a slave revolt led by Toussaint L'Ouverture, an independent republic was established in 1804 comprising the entire island of Hispaniola. The eastern part of the island revolted in 1843, forming the Dominican Republic. In the 1900s, Haiti was ruled by a series of dictatorships, including the repressive regimes of François Duvalier and his son Jean-Claude, who was ousted in 1986. Jean-Bertrand Aristide became Haiti's first democratically elected president in 1991. Port-au-Prince is the capital and largest city.

elision: Omission of a sound that would normally be pronounced in speaking a word.

ornery: Mean-spirited, disagreeable, and contrary in disposition; cantankerous.

alevin: A newly hatched salmon or trout that is still attached to the yolk sac.

elope: To run away with a lover, especially with the intention of getting married.

ululate: To howl, wail, or lament loudly, especially by alternating rapidly between two high-pitched sounds.

blottesque: In painting, executed with heavy blot-like touches.

bicameral: Composed of or based on two legislative chambers or branches.

practitioner: One who practices something, especially an occupation, profession, or technique.

celluloid: A colorless flammable material made from nitrocellulose and camphor and used to make photographic film.

matronymic: Of, relating to, or derived from the name of one's mother or maternal ancestor.

hunchback: An individual whose back is hunched due to abnormal convex curvature of the upper spine.

Argentina: A country of southeast South America stretching about 3,700 km (2,300 mi) from its border with Bolivia to southern Tierra del Fuego. The region was sparsely populated by indigenous peoples before the Spanish founded settlements there in the early 1500s. In 1776 Spain established a viceroyalty in present-day Argentina, Uruguay, Paraguay, and Bolivia. Argentina achieved its independence from Spain in 1816. Buenos Aires is the capital and the largest city.

renegade: One who rejects a religion, cause, allegiance, or group for another; a deserter.

quasi: Having a likeness to something; resembling.

pimiento: A garden pepper (Capsicum annuum) having a mild, sweet, red fruit.

maim: To injure, disable, or disfigure, usually by depriving of the use of a limb or other part of the body. synonym:mangle.

wrangle: To quarrel noisily or angrily. synonym:argue.

apophasis: Allusion to something by denying that it will be mentioned, as in I will not bring up my opponent's questionable financial dealings.

Uruguay: A country of southeast South America on the Atlantic Ocean and the Río de la Plata. Originally inhabited by various indigenous peoples, the area was colonized in the 1600s by the Spanish and Portuguese, with Spain establishing sole dominance after 1724. Uruguay declared independence from Spain in 1810 and from Argentina in 1814, struggling against Brazilian occupation to achieve full independence in 1828. Montevideo is the capital and the largest city.

forte: The strong part of a sword-blade or rapier, as opposed to the foible. Also spelled fort.

bower: A dwelling or habitation; particularly, a cottage; an unpretentious residence; a rustic abode.

atrophic: Pertaining to atrophy; characterized by atrophy; exhibiting or undergoing atrophy: as, an atrophic process; an atrophic organ.

low-lying: Lying close to water or ground level.

strophic: Relating to or consisting of strophes.

cabas: In France, a kind of basket, pannier, or frail, made of woven rush- or palm-leaves or grass, generally of a round form, serving to carry provisions, especially figs, dates, raisins, or prunes.

toponymic: Pertaining to toponymy: as, toponymic terminology.

watershed: The entire region draining into a river, river system, or other body of water.

headmistress: A woman who is the principal of a school, usually a private school.

Sri Lanka: An island country in the Indian Ocean off southeast India. Inhabited originally by the Vedda, the island was later invaded by the Sinhalese (6th century BC) and the Tamil (10th century AD). The island's lucrative spice trade was controlled from the 12th century onward by the Arabs, Portuguese, Dutch, and British. Ceylon became a British colony in 1802 and achieved independence in 1948. In 1972 the island was declared a republic, adopting the Sinhalese name of Sri Lanka. A civil war between the government and Tamil separatists began in 1983 and ended in 2009 with the defeat of the Tamil army. Colombo is the capital and the largest city.

vineyard: A tract of land where grapes are grown.

compositae: In zoology, a family of compound ascidians, corresponding to the family Botryllidœ; the Synascidiœ (which see).

nanotube: A hollow cylindrical or toroidal tube measuring nanometers in diameter, composed of atoms of a single element, typically carbon.

hoe: A tool with a flat blade attached approximately at a right angle to a long handle, used for weeding, cultivating, and gardening.

progestogen: Any of various substances having progestational effects; a progestin.

agriculturism: The art or science of agriculture.

well-rounded: Comprehensively developed and well-balanced in a range or variety of aspects.

achiote: The vernacular name in Central America of the arnotto-tree, Bixa Orellana.

vetoed: Simple past tense and past participle of veto.

taco: A corn tortilla folded around a filling such as ground meat or cheese.

Norteño: A Mexican gang or gang member, or a Mexican or Hispanic person

icteric: Relating to or affected with jaundice.

obduracy: The state or quality of being obdurate; especially, the state of being hardened against moral influences; extreme hardness of heart; rebellious persistence in wickedness.

alamort: In a half-dead or moribund condition; depressed; melancholy.

fane: An ancient temple; hence, poetically, any place consecrated to religion; a church.

orography: The study of the physical geography of mountains and mountain ranges.

aestival: Of or belonging to the summer.

scrimshaw: The art of carving or incising intricate designs on whalebone or whale ivory.

psaltery: An ancient stringed instrument played by plucking the strings with the fingers or a plectrum.

Europa: A Phoenician princess abducted to Crete by Zeus, who had assumed the form of a white bull, and by him the mother of Minos, Rhadamanthus, and Sarpedon.

doosra: A type of ball, bowled by an off-spin bowler, that, unlike a normal off break, spins from leg to off for a right-handed batsman; the off-spinner's version of the googly.

dilute: To make thinner or less concentrated by adding a liquid such as water.

bhangra: A Punjabi dance music traditionally performed during harvest festivals and weddings, characterized by the beating of a large, two-headed drum.

imprimatur: Official approval or license to print or publish, especially as granted by a censor or an ecclesiastical authority.

proverb: A short pithy saying in frequent and widespread use that expresses a basic truth or practical precept.

wasabi: A very pungent green Japanese condiment made from the root of the herb Wasabia japonica (syn. Eutrema wasabi) of the mustard family.

Costa Rica: A country of Central America between Panama and Nicaragua. Although Christopher Columbus reached Costa Rica in 1502, Spanish conquest of the native peoples of the area did not begin until 1563. The country achieved independence from Spain in 1821 as part of Mexican territory and declared itself a sovereign republic in 1838. San José is the capital and the largest city.

catasterism: A placing among the stars; a cataloguing or catalogue of the stars.

naos: In archaeology, a temple, as distinguished from hieron, a shrine (chapel) or sanctuary (in this latter sense not necessarily implying the presence of any edifice).

cabochon: A highly polished, convex-cut, unfaceted gem.

labefactation: A weakening or loosening; a failing; decay; downfall; ruin.

derivation: The act or process of deriving.

elite: A group or class of persons considered to be superior to others because of their intelligence, social standing, or wealth.

qawwali: A style of Muslim devotional music, especially among the Sufis, accompanied by drums and harmonium.

eelpout: Any of various bottom-dwelling marine fishes of the family Zoarcidae, having a large head and an elongated body with dorsal and anal fins that are continuous with the caudal fin.

pinnace: A light boat propelled by sails or oars, formerly used as a tender for merchant and war vessels.

version: A description or account from one point of view, especially as opposed to another.

Suriname: A country of northeast South America on the Atlantic Ocean. First colonized by the British, the region was ceded to the Netherlands as Dutch Guiana in 1667. It received limited autonomy in 1954 and achieved full independence in 1975. Paramaribo is the capital and the largest city.

gelato: An Italian ice cream or sorbet.

zabaglione: A dessert or sauce consisting of egg yolks, sugar, and wine or liqueur beaten until thick and served hot or cold.

exoteric: Not confined to an inner circle of disciples or initiates.

sleaze: A sleazy condition, quality, or appearance.

guideline: A statement or other indication of policy or procedure by which to determine a course of action.

argument: A discussion in which disagreement is expressed; a debate.

eryngo: Any of several plants of the genus Eryngium of the parsley family, having spiny leaves and dense clusters of small bluish flowers.

exanthema: A skin eruption accompanying certain infectious diseases.

adenography: That part of descriptive anatomy which treats of glands.

uakari: Either of two medium-sized fruit-eating arboreal monkeys (Cacajao calvus or C. melanocephalus) of Amazonia, having a nearly bare stomach with long hair on the shoulders and upper back and a short bushy nonprehensile tail.

diegesis: The presentation of a narrative without direct dramatic imitation of the events, scenes, or characters described.

prostyle: Having a row of columns across the front only, as in some Greek and Roman temples.

judogi: The uniform used for judo practice and competition, based on traditional Japanese clothing.

xanthocyanopsy: Color-blindness in which the ability to distinguish yellow and blue only is present, vision for red being wanting.

ubiety: The state of being in a definite place; ubeity.

platen: The roller in a typewriter that serves as the backing for the paper against which the type bars strike.

vernal: Of, relating to, or occurring in the spring.

waragi: A distilled alcoholic beverage made from bananas or millet.

bilberry: A low-growing deciduous shrub (Vaccinium myrtillus) of the heath family native to Eurasia and western North America, having edible bluish-black berries borne singly or in pairs, used for making jams, jellies, and juice and for medicinal purposes.

black tea: A dark tea prepared from fresh tea leaves that have been fully fermented before being dried.

Congo: A country of central Africa astride the equator. Inhabited originally by Pygmy peoples and later by migrating Bantu and Nilotic groups, the region came under the control of Leopold II of Belgium in the late 1870s and was annexed outright in 1908. Full independence was achieved in 1960. Army general Mobutu Sese Seko took control of the country in 1965, ruling until his ouster by rebel forces in 1997. Kinshasa is the capital and the largest city.

avast: Used as a command to stop or desist.

interlingua: A language used as an intermediate language in translating from a source language to a target language; -- used especially in machine translation by computers.

rhizosphere: The area of soil that surrounds and is affected by the roots of plants.

altruist: One who practises altruism; a person devoted to the welfare of others: opposed to egoist.

nandrolone: An anabolic steroid, 19-nortestosterone, that may be present naturally in minute quantities in the human body.

peep: To utter short, soft, high-pitched sounds, like those of a baby bird; cheep.

casino: A public room or building for gambling and other entertainment.

Czech Republic: A landlocked country of central Europe, made up of the historic regions of Bohemia, Moravia, and part of Silesia. It was a part of Czechoslovakia from 1918 until January 1993. Prague is the capital and largest city.

footfall: A footstep; the tread of the foot.

salopettes: trousers that form part of a ski suit.

thallus: A plant body undifferentiated into stem, root, or leaf.

marimba: A large wooden percussion instrument with resonators, resembling a xylophone.

periclean: Of or relating to Pericles (about 495-429 b. c.), the foremost citizen and practically chief of the state of ancient Athens at her greatest period; hence, pertaining to the age of the intellectual and material preëminence of Athens.

three-quarter: Relating to, consisting of, or extending to three fourths of the usual full length.

sheeple: People who are meekly submissive or easily swayed.

parti pris: An inclination for or against something or someone that affects judgment; prejudice or bias.

occiput: The back part of the head or skull.

anaphalantiasis: In pathology, the falling out of the eyebrows.

wagonette: A pleasure-vehicle, either with or without a top, holding six or more persons.

gabbro: A usually coarse-grained igneous rock composed chiefly of pyroxene and calcic plagioclase feldspar.

macadamize: To construct or pave (a road) with macadam.

cloche: A close-fitting woman's hat with a bell-like shape.

deliberately: With careful consideration or deliberation; with full intent; not hastily or carelessly: as, a deliberately formed purpose.

aardwolf: A mammal (Proteles cristatus) of southern and eastern Africa, similar to a hyena but feeding mainly on termites and insect larvae.

habromania: In pathology, insanity in which the delusions are of a gay character.

kentledge: Pig iron used as permanent ballast.

biloquist: One who can speak with two different voices.

uxoricide: The killing of a wife by her spouse.

funambulist: One who performs on a tightrope or a slack rope.

hypocrisy: The practice of professing beliefs, feelings, or virtues that one does not hold or possess; falseness.

Egypt: A country of northeast Africa and the Sinai Peninsula on the Mediterranean Sea. In ancient times it was a flourishing kingdom and one of the earliest known civilizations, known for its development of hieroglyphic writing and its achievements in agriculture, art, and architecture. It reached its height during the XVIII dynasty (1570–1342? BC) and declined after the seventh century BC, falling to various conquerors including the Assyrians, Greeks, Romans, Arabs, Turks, French, and British. Although nominally independent after 1922, it remained a British protectorate until 1936. A military coup in 1952 overthrew King Farouk I's constitutional monarchy, and a republic was established the following year. From 1958 to 1961 it was joined to Syria as the United Arab Republic. Cairo is the capital and the largest city.

tutelage: The capacity or activity of a guardian; guardianship.

right: Conforming with or conformable to justice, law, or morality.

precursor: One that precedes and indicates, suggests, or announces someone or something to come.

growler: One, such as a dog, that growls.

plumicorn: One of the pair of tufts of feathers, or egrets, also called ears and horns, on the head in sundry owls, as species of Bubo, Scops, Otus, or Asio; a feather-horn. Also (rarely) called corniplume. See cuts under Buboninæ and Otus.

timber: Trees or wooded land considered as a source of wood.

spite: Malicious ill will prompting an urge to hurt or humiliate another person.

independent: Not governed by a foreign power; self-governing.

eclipse: The partial or complete obscuring, relative to a designated observer, of one celestial body by another.

nyckelharpa: A stringed instrument once used in Sweden, essentially similar to the hurdy-gurdy, but sounded with a bow instead of a wheel. It had 4 principal strings of gut, 2 of which were drones, 8 sympathetic strings of metal, and 19 keys or tangents.

akimbo: In or into a position in which the hands are on the hips and the elbows are bowed outward.

cliché: A trite or overused expression or idea.

snowclone: A phrase or sentence made by substituting one or more words in a cliché, existing set phrase, or well-known sentence.

ludic: Of or relating to play or playfulness.

clarification: The act of clarifying; particularly, the clearing or fining of liquid substances from feculent matter by the separation of the insoluble particles which prevent the liquid from being transparent.

babesiosis: A tick-borne protozoan infection of animals, such as Texas fever of cattle, that is caused by species of Babesia.

panini: A type of sandwich made of a small loaf of bread, cut horizontally, filled with salami, ham, meat, cheese or other food.

scammony: An eastern Mediterranean plant (Convolvulus scammonia) having large roots that yield a resin formerly used as a cathartic.

sukiyaki: A Japanese dish of sliced meat, bean curd, and vegetables seasoned and fried together.

spinnaker: A large triangular headsail secured only at the corners, used on sailboats when running before the wind.

vagary: An unpredictable development or change of circumstances.

rune: A Finnish poem or section of a poem.

spicate: Borne in or forming a spike.

anarchism: The theory or doctrine that all forms of government are oppressive and undesirable and should be abolished.

puritanical: Rigorous in religious observance; marked by stern morality.

saraband: A fast, erotic dance of the 1500s of Mexico and Spain.

pascal: A unit of pressure equal to one newton per square meter.

abmho: A name proposed for the c. g. s. electromagnetic unit of conductance, admittance, or susceptance; 1 × 10 mhos.

tulipomania: A craze for the cultivation or acquisition of tulips; specifically, that which arose in the Netherlands about the year 1634, seized on all classes like an epidemic, and led to disasters such as result from great financial catastrophes.

prink: To adorn (oneself) in a showy manner.

supertonic: The second tone of a diatonic scale.

Athens: The capital and largest city of Greece, in the eastern part of the country near the Saronic Gulf. It was at the height of its cultural achievements and imperial power in the fifth century BC during the time of Pericles. Athens became the capital of modern Greece in 1834, two years after the country achieved its independence from Turkey.

angry: Feeling or showing anger; incensed or enraged.

Orlando: A city of central Florida east-northeast of Tampa. Originally a trade and processing center for cattle and oranges, it is now known for its aerospace industry and an extensive tourism and entertainment complex including theme parks and movie studios.

botany: The science or study of plants.

maglev: A high-speed train that operates by means of magnetic levitation.

interdict: To prohibit (an action or thing) or forbid (someone) to do something, especially by legal or ecclesiastical order.

selcouth: Rarely or little known; unusual; uncommon; strange; wonderful.

tyrotoxism: The aggregate of symptoms in poisoning by tyrotoxin or tyrotoxicon; cheese-poisoning.

kiosk: A small structure, usually open in front, used as a newsstand or a place for selling goods or conducting transactions, as at a bank.

Louisville: The largest city of Kentucky, in the north-central part of the state on the Ohio River southwest of Cincinnati. Originally the site of a fort built by George Rogers Clark in 1778, it is now the center of a large metropolitan area and home to the Kentucky Derby.

backstretch: The part of an oval racecourse farthest from the spectators and opposite the homestretch.

dystopian: Of or relating to a dystopia.

umbrella: A device for protection from the weather consisting of a collapsible, usually circular canopy mounted on a central rod.

scrape: To remove (an outer layer, for example) from a surface by forceful strokes of an edged or rough instrument.

mercurial: Of or relating to the god Mercury.

telecommunications: the science and technology of communication at a distance, especially the electronic transmission of signals; telecommunication

wander: To move about without a definite destination or purpose.

contango: A state in which the price of a futures contract is higher than the eventual or expected spot price of the underlying commodity or security.

automotive: Moving by itself; self-propelling or self-propelled.

Cincinnati: A city of extreme southwest Ohio on the Ohio River. Founded in 1788, it is a port of entry and a major commercial center.

guiser: One who goes from house to house whimsically disguised, and making diversion with songs and antics, usually at Christmas; a masker; a mummer.

dongle: A hardware device that renders inoperable certain software on a computer if the device is not attached to the computer.

smolt: A young salmon when it becomes covered with silvery scales and first migrates from fresh water to the sea.

majestic: Impressive or beautiful in a dignified or inspiring way. synonym:grand.

loess: A buff to gray windblown deposit of fine-grained, calcareous silt or clay.

buffalo: Any of several large African and Asian ruminant mammals of the family Bovidae, such as the water buffalo and the African buffalo.

censor: A person authorized to examine books, films, or other material and to remove or suppress what is considered morally, politically, or otherwise objectionable.

slow match: A match or fuse that burns slowly at a known rate and is used to set off explosives or fire cannons and muzzle-loading firearms.

truck driver: A person employed to drive a semi truck.

astoundingly: In an astounding or amazing manner; amazingly.

spontoon: A short pike carried by infantry officers and sergeants in the 1700s.

tmesis: Separation of the parts of a compound word by one or more intervening words; for example, where I go ever instead of wherever I go.

harlequin: A conventional buffoon of the commedia dell'arte, traditionally presented in a mask and parti-colored tights.

jade: Either of two distinct minerals, nephrite and jadeite, that are generally pale green or white and are used mainly as gemstones or in carving.

celadon: A pale to very pale green.

caregiver: An individual, such as a physician, nurse, or social worker, who assists in the identification, prevention, or treatment of an illness or disability.

orrery: A mechanical model of the solar system or parts of it.

merger: The act or an instance of merging.

refined: Free from coarseness or vulgarity; polite.

takeover: The act or an instance of assuming control or management of or responsibility for something, especially the seizure of power, as in a nation, political organization, or corporation.

rest mass: The physical mass of a body as measured by an observer who perceives the body as motionless. Rest mass is an inherent property of elementary particles.

genitrix: The biological mother of a child

gouache: A method of painting with opaque watercolors mixed with a preparation of gum.

ormolu: Any of several copper and zinc or tin alloys resembling gold in appearance and used to ornament furniture, moldings, architectural details, and jewelry.

Cai: Anglicized form of a common Chinese surname.

biota: The living organisms of a region or habitat.

wingding: A lavish or lively party or celebration.

sword knot: A decorative loop or tassel attached to the hilt of a sword.

Tampa: A city of west-central Florida on Tampa Bay, an inlet of the Gulf of Mexico. Established as a fort in 1824, the city developed as a cattle center and port of entry.

elver: A young eel of fresh or brackish waters.

aroph: A name formerly given to saffron.

osmium: A bluish-white, hard, brittle and extremely dense metallic element, found in small amounts in osmiridium, nickel, and platinum ores. It is used as a platinum hardener and in making pen points, phonograph needles, instrument pivots, and other wear-resistant items. Atomic number 76; atomic weight 190.2; melting point 3,033°C; boiling point 5,012°C; specific gravity 22.587; valence 2, 3, 4, 6, 8. cross-reference:Periodic Table.

ethane: A colorless, odorless gaseous alkane, C2H6, that occurs as a constituent of natural gas and is used as a fuel and a refrigerant.

bascule: A device or structure, such as a drawbridge, counterbalanced so that when one end is lowered the other is raised.

Kobe: A city of southern Honshu, Japan, on Osaka Bay southwest of Kyoto. A port and manufacturing center, it was almost entirely rebuilt after World War II. The city was badly damaged by an earthquake in 1995.

imari: Japanese porcelain wares (made in the town of Arita and exported from the port of Imari, particularly around the 17th century)

Robinia: A genus of leguminous trees and shrubs of the tribe Galegeæ, type of the subtribe Robinieæ; the locusts.

shock jock: A host of a shock radio program.

cineast: An enthusiast of film and the cinema

corposant: A ball of light, supposed to be of an electrical nature, sometimes observed in dark tempestuous nights about the decks and rigging of a ship, but particularly at the mastheads and yard-arms; St. Elmo's light or fire. Also called corpse-light.

stakeholder: One who has a share or an interest, as in an enterprise.

telegraph: A communications system that transmits and receives simple unmodulated electric impulses, especially one in which the transmission and reception stations are directly connected by wires.

mustachio: A mustache, especially a luxuriant one.

stagger: To move or stand unsteadily, as if under a great weight; totter. synonym:blunder.

clement: Inclined to be lenient or merciful.

sirocco: A hot humid south or southeast wind of southern Italy, Sicily, and the Mediterranean islands, originating in the Sahara Desert as a dry dusty wind but becoming moist as it passes over the Mediterranean.

palooka: An incompetent or easily defeated athlete, especially a prizefighter.

stot: To leap or bound high in the air with the legs straight, as do certain antelopes and deer.

reminiscent: Having the quality of or containing reminiscence.

whine: To produce a sustained, high-pitched, plaintive sound, as in pain, fear, or complaint.

interlanguage: The type of language produced by nonnative speakers when learning another language.

genome: The total genetic content contained in a haploid set of chromosomes in eukaryotes, in a single chromosome in bacteria or archaea, or in the DNA or RNA of viruses.

raid: A surprise attack by a small armed force.

ortolan: A small brownish bunting (Emberiza hortulana) of Eurasia and Africa, eaten as a delicacy.

Tamil Nadu: A state of southern India on the Bay of Bengal and the Palk Strait. A succession of kingdoms and empires ruled the region from prehistoric times until it fell under British control in the 1700s and 1800s. Chennai is the capital.

endue: To provide with a quality or trait; endow.

convey: To take or carry from one place to another; transport. synonym:carry.

sandbar: A ridge of sand formed in a river or along a shore by the action of waves or currents.

terete: Circular in cross section; cylindrical, sometimes with tapering ends.

bashful: Shy, self-conscious, and awkward in the presence of others.

undergo: To experience or be subjected to.

unravel: To undo or ravel the entangled, knitted, or woven threads of.

vitriol: Any of various sulfates of metals, such as ferrous sulfate, zinc sulfate, or copper sulfate.

winch: A stationary motor-driven or hand-powered machine used for hoisting or hauling, having a drum around which is wound a rope or chain attached to the load being moved.

vervain: One of several weedy plants of the genus Verbena, primarily V. officinalis, widely dispersed in warm and temperate regions in both hemispheres.

group: An assemblage of persons or objects gathered or located together; an aggregation.

tedious: Tiresome by reason of length, slowness, or dullness; boring. synonym:boring.

sucker: One that sucks, especially an unweaned domestic animal.

bacchante: A priestess or female votary of Bacchus.

stink: To emit a strong foul odor.

lounge: To move or act in a lazy, relaxed way; loll.

Massachusetts: A state of the northeast United States. One of the original Thirteen Colonies, it was the site of the first successful English settlement in New England when the Pilgrims of the Mayflower founded Plymouth in 1620. Governed by the Massachusetts Bay Company from 1629 until 1684, the colony was a leader in the move for independence from Great Britain and the site of the first battles of the Revolutionary War in 1775. Massachusetts ratified the United States Constitution in 1788. Boston is the capital and the largest city.

unnerve: To cause to lose courage or firmness of purpose.

touch: To cause or permit a part of the body, especially the hand or fingers, to come in contact with so as to feel.

threnody: A poem or song of mourning or lamentation.

sporadic: Occurring at irregular intervals or in isolated or scattered places; having no pattern or order: synonym:periodic.

loin: The part of the body of a human or quadruped on either side of the backbone and between the ribs and hips.

patency: The state or quality of being obvious.

hospitality: Cordial and generous reception of or disposition toward guests.

brace: A device that holds or fastens two or more parts together or in place; a clamp.

future: The indefinite time yet to come.

stigma: An association of disgrace or public disapproval with something, such as an action or condition: synonym:stain.

cudgel: A short heavy stick; a club.

shillelagh: A cudgel of oak, blackthorn, or other hardwood.

mystery: Occupation; trade; office; profession; calling; art; craft.

matriarchate: The position or power of a matriarch.

Shirley Temple: A non-alcoholic cocktail traditionally made with ginger ale, grenadine syrup, and orange juice garnished with a maraschino cherry and slice of lemon. The ginger ale is commonly substituted with lemon-lime soft drink, and the orange juice is commonly left out.

cruiser: One of a class of fast warships of medium tonnage with a long cruising radius and less armor and firepower than a battleship.

Aisne: A river of northern France rising in the Argonne Forest and flowing about 265 km (165 mi) northwest and west to the Oise River. Four major World War I battles were fought along its banks, including the final defeat of the Germans by French and American troops in September–October 1918.

Qi: the circulating life energy that in Chinese philosophy is thought to be inherent in all things; in traditional Chinese medicine the balance of negative and positive forms in the body is believed to be essential for good health

lamprey: Any of various elongated freshwater or anadromous fishes of the family Petromyzontidae, having a jawless sucking mouth with rasping teeth and often attaching to and parasitizing other fish.

stinkard: One who stinks; hence, a mean, paltry fellow.

halcyon: A kingfisher, especially one of the genus Halcyon.

verso: A left-hand page of a book or the reverse side of a leaf, as opposed to the recto.

barrel roll: A flight maneuver in which an airplane makes a complete rotation on its longitudinal axis while approximately maintaining its original direction.

strepitus: A noise: noting any sound heard on auscultation of the chest.

Ginza: A major shopping and entertainment district of Tokyo, Japan.

canton: A small territorial division of a country, especially one of the states of Switzerland.

embonpoint: The condition of being plump; stoutness.

hemlock: Any of various coniferous evergreen trees of the genus Tsuga of North America and eastern Asia, having small cones and short flat leaves with two white bands underneath.

skid: The action of sliding or slipping over a surface, often sideways.

court bouillon: A poaching liquid for fish whose ingredients usually include water, vinegar or wine, diced vegetables, and seasonings.

Schwyz: A town in Switzerland, the capital of the canton of Schwyz.

shalwar: loose trousers worn in some South Asian or Islamic countries, especially by women

phosphorus: A highly reactive, poisonous, nonmetallic element occurring naturally in phosphates, especially apatite, and existing in three allotropic forms, white (or sometimes yellow), red, and black (or violet). An essential constituent of protoplasm, it is used in safety matches, pyrotechnics, incendiary shells, and fertilizers and to protect metal surfaces from corrosion. Atomic number 15; atomic weight 30.9738; melting point (white) 44.15°C; boiling point 280.5°C; specific gravity (white) 1.82, (red) 2.16, (black) 2.25 to 2.69; valence 3, 4, 5. cross-reference:Periodic Table.

starry: Marked or set with stars or starlike objects.

buoy: A float moored in water to mark a location, warn of danger, or indicate a navigational channel.

Algeria: A country of northwest Africa bordering on the Mediterranean Sea. The region was settled c. 2000 BC by Berber-speaking people and later formed a part of the Roman, Byzantine, and Ottoman empires. Arab invaders in the seventh and eighth centuries introduced Islam and the Arabic language and culture. A French territory from 1848, Algeria gained its independence in 1962 after more than seven years of fighting. Algiers is the capital and the largest city.

pun: A play on words, sometimes on different senses of the same word and sometimes on the similar sense or sound of different words.

wimble: Any of numerous hand tools for boring holes.

avatar: The incarnation of a Hindu deity, especially Vishnu, in human or animal form.

slither: To move or slide by twisting or undulating the body over a surface, as in the manner of a snake.

exuberant: Full of unrestrained enthusiasm or joy.

auger: Any of various hand tools, typically having a threaded shank and cross handle, used for boring holes in wood or ice.

bombilla: A metal straw having a bulbous end perforated with holes that filters out mate leaves when drinking mate from a calabash.

strife: Heated, often violent conflict or disagreement. synonym:conflict.

Iran: A country of southwest Asia. Inhabited since c. 2000 BC by Iranian peoples, the region later became the core of the Persian Empire. After being conquered by Alexander the Great and ruled by the Parthian Arsacid dynasty, Persia was reestablished under the Sassanian dynasty (AD 224–651) and, after invasions by Arabs (7th century), Turks (10th century), and Mongols (13th century), was reestablished again under the Safavid dynasty (1502–1736). The country, renamed Iran in 1935, was ruled by the Pahlavi dynasty from 1925 until the ouster of Mohammad Reza Pahlavi (1979) in a revolution led by the Ayatollah Khomeini, who established an Islamic republic. Tehran is the capital and the largest city.

anacoluthon: An abrupt change within a sentence to a second construction inconsistent with the first, sometimes used for rhetorical effect; for example, I warned him that if he continues to drink, what will become of him?

girandole: A composition or structure in radiating form or arrangement, such as a rotating display of fireworks.

exegesis: Critical explanation or analysis, especially of a text.

setline: A long fishing line anchored at both ends and bearing baited hooks at regular intervals along its length.

infirmary: A place for the care of the infirm, sick, or injured, especially a small hospital or dispensary in an institution.

poi: A Hawaiian food made from the tuber of the taro that is cooked, pounded to a paste, and fermented.

craunch: To crush with the teeth; crunch. See crunch.

tilapia: Any of various cichlid fishes of the genera Tilapia, Oreochromis, and Sarotherodon, native to Africa and the Middle East and raised for food in many parts of the world.

eidetic: Of, relating to, or marked by extraordinarily detailed and vivid recall of visual images.

discretion: The quality of being discreet; circumspection.

Atlanta: The capital and largest city of Georgia, in the northwest part of the state. It was founded in 1837 at the end of the railroad line as Terminus and renamed Atlanta in 1845. Almost entirely burned on November 15, 1864, before the start of Union general William Tecumseh Sherman's march to the sea, the city was rapidly rebuilt and became the permanent state capital in 1877.

esclandre: Disturbance; a cause of scandal; a scene.

mahout: A person who takes care of, rides, and controls a tamed elephant.

leitmotiv: In music, a leading motive (which see, under leading).

felly: The rim or a section of the rim of a wheel supported by spokes.

philanderer: One who philanders; a male flirt.

withhold: To refrain from giving or granting: synonym:keep.

voyeur: A person who derives sexual gratification from observing the naked bodies or sexual acts of others, especially from a secret vantage point.

raster: A scanning pattern of parallel lines that form the image projected on a cathode-ray tube of a television set or display screen.

annelid: Any of various worms or wormlike animals of the phylum Annelida, characterized by an elongated, cylindrical, segmented body and including the earthworms and the leeches.

satrap: A governor of a province in ancient Persia.

abolish: To do away with; put an end to; annul.

spar: A wooden or metal pole, such as a boom, yard, or bowsprit, used to support sails and rigging.

electrolier: A bracket, pendant, or stand, often with branches, and ornamented, used for supporting incandescent electric lamps.

express: To set forth in words; state.

unobtrusive: Not undesirably noticeable or blatant; inconspicuous.

Iraq: A country of southwest Asia. Site of the ancient civilizations of Mesopotamia, the region later fell to the Persians (6th century BC), Greeks (4th century BC), Arabs (7th century), and Ottoman Turks (16th century). Iraq became a kingdom under a British mandate in 1921, achieved independence in 1932, and became a republic in 1958. The Baathist regime of Saddam Hussein invaded Iran (1980), triggering an eight-year war, and occupied Kuwait (1990) until forced to withdraw in the Gulf War. In the Iraq War, a US-led coalition overthrew Hussein (2003) and established a new government. Baghdad is the capital and largest city.

areology: The scientific investigation of the substance of Mars.

doxology: An expression of praise to God, especially a short hymn sung as part of a Christian worship service.

reredos: A decorative screen or facing on the wall at the back of an altar.

loon: Any of several fish-eating diving birds of the genus Gavia of northern regions, having a short tail, webbed feet, and a laughlike cry.

teriyaki: A Japanese dish of grilled or broiled slices of marinated meat or shellfish.

doorcase: The frame or casing which incloses a door, and in which it swings.

sunbath: An exposure of the body to the sun.

Nicene Creed: A formal statement of doctrine of the Christian faith adopted at the Council of Nicaea in AD 325 to defend orthodoxy from Arianism and expanded in later councils.

passive: Receiving or subjected to an action without responding or initiating an action in return.

metamorphosis: A transformation, as by magic or sorcery.

quasar: A compact, extremely bright celestial object whose power output can be hundreds to several thousand times that of the entire Milky Way galaxy. Quasars are among the most distant objects in the universe and are generally considered to be a form of active galactic nucleus.

decal: A picture or design transferred by decalcomania.

wigwag: To move back and forth; wag steadily or rhythmically.

atavistic: Pertaining to or characterized by atavism; atavic.

grotesque: Characterized by ludicrous, repulsive, or incongruous distortion, as of appearance or manner. synonym:ugly.

peculiar: Not ordinary or usual; odd or strange: synonym:strange.

goggles: Protective eyewear set in a flexible frame to fit snugly against the face.

zadruga: Among the South Slavic peoples, the association of all consanguineals into a coöperative organization, the members of which generally live in a complex of houses built within an inclosure and around the house of the stare-shina or chief of the community.

in rem: Against a thing, such as a piece of property, as in a lawsuit establishing its ownership.

impending: Hanging over; overhanging; suspended so as to menace; imminet; threatening.

metaphor: A figure of speech in which a word or phrase that ordinarily designates one thing is used to designate another, thus making an implicit comparison, as in “a sea of troubles” or

thermodynamics: Physics that deals with the relationships and conversions between heat and other forms of energy.

gerrymander: To divide (a geographic area) into voting districts in a way that gives one party an unfair advantage in elections.

Acadian: Of or relating to Acadia or its people, language, or culture.

lexeme: The fundamental unit of the lexicon of a language. Find, finds, found, and finding are forms of the English lexeme find.

unked: Unusual; odd; strange; ugly; hence, solitary; dangerous. [Obsolete or provincial.]

standard: Serving as or conforming to an established or accepted measurement or value.

workplace: A place, such as an office or factory, where people are employed.

watch: To look or observe attentively or carefully; be closely observant.

tare: Any of several vetches native to Europe.

pine: To feel a lingering, often nostalgic desire.

sacerdotalist: A supporter of sacerdotalism; one who believes in the priestly character of the clergy.

triadic: Of or pertaining to a triad; constituting or consisting of a triad or trinity.

flatulence: The presence of excessive gas in the digestive tract.

apostrophe: In rhetoric, a digressive address; the interruption of the course of a speech or writing, in order to address briefly a person or persons (present or absent, real or imaginary) individually or separately; hence, any abrupt interjectional speech. Originally the term was applied only to such an address made to one present.

rampike: A standing dead tree or tree stump, especially one killed by fire.

lucifer: A self-igniting match, ie. one which could be lit by striking on any surface (as opposed to safety matches which only light against the material on the side of the box).

exist: To have actual being; be real.

distress: To cause strain, anxiety, or suffering to. synonym:trouble.

mutant: An organism, cell, virus, or gene resulting from genetic mutation.

ex cathedra: With the authority derived from one's office or position.

individual: Of or relating to an individual, especially a single human.

supernaculum: On the nail: used of drinking, with reference to the custom of turning the glass over the thumb to show that there was only a drop left small enough to rest on the nail: as, to drink supernaculum.

instruction: The act, practice, or profession of instructing.

reversal: The act or an instance of reversing.

construct: To form by assembling or combining parts; build.

segregate: To separate or isolate from others or from a main body or group. synonym:isolate.

amrita: In Hinduism, the drink that is consumed by the gods and bestows immortality.

onager: A wild ass (Equus hemionus) of Asia, having an erect mane, a light brown coat, and a dark stripe along the back.

diastole: The normal rhythmically occurring relaxation and dilatation of the heart chambers, especially the ventricles, during which they fill with blood.

gerontocracy: Government based on rule by elders.

liturgy: A prescribed form or set of forms for public religious worship.

crispation: The act of crisping or curling.

pander: To act as a go-between or liaison in sexual intrigues; function as a procurer.

liaison: An instance or a means of communication between different groups or units of an organization, especially in the armed forces.

vex: To irritate, bother, or frustrate: synonym:annoy.

oath: A solemn, formal declaration or promise to fulfill a pledge, often calling on God, a god, or a sacred object as witness.

oread: Any of a group of mountain nymphs.

metonymy: A figure of speech in which one word or phrase is substituted for another with which it is closely associated, as in the use of Washington for the United States government or of the sword for military power.

collude: To act together, often in secret, to achieve an illegal or improper purpose.

malinger: To feign illness or other incapacity in order to avoid duty or work.

obnubilate: To darken or obscure with clouds; becloud.

collusion: An often secret action taken by two or more parties to achieve an illegal or improper purpose.

pending: Not yet decided or settled; awaiting conclusion or confirmation.

injustice: Violation of another's rights or of what is right; lack of justice.

wan: Unnaturally pale, as from physical or emotional distress.

exeat: Leave of absence granted to a student in the English universities.

caboose: The last car on a freight train, often having kitchen and sleeping facilities for the train crew, and used as a vantage point for spotting problems on the train, such as smoking brakes or the separation of cars. The introduction of electronic sensors has made the caboose unnecessary.

cebidae: A natural family including all the New World monkeys except marmosets and tamarins.

needfire: A fire produced by the friction of one piece of wood upon another, or of a rope upon a stake of wood.

puffball: Any of various fungi chiefly of the family Lycoperdaceae, having a ball-shaped fruiting body that when pressed or struck releases clouds of small spores.

Marianne: The personification of France, symbolizing liberty and reason and appearing on French coins, stamps, etc.

abate: To reduce in amount, degree, or intensity; lessen.

sassafras: A deciduous eastern North American tree (Sassafras albidum) having irregularly lobed leaves and aromatic bark, leaves, and roots.

nautical: Of, relating to, or characteristic of ships, shipping, sailors, or navigation on a body of water.

scheme: A systematic plan of action: synonym:plan.

tazza: A shallow ornamental vessel usually on a pedestal.

voucher: A piece of substantiating evidence; a proof.

farraginous: Composed of a variety of substances.

dhole: A wild Asian dog (Cuon alpinus) having reddish fur and large ears.

stylometry: a statistical method of analyzing a text to determine its author

procaine: A white crystalline powder, C13H20N2O2, used chiefly in its hydrochloride form as a local anesthetic in medicine and dentistry.

thorax: The part of the human body between the neck and the diaphragm, partially encased by the ribs and containing the heart and lungs; the chest.

topknot: A crest or knot of hair or feathers on the crown of the head.

quagmire: Land with a soft muddy surface.

unorthodox: Breaking with convention or tradition; not orthodox.

treatise: A systematic, usually extensive written discourse on a subject.

pacify: To ease the anger or agitation of (a person or the mind, for example).

escarpment: A steep slope or long cliff that results from erosion or faulting and separates two relatively level areas of differing elevations.

harass: To subject (another) to hostile or prejudicial remarks or actions; pressure or intimidate.

nauseate: To feel or cause to feel nausea.

sense datum: A basic unanalyzable sensation, such as a color or smell, experienced upon stimulation of a sense organ or receptor.

ununoctium: The systematic element name for the chemical element with atomic number 118 (symbol Uuo).

chowry: In the East Indies, a whisk or brush used to drive off flies, often made of the bushy tail of the Tibetan yak set in a decorated handle, and in this form one of the ensigns of ancient Asiatic royalty. Also spelled chourie, chowrie.

prince: A male member of a royal family other than the monarch, especially a son of the monarch.

jillaroo: A female jackaroo, a woman who does the job of a jackaroo.

lorimer: A maker of bits, spurs, and metal mountings for bridles and saddles; hence, a saddler.

curb roof: A roof having two slopes on each side, as a gambrel roof or a mansard roof.

birl: To cause (a floating log) to spin rapidly by rotating with the feet.

wedge: A piece of material, such as metal or wood, thick at one edge and tapered to a thin edge at the other for insertion in a narrow crevice, used for splitting, tightening, securing, or levering.

digestif: An alcoholic drink taken at the end of a meal, often thought to aid digestion.

fawning: The act of caressing or flattering servilely; mean obsequiousness.

augury: The art, ability, or practice of auguring; divination.

corniche: A road that winds along the side of a steep coast or cliff.

diorama: A three-dimensional miniature or life-size scene in which figures, stuffed wildlife, or other objects are arranged in a naturalistic setting against a painted background.

purdah: A curtain or screen, used mainly in India to keep women separate from men or strangers.

phlegmatic: Of or relating to phlegm; phlegmy.

windscreen: A screen for protection against the wind.

vegan: A vegetarian who eats plant products only, especially one who uses no products derived from animals, as fur or leather.

slithy: A nonce word in Lewis Carroll's Jabberwocky combining the senses of "slimy" and "lithe".

proponent: One who argues in support of something; an advocate.

Chiton: A taxonomic genus within the class Polyplacophora — certain molluscs.

oneiric: Of, relating to, or suggestive of dreams.

daily double: A bet won by choosing both winners of two specified races on one day, as in horseracing.

tarsier: Any of several small insectivorous primates of the genus Tarsius of Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, and the Philippines, being nocturnal and arboreal and having extremely large round eyes, a long tail, and long digits with nails except for the second and third toes, which have claws.

zaguan: A porch or a vestibule at the entrance of a house; entrance; hall.

encyclopedia: A comprehensive reference work containing articles on a wide range of subjects or on numerous aspects of a particular field, usually arranged alphabetically.

walter: To roll or wallow; to welter.

uprising: A popular revolt against a government or its policies; a rebellion.

arrhythmia: Irregularity in the force or rhythm of the heartbeat.

foresight: The ability or action of imagining or anticipating what might happen in the future.

surtitle: A translation of a segment of the libretto or other text or sometimes a brief summary of the plot projected onto a screen above the stage during a performance of an opera or other similar performance sung in a foreign language; a supertitle.

easting: The difference in longitude between two positions as a result of movement to the east.

acronym: A word formed by combining the initial letters of a multipart name, such as NATO from North Atlantic Treaty Organization or by combining the initial letters or parts of a series of words, such as radar from radio detecting and ranging.

klatch: A casual social gathering, usually for conversation.

maser: A device that generates or amplifies electromagnetic radiation, especially microwaves, of a coherent wavelength by stimulated emission.

serum: The clear yellowish fluid obtained upon separating whole blood into its solid and liquid components after it has been allowed to clot.

concupiscence: A strong desire, especially sexual desire; lust.

slovenly: Untidy, as in dress or appearance.

zygote: The cell formed by the union of two gametes, especially a fertilized ovum before cleavage.

per procurationem: by the agency of, especially when signing a letter in place of someone else

cumin: An annual Mediterranean herb (Cuminum cyminum) in the parsley family, having finely divided leaves and clusters of small white or pink flowers.

ripsaw: A coarse-toothed saw used for cutting wood along the grain.

catch-as-catch-can: Using or making do with whatever means are available; irregular.

jocund: Sprightly and lighthearted in disposition, character, or quality.

radiology: The branch of medicine that deals with diagnostic images of anatomic structures made through the use of electromagnetic radiation or sound waves and that treats disease through the use of radioactive compounds. Radiological imaging techniques include x-rays, CT scans, PET scans, MRIs, and ultrasonograms.

fer-de-lance: Any of several tropical American pit vipers of the genus Bothrops, typically having brown and grayish markings.

extracurricular: Being outside the regular curriculum of a school or college.

cadence: Balanced, rhythmic flow, as of poetry or oratory.

suite: A staff of attendants or followers; a retinue.

revoke: To invalidate or cause to no longer be in effect, as by voiding or canceling.

solace: Comfort in sorrow, misfortune, or distress; consolation.

spirits: Third-person singular simple present indicative form of spirit.

throughout: In, to, through, or during every part of; all through.

laurel: An evergreen tree (Laurus nobilis) of the Mediterranean region valued for its aromatic ovate leaves, used in cooking.

hoard: A supply or store of something held or hidden for future use.

azulejo: An earthenware tile of Spanish manufacture, painted and enameled in rich colors, especially one having a metallic luster.

forayer: One who takes part in a foray; a marauder. Formerly also forrayer.

solicitously: In a solicitous manner; anxiously; with care or concern.

hypogeum: A subterranean chamber of an ancient building.

milestone: A stone marker set up on a roadside to indicate the distance in miles from a given point.

interfere: To be or create a hindrance or obstacle.

Slovenia: A country of central Europe. In ancient times Illyrian and Celtic peoples inhabited the area, which was ruled by Rome after the first century BC and settled by Slavs in the sixth century AD. Slovenia came under Austrian control after 1335 and joined the Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes (later Yugoslavia) in 1918. During World War II Slovenia was divided among Germany, Italy, and Hungary, but returned to Yugoslavia after the war. Slovenia declared its independence from Yugoslavia in June 1991. Ljubljana is the capital and largest city.

scabrous: Having or covered with scales or small projections and rough to the touch.

prognathous: Having jaws or mouthparts that project forward to a marked degree.

windlass: Any of numerous hauling or lifting machines consisting essentially of a horizontal cylinder turned by a crank or a motor so that a line attached to the load is wound around the cylinder.

staycation: A vacation in which one does not travel away from home.

soliloquy: A dramatic or literary form of discourse in which a character talks to himself or herself or reveals his or her thoughts when alone or unaware of the presence of other characters.

rumba: A dance of Cuban origin, combining complex footwork with a pronounced movement of the hips.

madrina: In South America, the leading animal of a mule-train, usually distinguished by some head-ornament, chiefly by a bell dangling from the neck. In Spain the term is also used to designate the rope or leather band by which two mules are tied together; and for a wooden support in the shape of a pillar or column.

ulema: Muslim scholars trained in Islam and Islamic law.

transformative: Having power or a tendency to transform.

Albania: A country of southeast Europe on the Adriatic Sea. The region was settled in ancient times by Illyrians and later came under Roman, Byzantine, and Ottoman rule. Having declared independence in 1912, Albania was successively a principality, a republic (after 1925), a kingdom (after 1928), and a Communist state (after 1944). Elections in 1992 transferred power from the Communist Party to a nominally democratic government. Tiranë is the capital and the largest city.

pulsar: Any of several celestial objects emitting periodic, short, intense bursts of radio, x-ray, or visible electromagnetic radiation, generally believed to be quickly rotating neutron stars.

inamorata: A woman with whom one has an intimate romantic relationship.

acescent: Turning sour; becoming tart or acid by spontaneous decomposition, as vegetable or animal juices or infusions; hence, slightly sour; acidulous; subacid.

putti: Representations of Cupid-like nude children common in the art of the fifteenth and following centuries, especially in Italy.

tired: Exhausted of strength or energy; fatigued.

Bulgaria: A country of southeast Europe on the Black Sea. Settled in the 6th century AD by Slavs, it was subject to the Ottoman Empire from the late 14th century until 1908, when it became an independent kingdom. The Soviet Union invaded in 1944 and established the People's Republic of Bulgaria. Communist rule came to an end in 1989, and a democratic constitution was established in 1991. Sofia is the capital and the largest city.

darrein: In old law, last: as, darrein continuance; darrein presentment.

naevus: A congenital local discoloration of the skin, including nævus vascularis and nævus pigmentosus. Also called birth-mark, mother's mark, and nævus maternus. Compare mole.

stamnos: A two-handled jar having a broad round shape, a short neck, and a wide mouth, used by the ancient Greeks and Romans for storing and mixing liquids.

schlock: Something, such as merchandise or literature, that is inferior or poorly made.

putto: A representation of a small child, often naked and having wings, used especially in the art of the European Renaissance.

vitelline: Of, relating to, or associated with the yolk of an egg.

Mesozoic: Of, relating to, or being the era of geologic time from about 251 to 65 million years ago. The Mesozoic Era includes the Triassic, Jurassic, and Cretaceous Periods and is characterized by the development of flying reptiles, birds, and flowering plants and by the appearance and extinction of dinosaurs.

oboe: A slender woodwind instrument with a conical bore and a double-reed mouthpiece, having a range of three octaves and a penetrating, poignant sound.

eider: Any of several large sea ducks, especially of the genus Somateria of northern regions, having soft, commercially valuable down and predominantly black and white plumage in the male.

pragmatic: Dealing or concerned with facts or actual occurrences; practical.

handsel: A gift to express good wishes at the beginning of a new year or enterprise.

reeve: The elected president of a town council in some parts of Canada.

clergy: The body of people ordained or recognized by a religious community as ritual or spiritual leaders.

ushabti: In ancient Egypt, a figurine of a dead person, placed in their tomb to do their work for them in the afterlife.

pheromone: A chemical secreted by an animal, especially an insect, that influences the behavior or physiology of others of the same species, as by attracting members of the opposite sex or marking the route to a food source.

valetudinarian: A sickly or weak person, especially one who is constantly and morbidly concerned with his or her health.

tessellate: To form into a mosaic pattern, as by using small squares of stone or glass.

oribi: A small African antelope (Ourebia ourebi) having a light brown coat with white underparts, a short black tail, and short horns in the male.

bodhisattva: An enlightened being who, out of compassion, forgoes nirvana in order to save others.

octapla: A polyglot book (especially a Bible) in eight parallel columns. The name is especially given to Origen's Hexapla with the addition of a fifth and a sixth version.

altruistic: Pertaining or relating to altruism; regardful of others; having regard to the well-being or best interests of others: opposed to egoistic.

squalid: Dirty or deteriorated, especially from poverty or lack of care. synonym:dirty.

eudemonic: Relating or contributing to happiness; considered as relating or contributing to happiness.

apothem: The perpendicular distance from the center of a regular polygon to any of its sides.

Dapsang: a mountain peak in the Karakoram Range in northern Kashmir; the 2nd highest peak in the world (28,250 feet high)

roomette: A small private compartment in a railroad sleeping car.

plastron: A metal breastplate worn under a coat of mail.

achar: A condiment of South Asian origin typically made of fruits or vegetables pickled in oil, lemon juice or vinegar, salt, and spices.

xerophagy: The habit of living on dry food, especially a form of abstinence, as in the early church, in which only bread, herbs, salt, and water were consumed.

way station: A station between principal stations on a route, as of a railroad.

Singapore: A country of southeast Asia comprising Singapore Island and adjacent smaller islands. A trading center as early as the 14th century, Singapore was later part of Johor, a region of the southern Malay Peninsula, under the Malacca Sultanate. The island of Singapore was ceded to the British East India Company in 1819, and the city was founded the same year by Sir Thomas Raffles. The British took complete control in 1824 and added Singapore to the newly formed Straits Settlements in 1826. During World War II it was held by the Japanese (1942–1945) before being retaken by the British. Singapore became a crown colony in 1946, a self-governing state in 1959, part of the Federation of Malaysia in 1963, and a fully independent republic in 1965. The city of Singapore is the capital.

panda: A bear (Ailuropoda melanoleuca) of the mountains of central China, having woolly fur with distinctive black and white markings.

piacular: Making expiation or atonement for a sacrilege.

leeward: On or toward the side to which the wind is blowing.

pomelo: A tropical Southeast Asian tree (Citrus maxima) closely related to the grapefruit and having very large round fruit with a thick rind and coarse-grained pulp.

baculine: Of or pertaining to the rod, or to its use in punishment by flogging.

mar: To inflict damage, especially disfiguring damage, on.

fugleman: A leader, especially a political leader.

firmly: In a firm manner; solidly; compactly; strongly; steadily; with constancy or fixedness; steadfastly; resolutely; immovably: as, particles of matter firmly cohering; he firmly believes in fatalism; his resolution is firmly fixed.

ghetto: A usually poor section of a city inhabited primarily by people of the same race, religion, or social background, often because of discrimination.

pyxis: A capsule dehiscing transversely by a lid that falls off to release the seeds.

Tarzan: A heroic fictional character, raised in the jungle by apes.

indaba: A council or meeting of indigenous peoples of southern Africa to discuss an important matter.

urbanization: The process of rendering urbane or urban in character; the state of being urbanized.

Aaron: In the Bible, the elder brother of Moses who helped lead the Hebrews out of Egypt.

wadcutter: a special-purpose bullet designed for shooting paper targets, usually at close range and at subsonic velocities.

commitment: The act or an instance of committing, especially.

communicate: To convey information about; make known; impart.

money: A medium that can be exchanged for goods and services and is used as a measure of their values on the market, including among its forms a commodity such as gold, an officially issued coin or note, or a deposit in a checking account or other readily liquefiable account.

gaper: One who gapes, as from sleepiness, drowsiness, or dullness, or in wonder, astonishment, longing desire, or expectation.

theurgy: Divine or supernatural intervention in human affairs.

provender: Dry food, such as hay, used as feed for livestock.

diseuse: A woman who is a skilled and usually professional storyteller, poet, or other spoken-word performer.

matriculate: To admit or be admitted into a group, especially a college or university.
