polynomial: Of, relating to, or consisting of more than two names or terms.

encryption: The process or result of encrypting data.

griot: A storyteller in western Africa who perpetuates the oral tradition and history of a village or family.

emulate: To strive to equal or excel, especially through imitation.

obovate: Egg-shaped and flat, with the narrow end at the base.

wapiti: The North American stag or elk, Cervus canadensis, which is the North American representative of the stag or red deer of Europe, and resembles the latter, though it is much larger and of a stronger make, being one of the largest living representatives of the family Cervidæ.

extemporaneous: Carried out or performed with little or no preparation; impromptu.

disarming: Tending to allay suspicion or hostility; winning favor or confidence.

San Mateo: A city of northern California on San Francisco Bay between San Francisco and Silicon Valley.

translation: The act or process of translating, especially from one language into another.

palimpsest: A manuscript, typically of papyrus or parchment, that has been written on more than once, with the earlier writing incompletely scraped off or erased and often legible.

brotherhood: The state or relationship of being brothers.

offshore: Moving or directed away from the shore.

touchwood: Material, such as decayed wood, that is used as tinder; punk.

pochade: A slight, rough sketch which can easily be erased for correction.

blockade: The isolation of a nation, area, city, or harbor by hostile ships or forces in order to prevent the entrance and exit of traffic and commerce.

mother: To be or act as a mother to; treat in a motherly fashion.

otologist: One who is versed in otology, especially in its medical and surgical aspects; an aurist.

fascia: A sheet or band of fibrous connective tissue enveloping, separating, or binding together muscles, organs, and other soft structures of the body.

zanyism: The act or practice of imitation or mimicry.

trammel: A shackle used to teach a horse to amble.

crepidoma: The entire foundation of an ancient temple, including the stereobate and the stylobate.

llanero: An inhabitant of the llanos of South America.

gimcrack: A cheap and showy object of little or no use; a gewgaw.

primavera: Describing a light vegetable sauce, especially one served with pasta

defuse: To remove the fuse from (an explosive device).

aliquot: Of, relating to, or denoting an exact divisor or factor of a quantity, especially of an integer.

June: The sixth month of the year in the Gregorian calendar.

imagism: A literary movement launched by British and American poets in the early 1900s that advocated the use of free verse, common speech patterns, and clear concrete images as a reaction to Victorian sentimentalism.

seamark: A landmark visible from the sea, used as a guide in navigation.

fopdoodle: A stupid or insignificant fellow; a fool; a simpleton.

enigma: One that is puzzling, ambiguous, or inexplicable.

lusty: Full of vigor or vitality; robust.

herald: A person who carries or proclaims important news; a messenger.

chattel: An article of movable personal property.

purified: Made or rendered pure or more pure.

downwash: The downward deflection of air from a moving object, such as an airplane wing or propeller.

nutrition: The process of nourishing or being nourished, especially the process by which a living organism assimilates food and uses it for growth and for replacement of tissues.

exequy: plural Funeral rites; the ceremonies of burial; obsequies.

eigengrau: The dark grey colour seen by the eyes in perfect darkness, as a result of signals from the optic nerves.

Guatemala: A country of northern Central America. The site of a Mayan civilization dating back to 1500 BC, the area was conquered by Spain in 1524. After independence was achieved (1821), Guatemala joined in a federation of Central American states (1825–1838) before becoming a separate republic in 1839. Guatemala is the capital and the largest city.

trilithon: A prehistoric structure consisting of two large stones set upright to support a third on their tops, found especially in Europe.

mercy: Compassionate treatment, especially of those under one's power; clemency.

lamentable: Inspiring or deserving of lament or regret; deplorable or pitiable. synonym:pathetic.

harmonious: Exhibiting accord in feeling or action.

gravitas: Seriousness or solemnity in demeanor or treatment.

marmalade: A clear, jellylike preserve made from the pulp and rind of fruits, especially citrus fruits.

Turkmenistan: A country of west-central Asia east of the Caspian Sea. Once part of ancient Persia and later ruled by Arabs (8th century), Turks (11th century), Mongols (13th–14th century), and Uzbeks (late 15th century), it was annexed by Russia in 1881 and became a constituent state of the USSR, the Turkmen Soviet Socialist Republic, in 1925. Turkmenistan declared its independence in 1991 following the collapse of the Soviet Union. Ashgabat is the capital and the largest city.

earthquake: A sudden movement of the earth's crust caused by the release of stress accumulated along geologic faults or by volcanic activity.

Canada: A country of northern North America. The original inhabitants of the region include the Inuit and First Nations. European colonists arrived in eastern Canada in the early 1600s, and the area was claimed by the French and then ceded (1763) to the English after the Seven Years' War. Confederation of the territories and provinces of British North America, which eventually included all land north of the United States, began in 1867 and ended with the addition of Newfoundland in 1949. The Statute of Westminster (1931) confirmed Canada's status as an independent Dominion within the Commonwealth. Ottawa is the capital and Toronto the largest city.

yellow: The hue of that portion of the visible spectrum lying between orange and green, evoked in the human observer by radiant energy with wavelengths of approximately 570 to 590 nanometers; any of a group of colors of a hue resembling that of ripe lemons and varying in lightness and saturation; one of the subtractive primaries; one of the psychological primary hues.

precocious: Manifesting or characterized by development, aptitude, or interests considered advanced for a given age.

scarlatina: Same as scarlet fever (which see, under fever).

myelin: A white fatty material, composed chiefly of lipids and lipoproteins, that encloses certain axons and nerve fibers.

diremption: In veg. teratol., the abnormal displacement of leaves. See displacement, 6.

favonian: Of or relating to the west wind.

reticulate: Resembling or forming a net or network.

stridulation: The act, process, or function of stridulating; the power of so doing, or the thin, harsh, creaking noise thus produced; a shrilling.

bible: A comprehensive manual that describes something. (e.g., handyman’s bible).

domesticate: To cause to feel comfortable at home; make domestic.

manual: Of or relating to the hands.

grisaille: A style of monochromatic painting in shades of gray, used especially for the representation of relief sculpture.

bingle: A minor collision, especially between motor vehicles.

illusionist: An adherent of the doctrine of illusionism.

tempus fugit: time flies (used as an alternative to this phrase).

fanatic: A person marked or motivated by an extreme, unreasoning enthusiasm, as for a cause.

bungle: To carry out badly or ruin through ineptitude; botch. synonym:botch.

Israel: The State of Israel, a modern country in the Middle East, at the eastern shore of the Mediterranean.

hymeneal: Of or relating to a wedding or marriage.

irascible: Prone to outbursts of temper; easily angered.

scrambler: An electronic device that scrambles telecommunication signals to make them unintelligible to anyone without a special receiver.

swear: To make a solemn declaration, invoking a deity or a sacred person or thing, in confirmation of and witness to the honesty or truth of such a declaration.

synchronicity: The state or fact of being synchronous or simultaneous; synchronism.

reconnoiter: To make a preliminary examination of (an area or a group, for example), usually by moving around and observing, in order to gather information, especially for military purposes.

undergird: To support or strengthen from beneath.

Arizona: A state of the southwest United States on the Mexican border. It was admitted as the 48th state in 1912. Explored by the Spanish beginning in 1539, the area was acquired by the United States in 1848 through the Treaty of Guadalupe Hidalgo. Phoenix is the capital and the largest city.

remoulade: A popular condiment in many countries, usually mayonnaise-based.

ledger line: A short line placed above or below a staff to accommodate notes higher or lower than the range of the staff.

Saqqara: A village of northern Egypt near Cairo. It is the site of the oldest Egyptian pyramids, including the Step Pyramid built for the ruler Zoser during the III Dynasty (c. 2650–2580 BC).

Quebec: A province of eastern Canada. Originally the inhabited portion of New France along the St. Lawrence River, it became the Province of Quebec when it was awarded to Great Britain by the Treaty of Paris in 1763. In 1771 it was divided into Upper Canada (now Ontario) and Lower Canada. The two provinces were reunited in 1841 as the Province of Canada and separated once again with Confederation in 1867. French influence has remained dominant. Quebec is the capital and Montreal the largest city.

planar: Of, relating to, or situated in a plane.

ostracod: Any of numerous small chiefly aquatic crustaceans of the class Ostracoda, having a bivalve carapace and including many extinct species that are commonly found as fossils.

rachitis: A disease of very early life, characterized by a perversion of nutrition of the bones, by which uncalcified osteoid tissue is formed in place of bone, and the resorption of bone is quickened.

stasimon: In anc. Gr. lit., any song of the chorus in a drama after the parodos.

sniveling: Running at the nose; drawing up the mucus in the nose with an audible sound; hence, figuratively, whining; weakly tearful; affecting tearfulness: much used loosely as an epithet of contempt.

lunisolar: Of or caused by both the sun and the moon.

syllogism: A form of deductive reasoning consisting of a major premise, a minor premise, and a conclusion; for example, All humans are mortal, the major premise, I am a human, the minor premise, therefore, I am mortal, the conclusion.

escapology: The art, skill, or practice of escaping.

hatchet: A small, short-handled ax for use in one hand.

gynecologist: One versed in, or engaged in the study and practice of, gynecology.

Xerxes: Xerxes I, a Persian king of the Achaemenid dynasty who reigned 485-465 BC.

craft: Skill in doing or making something, as in the arts; proficiency. synonym:skill.

convenience: The quality of being suitable to one's comfort, purposes, or needs.

nacreous: In bacteriology, applied to colonies which are of a translucent, grayish-white color with a pearly luster.

suddenly: In a sudden or unexpected manner; unexpectedly; hastily; without preparation or premeditation; quickly; immediately.

uranography: The branch of astronomy concerned with mapping the positions of stars, galaxies, and other celestial bodies on the celestial sphere and with studying historical celestial maps.

amnesty: A general pardon granted by a government.

assets: In law: Sufficient estate; property sufficient in the hands of an executor or heir to pay the debts or legacies of the testator or ancestor to satisfy claims against it. Any goods or property or right of action properly available for the payment of a bankrupt's or a deceased person's obligations or debts: generally used to signify resources for the payment of debts, etc.

androcentric: Centered or focused on men, often to the neglect or exclusion of women.

incumbent: Imposed as an obligation or duty; obligatory.

trail: To allow to drag or stream behind, as along the ground.

accipitrine: Of or pertaining to the Accipitres or raptorial birds, or

votive: Given or dedicated in fulfillment of a vow or pledge.

murine: Of or relating to a rodent of the subfamily Murinae, which includes the house mouse and the brown rat.

phronesis: Practical judgment; the faculty of conducting one's self wisely.

subterfuge: Deception used to achieve an end.

bier: A stand on which a corpse or a coffin containing a corpse is placed before burial.

Illampu: A peak, 6,368 m (20,892 ft) high, in the Andes of western Bolivia northwest of La Paz.

breed: To produce (offspring); give birth to or hatch.

phenomenon: An occurrence, circumstance, or fact that is perceptible by the senses.

dispatch: To relegate to a specific destination or send on specific business. synonym:send.

eclaircissement: The clearing up of anything which is obscure or not easily understood; an explanation.

intransigent: Refusing to moderate a position, especially an extreme position; uncompromising.

antagonize: To incur the dislike of; provoke hostility or enmity in.

ephemeral: Lasting for a markedly brief time.

bibliography: A list of the works of a specific author or publisher.

rancor: Bitter, long-lasting resentment; deep-seated ill will.

askari: A member of a local African military or police unit serving in a European force

Aquila: A constellation in the Northern Hemisphere and the Milky Way near Aquarius and Serpens Cauda.

jimply: In a jimp or neat manner; neatly.

decoy: A living or artificial bird or other animal used to entice game into a trap or within shooting range.

lure: Something that tempts or attracts with the promise of pleasure or reward.

Dallas: A city of northeast Texas on the Trinity River east of Fort Worth. Founded in 1841, it grew as a cotton market in the late 1800s and is now a major commercial center.

longevity: Long life; great duration of life.

vapidity: The quality or state of being vapid, dull, or insipid; vapidness.

legato: In a smooth, even style without any noticeable break between the notes. Used chiefly as a direction.

welladay: An altered form of wellaway, simulating day—the present time, either as the witness or the cause of distress, being often brought into ejaculations of this kind. See wellaway.

ottava rima: A stanza of verse consisting of eight lines in iambic pentameter rhyming abababcc.

calembour: A pun; a play on words.

shamrock: A plant having compound leaves with three small leaflets, especially a clover or wood sorrel.

Passover: A holiday beginning on the 14th of Nisan and traditionally continuing for eight days, commemorating the exodus of the Hebrews from Egypt.

Germany: A country of north-central Europe. Occupied since c. 500 BC by Germanic tribes, the region became part of the Frankish empire by the sixth century AD. Later it became a loose federation of principalities and the nucleus of the Holy Roman Empire until the imperial state was broken up by Napoleon in 1806. Germany became a confederation after 1815 and then an empire centered around Prussia (1871–1918). Following its defeat in World War I, it was reorganized as the Weimar Republic, which collapsed when Adolf Hitler rose to power and formed the Third Reich. Germany's defeat in 1945 at the end of World War II resulted in its division into four occupation zones, each controlled by an Allied power. Out of the US, French, and British zones West Germany was established in 1949, while the Soviet zone became East Germany. The two Germanies were reunified in 1990 after the fall of the East German Communist government. Berlin is the capital and largest city.

largo: In a very slow tempo, usually considered to be slower than adagio, and with great dignity. Used chiefly as a direction.

thistledown: The silky down attached to the seedlike fruit of a thistle.

deckle: A frame used in making paper by hand to form paper pulp into sheets of a desired size.

hempen: Of, relating to, or resembling hemp.

rhodamine: Any of several synthetic red to pink dyes having brilliant fluorescent qualities.

deesis: An invocation of, or address to, the Supreme Being.

chinchilla: Either of two rodents of the genus Chinchilla that are native to the mountains of South America and are widely raised in captivity for their soft, pale gray fur.

Texas: A state of the south-central United States. It was admitted as the 28th state in 1845. Explored by the Spanish in the 1500s and 1600s, the region became a province of Mexico in the early 1800s. Texans won their independence in 1836 after a gallant but losing stand at the Alamo in February and a defeat of Santa Anna's forces at the Battle of San Jacinto (April 21). Denied admission as a state by antislavery forces in the US Congress, the leaders of Texas formed an independent republic that lasted until 1845. Austin is the capital.

engender: To bring into existence; give rise to.

midshipman: A student training to be a commissioned naval officer, especially a student at a naval academy.

plague: A highly infectious, usually fatal, epidemic disease; a pestilence.

carafe: A glass or metal bottle, often with a flared lip, used for serving water or wine.

focus: The distinctness or clarity of an image rendered by an optical system.

crewel: Loosely twisted worsted yarn used for fancywork and embroidery.

macron: A symbol ( ¯ ) placed over a vowel to show that it has a long sound.

Irish: Of or relating to Ireland or its people, language, or culture.

picot: A small embroidered loop used in a series to form an ornamental edging on lace or fabric.

leprechaun: In Irish folklore, a mischievous elflike creature or fairy who grants wishes or reveals the location of hidden treasure when captured.

cozens: Third-person singular simple present indicative form of cozen.

dirigisme: The practice or inclination to direct (activities) by a central authority. See also dirigiste.

exiguity: The quality or condition of being scanty or meager.

samogon: In Russia, home-distilled illegal spirit, similar to vodka; moonshine.

pugilist: A boxer; one who fights with his fists.

emulous: Eager or ambitious to equal or surpass another.

icarian: Pertaining or relating to Icarus, the son of Dædalus, who, to escape the wrath of Minos, is fabled in Greek legend to have fled from Crete with his father on wings fastened on with wax.

validate: To establish the soundness, accuracy, or legitimacy of: synonym:confirm.

woolgathering: The act of gathering wool: usually applied figuratively to the indulgence of idle fancies or to any foolish or fruitless pursuit.

utterance: The last or utmost extremity; the bitter end; death.

lace: A cord or ribbon used to draw and tie together two opposite edges, as of a shoe.

connoisseur: A person with expert knowledge or training, especially in the fine arts.

summarize: To make a summary or make a summary of.

travel: To go from one place to another, as on a trip; journey.

motorboat: A boat propelled by an internal-combustion engine or other motor.

bipolar: Relating to or having two poles or charges.

Pontiac: Ottawa leader who led Native Americans in a revolt against the British in the Great Lakes region (1763–1766).

reckless: Acting or done with a lack of care or caution; careless or irresponsible.

figurehead: A carved figure on the prow of a ship.

xenopus: Any of various aquatic, tongueless, clawed frogs of the genus Xenopus of southern Africa, certain species of which, especially the African clawed frog, are widely used for biological research.

lotic: Of, relating to, or living in moving water.

agitprop: Political propaganda, especially favoring communism and disseminated through literature, drama, art, or music.

jojoba: An evergreen dioecious shrub (Simmondsia chinensis) of the southwest United States and northern Mexico, having opposite, leathery leaves and seeds that yield an oil used in cosmetics and as a lubricant.

Machiavellian: Of or relating to Machiavelli or Machiavellianism.

scrappy: Consisting of scraps; made up of odds and ends; fragmentary.

skinny: Having very little bodily flesh or fat, often unattractively so; very thin. synonym:lean.

liberty: The condition of being free from confinement, servitude, or forced labor.

Parsee: One of the descendants of those Persians who settled in India about the end of the seventh and the beginning of the eighth century in order to escape Mohammedan persecution, and who still retain their ancient religion, now called Zoroastrianism. See Gueber.

photovore: A robot that is powered by solar cells and moves towards light to "feed".

abampere: The centimeter-gram-second electromagnetic unit of current equal to ten amperes.

Tunisia: A country of northern Africa bordering on the Mediterranean Sea. Settled in ancient times by the Phoenicians and dominated after the 6th century BC by the Carthaginians, the area later fell to the Romans (2nd century BC), Vandals (5th century AD), and Byzantines (6th century) before being conquered by the Arabs in the 7th century. Tunisia was taken over by the Ottoman Turks in the late 16th century and, as one of the Barbary States, was used as a base by pirates raiding ships in the Mediterranean. It became a French protectorate in 1881 and achieved full independence in 1956. Tunis is the capital and the largest city.

brasserie: A restaurant serving alcoholic beverages, especially beer, as well as food.

apnea: Temporary absence or voluntary cessation of breathing.

bandeau: A narrow band for the hair.

protest: To express a strong objection to (something).

earth-goddess: a goddess of fertility and vegetation.

earthling: One, especially a human, that inhabits the planet Earth.

rivulet: A small brook or stream; a streamlet.

coopery: The trade of a cooper; cooperage.

ollie: A skateboarding maneuver in which the rider lifts the board into the air by pressing down on it with the rear foot, raising the front foot, and then raising the rear foot.

codon: A sequence of three adjacent nucleotides constituting the genetic code that determines the insertion of a specific amino acid in a polypeptide chain during protein synthesis or the signal to stop protein synthesis.

flumpet: A musical instrument that blends qualities of the trumpet and flugelhorn.

aquifer: An underground layer of permeable rock, sediment, or soil that yields water. Aquifers can range from a few square kilometers to thousands of square kilometers in size.

arid: Lacking moisture, especially having insufficient rainfall to support trees or woody plants.

nozzle: A projecting part with an opening, as at the end of a hose, for regulating and directing a flow of fluid.

upholstered: Covered in or characterized by upholstery.

refraction: The turning or bending of any wave, such as a light or sound wave, when it passes from one medium into another of different optical density.

spanner: A wrench having a hook, hole, or pin at the end for meshing with a related device on another object.

Angara: A river of central Russia flowing about 1,850 km (1,150 mi) north and west from Lake Baikal to the Yenisey River.

revert: To go back to a former condition, practice, subject, or belief.

catachresis: The misapplication of a word or phrase, as the use of blatant to mean “flagrant.”

mysophobia: An abnormal fear of dirt or contamination.

parageusia: Perverted sense of taste. Also parageusis.

aposiopesis: A sudden breaking off of a thought in the middle of a sentence, as though the speaker were unwilling or unable to continue.

fulsome: Excessively flattering or insincerely earnest. synonym:unctuous.

timocracy: A state described by Plato as being governed on principles of honor and military glory.

exordium: A beginning or introductory part, especially of a speech or treatise.

arion: A genus of pulmonate gastropods, by some referred to the family Limacidæ and subfamily Arioninœ, but now generally considered as the type of a family Arionidœ, including several species of slugs, of which A. ater, the black slug, is a characteristic example.

welder: A person who welds, especially as a profession.

ebriety: Drunkenness; intoxication by spirituous liquors; derangement of the mental functions caused by drink.

arenicolous: Growing, living, or burrowing in sand.

exhort: To urge by strong, often stirring argument, admonition, advice, or appeal.

equivalent: Equal, as in value, force, or meaning.

ramify: To have complicating consequences or outgrowths.

belvedere: A roofed structure, especially a small pavilion or tower on top of a building, situated so as to command a wide view.

epiphyte: A plant, such as a tropical orchid or a staghorn fern, that grows on another plant upon which it depends for mechanical support but not for nutrients.

extreme: Most remote in any direction; outermost or farthest.

dactylonomy: The art of counting or numbering on the fingers.

variegated: Having streaks, marks, or patches of a different color or colors; varicolored.

upset: To cause to overturn; knock or tip over.

vesper: A bell that summons worshipers to vespers.

allay: To calm or pacify (an emotion); set to rest.

domestic: Of or relating to the family or household.

tabbouleh: A Lebanese salad made with bulgur wheat and finely chopped scallions, tomatoes, mint, and parsley.

epigram: A short, witty poem expressing a single thought or observation.

halberd: A weapon of the 1400s and 1500s having an axlike blade and a steel spike mounted on the end of a long shaft.

oedema: An excessive accumulation of serum in tissue spaces or a body cavity

biophony: the cumulative non-human sound produced by living organisms in a given biome.

colorblind: Partially or totally unable to distinguish certain colors.

backhand: Made with the back of the dominant hand facing forward.

shove: To push quickly, forcefully, or roughly: synonym:push.

condition: A mode or state of being: synonym:state.

unrequited: Not given, rewarded, or felt in return.

gainsay: To declare to be false; deny. synonym:deny.

dissolute: Lacking moral restraint; indulging in sensual pleasures or vices.

peace-pipe: The calumet or pipe of the American Indians, considered as the symbol of peace between tribes, etc., the smoking of it being the accompaniment of a treaty; the “pipe of peace.”

Calumet: A major industrial region of northeast Illinois and northwest Indiana on Lake Michigan adjacent to Chicago.

barrette: A small clasp for holding the hair in place.

cassia: Any of various chiefly tropical or subtropical trees, shrubs, or herbs of the genus Cassia in the pea family, having pinnately compound leaves, usually yellow flowers, and long, flat or cylindrical pods.

bobolink: An American migratory songbird (Dolichonyx oryzivorus), the male of which has black, white, and yellowish plumage.

enqueue: To add an item to a queue.

sessile: Permanently attached or fixed; not free-moving.

amative: Relating to or inclined toward love, especially sexual love; amorous.

homoiconicity: A property of some programming languages, in which the primary representation of programs is also a data structure in a primitive type of the language itself.

machination: The act of scheming or plotting.

impregnable: Not pregnable; not to be taken or reduced by force: as, an impregnable fortress.

surcoat: A loose outer coat or gown.

ratite: Relating to or being any of a group of flightless birds having a flat breastbone without the keellike prominence characteristic of most flying birds.

omicron: The 15th letter of the Greek alphabet.

cascabel: A small, round, medium-hot dried chili.

dithyramb: A frenzied, impassioned choric hymn and dance of ancient Greece in honor of Dionysus.

yoke: A contoured crossbar having two U-shaped attachments that fit around the necks of a team of oxen or other draft animals, with a central ring for hitching the team to a cart, plow, or other load.

perish: To die or be destroyed, especially in a violent or untimely manner.

vexation: The condition of being vexed; annoyance.

winner: One that wins, especially a victor in sports or a notably successful person.

paginal: Of, relating to, or consisting of pages.

rhodora: A deciduous shrub (Rhododendron canadense) in the heath family, native to northeast North America, having rose-purple flowers that bloom before the leaves appear.

jacklight: A light used as a lure in night hunting or fishing.

bipartisan: Of, consisting of, or supported by members of two parties, especially two major political parties.

candidate: A person who seeks or is nominated for an office, prize, or honor.

collective: Assembled into or viewed as a whole.

entice: To attract (someone), usually to do something, by arousing hope, interest, or desire: synonym:lure.

Vistula: A river of Poland, about 1,050 km (650 mi) long, rising near the border of the Czech Republic and flowing in an arc northeast, northwest, and north to the Gulf of Gdańsk.

atrip: Just clear of the bottom. Used of an anchor.

paleontology: The study of the forms of life existing in prehistoric or geologic times, as represented by the fossils of plants, animals, and other organisms.

Oklahoma: A state of the south-central United States. It was admitted as the 46th state in 1907. The western part was organized in 1890 as the Oklahoma Territory, which was merged with the adjoining Indian Territory to form the present state boundaries. The Dust Bowl of the 1930s forced many farmers to move west as migrant laborers. Oklahoma City is the capital and the largest city.

bosky: Having an abundance of bushes, shrubs, or trees.

Alaska: A state of the United States in extreme northwest North America including the Aleutian Islands and Alexander Archipelago and separated from the other mainland states by Canada. Purchased from Russia in 1867, Alaska received an influx of settlers during the Alaskan gold rush of the 1890s and was admitted as the 49th state in 1959. It includes a vast area of Arctic wilderness and is home to a large population of Alaska Natives. Juneau is the capital and Anchorage the largest city.

Nisan: The first month of the year in the Jewish calendar.

offset: An agent, element, or thing that balances, counteracts, or compensates for something else.

craton: A large portion of a continental plate that has been relatively undisturbed since the Precambrian Era and includes both shield and platform layers.

syndyasmian: Noting the pairing of animals or their paired state; nuptial; gamic; pertaining to the sexual relation.

buxom: Healthily plump and ample of figure.

embedded: enclosed or fixed firmly in a surrounding mass; surrounded on all sides.

amphetamine: A colorless, volatile liquid, C9H13N, used as a central nervous system stimulant in the treatment of certain conditions, such as attention deficit hyperactivity disorder, depression, and narcolepsy, and used illegally as a stimulant.

yield: To give forth by a natural process, especially by cultivation.

digital: Relating to or resembling a digit, especially a finger.

trend: A general tendency or course of events: synonym:tendency.

disavow: To disclaim knowledge of, responsibility for, or association with.

sociogenic: Arising from or imposed by society.

mycoremediation: The use of fungi to degrade or sequester contaminants in the environment.

quirkyalone: Someone who enjoys being single (but is not opposed to being in a relationship) and generally prefers to be alone rather than dating for the sake of being in a couple.

glean: To gather grain left behind by reapers.

goodbye: Used to express an acknowledgment of parting.

modus vivendi: A manner of living; a way of life.

obbligato: Not to be left out; indispensable. Used of an accompaniment that is an integral part of a piece.

lexigram: A symbol that represents a word but is not necessarily indicative of the object referenced by the word, used in studies of communication.

panzanella: An Italian salad made with chunks of dry or toasted bread, basil, tomatoes, and other vegetables, and tossed or marinated in a vinaigrette.

pachymeter: An instrument for measuring small thicknesses. One form determines the thickness of paper; another is adapted for measuring the thickness of glass. Also pachometer.

burlesque: A literary or dramatic work that makes fun of something, often by means of outlandish exaggeration.

efficacy: Power or capacity to produce a desired effect; effectiveness.

vehemently: In a vehement manner; with great force or violence; urgently; forcibly; ardently; passionately.

litigious: Of, relating to, or characterized by litigation.

conglomerate: To form or gather into a mass or whole.

yacca: Either of two West Indian evergreens, Podocarpus Purdieana and P. coriacea, trees becoming respectively 100 feet and 50 feet high, and affording timber suitable for cabinet and plain purposes.

palpal: Forming or formed by a palp; pertaining to a palp or to palpi; palpiform.

iroko: A valuable timber-tree of West Africa, Chlorophora excelsa, of the mulberry family. Its wood has a finely mottled grain and is much used for building purposes on account of its resisting the attacks of termites.

gutta: One of a series of small ornaments in the shape of truncated cones used on a Doric entablature.

biohacker: A person who manipulates DNA or other aspects of genetics either for fun, or maliciously

paroxysm: A sudden outburst of emotion or action.

amalgamation: The act of amalgamating or the condition resulting from this act.

primo: The principal part in a duet or ensemble composition.

quatrefoil: A representation of a flower with four petals or a leaf with four leaflets, especially in heraldry.

Tradescantia: A genus of monocotyledonous plants, type of the tribe Tradescantieæ in the order Commelinaceæ.

tacrine: A drug, C13H14N2, used in its hydrochloride form to treat memory loss and other cognitive deficits in people with Alzheimer's disease.

cosplay: this sense?) (countable) A costume that imitates a (usually fictional) character, especially from Japanese media (such as manga, anime, tokusatsu, video games, and Japanese pop music bands).

lichen: A composite organism made up of a fungus, usually an ascomycete, that grows symbiotically with an alga or a cyanobacterium and characteristically forms a crustlike or branching growth on rocks or tree trunks.

coverall: A loose-fitting one-piece work garment worn to protect clothes.

ichor: The rarefied fluid said to run in the veins of the gods.

alembic: An apparatus consisting of two vessels connected by a tube, formerly used for distilling liquids.

The peninsula was explored by Juan Ponce de León in 1513 and became the center of a Spanish settlement that included the southeast part of the present-day United States. Spain finally ceded the area in 1819. Tallahassee is the capital.

Quantico: A town of northwest Virginia on the Potomac River south-southwest of Alexandria. A US Marine Corps base was established here in 1918.

ancilla: A genus of mollusks. See Ancillinæ.

fitful: Occurring in or characterized by intermittent bursts, as of activity; irregular.

quinceañera: A celebration of the fifteenth birthday of a Hispanic or Latina girl, typically including a Roman Catholic Mass and often serving as a social debut.

hussar: A horseman of the Hungarian light cavalry organized during the 1400s.

São Tomé and Príncipe: An island country in the Gulf of Guinea off western Africa. Probably uninhabited at the time of European discovery in 1471, the islands were settled (1483) by the Portuguese, who held them, except for a period of Dutch rule in the 1600s, until they gained full independence in 1975. São Tomé is the capital.

epicarp: In botany, the outer skin of fruits, the fleshy substance or edible portion being termed the mesocarp, and the inner portion the endocarp. See cut under endocarp.

lurgy: A fictitious, highly infectious disease; often used in the phrase "the dreaded lurgi", sometimes as a reference to flu-like symptoms

Aegisthus: The son of Thyestes and lover of Clytemnestra. He helped Clytemnestra kill her husband Agamemnon upon Agamemnon's return from the Trojan War.

São Paulo: A city of southeast Brazil west-southwest of Rio de Janeiro. Founded by Jesuits in 1554, it developed rapidly as an industrial and commercial center after the 1880s and is now the largest city in South America.

lentigo: A small, flat, pigmented spot on the skin.

periodontics: The branch of dentistry that deals with the diagnosis and treatment of diseases and disorders of the gums.

ethologist: One versed in ethology; one who studies or writes on the subject of manners and morals.

hanap: A large drinking-goblet, especially the vessel from which the chief guest at an entertainment or the presiding dignitary was served.

lather: A foam formed by soap or detergent agitated in water, as in washing or shaving.

slaughter: The killing of animals especially for food.

Baton Rouge: The capital of Louisiana, in the southeast-central part of the state on a bluff above the Mississippi River. Founded in 1719 as a French fort, it became the state capital in 1849 and was captured (May 1862) by Union admiral David Farragut during the Civil War. It is a major port of entry and oil-refining center.

vendor: One that sells or vends something.

tequila: An alcoholic liquor distilled from the fermented sap of the blue agave.

Tokyo: The capital and largest city of Japan, in east-central Honshu on Tokyo Bay, an inlet of the Pacific Ocean. Founded in the 1100s as Edo, the city was renamed Tokyo when it became the imperial capital in 1868. Much of the city was destroyed by an earthquake in 1923 and by bombing raids during World War II.

entr'acte: The interval between two acts of a theatrical performance.

buckram: A coarse cotton or linen fabric heavily sized with glue, used for stiffening garments and in bookbinding.

termagant: A woman regarded as quarrelsome or scolding; a shrew.

gay: Of, relating to, or having a sexual orientation to persons of the same sex.

filigree: Delicate and intricate ornamental work made from gold, silver, or other fine twisted wire.

undulate: To move in waves or with a smooth, wavelike motion.

acuity: Acuteness of vision or perception; keenness.

exaltation: The act of exalting or the condition of being exalted.

Tbilisi: The capital and largest city of Georgia, in the southeast part of the country on the Kura River. An ancient city astride trade and migration routes between Europe and Asia Minor, it was the capital of an independent Georgian state from 1122 to 1236 and was held by Mongols, Persians, and Turks before coming under Russian control in 1801. Tbilisi was the capital of the Transcaucasian Soviet Federated Socialist Republic (1922–1936) and the Georgian Soviet Socialist Republic (1936–1991).

tranche: A portion of a total, especially of a block of assets such as cash or securities.

deemster: A judge; one who pronounces sentence or doom; specifically, the title of two judges in the Isle of Man who act as the chief justices of the island, the one presiding over the northern, the other over the southern, division. Compare doomster.

truncheon: A short stick carried by police; a billy club.

undue: Exceeding what is appropriate or normal; excessive.

uremia: A toxic condition resulting from kidney disease in which there is retention in the bloodstream of waste products normally excreted in the urine.

accommodate: To have enough space for: synonym:contain.

spittlebug: Any of various small insects of the family Cercopidae that feed on plant sap and whose larvae produce cuckoo spit.

andragogy: The methods or techniques used to teach adults.

Monte Carlo: A town of Monaco on the Mediterranean Sea and the French Riviera. It is a noted resort famed for its casino and luxurious hotels.

Kenya: A country of east-central Africa bordering on the Indian Ocean. The site of many fossils of early human species, Kenya was inhabited during historic times by various Cushitic, Nilotic, and Bantu peoples including the Kikuyu and the Masai. The coast was settled by Arab traders in the 8th century AD and later (16th–18th century) by the Portuguese. Kenya became a British protectorate in 1890 and crown colony in 1920. It achieved independence in 1963. Nairobi is the capital and the largest city.

assess: To determine the value, significance, or extent of; appraise. synonym:estimate.

reduce: To bring down, as in extent, amount, or degree; diminish. synonym:decrease.

India: A peninsula and subcontinent of southern Asia south of the Himalaya Mountains, occupied by India, Nepal, Bhutan, Pakistan, and Bangladesh.

Tuareg: A member of a traditionally Muslim, Berber-speaking people inhabiting the western and central Sahara and western Sahel of northwest Africa.

clearance: The act or process of clearing.

stoup: A basin or font for holy water at the entrance of a church.

bibliophobia: A dread or hatred of books.

phobia: A persistent, abnormal, and irrational fear of a specific thing or situation that compels one to avoid it, despite the awareness and reassurance that it is not dangerous.

apiary: A place where bees and beehives are kept, especially a place where bees are raised for their honey.

indigence: The state of being poor; poverty.

vitreous: Of, relating to, resembling, or having the nature of glass; glassy.

output: An amount produced or manufactured during a certain time.

outpost: A detachment of troops stationed at a distance from a main force to guard against surprise attacks.

nyala: Either of two African antelopes of the genus Tragelaphus having vertical white stripes on the body, especially T. angasii of southeast Africa, the male of which has spirally twisted horns and long black hair along the neck and underside.

sardonyx: An onyx with alternating brown and white bands of sard and other minerals.

gadget: A small specialized mechanical or electronic device; a contrivance.

cull: To pick out from others; select.

frieze: A coarse, shaggy woolen cloth with an uncut nap.

ketch: A two-masted fore-and-aft-rigged sailing vessel with a mizzenmast stepped aft of a taller mainmast but forward of the rudder.

willet: A large grayish sandpiper (Tringa semipalmata) of the Americas whose wings show a black and white pattern when the bird is in flight.

quelea: Any of several African weaverbirds of the genus Quelea, especially Q. quelea, a small red-billed bird that is destructive to grain crops.

polyglot: Speaking, writing, written in, or composed of several languages.

tsardom: the territory ruled by a tsar

actioned: Simple past tense and past participle of action.

spikenard: An aromatic perennial herb (Nardostachys grandiflora) of the Himalaya Mountains, having rose-purple flowers.

cad: A man whose behavior is unprincipled or dishonorable.

oleander: A poisonous Eurasian evergreen shrub (Nerium oleander) with narrow leathery leaves, widely cultivated for its showy fragrant white, rose, or purple flowers.

rissole: A small, pastry-enclosed croquette of finely minced meat or fish, usually fried in deep fat.

shrug: To raise (the shoulders), especially as a gesture of doubt, disdain, or indifference.

concatenation: The state of being concatenated or linked together; a relation of interconnection or interdependence.

umbel: A flat-topped or rounded flower cluster in which the individual flower stalks arise from about the same point, characteristic of plants in the parsley family, such as Queen Anne's lace.

Leander: A youth who loved Hero and drowned during one of his nightly swims across the Hellespont to be with her.

testudo: A Roman siege device consisting of a movable screen protecting the besiegers' approach to a wall.

frondeur: In French history, a member of the Fronde.

denouement: The final resolution or clarification of a dramatic or narrative plot.

bivouac: A temporary encampment often in an unsheltered area.

arête: A sharp, narrow mountain ridge or spur.

endorphin: Any of a group of peptide hormones that bind to opiate receptors and are found mainly in the brain. Endorphins reduce the sensation of pain and affect emotions.

apostasy: Abandonment of one's religious faith, a political party, one's principles, or a cause.

scortatory: Pertaining to or consisting in lewdness.

dais: A raised platform, as in a lecture hall, for speakers or honored guests.

rabble: To speak confusedly; talk incoherently; utter nonsense.

idle: Of machinery, doing no direct work; merely changing the direction of motion: as, an idle gear; also, running merely to carry transmission-elements: as, an idle pulley (which see).

yen: A strong desire or inclination; a yearning or craving.

prognosticate: To predict according to present indications or signs; foretell. synonym:predict.

bestride: To sit or stand on with the legs astride; straddle.

deadlight: A strong shutter or plate fastened over a ship's porthole or cabin window in stormy weather.

vernissage: A private showing held before the opening of an art exhibition.

befana: Primarily, in Italy, an Epiphany present or gift.

trove: A collection of valuable items discovered or found; a treasure-trove.

zaftig: Having a full, shapely figure. Used of a woman.

colonization: The act or process of establishing a colony or colonies.

suborn: To induce (a person) to commit an unlawful or evil act.

suffer: To feel pain or distress; sustain injury or harm.

sprout: To begin to grow; give off shoots or buds.

creep: To move with the body close to the ground, as on hands and knees.

theoxenia: Hospitality towards a god who visits as a guest.

semaphore: A visual signaling apparatus with flags, lights, or mechanically moving arms, as one used on a railroad.

firmament: The vault or expanse of the heavens; the sky.

placket: An opening or slit in a garment, as at the collar or sleeve of a shirt, that makes the garment easy to put on.

fichu: A woman's triangular scarf of lightweight fabric, worn over the shoulders and crossed or tied in a loose knot at the breast.

silenus: Any of the minor woodland deities and companions of Dionysus, depicted on Greek vases as men with the tails, ears, and hooves of horses.

lingam: A stylized phallus worshiped as a symbol of the god Shiva.

bogeyman: A goblin; a bugbear; a bogey{1}. This is the form used by parents to frighten children.

ergophobia: A morbid aversion to labor. Compare ergasiophobia.

nyctophobia: An abnormal fear of the night or darkness.

nostrum: A medicine whose effectiveness is unproved and whose ingredients are usually secret; a quack remedy.

paradoxure: Any species of the genus Paradoxurus; a palm-cat or palm-marten.

morpho: Any of various large nymphalid butterflies of the genus Morpho of tropical regions of the Americas, noted for the brilliant iridescent blue color of their wings.

crants: A garland carried before the bier of a maiden and hung over her grave.

Bethel: A town of ancient Palestine north of Jerusalem. It is now a major archaeological site.

coda: The concluding passage of a movement or composition.

unencumbered: not burdened with worries, cares or responsibilities

refusenik: A usually Jewish citizen of the Soviet Union who was denied permission to emigrate.

subphylum: A taxonomic category of related organisms ranking below a phylum and above a class.

penniform: Having the form of a quill or feather; resembling a feather in form.

vindicated: Simple past tense and past participle of vindicate.

omnipotence: Almighty power; infinite power as an attribute of deity; hence, God himself.

sitzmark: A hollow made in the snow by a skier who has fallen backward.

Hawaii: A state of the United States in the central Pacific Ocean including all of the Hawaiian Islands except Midway. It became a US territory in 1900 and was admitted as the 50th state in 1959. The islands were conquered and united by King Kamehameha I between 1795–1810, and the last Hawaiian monarch, Queen Liliuokalani, was deposed in 1893. Honolulu, on Oahu, is the capital and the largest city.

skinflint: One who is very reluctant to spend money; a miser.

gentile: A person who is not Jewish.

publish: To prepare and issue (a book, music, or other material) for public distribution, especially for sale.

rotor: A rotating part of an electrical or mechanical device.

helot: One of a class of serfs in ancient Sparta, neither a slave nor a free citizen.

rille: A long, narrow, roughly straight channel or groove on the surface of a solar system body like a planet or moon.

execrate: To declare to be hateful or abhorrent; denounce.

myosin: The most common protein in muscle cells, responsible for the elastic and contractile properties of muscle. It combines with actin to form actomyosin.

kakizome: the first calligraphy written at the beginning of a year

ad hoc: For the specific purpose, case, or situation at hand and for no other.

jibe: To shift a fore-and-aft sail from one side of a vessel to the other while sailing before the wind so as to sail on the opposite tack.

laminar: Composed of or disposed in laminæ, or thin plates or layers; lamellar.

merle: Having a coat with irregular streaks or speckles of a contrasting color. Used of certain dogs.

brava: Used to express approval of a woman, especially for a performance.

microburst: A sudden, violent downdraft of air over a small area. Microbursts are difficult to detect and predict with standard weather instruments and are especially hazardous to airplanes during landing or takeoff.

kimchi: A usually spicy Korean dish made of vegetables, such as cabbage or radishes, that are salted, seasoned, and allowed to ferment.

muckibus: Confused or muddled with drink; tipsy; maudlin.

peregrination: A traveling from one country or place to another; a roaming or wandering about in general; travel; pilgrimage.

utility: The quality or condition of being useful; usefulness.

id: In Freudian theory, the division of the psyche that is totally unconscious and serves as the source of instinctual impulses and demands for immediate satisfaction of primitive needs.

contretemps: An unforeseen event that disrupts the normal course of things; an inopportune occurrence.

wastrel: One who wastes, especially one who wastes money; a profligate.

theandric: Relating to or existing by the union of the divine and human natures, or by the joint agency of the divine and human natures: as, the theandric operation (the harmonious coöperation of the two natures in Christ).

rhyton: A hornlike drinking vessel of ancient times, often having a pointed end shaped like an animal or animal's head.

sob: To weep aloud with convulsive gasping; cry uncontrollably. synonym:cry.

syndicate: An association of people or firms formed to promote a common interest or carry out a business enterprise.

arraigned: Simple past tense and past participle of arraign.

clairaudience: The supposed power to hear things outside the range of normal perception.

sagacity: The quality of being discerning, sound in judgment, and farsighted; wisdom.

surnape: A second table-cloth laid over the larger cloth at one end, as before the master of the feast.

harmattan: A dry dusty wind that blows along the northwest coast of Africa.

eyas: A nestling hawk or falcon, especially one to be trained for falconry.

shindig: A festive party, often with dancing.

masquerade: A costume party at which masks are worn; a masked ball.

raglan: Having or being a sleeve that extends in one piece to the neckline of the garment, with slanted seams from the armhole to the neck.

furbelow: A ruffle or flounce on a garment.

gouge: A chisel with a blade that has a rounded, angled, or troughlike indentation along its length.

tellurite: In chem., a compound of tellurous acid and a base.

affluenza: Materialism or overconsumption in affluent societies, seen as a societal and environmental menace, as in large-scale consumer debt and product waste.

cilium: A microscopic hairlike process extending from the surface of a cell or unicellular organism. Capable of rhythmical motion, it acts in unison with other such structures to bring about the movement of the cell or of the surrounding medium.

dilettante: One who dabbles in an art or a field of knowledge.

cesarean: Of or relating to a cesarean section.

peripatetic: Walking about or from place to place; traveling on foot.

cyclorama: A large composite picture placed on the interior walls of a cylindrical room so as to appear in natural perspective to a spectator standing in the center of the room.

penchant: A definite liking; a strong inclination. synonym:predilection.

douceur: Money given as a tip, gratuity, or bribe.

savarin: a sponge cake baked in a ring mold

octad: A group or sequence of eight.

vault: An arched structure, usually of masonry or concrete, serving to cover a space.

tanager: Any of various songbirds of the family Thraupidae of the Americas, often having brightly colored plumage in the male.

thurifer: An acolyte who carries a thurible.

manipulate: To move, arrange, operate, or control by the hands or another body part or by mechanical means, especially in a skillful manner: synonym:handle.

volition: The act of making a conscious choice or decision.

throwster: One that twists fibers into thread.

hauberk: A long tunic made of chain mail.

Loki: A god who created discord, especially among his fellow gods.

andvari: (Norse mythology) a dwarf who possessed a treasure that was stolen by Loki

Miriam: Sister of Moses and Aaron, and the daughter of Amram and Jochebed.

Endymion: A handsome young man whom Selene loved and whose youth was preserved by eternal sleep.

farrago: An assortment or a medley; a conglomeration.

toyon: An evergreen shrub (Heteromeles arbutifolia) in the rose family, native to California and Baja California, having leathery leaves, small white flowers in large panicles, and red berrylike fruit.

alimentary: Concerned with food, nutrition, or digestion.

metastasis: Transmission of pathogenic microorganisms or cancerous cells from an original site to one or more sites elsewhere in the body, usually by way of the blood vessels or lymphatics.

stoic: One who is seemingly indifferent to or unaffected by joy, grief, pleasure, or pain.

hilarious: Characterized by or causing great merriment.

cyclopel: A rhythmic silt–clay lamination formed in a tide-water glacial marine inlet.

jaw: Either of two bony or cartilaginous structures that in most vertebrates form the framework of the mouth and hold the teeth.

telamon: A figure of a man used as a supporting pillar.

Manila: The capital of the Philippines, on southwest Luzon Island and Manila Bay, an inlet of the South China Sea. Founded in 1571, the city was controlled by Spain until it was seized by US troops in 1898 during the Spanish-American War. It was held by the Japanese from 1942 to 1945 during World War II.

official: Of or relating to an office or a post of authority.

erstwhile: In the past; at a former time; formerly.

prebend: A stipend historically drawn by a beneficed canon of a cathedral or collegiate church.

typocosmy: A representation of the world; universal terminology.

berth: Sufficient space for a vessel to maneuver; sea room.

chad: Scraps or bits of paper, such as the perforated edges of paper for tractor feed printers or the tiny rectangles punched out from data cards.

bandy: To toss or throw back and forth.

stupendous: So great in scope, degree, or importance as to amaze.

break: To cause to separate into pieces suddenly or violently; smash.

kleptocrat: A ruling figure in a kleptocracy.

schismatic: Of, relating to, or engaging in schism.

mufti: A Mohammedan law-officer whose duty it was to expound the law which the kadi was to execute.

mapinguary: A legendary red-furred ground-dwelling sloth-like creature said to live in the Amazon rainforests of Brazil and Bolivia.

heuristic: Of or relating to a usually speculative formulation serving as a guide in the investigation or solution of a problem.

warren: An area where rabbits live in burrows.

hireling: One who works solely for compensation, especially a person willing to perform for a fee tasks considered menial or offensive.

folie a deux: the simultaneous occurrence of symptoms of a mental disorder (as delusions) in two persons who are closely related (as siblings or man and wife)

acrostic: A poem or series of lines in which certain letters, usually the first in each line, form a name, motto, or message when read in sequence.

intemperate: Not temperate or moderate, especially in rhetoric or tone; unrestrained: synonym:excessive.

profligacy: The character or condition of being profligate; a profligate or very vicious course of life; abandoned conduct; shameless dissipation.

surreal: Having qualities attributed to or associated with surrealism.

doughy: Having the consistency or appearance of dough.

desultory: Moving or jumping from one thing to another; disconnected.

wintry: Belonging to or characteristic of winter; cold.

vidimus: An examination or inspection: as, a vidimus of accounts or documents.

telegony: In biology, the supposed influence of a first sire upon the progeny subsequently borne by the mother to other sires. Most breeders are believers in telegony, although careful experiments have failed to show any scientific basis for their opinion.

gaffe: A clumsy social error; a faux pas.

apothegm: A terse, witty, instructive saying; a maxim.

provost: A university administrator of high rank.

viviparous: Giving birth to living offspring that develop within the mother's body. Most mammals and some other animals are viviparous.

heliostat: An instrument in which a mirror is automatically moved so that it reflects sunlight in a constant direction. It is used with a pyrheliometer to make continuous measurements of solar radiation.

beefalo: A hybrid that results from a cross between the North American bison (buffalo) and beef cattle and is typically3/8bison and5/8domestic cattle. Beefalo yields leaner beef than conventional breeds of cattle.

reechy: Tarnished with smoke; sooty; foul; squalid; filthy.

aggression: Hostile or destructive behavior or attitudes.

injurious: Causing or tending to cause injury; harmful.

tremolo: A tremulous effect produced by rapid repetition of a single tone or by rapid alternation of two tones.

Murcia: A region and former kingdom of southeast Spain on the Mediterranean Sea. Settled by Carthaginians, it was conquered by the Moors in the 8th century and became an independent Moorish kingdom in the 11th century. It was annexed by Castile in 1266.

stemware: Glassware mounted on a stem with a broad base.

ephod: A vestment worn by ancient Hebrew priests.

hyssop: A woody Eurasian plant (Hyssopus officinalis) in the mint family, having spikes of small blue or violet flowers and aromatic leaves used in perfumery, as a condiment, and formerly in medicine.

complaisant: Exhibiting a desire or willingness to please; cheerfully obliging.

ecumenical: Of worldwide scope or applicability; universal.

tafia: A cheap rum distilled from molasses and refuse sugar in the West Indies.

syconium: The fleshy multiple fruit of a fig, consisting of the enlarged, hollow, rounded floral receptacle with numerous fruitlets inside.

eupatrid: A member of the hereditary aristocracy of ancient Athens.

madcap: Behaving or acting impulsively or rashly; wild.

eurythmics: A system of music education developed by Émile Jaques-Dalcroze, in which body movements are used to develop awareness of rhythm and musical form.

muttonchops: Side whiskers that are narrow at the temple, broad along the lower cheek or jawline, and separated by a shaven chin.

specificity: The state of being specific, or of having a specific character or relation; specific affinity, cause, origin, or effect; specificness.

switch: An exchange or a swap, especially one done secretly.

cultivate: To improve and prepare (land), as by plowing or fertilizing, for raising crops; till.

pathogen: An agent that causes disease, especially a virus, bacterium, or fungus.

colleague: A fellow member of a profession, staff, or academic faculty; an associate. synonym:partner.

taigle: To entangle; impede; hinder; hence, to fatigue; weary.

portmanteau: A large leather suitcase that opens into two hinged compartments.

brunch: A meal typically eaten in the late morning or early afternoon as a combination of breakfast and lunch.

Velcro: A trademark for a fastening tape consisting of a strip of nylon with a surface of minute hooks that fasten to a corresponding strip with a surface of uncut pile.

spork: An eating utensil having a spoonlike bowl and tines.

mirth: Gladness and merriment, especially when expressed by laughter.

acerbated: Simple past tense and past participle of acerbate.

wok: A metal pan having a rounded bottom, used especially for frying and steaming in Asian cooking.

unitary: Of or relating to a unit.

wonton: A noodle-dough dumpling filled typically with spiced minced pork or other ground meat, usually boiled in soup or fried and eaten as a side dish.

include: To contain or take in as a part, element, or member.

upkeep: Maintenance in proper operation, condition, and repair.

matutinal: Of, relating to, or occurring in the morning; early.

vade mecum: A useful thing that one constantly carries about.

arabis: A large genus of plants, of the order Cruciferæ; wall- or rock-cress.

heterosis: In grammar and rhetoric, same as enallage.

mouffle: The loose covering around the nose and upper lips of the moose or elk. Prized for stewing or roasting.

bibliophage: A person who loves books; a bookworm.

yeoman: An attendant, servant, or lesser official in a royal or noble household.

bounteous: Existing in, characterized by, or producing abundance.

hassel: Norwegian chemist noted for his research on organic molecules (1897-1981)

integration: The act or process of integrating.

levee: An embankment on the margin of a river, to confine it within its natural channel: as, the levees of the Mississippi.

swannery: A place where swans are bred and reared.

mullion: A vertical member, as of stone or wood, dividing a window or other opening.

psychopath: A person who engages repeatedly in criminal and antisocial behavior without remorse or empathy for those victimized.

delude: To cause to hold a false belief; deceive thoroughly: synonym:deceive.

parody: A literary or artistic work that imitates the characteristic style of an author or a work for comic effect or ridicule.

belabor: To talk or write about at length or excessively; harp on.

cancelled: Simple past tense and past participle of cancel.

dopey: Dazed or lethargic, as if drugged.

usufruct: The right to the use and profits of something belonging to another.

stotinka: a unit of currency in Bulgaria, equal to one-hundredth of a lev

ovule: A structure in seed plants that consists of the embryo sac surrounded by the nucellus and one or two integuments and that develops into a seed after it is fertilized.

vitric: Of the nature of, or pertaining to, glass or any vitreous material.

binaural: Having or relating to two ears.

cornu: A part or structure, such as a bony protuberance, that resembles a horn.

tinea: A fungal infection of the skin known generally as ringworm.

galantine: A dish of boned, stuffed meat or fish that is poached and served cold coated with aspic.

umami: A taste sensation produced by the presence of glutamates and nucleotides and associated with meats and other high-protein foods. It is sometimes considered to be a fifth basic taste along with the tastes sweet, sour, salty, and bitter.

Beijing: The capital of China, in the northeast part of the country. It served as Kublai Khan's capital (13th century) and the capital of the Ming and Qing dynasties (1421–1911). From 1928 to 1949 it was known as Peiping. It is a major commercial and industrial center and the political, educational, and cultural center of the country.

antediluvian: Occurring or belonging to the era before the Flood.

Gironde: The party of the Girondists taken collectively: as, the Rolands were leaders of the Gironde.

filibeg: A plaited petticoat or skirt reaching only to the knees, worn by men in the Highlands of Scotland; a kilt.

miaul: To cry as a cat; mew.

palilalia: A complex tic comprising the repetition or echoing of one's own spoken words, which may sound like stuttering.

coefficient: A number or symbol multiplied with a variable or an unknown quantity in an algebraic term, as 4 in the term 4x, or x in the term x(a + b).

fig: Any of various trees or shrubs of the genus Ficus, especially F. carica, native to the Mediterranean region and widely cultivated for its edible multiple fruit.

trope: A figure of speech using words in nonliteral ways, such as a metaphor.

bearing: The manner in which one carries or conducts oneself: synonym:behavior.

mannish: Of or relating to men; masculine.

mirador: A window, balcony, or small tower affording an extensive view.

coeval: Originating or existing during the same period; lasting through the same era.

Qatar: A country of eastern Arabia on a peninsula in the southwest Persian Gulf. A traditional monarchy, it was a British protectorate from 1916 until 1971, when it became independent. Oil was first produced commercially in 1949, and its production still dominates Qatar's economy. Doha is the capital and the largest city.

esplanade: A flat open stretch of pavement or grass, especially one designed as a promenade along a shore.

calumniate: To make maliciously or knowingly false statements about. synonym:malign.

rococo: A style of art, especially architecture and decorative art, that originated in France in the early 1700s and is marked by elaborate ornamentation, as with a profusion of scrolls, foliage, and animal forms.

elflock: A knot of hair twisted by elves; a knot twisted as if by elves; hence, in the plural, hair in unusual disorder.

refractory: Showing or characterized by obstinate resistance to authority or control.

applicable: Capable of being applied; relevant or appropriate.

incursion: An aggressive entrance into foreign territory; a raid or invasion.

radicalize: To make radical or more radical.
